<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Memories of Moscow
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian retrospective ...
</P>
<P>
   I've made seven trips to Moscow since 1990. This last visit,
indeed, may be my last.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying I liked Moscow better under communism. But
neither do I like what it's become since the fall of communism.
</P>
<P>
   Notes from along the way:
</P>
<P>
   _ At Moscow's airport, the first greeting that visitors receive
is that of capitalism. There are now ads, in English, above the
booths where passports are checked.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prostitutes, whose prices range as high as $250, are
commonplace on Moscow streets. In the days of the Communist state,
unmarried couples weren't even allowed to check into a hotel room.
Women wrestlers, in the guise of hall attendants, made sure no one
sneaked in.
</P>
<P>
   _ So congested were the recent hordes of hookers that members of
Parliament were having to fight their way through the crowds to get
to their hotels. A special law had to be passed restricting
prostitutes to certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nudity on TV, which flourished with the fall of communism, has
also been restricted and is now seen only on paid channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moscow has become one of the most expensive cities in the
world. Eight years ago a lavish apartment in downtown Moscow could
be had for about $50,000. The price now is closer to $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moscow's new extravagant shopping center, near Red Square, is
named Manehz in honor of the czar's palace-style stables where
aristocrats exercised their horses.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Manehz opened, crowds wandered about the mall in awe of
its opulence (including a three-story fountain flanked by glass
elevators), not unlike the Bolsheviks after they had stormed the
czar's residence.
</P>
<P>
   _ I love the Russian sayings. One that I heard for the first
time on this trip was, ``When I spoke, she looked into my mouth.''
What it means, I'm told, is that she sought my wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Something I noticed about the mouths of Russians, they're
beginning to wear braces on their teeth. Nor do you see so many
people with stainless steel teeth, commonplace during Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maybe that has something to with the fact that I met a
saleslady who actually smiled, a rarity in Moscow. Most stores
operate as if they were still under communism when everyone was
treated the same _ with contempt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware of famous brands of liquor sold here. They're often
counterfeit. No telling what you end up drinking.
</P>
<P>
   _ A waiter, presented with my American Express card, couldn't
believe the card notation that I'd been a member since 1970. ``I
had no idea American Express had been around for so long,'' he
said, amazed.
</P>
<P>
   _ When I first visited Moscow, it was routine for a driver to
remove the vehicle's windshield wipers when leaving it parked.
Otherwise, they would likely be stolen. I noticed this trip that's
no longer the practice, which I mentioned to a Russian friend.
``Right,'' he said. ``Now they just steal still the whole car.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
