<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CLINTON FINALLY ADMITS IT _ SO WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   Don't
you just love it? All those moralists thumping their chests and
wagging their accusatory fingers at President Clinton. They have
eagerly read and memorized the varied accounts of Clinton's affair
and throughout it all clucked their tongues disapprovingly _ while
lapping up a daily diet of alleged sexual details.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They can be titillated and self-righteous at the same time _
such is the hypocrisy of America's Puritan heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the media has danced like a gaggle of gleeful puppets
in this long charade _ playing to the sexual schizophrenia of the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   Sex _ as a nation we don't know what to do about it. Some want
all references to sex eliminated from books and the Internet,
others will buy something they don't need if it's sold in a sexy
manner, as any advertising director can verify.
</P>
<P>
   Self-righteous moralists can't get enough of the nitty-gritty on
the president's sex life _ so they can feel and act superior. They
would deny, however, any tingling sensations that might arise from
their prurient interests.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday night, a hounded and subpoenaed Clinton finally
publicly admitted that he had sex _ ``an inappropriate
relationship,'' as he called it _ with Monica Lewinsky. Even so, he
didn't quite confess to what he had denied previously.
</P>
<P>
   Some pundits act shocked; others call for him to step down _ as
if Clinton were the only president who had affairs while in office.
These commentators seriously need a reality check. They act as if
they are totally naive about the relationship between power and
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Power is an aphrodisiac _ to those who have it and to those in
proximity. From the kings and queens of England to the generals in
the early republic, power has been granted sexual favors.
</P>
<P>
   Others comment that Clinton's presidency will be diminished in
the view of history. Have any presidencies been diminished
historically because of rambunctious sexual cavorting? Not one _
from Washington to Jefferson to Kennedy and Johnson. Presidencies
are historically judged on leadership and the state of the nation
when they ended their tenures.
</P>
<P>
   When the years erase the topical and irrelevant, only the
accomplishments remain.
</P>
<P>
   Were any of the two dozen known philandering presidents forced
to admit that they had affairs while in office? No.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the president was respected, even if a particular
president wasn't. Such investigations would have been squelched.
Now, the office has been so degraded that Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
can call the president a jerk on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   Is a president's sexual behavior the public's business?
Generally, no.
</P>
<P>
   No more than it's the president's business to look into our
sexual partners. The only time such revelations would be important
is if there was a significant showing that the president's ability
to lead the country was severely compromised by the relationship.
There's been no such showing.
</P>
<P>
   What has hampered the president is Special Prosecutor Kenneth
Starr's politically-motivated investigation and chipping away at
the office of the president. Through his actions, Starr may have
seriously diminished future presidential prerogatives.
</P>
<P>
   Starr took years and what some estimate will be a $50 million
tab to uncover this illicit relationship between two consensual
adults. Was it worth it? Only to those Republicans who have been
harboring retribution in their dark hearts _ anxious to pay back
Democrats for bringing President Nixon down.
</P>
<P>
   After the air strikes against terrorists in Afghanistan and
Sudan, ordered by the president, Republican Sens. Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania and Dan Coats of Indiana cast doubt on Clinton's real
motivation. They intimated that the attacks were to deflect the
public's attention from the Lewinsky affair. Paybacks for Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   If we were to split Starr's $50 million into 50 portions --- $1
million to investigate each state house in our nation, there would
be many uncomfortable governors looking for places to hide.
</P>
<P>
   How many people could withstand such scrutiny into their private
lives?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sex isn't your Achilles' heel _ perhaps greed is, or
cruelty, or alcohol, or temper, or lack of courage. A hound dog
prosecutor like Starr could make you look like a fool. He's turned
his office into that of an old-time divorce detective _ hiding in
order to snap incriminating photos and gather semen-stained
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone be shocked that the president denied a sexual
liaison with Lewinsky? Most men and women when asked about an
illicit sexual relationship deny it. They deny it to cover their
tracks, to protect the other person in the affair, to protect their
wives or husbands. They deny it in order to provide time to think,
to provide cover. Sometimes they deny it so that the relationship
can continue. It's human nature.
</P>
<P>
   It's reality.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine also that the answer given is going to be broadcast to
the entire nation. Wouldn't most people deny?
</P>
<P>
   The real question: Why was it anyone's business?
</P>
<P>
   The Starr investigation was outrageously rampant _ from an
Arkansas land deal to sex in the Oval Office _ but politically
impossible for a Democratic president with a GOP-controlled
Congress to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Starr conducted a fishing expedition that eventually found
evidence of the president's weakness. He has such latitude, money
and resources, and political motive that anyone he targets can be
brought down.
</P>
<P>
   Special prosecutors can be useful to the publ they bring
to light fraud and illegal activities of those in high office. But
Starr has crossed into a tawdry, tabloid-style investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to the people to put an end to this travesty. The
special prosecutor law must be revised and strict restrictions put
on the office. The sooner, the better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
