<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORING-TV26-COX     08-25 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORING-TV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most of the new network shows boring, witless
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there was an award for funniest network TV slogans, ABC would
win in a landslide. I love such lines as ``TV, so good they named a
frozen meal after it.'' Or ``Before TV, two World Wars. After TV,
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's one line you won't see on ABC _ but should.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV is bad. Get cable. Now!''
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing to laugh about. With the debut of Fox's That '70s
Show and Holding The Baby, the network TV season officially kicked
off. Over the next two months, you'll be bombarded with 34 new
shows.
</P>
<P>
   And the buzz on most of those shows can be summed up quite
succinctly: bad.
</P>
<P>
   What we're about to witness, I'm afraid, is one of the worst TV
seasons in recent memory. That's not a great revelation. TV's been
bad before (remember NBC's Supertrain?) Of the 36 shows that
debuted last fall, only three (Ally McBeal, Dharma &AMP; Greg and
Working) will return this year.
</P>
<P>
   There were several shows that deserved to come back, though, but
didn't. Nothing Sacred was nothing short of brilliant. After
stumbling badly, Brooklyn South and Michael Hayes finally found
their way. The Gregory Hines Show was the season's smartest comedy,
and 413 Hope St. was raw and intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming season looks so woefully mediocre, raw and
intelligent are two adjectives I'll be hard-pressed to use. Madison
Avenue is grumbling. Fellow TV critics are shaking their heads and
even some network producers are privately wondering what's going
on. You know a season's in trouble when Lifetime has three of the
season's best shows.
</P>
<P>
   Although the problem is a complex one, it essentially boils down
to lousy writing. With seven networks (including the upcoming Pax
TV), a host of cable networks and syndicators, the writing talent
pool is maxed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks are not getting the best writers, and it's
showing up on the screen every night from 8-to-11 p.m.,'' says John
Rash, a senior vice president of broadcast relations at
Campbell-Mithun-Esty, a Minneapolis, Minn., marketing
communications company. ``The networks have been doing business the
same way for decades, yet the need for product is much higher than
it's ever been. All the studios are competing for the same writers,
the same stars and the same concepts. That caught up to all of the
networks this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny-pinching networks are also caught up in too much deal
making. Instead of putting the best shows on the air, networks are
often contractually beholden to studios and stars. And all the
networks are looking to cut costs by owning their own shows.
Unfortunately, those programs, many of which don't deserve shots on
local access channels, get on the air first.
</P>
<P>
   Says Tom Werner, producer of such hits as The Cosby Show,
Roseanne and 3rd Rock from the Sun: ``The agendas that the networks
have right now are very mixed. It's not just about the best program
in the best time period.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy Brown creator Diane English is more blunt: ``If you don't
like what you see on TV, sometimes you're seeing a deal on the
screen rather than someone's passion or vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-shy networks are also afraid of taking risks. For every Ally
McBeal, there's a Union Square. I mean, how many more shows
featuring working women at a magazine or three twentysomething
people living in a huge apartment can we take?
</P>
<P>
   The networks know the stakes are high and that viewers are
tuning out. Audience erosion is at an all-time high. Last year, an
astounding 1.4 million households stopped watching network TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe the network television business is a very
good business, but changes must be made to ensure the networks
provide more diverse assortment of programming,'' says Leslie
Moonves, CBS' president and CEO. ``The relentless pursuit of
demographics is turning the network business into narrow-casting.''
</P>
<P>
   And boring-casting.
</P>
<P>
   What do we have to look forward to this fall? Two shows about a
black family moving into an all-white neighborhood. Bo Derek as a
shapely cattle rancher in Hawaii. A smart-mouthed, Boston bartender
who would make Howard Stern blush. A weak Larry Sanders rip-off
that takes place at an ESPN-like sports show. And the most
ridiculous of all? A butler who becomes President Lincoln's
confidant. It's a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not making this stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   NBC didn't say it, but its schedule is so weak, entertainment
president Warren Littlefield tried to hide its poor shows with a
bunch of fancy, chest-thumping charts and graphics during a recent
preview for the press. Sorry, Warren, but we don't care if NBC came
in first or second place every night of the week last year. It
doesn't matter that the network is reaching those money-spending,
18- to 49-year-old viewers Madison Avenue craves.
</P>
<P>
   What's really important is why your comedies look like UPN
rejects. And why is your schedule so lily white?
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said about the other networks. While TV has
never made developing strong minority-themed shows a priority, it
looks as if the networks have abandoned the idea completely. During
one of CBS' presentations at the press tour, one of the network
publicists pulled me aside and told me how embarrassed she was at
the lack of diversity on CBS' shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at them, they're all white-bread and look like Ken and
Barbie,'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   I nodded and agreed. But that's nothing new, and it's getting
worse. Networks never have satisfactory answers, but at least they
make some feeble response about addressing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams, Home Improvement's creator, came right out and
said it. When asked why the big three networks (ABC, NBC, CBS) have
trimmed minorities from their shows, he shrugged, ``The WB has
taken that audience ... there is an outlet for that programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that wasn't the intent, but it was an arrogant and glib
response. The translation: Black audiences have The Wayans Bros.,
so what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   But before you start making Blockbuster plans every night, don't
think there's nothing worth watching this season. A few shows hold
promise. ABC's romantically sweet Cupid and the sinister Fantasy
Island look interesting. That '70s Show is the season's funniest
new sitcom. The WB's witch drama/comedy Charmed looks charming,
UPN's time travel drama Seven Days is a nice thrill ride and CBS'
retro-detective drama Buddy Faro is worth a look. (Our annual TV
preview of fall shows will run next month when most shows
premiere.)
</P>
<P>
   And there's always the hope that a few sleeper hits will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of TV's problems, not everyone believes it's getting
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those people that thinks network television is as
good as it's ever been,'' says Diane English, executive producer of
Fox's new comedy Living In Captivity. ``I think the bar keeps
getting raised ... I don't think that we're in a huge slump of
quality. I think that there's so much competition for our time,
Americans have a lot less time to spend watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   You're wrong, Diane.
</P>
<P>
   Why do you think more people are watching less network TV? Bad
shows. Create good shows, and viewers will come.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens on a more consistent basis, maybe we can
seriously answer this ABC slogan: ``If TV's so bad for you, why is
there one in every hospital room?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
