<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAT-70S-SHOW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kooky humor plentiful as `That '70s Show' looks at Me Decade
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polyester leisure suits. Garish platform shoes and _ yikes! _
The Captain and Tenille.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Me Decade is back in psychedelic living color on That
'70s Show, Fox's kooky blast-from-the-past sitcom. Remember The
Brady Bunch? Well, imagine if Marcia &AMP; Co. weren't such do-right
squares. Think Greg trying to cop some brew from his parents'
swinging disco party. (Yeah, we know it's tough imagining Mike and
Carol doing the bump to Play That Funky Music White Boy, but work
with us.) Think Peter, Marcia and Greg having a pot party in the
basement. Think Jan steaming up the back seat of a Vista Cruiser
with a studly teen.
</P>
<P>
   Now you have a better idea of what That '70s Show is all about.
The year is 1976. The place: suburban Wisconsin. Eric Foreman
(Topher Grace) and his buddies are typical '70s teens. They like to
party, tease their uptight parents and make out with the opposite
sex. Hey, come to think of it, that describes many of today's
teens.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, since this is the '70s, we see a lot of smile buttons,
goofy haircuts and toothy Farrah Fawcett posters that actually
talk.
</P>
<P>
   To get away from his parents, Eric hangs out in the basement
with his cool crew, including the sexy, next-door-neighbor Donna
(Laura Prepon); Kelso (Ashton Ketcher), the hunky, but dense as
Vinny Barbarino guy; his spoiled girlfriend Jackie (Mila Kunis);
conspiracy buff Hyde (Danny Masterson); and Fez (Wilmer
Valderrama), a foreign-exchange student who sounds a lot like
Taxi's Latka.
</P>
<P>
   That '70s Show is a goofy, laugh-out-loud hoot. As the deadpan
Eric, Grace is particularly funny. The guy's blank stares say more
than three pages of dialogue. You can tell the 3rd Rock From the
Sun creators (Bonnie and Terry Turner) are behind this often manic,
live-action cartoon. When the laughs aren't coming (and there are a
few of those moments), the Turners jazz up the show with clever
scenes and odd camera angles.
</P>
<P>
   The funniest is when a wide-eyed, stoned-on-reefer Eric tries to
look cool while talking to his folks. The problem? The walls keep
spinning in front of him. In an inspired fantasy scene, the kids
mimic what they think their parents are talking about at a party.
``Hey everybody, let's hustle!''
</P>
<P>
   You should hustle to check out this sweet and often hilarious
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
