<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AARON-ECKHART26-COX     08-25 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AARON-ECKHART26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actor performs almost too well in cruel roles
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past year, actor Aaron Eckhart has been receiving hate
mail.
</P>
<P>
   His film debut as a sadistic male chauvinist who cruelly toys
with a hearing-impaired secretary in the controversial film In the
Company of Men proved too persuasive for some moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhart understands the reaction. ``Nobody knows who I am, so
they have no other choice but to believe that that is me. They say,
`I hate you,' and I say, `Thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Eckhart and director Neil LaBute have teamed up on another
downbeat movie about male-female relations, Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors, co-starring Ben Stiller, Jason Patric and Nastassja
Kinski, which opened Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely to endear Eckhart any more to audiences, for he
plays Barry, an unsympathetic, unfeeling schmo, adrift in one of
the movie's loveless relationships. The story concerns six
intertwined, 30-ish, lost souls whose lives are disrupted by an act
of infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as a 90-minute concentration on the lows of
relationships,'' says the single,
</P>
<P>
   unattached Eckhart, 30. ``I think men and women can be honest,
but I think somewhere in that relationship, you're going to hit the
lows that are seen in this film.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute sees his new feature, which covers everything from
adultery to rape, as more skeptical than cynical. ``I think there's
less abject cruelty in this movie, but I think there's casual
brutality that is actually worse, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not moviegoers warm to his characters, Eckhart knows
they are good showcases for his fledgling career. ``The challenge
with this character was to capture the reality of a man who is
flying out of control, a man who is knee-deep in quicksand and
going down,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long ago that Eckhart was toiling in LaBute's
hometown of Fort Wayne, Ind., making In the Company of Men under
penny-pinching conditions with no illusions about the movie's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think that movie would be seen,'' he says.
``Imagine that we're shooting a movie with no professionals, no
expectations, (for) $25,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing arrangements were unusual, to put it mildly. ``Neil
made a deal with his next-door-neighbor, who had gone away for the
summer,'' says Eckhart. ``He would mow their lawn if we could stay
in the house. And it was just sweltering hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then In the Company of Men caused shock waves at last year's
Sundance Film Festival, winning the Filmmakers Trophy and gaining
LaBute a development deal with Gramercy Pictures. So he dusted off
Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors, based on his play that Eckhart appeared
in during their college days at Brigham Young University. The
budget ballooned to $4 million, chump change by major studio
standards, but relatively cushy to Eckhart. ``We weren't having
bologna sandwiches,'' he says with a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Now LaBute and Eckhart are known quantities, at least on the
independent film circuit. And they have to worry about living up to
their first release. ``Oh, we were so conscious of the sophomore
slump,'' says Eckhart. ``The idea that we were just lucky the first
time. People would ask me, `Is your best work behind you?' I'd go,
`Uh, well, I hope not.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the publicity trail, sipping iced tea and chatting in a Fort
Lauderdale hotel restaurant, the slim, clean-shaven, blond-haired
Eckhart looks nothing like his character in Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors. To convey the lumbering, gone-to-seed Barry, Eckhart
grew a thin moustache, had his hair dyed a mousy brown and gained
30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do anything for a film that I thought was necessary,''
he says. ``I'd do anything physically possible that I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but gaining 30 pounds, that sounds like too much suffering
for your art. ``It hurt like hell, just eating more than you ever
thought you could eat,'' he recalls with a wince. ``And it didn't
take for the first week, and I was getting pretty disappointed.
Then all of a sudden, bam! When you shove enough butter into your
face, it'll catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Then how did he lose the weight? ``I ran. I ran from the women
who saw In the Company of Men,'' Eckhart quips. ``Instead of a
pizza, I'd eat a salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got another job, and that put the pressure on. You
don't know how much weight you lose, when you know in two months
you have to take off your shirt in front of the camera,'' he notes.
``All of a sudden, you get real motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   That movie, already completed for a possible Christmas release,
is Rescue Me, co-starring Elisabeth Shue as his autistic sister,
who boosts her intelligence through an operation, then regresses
back to her original state. ``Our parents have died, and she comes
to live with me, so it's kind of like a Rain Man in that way,'' he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhart says he liked the script and particularly liked not
playing another male chauvinist clod. ``Now directors are seeing
this film, through screenings, going, `Wow, let's think about him
differently.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Eckhart wants to keep working with LaBute and remain a
member of the director's informal repertory company.
``Absolutely,'' he says. ``Orson Welles and Joseph Cotten,''
referring to the director-actor duo from the Mercury Theater and
Citizen Kane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope so,'' says LaBute. ``He's very easy to work with
and he's a great interpreter of what I've been able to do so far,
so why wouldn't I go there again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we plan to do something else,'' agrees Eckhart. ``Neil
and I kind of look at this as a trilogy, so we have to complete the
trilogy.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's another shoe to drop? ``No,'' corrects Eckhart,
``another body to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
