r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN26-COX     08-25 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Streaking in baggy pants
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. There is little that warms the hearts of
teenagers more than the knowledge that they have totally grossed
out a grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   Hence: purple hair, pierced tongues, and a skull and crossbones
tattooed on an otherwise noble brow.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly stated: Kids like to make us sweat.
</P>
<P>
   This undeclared war between the generations has been going on
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Picture the following dinner table conversation: Father: ``So,
Attila, where are you off to tonight?'' Long-haired and noticeably
grungy kid mumbles with his mouth full: ``I thought I'd pick up a
few Huns and take over Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother: ``You're not leaving the tent looking like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Attila (whining): ``Like what? This is what all of the other
barbarians are wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a story as old as time, bearing out the syllogism: IF the
grown-ups don't like it, THEN the kids are gonna' do it. And often.
</P>
<P>
   In Opelousas, La., respectable folks have taken issue with young
males roaming the streets in britches so baggy anyone would swear
there used to be another kid living in there with them. Concerned
citizens insisted there ought to be a law against kids having more
underwear above the belt than below it.
</P>
<P>
   Well of course there is such a law and the Opelousas police are
invoking it. Youthful offenders caught with their Jockeys hanging
out can be sent up for six months on an ``indecent exposure'' rap.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of prophetic, I'm thinking, considering the whole
droopy-drawers fad began in New York's inner city where a bunch of
kids with little else on their minds decided to mimic the beltless
prison look because it's decidedly ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Obvious question: Why would any kid want to shlep around in his
fat Uncle Arthur's jeans with his skivvies hanging out?
</P>
<P>
   Obvious answer: To annoy the big folks. Why else?
</P>
<P>
   The tacky-trouser craze struck our village a while back but
didn't last. Only a handful of youngsters felt the need to make a
statement by lowering their pants to half-mast. Most felt it was a
real stupid look.
</P>
<P>
   Adults around here aren't much into jailhouse dress so they just
figured the kids with the half-bared backsides came from poor
families where their mommas were still buying clothes two sizes too
big so's they'd have room to grow into them. See what I'm saying?
Grownups are seriously deficient in ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is it with kids? Do they really feel their day has been
wasted if they haven't grossed out their parents, outraged an
adult, and defied at least one authority figure?
</P>
<P>
   Yup.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   I dunno.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one sure-fire cure for their antics. Indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Remember streaking? Where everything from major league ball
games to Junior League teaparties were fodder for folks suffering
from Godiva's syndrome _ only without the horse? My son was nine or
ten when that fad hit and although he didn't appear to be paying
any attention to reports of the latest outbreaks of naked
nip-and-tuck, I soon learned better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' I heard whispers coming from the backyard tent, ``but
what if your mom catches us?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dark,'' another voice answered, ``and if we're quiet she
won't know.''
</P>
<P>
   I stopped mid-stride, stabilized the tray of milk and brownies I
was carrying, and tiptoed closer. ``So when do we take our clothes
off?''
</P>
<P>
   That I recognized as my son's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not til we're in the woods and it's safe,'' the first voice
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not really streaking if there's nobody to see us,'' my
son reminded his buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' agreed the other voice, ``but if somebody sees us
we're going to be in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided it was time to make my shadowy presence known. ``Snack
time,'' I called out as a warning as I tromped through the pine
needles outside the tent. ``What are y'all up to?'' I asked,
pretending ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   Silence. I put the tray down on the old milk crate they were
using as a coffee table and prepared to leave. My son couldn't
resist sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking about going streaking,'' he said. I knew this
was a test so I casually asked where. ``Dunno.'' I asked if they
wanted me to drive them. ``No-ooo!'' was the unanimous and
immediate reply. I turned and left, wishing them a good night and
sweet dreams. Of course, I dozed in front of the den window all
night to be sure no little jaybirds took off running down Brookside
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   The following night as I tucked my son into his bottom bunk, I
asked how the streaking had gone. He said it hadn't and I asked
why. ``Mom,'' he said quite seriously leaning up on one elbow to
look me in the eye, ``you took all of the fun out of it. Kids don't
want their moms to drive them when they're going streaking.''
</P>
<P>
   I apologized.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm thinking, maybe if grownups can stand it long enough,
green hair and platform tennies will fade into well-deserved
oblivion. And as for bared backsides? I can't help wondering what
would happen if schools tacked a nudity clause in the dress code
section of the student handbook: Absolutely no clothes will be
allowed on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, I suspect, we'd be witnessing a return to the
Victorian era. And the best part? The kids would think it was all
their idea.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
She may be e-mailed at: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
