A0740 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN26-COX     08-25 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take heart - kind souls quietly doing good deeds
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are one of those people who go around committing random
acts of kindness and senseless acts of beauty out of sheer
anonymous decency, the jig might be up.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody might rat you out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I keep a file on doers of good deeds, and I encourage
readers to tell on their friends. Cases in point:
</P>
<P>
   Donald Keller, of Lake Park, a.k.a. ``Dr. Duke,'' has
``adopted'' Lake Park Elementary to benefit from his magic show on
safety, and once a year brings in his mechanical toy circus animals
for a ``hands on'' exhibition. ``Dr. Duke'' is also suspected of
playing anonymous Santa every year with cash gifts for needy
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   When the West Palm Beach law firm of Bakst, Cloyd and Bakst took
on a pro bono case for the Legal Aid Society of Palm Beach County,
lawyer Tina Talarchyk learned the plight of ``Dorothy,'' an
asthmatic 70-year-old grandmother who was caring for her
grandchildren in an un-air-conditioned mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor woman, who is overweight and also has emphysema, was
suffering terribly from the heat in that trailer, and could hardly
breathe,'' Talarchyk said. ``I tried to get her some government
help, but the red tape was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   So she called the Home Depot in West Palm Beach on State Road7
and asked manager Devin Wagaman if she could get a deal on a
scratched or dented air conditioner. ``Mr. Wagaman called a day or
two later and said he had an air conditioner that the store wished
to donate. He was fabulous. When I came to the store, he just said,
`Here you go,' and I signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Palm Beach Post paper carriers' random acts of kindness at
the scene of separate fires have been upgraded by me to a random
act of alertness in one case and random act of genius in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition for alertness in the face of surliness goes to
Ronald Hodgkins of Boynton Beach, who saw flames erupting from the
Four Sea Suns condominiums at 1800 N.E. Third Court. He ran to the
apartments, banging on doors, trying to rouse the residents, who
evidently could not hear the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   So he banged harder until finally, a cranky resident came to the
door and demanded:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you knocking at 5a.m.? Don't you know everyone is
sleeping?''
</P>
<P>
   After rousing the residents _ all of whom escaped without injury
_ Hodgkins called 911 and then finished his route.
</P>
<P>
   While Post carrier John O'Hearn, 32, of Lake Worth, and Ray
Alvarez, 42, of West Palm Beach, have already been recognized for
rescuing an infant and two other children from a burning house in
West Palm Beach on Aug. 15, the way they teamed up deserves
mention.
</P>
<P>
   After Alvarez used a shutter to break a window, O'Hearn, passed
3-month-old Michael Dellapietro and 6-year-old Austin Buzon through
the window. Then, by leaning into the choking smoke with a garden
hose, O'Hearn shouted for Katie Lyn Thompson, 3, to follow the
stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a wet arm and pulled her to safety,'' O'Hearn said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know about a Random Act of Kindness? Write Ron Wiggins at
Box 24700, West Palm Beach, FL 33416-4700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
