<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0741 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLADE-REVIEW26-COX     08-25 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLADE-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anemic cliches deserve a stake through the heart
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ `Blade' Starring: Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff, Kris
Kristofferson, Traci Lords Director: Stephen Norrington
Screenwriter: David S. Goyer MPAA rating: R for gore, violence,
language
</P>
<P>
   `Blade'' touts itself as a different kind of vampire movie, and
in a few small ways it is.
</P>
<P>
   Its lead vampire is a martial arts-flinging superhero (Wesley
Snipes). The sinister, neck-noshing vampires dress like lounge
hipsters and hang out at a techno club (they're nocturnal; they
like to party). There's a garlic serum that staves off the bummer
effects of a vampire bite. And, while silver bullets and sunlight
can ruin a vampire's night, here ``Crosses don't do squat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cool.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Blade'' is similar to many vampire movies in that it's not
very good. Fraught with cliches and based on the Marvel Comics
character _ one of the first African American comic book heroes _
``Blade'' cross-weaves the dark, steely-sleek worlds of ``Batman''
and ``The Crow'' with bursts of Hong Kong action high jinks and all
the inane trappings of the blood-drinking genre. It looks neat, but
it sucks.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder screenwriter David Goyer also penned ``The Crow:
City of Angels'' (as well as ``Dark City''). In look, feel and
plot, ``Blade'' is uncomfortably close to ``The Crow,'' not to
mention ``Batman.'' All three follow brooding comic book heroes who
wear highly accessorized black costumes as they seek to avenge the
brutal murders of their loved ones. They're Hamlet, with 'tude.
</P>
<P>
   But Blade is a stiff, particularly humorless, type-A tree trunk
shrouded not so much in creepy mystique as chronic personality
deficiency. The tattooed vampire hunter speaks in curt, breathy
grunts _ Clint Eastwood with asthma _ and races around in his black
hot-rod armed with automatic weapons and the samurai sword that's
his namesake. Then he kicks vampire booty.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes _ one of those ``What happened to?'' actors whose career
instills deep concern _ cuts a dark if not terribly menacing or
sympathetic figure as the laconic Blade. He's so starched that
every time he breaks into martial arts, it's a revelation. Even his
deadpan one-liners (``It's open season on all suckheads'') move
like falling timber.
</P>
<P>
   In Goyer's maddeningly formulaic story, Blade is out to get
revenge for the death of his mother, who was bitten by a vampire
while pregnant with baby Blade and died giving birth. That makes
Blade a dreaded ``half-breed'' _ a man equipped with a vampire's
immortality, super-strength and regenerative powers (his wounds
heal like that), but none of its weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   With assistance from his pal Whistler (a biker bar-ready Kris
Kristofferson who looks like he should be called Thor), Blade takes
intravenous blasts of garlic concentrate to immunize him from the
ill traits of vampirism.
</P>
<P>
   Blade proves a formidable weapon against an underground army of
vampires who plan to take over the world. The vampires run their
affairs like a Mafia family _ all dark suits, boardroom rituals and
a seesawing hierarchy, which is threatened by punky renegade Deacon
Frost (a perfunctorily vile Stephen Dorff).
</P>
<P>
   Frost heads a band of mutinous, but terribly hip, vampires who
want it all. He also runs one of those all-night dance clubs
haunted by sun-shy vampires and crank fiends. We know Frost is pure
evil because he listens to electronica.
</P>
<P>
   Duck for flying body parts, ripping flesh and tsunamis of blood
when Blade confronts Frost and his stereotypical minions (aloof and
pretty moll; cackling, maniacal henchman). Good battles evil and
all that stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Norrington saturates ``Blade'' in MTV-style
gloss, but his feeble vision is eclipsed by the equally derivative
art direction and cartoonish computer effects. Norrington's notion
of directorial flare is to show a close-up of someone lighting a
cigarette and to amplify the crackling sound of burning tobacco.
It's an old trick done by a thousand young action directors. So is
this dull ``Blade.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
