<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0742 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATSUIT26-COX     08-25 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATSUIT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm slick, shiny and not sweating. I'm a vinyl Avenger
 &HT;    By Carolyn Kelly
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Ordinarily, you won't see me in shrink-wrapped clothes.
And in general, I'm not one to cavort around town looking like a
dominatrix, even if I haven't done laundry in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here I am, weighing iceberg lettuce in Central Market on a
Saturday afternoon, dressed in a skin-hugging black vinyl cat suit.
Heads are swiveling, eyebrows are arching, voices are lowering.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this matters; I'm on important business. I'm trying
to determine if a woman can go about her day in Central Texas in a
slinky one-piece getup like the one Uma Thurman sports as Emma Peel
in ``The Avengers,'' the recently released cinematic dud.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the movie's shortcomings, Mrs. Peel's appeal from the
'60s TV show carries on. In her heyday, the sultry British
character was all the rage. As played by Diana Rigg, Mrs. Peel was
sexy and sardonic _ all style and smarts _ with a mod, mod wardrobe
. She was the cat's meow.
</P>
<P>
   While wearing her trademark cat suit, Mrs. P. could karate chop
evil chaps without ripping a seam, then languorously toast her
triumph with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   But what about her off hours, after dastardly deeds are avenged,
after Emma and John Steed trade flirtatious barbs and she hops into
her sporty Lotus Elan?
</P>
<P>
   What about doing this in Austin? Call me half-baked, but I was
going to zip myself inside this impossibly impractical,
ultra-form-fitting, head-to-toe apparel, in steamy August. And then
go shopping, run errands, catch a movie.
</P>
<P>
   My first mission was to find a cat suit.
</P>
<P>
   The J. Peterman catalog offers a genuine ``Avengers'' cat suit
of ``faux leatherette'' for a mere $2,000. Way over budget. I
called lingerie stores and costume shops, rejecting outfits that
included cat tails or perky ears. Though I'm sure Mrs. Peel never
browsed the clothing racks at erotica shops, I did. For $260,
Forbidden Fruit stocks a suit of latex, for that sensual
rubber-glove feel, with a zipper located where the moon don't glow.
My mother would have a conniption.
</P>
<P>
   I stumbled across success at the Bazaar Back Stage, where a
spit-shiny little vinyl number (a comfy 60 percent PVC, 40 percent
nylon; machine wash) for only $41.50 caught my eye. Though the
waistline was a bit baggy, a seamstress zealously took in every
spare inch until my outlandish outfit was sufficiently
asphyxiating. At least I'll never have to iron it.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I retrieved a pair of knee-high boots from my closet,
borrowed an incredibly wide belt and finished off the look with
Isotoner gloves. Voila. Pure Mrs. Peel.
</P>
<P>
   (OK, so maybe I don't have Uma Thurman's Architectural Digest
bone structure, lustrous almond eyes, air-pumped lips or conical
breasts. The voluptuous actress playing Emma Peel and I do share
some similarities: we both have a couple of X chromosomes and we
both have cat suits.)
</P>
<P>
   After contemplating the underwear question (should I wear any?),
I venture out with little more than a thin layer of baby powder
under my full-body rain slicker.
</P>
<P>
   At Central Market, I discover perhaps the only blessing of
wearing fabric that gasps for breath. For the first time ever, I'm
not shivering in the frosty produce department.
</P>
<P>
   Here, amid the bright green vegetables, strangers look my way
and then quickly glance down. Several heads whiplash around as I
wander the aisles, squishing and squeaking in my rubbery suit. I
start to feel like the star of some oddball performance art piece.
Only nobody is getting it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the bakery department, among the rustic bread
loaves, somebody hits a bull's-eye when a 20something guy says,
``Emma!'' barely within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   As I stroll by, one potbellied man shouldering a canvas Central
Market bag slowly rotates in my direction, like a surveillance
camera. Another older man, only a few feet away, eyes me, forehead
to toes and back up again. Their internal compasses follow my
costume like true north.
</P>
<P>
   Several folks kindly inquire whether I am overheating. And as I
hand my money to a bright-faced young girl working behind the cafe
counter, she says, with much sincerity, ``Everybody loves your
outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, from place to place.
</P>
<P>
   The guy selling dog chews at Bark n Purr pet shop keeps a poker
face, and the convenience store clerk chuckles discreetly. But
mostly, I feel eyes fixing on my outrageous garb, then dodging
away. Women slowly raise their menus for whispered fashion
critiques. Others beckon friends to hurry, come take a look. One
tipsy fellow sticks his index finger in my face and ventures a
guess: ``Cat Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm just thankful my cat suit doesn't garner any catcalls.
</P>
<P>
   As evening sets in, I head to the theater to see _ what else? _
``The Avengers.'' I'm accompanied by two friends, who graciously
tote my purse; after all, cat suits don't have pockets.
</P>
<P>
   After passing through the lobby with little fanfare, it feels
good to sit in a dark theater. I hadn't eaten much all day _ afraid
of bursting out of my clothing _ so I hunker down and hide behind a
giant popcorn tub. Soon I am wincing from the lousy dialogue and,
unbelievably, shaking from the icebox temperatures. I have the urge
to give the theater's thermostat a good ol' Mrs. Peel karate kick.
And to think I had worried about a cat suit meltdown. Only once
during my heavily air-conditioned day did I ever break a sweat _
while ever-so-glamorously pumping gas.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie mercifully ends and the crowd funnels toward the
exit, I feel the first flush of cat suit embarrassment. Why
couldn't I be dressed in a ``Titanic'' costume?
</P>
<P>
   But nobody cares, as I walk to my car in my rubbery, glossy,
downright silly cat suit. After all, this is Austin, and they've
seen a lot weirder.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Mrs. Peel would say, it's time for a champagne toast. Now
somebody help get me out of this thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
