<SLUG> BC-CHELSEA-CLINTON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chelsea vulnerable as only child
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ People can only guess the impact of her father's
admission. A front-page picture of Chelsea Clinton recently showed
her holding hands with her parents, the young woman bridging the
gap between the president and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   And we wonder: What is this doing to Chelsea? What does a
dysfunctional marriage do to the psyche of an older child? What
happens when a parent makes a revelation that rips the heart of a
family?
</P>
<P>
   It likely forces an older child to re-evaluate the parent, says
Carl Pickhardt, an Austin psychologist and author of several
parenting books, including ``Keys to Parenting the Only Child.''
``You have to reconcile what the world is saying and what you have
been led to believe. It's an enormous sense of betrayal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Drake, a licensed marriage and family counselor in Austin,
agrees. ``A child will rethink their parents. This is the person
who taught me to tell the truth who is now lying. It's heavy,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   It gets more complicated with only children. ``To some degree in
a one-child family, there is a highly emotional and sensitized
relationship. They are sensitive and considerate of each other. It
is a three-person marriage, and they treat each other as equal
partners,'' Pickhardt says.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of infidelity on a marriage is harsher on older
children, especially in the 18 to 23 age group, which is considered
the last stage of adolescence. Of course, older children understand
a parent's actions more _ from a standpoint of the meaning of an
infraction _ but it goes beyond that, says Drake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little kids don't have the maturity for adult issues. However,
a 19- or 20-year-old comes to view her parents more as people.
However, it's still traumatic to enter the adult business of their
parents. A daughter still wants to say, 'Dad, I want you to be the
Dad you've told me about all these years,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The issues confronting an older child are deeper than they can
be explained: mistrust, betrayal, embarrassment and anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be like your world blowing up,'' says Jamie Ross of
Austin, a junior at Wake Forest University.
</P>
<P>
   She has what she describes as the ultimate close relationship
with her parents, Richard and Sharon Ross. To talk about them
cheating is absolutely foreign. ``We're best friends. We talk about
everything. I have so much respect for them. They are so in love.
They're brought us up the best way possible. I've been incredibly
blessed,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   However, if her father were to ever do the unthinkable and
reveal an adulterous affair, ``I'd wonder about everything that
came out of his mouth. Is it the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   There would be humiliation. ``I'd be horribly embarrassed.
Chelsea's at Stanford, a long way from home. She depends on her
friends when she has to talk to someone at 3 o'clock in the
morning. You know her friends have been watching all this, and
they've formed opinions. Who can she trust? Who can she talk to? It
makes me wonder,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   However, because the 21-year-old sees her parents as adults and
human beings, it would help her cope. ``I think I would forgive my
father because that's what he's always taught me. I'd see him as a
human being who made a mistake. You just don't abandon the people
you love,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Pickhardt agrees. ``Something like this may alter a child's
perception but it doesn't alter the love she has for a parent. It
may give a child a greater compassion of the frailties of a
parent,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   However, it could also destroy the child's belief that marriage
can be wonderful. ``They lose hope that marriage can be monogamous.
It puts question marks that it may happen to them in their
marriage,'' says Drake.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
