A0745 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOUGLAS-SHOW26-COX     08-25 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUGLAS-SHOW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mike's memories
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The list of guests featured on The Mike Douglas Show reads like
a ``who's who'' of Hollywood in the '60s and '70s:
</P>
<P>
   John Lennon and Yoko Ono (who co-hosted the show for a week in
1972) _ ``We thought he was kidding when we asked him who he wanted
on the show and he said the Chicago Seven. So we booked them.
(Black Panther Bobby Seale and Jerry Rubin were on the same show as
President Nixon's surgeon general. Things got ugly quick.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thrill of his life, though, was when we had his
idol, Chuck Berry, on the Wednesday show that week he hosted. He
was so happy that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods _ ``I was sitting at home watching a local show in
California and they had this little kid, cute as a button, 2 1/2
years old. The thing that was unusual was that here you had this 2
1/2-year-old swinging the club like an adult. So we had him on the
show. It was scary how good he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixteen years later, that kid came to me and sought me out at
the L.A. Open. I was hosting the Open that year ... and he came up
to the first tee. He was about 6-foot-1, and he said, `Mr. Douglas,
I'm Tiger Woods,' and I said, `Boy, how you've changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Johnny, Merv and Dinah, Mike Douglas held his own
during the heyday of TV talk shows. Here's his take on a few
well-known shows:
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Carson: ``He was the best. Anyone who watched him knew
that. He could get more laughs out of one look ... He could always
dig himself out if he was bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch the other two shows (Jay Leno and David Letterman),
and you make up your own mind. My golly, they're not even in the
same ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell: ``She's great. I love Rosie. She does what I
think is the most important thing: she listens. How can you have a
conversation if you don't listen to what the guest is saying?
Whenever anyone asks for advice, that's what I tell them. Just
listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Springer: ``I think he's truly dangerous, what he's doing.
A kid comes home after school and sees that, how could someone not
be affected by that?''
</P>
<P>
   More of Mike's memories
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Davis Jr.: ``The first time I had Sammy on ... I told my
executive producer and director that they had to get rid of all the
guests. We had five or six guests booked, but I told them, `He'll
do the whole 90 minutes. He will sing. He will dance. He will do
impersonations. He will play the drums. He will do the whole
thing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me how I knew this and I said, `Have you ever seen
him perform live? The man could do two hours standing on his head.'
He did an unbelievable show. Ninety minutes later, the audience was
limp.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Mitchell: ``She said to me when we finished taping that
week, `If this show was live, I'd give you a show that would blow
everybody out of the water.' She was going to tell me all about
Nixon and would have done it on the air. Two days after we finished
the show, he resigned.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry Gordy: ``I had Berry Gordy say to me one time, `You're the
guy who made the label (Motown) for us.' We used his people when no
one else would. I had Stevie Wonder on the show when he was 12. You
could see what a talent this kid was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey: ``He does better impressions than anyone ever!
Better than Rich Little, better than anyone. He must have the best
ear in the world. When he does Sammy Davis, he has the quality of
the voice, the posture, everything. He's incredible, this guy. He'd
go into a comedy club and paralyze people. And he's thrown all that
material away!''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Cash: ``There was a time when he was having trouble with
pills and alcohol, and he had to cancel once. I'll tell you what a
gentleman he is. A couple years later, I was doing The Carol
Burnett Show, and I was backstage and heard this voice. And his
voice, it can only be one voice. He came in my dressing room and
said, `I owe you a show.' I said, `No you don't, Johnny.' And he
said, `I want to do the show, and I don't want any money for it. I
did a terrible thing and I'm sorry, and I was having problems in
those days. So we booked him, and he brought his whole band, all
the girl singers, his wife June Carter. He did the show and gave
the money to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only three people in 23 years canceled on us. One was Johnny
Cash. Another was Roger Miller. He was an enormous talent, but he
got on the wrong plane, went to the wrong city and missed the show.
He called and said, ``I was having a bad day, and I went to the
gate and got on the wrong plane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevy Chase was the other no-show. Not a phone call from him
explaining why, nothing. I just don't understand people like that.
You know, it's the biggest stars, stars like John Wayne, Bob Hope,
Lucille Ball, they are the best. It's not the people who are
teetering.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
