<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIENDS-N-NEIGHBORS26     08-25 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDS-N-NEIGHBORS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad behavior is the norm for these despicable pals
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ `Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors' Starring: Ben Stiller,
Catherine Keener, Jason Patric, Amy Brenneman, Aaron Eckhart,
Nastassja Kinski Director: Neil LaBute Screenwriter: Neil LaBute
MPAA rating: R for sexually explicit language, adult themes
</P>
<P>
   Neil LaBute's chatty acid-bath ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' is
the writer-director's follow-up to last year's savage and
incendiary ``In the Company of Men.'' It's difficult to figure
which movie is more pungently, unrepentantly vicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men'' was cruel and nasty with pointed specificity: Two
misogynist SOBs target a pretty, deaf woman and sexually play her
like a wounded mouse before biting her head off and chewing between
triumphant cackles _ all figuratively speaking, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends' '' malignancy is more expansive: Six lovelorn
characters knit a cat's cradle of lies, insults, betrayal and
revenge, with the outcome a steaming battlefield of mutilated egos.
War is hell? Try love.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute wields his misanthropy the way David Mamet does. He's
convinced backstabbing and verbal violence are banal human
pastimes, not merely social pathologies, and amplifies this view to
deafening levels for heightened dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   He's fascinated by this behavior and observes it like a maker of
nature films. Camera hidden in the brush, he captures our species
as it conducts its exotic social rituals. He also captures those
wincing scenes of predation; the lion always gets the gazelle.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it all so chilling is that LaBute never blinks. He
remains an amorally distant and nonjudgmental spectator. Like the
callous nature shooters who watch the food chain without heroically
disrupting it, LaBute is aloof, and you just know he's smirking
behind that tree.
</P>
<P>
   Richly written and incisively acted by a cast that includes
Jason Patric, Amy Brenneman, gifted indie princess Catherine Keener
and Ben Stiller, in perhaps his best performance, ``Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors'' is the sort of bleak comedy of manners Woody Allen
would have made if he was of a different era. (Scenes and
characters frequently echo those in ``Manhattan.'') We laugh at how
sick people can be, then curdle at the similarities to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Populated by smart, urban neurotics, the movie, like Allen's, is
obsessed with sex, positively drenched in the concept of coitus.
But there's not a single nude scene. What's nude are the
characters' interiors, stripped of flattering light, dignity and
self-worth. The unsparing candor is squirm-inducing.
</P>
<P>
   The extremity of the cruelty nudges the movie into the absurd,
bordering on an especially cerebral brand of farce. The tip-off
LaBute is operating on levels viewers may not anticipate arrives in
an over-the-top scene in which Patric's psychotic scoundrel
describes in unreal detail his ``best f----.'' (If any more
dialogue were to be transcribed, this page would become a hailstorm
of Morse code dashes.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the movie's meticulous structure, the six characters _
two married couples, Patric's icy misogynist and Nastassja Kinski's
lesbian artist's assistant _ seem to float about in a largely
plotless universe. The ``friends'' have each other over for dinner,
meet at cafes and used book stores, bond at the gym, make
acquaintances at art galleries, and engage in various degrees of
really bad sex. (The ``Manhattan'' echoes grow louder.)
</P>
<P>
   The characters' names and the movie's urban setting are never
spoken; LaBute doesn't want to distract us from the psychological
hell he's constructing with tactile trivia. What LaBute, an alert
and expressive visualist, is concerned with are his characters'
actions and words, and his literate, tightly crafted and shrewdly
nuanced writing bears this out. The story emerges from what these
flawed people do; their fate never seems preordained by a narrative
blueprint. They act horrendously, then feel bad. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   This makes room for the excellent performers to develop
full-bodied characters. A lesser cast would kill this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller, as the stammering Woody character, shows again he is
our best modern parodist. Keener is sharp and typically commanding.
Patric will repulse you with his twisted intensity. And Aaron
Eckhart, so convincingly repugnant in ``In the Company of Men,''
embodies the sad cuckold, complete with added flab, a dreadful
mustache and a matted, Hitlerian haircut.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute is shaping up as an exciting filmmaker with a singular
satirical spin. His work is sophisticated and uncompromising in
ways that make you laugh and think with equal vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'' is a darkly audacious film (the chamber orchestra
playing Metallica songs over the credits hints at things
subversive) that bristles with the prickly stuff of life. And the
fiendish LaBute finds clever ways of weaving in his ugly themes.
When a character drop kicks a plastic fetus, you're suddenly
watching allegory.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
