<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0747 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONG26-COX     08-25 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONG26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writer Jong comments on first lady's 'deal with the Devil'
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Twenty-five years after ``Fear of Flying,'' feminist
poet Erica Jong revisits the war between the sexes in a new book,
``What Do Women Want?'' due out in September from HarperCollins.
Its subtitles: ``Bread. Roses. Sex. Power.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, Jong dedicates a chapter to her observations on first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Here's a sample of what she writes
about the Clinton's political marriage:
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our rock stars bizarre and our First Ladies ordinary.
HRC will never be ordinary if she lives to be 127. ... The Clinton
administration and the Clinton marriage are both historic. As a
couple, the Clintons raise major issues about politics and sexual
politics. They are the first couple to have been elected President
of the U.S. jointly. It is clear that without HRC's participation,
Bill Clinton would have gone right down the Gary Hart sewer.
Because his wife stood by him on that first Barbara Walters
interview in 1992 ... the first Clinton campaign was able to
weather and rise above what had been killing sexual crises for
other presidential candidates. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Hillary Rodham Clinton's forgiveness, Bill Clinton's
appetites would have sunk him. But because of her fierce
protectiveness, the presidency has triumphed over past bimbo
eruptions, even made them seem suspect and irrelevant. Hillary has
almost single-handedly revolutionized the political marriage. ...
The very American ideal of a 'power couple' who add up to more than
the sum of their parts was perfected during the Clinton presidency.
After the unveiling of Monica Lewinsky and Kathleen Wiley, Hillary
Clinton claimed even more power in the marriage. She became Bill
Clinton's indispensable character witness. And even though nobody
believed in his character, Hillary loomed larger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``... Bill Clinton seems to have the best of Hillary: She
validates his feminist credentials with the electorate while he
remains free to go on being a Dogpatch Bob Packwood _ supporting
womankind in public, groping individual women in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal of the Clinton marriage fascinates me. ... Clearly
Hillary Rodham Clinton figured out in law school that if the time
was not yet ripe for a woman President, it was likely to be ripe
for a guy as driven and smart and personable as Bill Clinton. And
she could be his chief adviser, patron ... cheering and booing
sections, and disciplinarian. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume that Bill Clinton's erotic life is no better and no
worse than any other male politician's. ...``I'm glad his political
agenda is feminist. ... Hillary Clinton ... is in the same bind as
many strong, intelligent women. She has made her deal with the
Devil and now she must live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morris is the book editor for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
