<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIKE-DOUGLAS26-COX     08-25 1792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIKE-DOUGLAS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's Mike Douglas
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    ART AVAILABLE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genevieve Douglas walks to a corner of the walnut-paneled den in
her North Palm Beach home and randomly pulls a gold-covered
scrapbook from a shelf. There are dozens more stacked side-by-side,
reaching to the ceiling, making the wall glimmer amid the dark
woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which one is this, I wonder?'' she says softly, almost to
herself. She gently peels the binder open and the first page is
filled by a black and white photo of her husband and his friend.
She calls to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike ... this one is of you and Marlon.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon. Brando. With her husband, Mike. Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' he says. ``Greatest actor there ever was, in my
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of scrapbook collection you accumulate when you
host 6,000 episodes of a TV talk show over 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   The scrapbooks were his wife's idea. Every celebrity who spent a
week co-hosting The Mike Douglas Show got a copy of photos shot on
the set. Didn't matter if you were Sammy Davis Jr., John Lennon or
Wayne Rogers, everybody got one. And, since he was the host,
Douglas got one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the 73-year-old star needs them to remember his five
decades in the entertainment industry. Born on the west side of
Chicago, he became a singer in his teens, eventually playing
nightclubs and fronting Kay Kyser's big band. (It was Kyser who
switched his stage name from Michael Dowd to Douglas.)
</P>
<P>
   As a staff singer in town at NBC affiliate WGN, he got his first
break when host Ernie Simon couldn't make it on the air one day to
broadcast a morning show called Hi Ladies. Douglas went on and had
to wing it. ``It felt so good to me. It was so natural. That was
the beginning of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, Westinghouse was looking for an unknown to
host a show, someone who could sing, dance, do a serious interview
and take a pie in the face on occasion. An executive was watching
TV one day, saw Merv Griffin on a game show and was reminded of
Douglas, who at the time was between jobs in Los Angeles. In 1961,
The Mike Douglas Show debuted.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15 years have passed since his last show.
Westinghouse, which co-owned the show with Douglas, replaced him in
1980 with John Davidson. Douglas carried on in syndication for
three more years, paying the $8million budget on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Today, his life with Genevieve _ 53 years of marriage and
counting _ has downshifted into a relaxing blur of grandchildren,
golf and dinners with friends who live in the exclusive golf club
community of Lost Tree Village.
</P>
<P>
   The couple vacationed for years in Palm Beach County before
leaving Hollywood in 1994. They bought their current home in 1997,
and spend a great deal of time with their daughters, two of whom
live in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the nicest people I have ever met,'' says friend
Betty DiVosta. She and her husband, Buz, the Palm Beach County real
estate developer, live about 10 houses away and have dinner with
the Douglases every few weeks. Douglas often shares tales of his
showbiz life, but doesn't make a point of doing so. ``He's kind,
very warm and a sincere person,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Douglas' golf course house, with marble floors, grand piano
near the entrance and azure pool out back, is impressively
extravagant but homey nonetheless. It's a fraction of the size and
price he paid in the '80s for a $2.3million Beverly Hills mansion,
but it's more than comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we looked at that place Donald Trump owns now,
before he bought it ... beautiful place,'' Douglas offers. ``We
decided not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mar-a-Lago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. Beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at his age and with all this domestic bliss, you get the
sense he could don the jacket, grab the microphone, belt out a tune
and start all over again without missing stride. He could make it
on recollections alone.
</P>
<P>
   Point to any photo on the wall of his den or in a scrapbook, and
invariably an entertaining yarn is attached. As he sits on the end
of an expensive leather couch, he casually but proudly talks about
the five Emmy awards or his star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
Dressed in gray slacks, black loafers and a light pink Oxford
button-down with his initials stitched on the pocket, the memories
spill forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Charles?'' he says, as a smile sneaks into the corner of
his mouth. ``We got Ray Charles to ride a motorcycle. He wanted to
do it. He had a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   Point to the photo of Barbra Streisand. ``The purest voice I've
ever heard. We had her on the show several times when she first
started. She walked around backstage pointing at her throat and not
talking. We started to panic until we realized she was just saving
her voice for the show. She was magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   Point to the photo of Mike and actor Wayne Rogers standing with
... Mother Teresa?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling I was in the presence of somebody very, very
special. I was so in awe of this woman. I had difficulty doing that
interview. Wayne was co-host that week.''
</P>
<P>
   As everything from the '70s gets a rehash in the '90s, Mike
Douglas is being rediscovered. His dormant career is starting to
awaken. His autobiography is due to be published by the end of the
year. He's making public appearances on talk shows and will be
performing with Marvin Hamlisch and the Pittsburgh Symphony
Orchestra in October. VH1 has broadcast old tapes of his shows, and
Rhino Records has issued a box-set of five shows on which John
Lennon and Yoko Ono were hosts in 1972. There are rumblings about a
possible radio show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turn down a lot of stuff,'' Douglas says without a hint of
braggadocio.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the overdue recognition he's receiving from the
latest generation of TV talkers. In an era when Jerry Springer is
TV's tawdry king, Rosie O'Donnell and Howie Mandel are having
success with what has been labeled ``Nice TV.'' The mixture of
entertaining, non-threatening interviews, guest hi-jinks and
musical performances should be renamed ``Mike TV,'' since it was
the formula Douglas worked so well.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell openly claims hers is a carbon copy of The Mike
Douglas Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of show I set out to make, a show where guests
feel safe and respected,'' O'Donnell said during a recent telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch Mike every day after school,'' she said. ``I'd
sit down with a bowl of popcorn at my grandmother's house, and I
just loved it. He was always so hopeful and fun. And he always
seemed like he was friends with the people he was interviewing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the perks of having your own show is that you can invite
your idols to appear. A few months back, O'Donnell asked Douglas to
be a guest. He was apprehensive at first _ it had been almost 15
years out of the spotlight _ but he agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came out, the audience stood and cheered and I was,
like, my goodness,'' Douglas said, still floored by the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   For Mandel, who grew up watching in Toronto, The Mike Douglas
Show holds special significance because it was the first American
talk show he appeared on as a stand-up comic in 1979. Mandel's talk
show debuted two months ago, and he also has scheduled Douglas to
appear. The show was scheduled to be taped last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Hollywood, it was so intimidating, and yet he
had such an easygoing persona,'' Mandel remembered. ``He put me
immediately at ease when I sat down. A good talk show host is like
the host of a party in his own home, and that's the way Mike was.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of today's daytime talk shows, Mandel says Douglas'
show excelled because of the mix of guests. One day's panel might
feature a politician sitting next to a rock star, who was next to a
doctor, who was next to a militant activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly was a variety show,'' Mandel says. ``Every 7 minutes,
it was something fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the reason Douglas' simple formula flourishes amid
Springer's controlled riots or Howard Stern's potty-mouth pranks,
O'Donnell and Mandel agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you give people the option, they're always going to
choose something like Mike,'' she says. ``Something like Springer
has a short shelf life.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Mandel says, ``Good solid entertainment always works.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas explains the mix of guests this way: ``I had a producer
who was insane. He'd send me into cages with wild tigers, telling
me it's harmless and that there won't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything unexpected ever happen? Are you kidding me? Every 10
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Spend enough time with the Douglases and the topic invariably
turns to family.
</P>
<P>
   There are the daughters who all graduated college. There are the
grandchildren, one of whom is an accomplished amateur golfer.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the love of his life, Genevieve. The two still
act like love-struck kids. Which isn't out of character, since he
met her when she was a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew her brother and he would tell me, `You ought to see my
kid sister.' Gen was 16 when I first met her and she was 17 when I
proposed to her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both kids, but it worked,'' she adds. ``I had written
in my diary when I met Mike, `Some day I'm going to marry him.'''
</P>
<P>
   She gets self-conscious at the memory. ``It sounds like we
didn't know what we were doing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I knew what I was doing,'' he says, with a lusty wink at
her. She dips her head and grins shyly.
</P>
<P>
   In 53 years, she's never had a job outside the home. Raising the
kids and building their marriage was enough. ``There's only one
star in the family. Whatever support I can give Mike, that's my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is nothing if not practical about the recent attention.
He doesn't need the money. He claims not to miss the grind _ ``The
only thing I miss is getting a good table at a restaurant'' _ and
he knows that although the adulation is rewarding, he's still been
away from television for a long time. To illustrate this, he has a
story, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Seems once in the later years of the show, he booked Michael
Keaton, who was a stand-up comic at the time, before he became a
star in Beetlejuice and Batman. During a commercial break, Keaton
told Douglas, ``Mr. Douglas, do you know what my real name is? Mike
Douglas. I had to change it because of you.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Douglas is watching The Tonight Show. The
guests: Keaton and Michael Douglas, the actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the show, Keaton leans over to Douglas and says, `Mr.
Douglas, do you know what my real name is? Michael Douglas. I had
to change it because of you.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way Hollywood works,'' he says with a slight
chuckle. ``That's show business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
