<HEADER>
A0749 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TICKET-BOOTHS26-COX     08-25 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKET-BOOTHS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TKTS celebrates 25 years helping shows break a leg
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I hate to stand in lines. It's bad enough when I have
to wait at the bank, but it's far more aggravating wasting time in
line when I'm on vacation. With one exception.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for half-price theater tickets at the TKTS booth in New
York not only makes economic sense, but is itself a dose of street
theater performance art. Located at 47th Street and Broadway, on a
triangular block known as Duffy Square, the booth has been luring
bargain hunters and keeping many a show afloat with extra revenue
for the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   It opened in June 1973, and the idea caught on instantly with
the public. Today, when the booth opens daily at 3 p.m. (10 a.m. on
matinee days), there will be a line all the way down to 46th Street
that usually snakes back to 47th. But food vendors, steel band
percussionists and out-of-work actors with handbills for nearby
restaurants know a captive audience when they see one, so they
descend on the block with their street pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The TKTS booth is also a site where cast members of current
shows often come to campaign for ticket sales. The more sales they
can generate, even at a discount, the more likely their shows will
remain open and they can keep working. After all, their
enthusiastic entreaties can, sad to say, be at least as
entertaining as some of the shows they are in.
</P>
<P>
   And since the common denominator of all the people standing on
the TKTS line is that they want to attend the theater that day, it
is an easy matter to strike up a conversation about what those
around you have already seen, hope to see or wouldn't be caught
dead seeing. Opinions get shared, and unsavvy out-of-towners seek
critical advice (``Cats. Is that any good? What's that about,
anyway?'' ``Well, it helps if you're under 10. About two-and-a-half
hours.'') Think of it as a living, breathing theater chat room, and
time passes surprisingly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If the buying public embraced the booth from its start, some
show producers were understandably wary of slashing their prices.
Sure, gaining half of a ticket's face value is better than having
the seat remain empty, but producers worried that last-minute
impulse purchasers would head to the discount booth rather than the
theater box office.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, some do. That's certainly where I head if I haven't
made advance plans. Arriving unexpectedly early into New York in
May, in time for a matinee, I hopped on line and snagged an
excellent seat for The Beauty Queen of Leenane, the Irish play that
went on to win four Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   All shows not available
</P>
<P>
   They may still grumble about it _ theater producers are
notorious grumblers, anyway _ but these days, it is the rare show
that does not consign some tickets to the half-price booth. Ten
years after it opened, Phantom of the Opera has yet to use the
booth, a reflection on its continued fanatical following. Of other
holdover hits, only Rent and Chicago are selling well enough to not
need the booth's push. There is also no point in checking TKTS's
electronic display if you're intent on seeing this year's big hits
_ The Lion King, Ragtime and Cabaret. Not yet, at least.
</P>
<P>
   But it is just a matter of time, says TKTS's head treasurer
James Gatens, who has been with the booth since it opened a quarter
of a century ago. ``You see, the theater ticket business is very
much like life,'' he says philosophically. ``In the beginning,
people need help to get started. Then they get real strong in the
middle at some point, and then, towards the tail end, they start
weakening again, and they need help again.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked which formerly sold-out shows have since extended their
lives through discount sales, Gatens mentions Cats and Miss Saigon.
``We sell a lot of seats for them,'' he says. ``The most popular
show we have right now on the board would be Titanic, last year's
Tony winner. They're starting to use us on a fairly regular
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Variety, the TKTS booth accounts for about one
ticket out of every seven sold for a Broadway or off-Broadway show.
Speaking in early June, just after the Tony Awards, Gatens said,
``This week, we'll sell about 37,000 seats, and we'll return back
to box offices approximately $1.3mil-lion.'' No wonder producers
have come to appreciate the booth.
</P>
<P>
   How many tickets to consign to the TKTS booth or whether to use
the booth at all is completely up to each show. And a new option
started about five years ago allows producers to offer a 25 percent
discount instead of 50 percent. It's an enticement for relatively
healthy shows to use the booth sooner and more frequently. At the
moment, Jekyll &AMP; Hyde has been selling 25 percent off seats at
TKTS.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1973, there have been some significant changes in the
booth's physical plant and its operations. ``We even have bathroom
facilities here now, which we didn't have for the first 15 years,''
says Gatens. ``We had to run across the street to Wienerwald or the
hotels in the area to use their facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all computerized now
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of runners, the booth used to employ a squad of
couriers to shuttle tickets from the city's various box offices to
TKTS to be sold. Today, ticket sales are about 90 percent
computerized, so seats can be consigned for discount with the press
of a button. Each show seems to have its own strategy for when to
send tickets to the booth, how many and how often. That's why
Gatens can't answer the one question everyone wants to know, ``When
is the best time to come to get great seat locations?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk up here at 3 o'clock and get the best seats in
the house, or they might be released much later in the day,'' says
Gatens. ``There's no set policy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He can tell you that the line is longest in the first hour of
sales, 10 to 11 a.m. for matinees and 3 to 4 p.m. for evening
performances. By noon for matinees or 6 p.m. for evenings, the line
has usually dwindled to its shortest point.
</P>
<P>
   If you really don't like lines, and you don't mind going
downtown, TKTS has a satellite booth on the mezzanine of Two World
Trade Center. The lines are shorter, it is air-conditioned and
sheltered from the elements, and it opens weekdays at 11 a.m. to
accommodate workers on their lunch breaks. It is also worth
remembering that matinee tickets are sold here the day before the
performance _ Friday for Saturday's matinee, for instance. About 15
to 17 percent of TKTS sales come from the World Trade Center
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   At 25, the TKTS booth is healthy and successful. So is Broadway
at 100, thanks in part to the sales generated by the half-price
booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make big hits bigger, we don't make bad shows any
worse,'' says Gatens. ``It's those middle-of-the-road shows that
need that extra percentage to keep the doors open. That's what we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-21-98 1955E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
