<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEIRD-MARRIAGE26-COX     08-25 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIRD-MARRIAGE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trysting the night away: Bill, Monica are frolicking in historic
company
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Jung said a man who has not passed through the inferno of
his passions has not overcome them. If Bill Clinton is feeling
heat, it may be because he lingered too long in the inferno.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is old and seemingly hard to learn: Affairs are
dangerous, possibly wrong, professionally destructive and wrenching
to loved ones. Or, they may not be. Peccadilloes march, stumble and
steal hand in hand through history with the greats, near greats and
not-so-greats.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes everybody wins. Usually, someone loses.
</P>
<P>
   Louis XV, 18th-century French king, learned when you give away
the keys to the kingdom for reasons of the flesh the kingdom
becomes unglued as well as unlocked. His mistress, Madame de
Pompadour, ruled as virtual queen for 20 years, sinking France into
wars, taxes and famine. On the plus side she financially supported
artists and poets, most now forgotten. Her tastes ran to the
pedestrian except in lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stewart Parnell, leader of the Irish freedom movement in
the late 19th century, scuttled Ireland's cause when he took up
with Katherine O'Shea, the wife of an army captain. Parnell's fall
gave Britain the leverage to rule parts of Ireland to this day.
</P>
<P>
   John Profumo, British war minister, learned in 1963 that
sleeping with the enemy is not a good idea for war minsters. When
his mistress, Christine Keeler, turned out to be a call girl,
tongues wagged but eyes winked. When she turned out to be a
confidant to Soviet spies, Profumo's career ended with a whimper.
He exchanged his life of philandering for one of philanthropy and
was later cited by the queen. For his good deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand Russell, perhaps the greatest logician of the 20th
century, said that ``civilized people cannot fully satisfy their
sexual instinct without love.'' Married four times, divorced three,
Russell was known to park his bicycle in front of houses wherein
lived the wives of fellow professors. For tea, we presume. Or,
perhaps he was looking for love. Anyway, he was tossed out of the
City College of New York in 1949 as ``an enemy of morals.'' His
1932 book, Marriage and Morals, is considered a classic by many
progressive thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hart challenged the press to put a tail on him during his
1988 presidential bid in order to dispel rumors of sexual misdeeds.
The press did. Hart, who was married, quit the race soon after the
press photographed him and friend Donna Rice in an unpresidential
pose.
</P>
<P>
   The press need not get on its high horse. William Randolph
Hearst, who took yellow journalism to new shades of jaundice during
the Spanish-American War, lived openly with his mistress, actress
Marion Davies, in his California mansion. His wife never
editorialized, in public anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Affairs in American politics often _ but not always _ lack the
finesse of French trilateral commissions, where it is de rigeur to
keep one's mistress not quite hidden. Read biographies of former
French President Francois Mitterrand for more details.
</P>
<P>
   On one end of our spectrum we have the discreet (and unverified)
assignations of FDR, who is rumored to have found succor in the
arms of another woman. The same has been said of Eleanor. Perhaps
because of grace and strength of character, their partnership
transcended any lapses. Same with JFK and Jackie. Ditto Dwight
Eisenhower and his wartime assistant, Kay Summersby. We'll never
know exactly what happened. The pat answer is the press was less
willing to dig into private lives in our more innocent past. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the targets of suspicion displayed more intelligence
and stealth than some of their modern counterparts. Remember
Arkansas Congressman Wilbur Mills splashing with Fanne Fox in the
Tidal Basin in the middle of Washington, D.C.? And Oregon Sen.
Robert Packwood who, it seems, wanted to date all his female
employees. Gary Hart. Ted Kennedy. President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some men dare to hope; others dare to grope.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians with a wandering eye might keep Tallulah Bankhead's
admonition in mind: ``Never practice two vices at once.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of fine art seems more forgiving of conjugal
trespassers. Artists, actors, writers _ being artistes _ raise
angst, insecurity and their need for freedom to the level of ...
art. Fiction, but art.
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald was so obsessed by his sexual credentials he
took heavily to drink and the company of men and women who told him
what he wanted to hear. He might not have even dallied, but his
writing suffered. So did his wife, Zelda, who went insane.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Dietrich and her husband, Rudolf Sieber, helped each
other procure lovers.
</P>
<P>
   William Shawn, former New Yorker editor, kept two phones by the
side of his bed, according to a recent memoir by his mistress,
Lillian Ross.
</P>
<P>
   One phone was for her exclusive use.
</P>
<P>
   The affair had lasted for decades. Toward the end, she called on
the private line to check on Shawn as his health declined. One
night, Shawn's wife answered. He's gone, she said, and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   The list of history's philandering painters, actors, publishers,
poets and pundits is far too long to print here.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe one of their own best explains mankind's flirtation with
dangerous flirtation:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bawdy planet.'' Shakespeare, The Winter's Tale, Act I,
Scene 1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
