r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-METRO26-COX     08-25 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-METRO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Capital Metro makes top-job offer
 &HT;    By Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Capital Metro, which has been without a general
manager since December, is getting a new boss from Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors voted recently to begin negotiating with
Karen Rae, acting director of surface transportation for the
Niagara Frontier Transportation Authority in Buffalo, to take over
Capital Metro's top job.
</P>
<P>
   Board members, who struggled with a decision for several months,
said Rae, 43, stood out because of her passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to be impressed with how dynamic she is,'' board
Chairman Lee Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Board member George Denny, mayor of Cedar Park, said he heard
high praise for Rae at a recent transit conference he attended. He
said Rae is energetic and experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed with her,'' Denny said.
</P>
<P>
   But Walker said it was more than the energy they saw on the
surface that won board members over. It was Rae's reputation in
Buffalo for community involvement and her ability to scrap for
limited dollars in hard economic times that made their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is somebody who's very frugal,'' Walker said. ``They have
not had the relative abundance we have here. They've had to do with
less and less.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason it's unlikely Rae will turn down a chance to
come to Capital Metro, where she will have better resources _ a
one-cent dedicated sales tax that is bring in more money each year
_ to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Board members Monday worried about the risk of announcing their
top choice without a firm contract in hand, but Walker said he
thought the board had to be open with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief is that if we run an open shop, we'll be ahead of
the game here,'' Walker said. ``Obviously, if we can't reach a
deal, we can't reach a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rae said she doesn't think it will be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely committed to getting there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Rae makes a little less than $77,000. If she chose to
stay in Buffalo, her salary would be $85,000. Capital Metro's
former general manager, Justin Augustine III, received $118,500 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Rae said she knows there will be challenges at Capital Metro,
particularly in changing negative perceptions of Capital Metro in
the community. But Rae called working in the community ``the thing
I love to do most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very interesting to get out and talk to the
public,'' she said. Rae put that interest to use during the 14
months before the Buffalo transit authority started a pilot program
called Hublink that attempts to link inner-city workers to suburban
jobs and make suburb-to-suburb commuting easier.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, Rae attended about 90 community
meetings, trying to get an idea exactly what the community wants
and needs from its transit authority.
</P>
<P>
   The same concept is needed in Austin, Rae said, where she'd like
community members to determine what service standards they want,
whether it's the frequency of service or the size of the buses.
</P>
<P>
   Rae said she has taken a close look at a performance review
released last month by the state comptroller's office that was
critical of Capital Metro. She said it was a well-done audit that
serves as ``a good road map'' to turning the agency around.
</P>
<P>
   But she stressed that audits, by their nature, often leave out
the things an agency does well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My challenge is to find those strengths and build on them,''
Rae said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, Denny and board member Margaret Gomez, a Travis County
commissioner, will negotiate with Rae. Board members said they hope
to have Rae at Capital Metro by Oct. 1, when a new budget year
begins.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the board of directors got a budget preview that
includes plans to operate the bus system on about two-thirds of the
agency's $100 million sales tax levy. Earlier this year, the board
and staff struggled to get bus operations to three-quarters of the
sales tax and to reserve one-quarter for future rail or other
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a healthy economy _ sales tax revenue is forecast to
increase 5 percent _ more money can be set aside for future
projects. At the same time, operating expenses could increase 8
percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   The draft budget will be released in the near future. The board
is expected to approve a budget Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
