r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATTLE-CANADA26-COX     08-25 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATTLE-CANADA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheaper Canadian cattle driving down US prices
 &HT;    By Heather McGregor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Western beef producers are organizing
and raising money to pursue an international trade complaint
against Canada. They allege that subsidized Canadian beef imports _
boxed and on the hoof _ are driving down domestic calf prices by
$100 to $250 a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have market fluctuation anymore. We're just getting
slammed,'' said Kathleen Sullivan Kelley of Meeker, a rancher and
vice president of Ranchers-Cattlemen Action Legal Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The R-CALF group argues that since Canada can no longer sell
beef to Asia because of economic troubles there, it's exporting as
many as 1.5 million cattle a year to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   And Canadian producers are subsidized by a variety of government
programs that allow them to sell cattle to U.S.-based packers at
below-cost prices, the group contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is slamming down domestic prices, while we as an industry
can't even begin to meet our U.S. consumer demand,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   Below-cost imports are skewing the standard economic rule that
heavy demand and short supply leads to higher prices, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in our fifth year of reduced cattle prices, and
nationwide we're down 10 million head since 1994. We'll see as much
as a 30 percent reduction in producers in the next year, ranchers
simply selling off their cattle and going out of business,'' Kelley
said.
</P>
<P>
   The economic strain on the beef industry is as much blamed on a
concentration of ownership in the meat packing industry as on
imports. While a separate lawsuit against Iowa Beef Processors is
underway in federal court by Midwestern cattle growers, ranchers in
the northern tier states are focusing on imports.
</P>
<P>
   R-CALF founders Leo McDonnell of Columbus, Mont., and Mike
Callicrate of St. Francis, Kans., have gone on the lecture circuit
of town meetings in Montana, Wyoming, Nebraska and the Dakotas.
Crowds of 350 to 800 have turned out in recent weeks, and the
organizers have had no trouble raising the $50,000 needed to retain
legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley plans to make an organizing swing through Texas starting
in mid-September. She is available to speak to groups in Colorado
until then.
</P>
<P>
   They must raise an estimated $1.5 million to fight the entire
legal battle, and they must prove that at least 300,000 cattle
growers _ 25 percent of the nation's total _ support the action.
</P>
<P>
   R-CALF has hired Stewart &AMP; Stewart, a Washington, D.C., law firm
that has specialized in international trade disputes for more than
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The group could pursue up to three avenues of complaint, said
attorney Terence Stewart, and the action will likely be filed in
September:
</P>
<P>
   _ An Anti-Dumping petition could be filed with the U.S.
Department of Commerce and the U.S. International Trade Commission.
The petition would allege that Canadian beef is being sold in U.S.
markets at below-cost prices. In a briefing document, Stewart
states that his evaluation ``suggests that imports from Canada are
being sold in the U.S. at dumping margins that are significant
under U.S. law.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A Countervailing Duty petition could also be filed with the
same two federal agencies. The petition would allege that the
Canadian government is offering subsidies to growers that allow
them to export beef at below-cost prices. Stewart's analysis
``suggests there is a large number'' of such subsidies benefitting
Canadian beef exports.
</P>
<P>
   The petitions would trigger year-long investigations by the two
agencies, involving extensive research on pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Commerce officials must rule on the allegations of
dumping and unfair subsidies. International Trade Commission
officials must determine damages to the U.S. cattle industry caused
by imports.
</P>
<P>
   If both agencies see a serious problem, then Commerce officials
will direct the U.S. Customs office to collect extra import fees to
offset the dumping or subsidy margins.
</P>
<P>
   _ A complaint alleging violation of the North American Free
Trade Agreement may also be filed with the U.S. Trade
Representative. A Section 301 complaint would be aimed directly at
the Canadian government.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. Trade Representative's office accepts the complaint,
it would initiate talks with Canadian trade officials in hopes of
convincing the country to trade more fairly. If such a deal can't
be struck, the U.S. could impose prohibitively high tariffs on
Canadian goods, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   The focus at present is on Canada, Kelley said, but cattle
growers are watching the southern border as well. Mexican cattle
imports are of concern, and Congress will consider this fall
whether to enact ``fast track'' legislation that would bring Brazil
and Argentina into the NAFTA free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
   Like Canada, Brazilian and Argentinian producers are looking for
a new market following the Asian economic collapse. With a high
demand for beef and few trade barriers, the U.S. market is a
logical choice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
