</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATTLE-CANADA-RANCHER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lower meat prices steer industry downhill
 &HT;    By Heather McGregor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW CASTLE, Colo. _ Barton Porter supported the North American
Free Trade Agreement, but now he feels that U.S. beef packers are
taking advantage of the open border to buy cheap Canadian cattle.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1994, fat cattle sold for an all-time high of $80
to $84 a hundredweight. Since early 1997, however, the price has
stuck below $60 a hundredweight, said Porter, 74, a rancher and
feeder.
</P>
<P>
   Porter buys steers and heifers from growers all over the West.
He ships them to feedlots in Kansas where they spend about four
months fattening up on grain, and then sells them to a
slaughterhouse. He rarely sees the animals, and does his business
over the telephone, often with buyers he's never met in person.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the kitchen table in his ranch house up Alkali Creek,
south of New Castle, Porter pulls out the balance sheets to
illustrate the financial squeeze growers and feeders are under.
</P>
<P>
   He spent from $70 to $75 a hundredweight to buy the cattle, and
they put on an average of 400 pounds in the feedlot. By the time he
pays the feedlot bill, about $250, he's got about $750 invested in
each animal.
</P>
<P>
   But at the current fat cattle price of $59 a hundredweight,
Porter is selling those cattle for about $650 a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cattle are losing $100 a head. We'd need a price of at
least $65 (a hundredweight) just to break even,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't correlate that exactly to the Canadian situation, but
if they couldn't buy those cattle from Canada, it would certainly
raise our price here,'' Porter said. ``I'm kind of a free trade
advocate myself, but maybe we need some government intervention to
subsidize our operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Porter does a bit more math to bring home his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just us taking these losses,'' he said. About 650,000
cattle are sold to slaughter every week in the U.S. At a $100 a
head loss, the nation's cattle growers are collectively losing $65
million a week.
</P>
<P>
   Porter's grandfather homesteaded on Alkali Creek in 1904. Barton
and his bride, Martha, started ranching in 1949, and they have
grown the place to 3,600 acres where they run about 600 yearlings.
The ranch's 700 irrigated acres produce 1,500 tons of hay a year.
</P>
<P>
   Porter sells hay, and he sells hunting privileges, but he admits
that the ranch doesn't make money. ``It's a lifestyle, really,'' he
said. Behind him on the kitchen counter, a dozen jars of freshly
canned apricots glow in the morning light.
</P>
<P>
   Porter's feeder trade of up to 2,200 head a year is what keeps
the place afloat, and that's why he is so concerned about the long
spate of low prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're taking $59, there's no way it will work out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
