A0758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-NEW-SYSTEMS26-CO     08-25 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-NEW-SYSTEMS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell passes on cheaper PCs: Too much trouble
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. and other personal
computer makers announced several new systems recently that
incorporate the newest processors from Intel Corp., including a new
and improved chip for the sub-$1,000 market.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, however, will not use the chip to enter the fast-growing
market for computers that cost less than $1,000. It remains the
last of the major PC makers without a sub-$1,000 PC.
</P>
<P>
   The Round Rock-based company will use Intel's new Celeron chip
to help launch a new line of its Dimension computers, its consumer
and small business line, that start at $1,399. That will be Dell's
lowest-priced computer for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also introduced its most powerful OptiPlex, the desktop
computer for large customers. It is powered by Intel's newest
Pentium II, a 450-megahertz microprocessor that is considered an
evolutionary, not revolutionary, improvement over the 400-megahertz
Pentium II. The high-end OptiPlex GX1p with the 450-megahertz
Pentium II starts at about $3,100.
</P>
<P>
   New products from Dell, Compaq Computer Corp. and others were
expected with Intel's formal announcement of the new
microprocessors, which are the brains of computers. It has become
the pattern in the industry in recent years for PC manufacturers to
base new computers on the improved processors that come once or
twice annually from Intel, whose chips run an estimated 80 percent
of PCs in use today.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, from the industry's point of view, the new processors
are accompanied by significant ``buzz'' or anticipation, such as
the intense interest that Apple Computer Inc.'s iMac has generated.
That typically translates into more sales.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation of the new offerings from Intel was relatively
modest.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, although less powerful than the Pentium II, the new
300-megahertz and 333-megahertz Celeron chips have attracted more
attention than the 450-megahertz Pentium II because the Celeron
introduced in April was a disappointment, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new chip is what the Celeron should have been to start
with,'' said Keith Diefendorff of Microprocessor Report, a
chip-industry publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Celeron been there when it was introduced, Intel wouldn't
have lost quite as much market share in the sub-$1,000 market.''
</P>
<P>
   Microdesign Resources, the Silicon Valley firm that publishes
the newsletter, estimates that AMD had 54 percent of the budget-PC
market in June, compared with 40 percent for Intel. AMD
manufactures processors in Austin and California.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Thomsen, a researcher at Microdesign Resources, said those
estimates don't give a complete picture of the chip's sales because
many of them ended up in computers that sold for more than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the original Celeron had shortcomings, which opened the
door for AMD and Cyrix, the Dallas chip maker that is owned by
National Semiconductor Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Dell ignored it because it did not have a backside, or level 2
cache, which stores data on the chip for faster processing. The new
Celeron has 128 kilobytes of L2 cache.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what was in the pipeline,'' said Dell spokesman T.R.
Reid, explaining that Dell decided to wait until Celeron had the
cache feature before putting the chip in its computers.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell remains the sole major computer maker to eschew the
sub-$1,000 market, which accounts for an estimated 10 percent of PC
sales. Dell has long targeted more sophisticated customers who are
likely to buy more high-end machines where profit margins are
somewhat higher.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, buyers of cheaper PCs tend to be less computer
savvy and require more assistance, Dell executives argue. Taking
care of them adds to costs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Dell sees little demand for a budget PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not where our customers are taking us,'' Reid said.
``That, combined with the fact that we've got a variety of growth
opportunities, perhaps more than we can effectively manage, (means)
it becomes a matter of choices, and to focus on the higher end of
the market is an obvious choice for us.'' iDOT.com, a new Austin
company that sells PCs exclusively over the World Wide Web, offered
a $999 computer using the 300-megahertz Celeron processor. The
company offers 450-megahertz Pentium II products starting at
$1,799.
</P>
<P>
   Monitors start at $99, iDOT said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
