r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIO-GRANDE-FLOOD26-CO     08-25 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIO-GRANDE-FLOOD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laredo prepares for flood wave on Rio Grande
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Laredo braced for a fast-moving flood wave on
the Rio Grande that is expected to crest at levels at least four
times about flood stage and could close the Laredo bridge later
this week, forecasters said Monday, August 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not historic, but this is very serious flooding,'' said
Daryl Williams, a National Weather Service forecaster.
</P>
<P>
   The flood wave, which was reported to be a mile wide, will reach
34 to 36 feet at Laredo, where the river floods at 8 feet, Williams
said. ``This will be a full 15 feet below the record flood in June
of 1954, but it's still bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State, federal and Laredo officials met Monday night at City
Hall to prepare for the flood wave. At 36 feet, the crest would be
almost at the level of the international bridge spanning the Rio
Grande in downtown Laredo. It raised the possibility that the
heavily traveled thoroughfare to Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, might have
to be closed.
</P>
<P>
   If floodwaters lap at bridge level, ``We'd rather take the
precaution of closing it,'' said Marco Alvarado, public information
officer for the City of Laredo. ``We're ready to take action if
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Alvarado said, authorities were warning
residents along the river banks to be prepared to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   The crest was moving Monday night and this morning through the
sparsely populated ranch country south of Eagle Pass. It must
travel about 125 miles to reach Laredo by Wednesday afternoon,
Williams projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's moving fast,'' said Ken Rakestraw with the
International Boundary and Water Commission. Water typically takes
2 1/2 days to travel from Eagle Pass to the Falcon Reservoir, south
of Laredo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get from Eagle Pass to Laredo in a little over a day is
fast, but that's typical for a flood wave,'' Rakestraw added.
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters were the result of the remnants of Tropical
Storm Charley, which stalled Monday morning over the Del Rio area,
north of Eagle Pass, before moving slowly north and east during the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The computer models projected the storm would move north and
west, Williams said, ``but nothing has gone as it should.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters had expected Charley, which swept through Central
Texas over the weekend, to continue toward Mexico and West Texas,
breaking up as it went. Instead, the system stalled, dumping a
flood on ground that had been parched until rains earlier last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been dry all year, and they get all of it in one week,''
Williams said. ``If the rain stopped right now (Monday), we'd still
have problems'' in the Del Rio area.
</P>
<P>
   The International Amistad Reservoir north of Del Rio was 60 feet
below normal levels, so it absorbed floodwaters north of the city.
But nothing could stop flooding south of the international dam
toward Del Rio and Eagle Pass.
</P>
<P>
   Even rural areas were being hit hard. Sgt. Pedro Hinojosa of the
Maverick County sheriff's office said many ranch houses are built
near the river. Border Patrol helicopters were flying up and down
the Rio Grande on Monday afternoon, warning residents about the
flood wave, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reports of people stranded in trees,'' Hinojosa said.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding is worse on Mexico's side of the river, he said,
because the bank is lower.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Fain, a University of Texas at El Paso professor who has
studied the Rio Grande, said the brush country between Eagle Pass
and Laredo has few people on either side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly small villages, ranches and farms,'' Fain said.
``There are some pretty helpless people in those settlements. To
them, this could be a calamity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
