</P>
<P>
   STILLER-KINGS _ They're back! ``Seinfeld's'' Jerry Stiller stars
in ABC's ``The King of Queens.'' (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   THAT-70S-SHOW _ That '70s Show is a goofy, laugh-out-loud hoot.
As the deadpan Eric, Grace is particularly funny. The guy's blank
stares say more than three pages of dialogue. You can tell the 3rd
Rock From the Sun creators (Bonnie and Terry Turner) are behind
this often manic, live-action cartoon. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORING-TV _ With the debut of Fox's That '70s Show and Holding
The Baby, the network TV season officially kicked off. Over the
next two months, you'll be bombarded with 34 new shows. And the
buzz on most of those shows can be summed up quite succinctly: bad.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AARON-ECKHART _ For the past year, actor Aaron Eckhart has been
receiving hate mail. His film debut as a sadistic male chauvinist
who cruelly toys with a hearing-impaired secretary in the
controversial film In the Company of Men proved too persuasive for
some moviegoers. Now, Eckhart and director Neil LaBute have teamed
up on another downbeat movie about male-female relations, Your
Friends &AMP; Neighbors. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MIKE-DOUGLAS _ This is the kind of scrapbook collection you
accumulate when you host 6,000 episodes of a TV talk show over 23
years. The scrapbooks were his wife's idea. Every celebrity who
spent a week co-hosting The Mike Douglas Show got a copy of photos
shot on the set. Not that the 73-year-old star needs them to
remember his five decades in the entertainment industry. (Houck,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOUGLAS-SHOW _ The list of guests featured on The Mike Douglas
Show reads like a ``who's who'' of Hollywood in the '60s and '70s.
(Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET-BOOTHS _ Waiting for half-price theater tickets at the
TKTS booth in New York not only makes economic sense, but is itself
a dose of street theater performance art. The booth has been luring
bargain hunters and keeping many a show afloat with extra revenue
for the past 25 years. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   FRENDS-N-NEIGHBORS _ Neil LaBute's chatty acid-bath ``Your
Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' is the writer-director's follow-up to last
year's savage and incendiary ``In the Company of Men.'' It's
difficult to figure which movie is more pungently, unrepentantly
vicious. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CATSUIT _ I'm trying to determine if a woman can go about her
day in Central Texas in a slinky one-piece getup like the one Uma
Thurman sports as Emma Peel in ``The Avengers,'' the recently
released cinematic dud. (Kelly, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLADE-REVIEW _ `Blade'' touts itself as a different kind of
vampire movie, and in a few small ways it is. But ``Blade'' is
similar to many vampire movies in that it's not very good. (Garcia,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JONG _ AUSTIN _ Twenty-five years after ``Fear of Flying,''
feminist poet Erica Jong revisits the war between the sexes in a
new book, ``What Do Women Want?'' due out in September from
HarperCollins. Its subtitles: ``Bread. Roses. Sex. Power.'' In it,
Jong dedicates a chapter to her observations on first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton. Here's a sample of what she writes about the
Clinton's political marriage: (excerpt follows). (Morris, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ What do a vampire slayer, a birth control activist,
and a cybersex editrix have in common? They're all women, for one
thing. For another, they're on George ($2.95) magazine's list of
the ``20 Most Fascinating Women in Politics.'' (And other reviews
of this week's magazines.) (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED 8/24.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ Look closely, and there's something for Elton
John fans of almost any age available or coming to market. For
starters, there's the lightly publicized compilation of others'
tunes that he recorded early in his career, ``16 Legendary Covers
From 1969/70.'' It includes versions of ``Up Around the Bend,''
``Love of the Common People'' and ``Spirit in the Sky.'' (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ The two pleasantest words in our language, I'm
thinking, may be comfort and joy. Marianne Gilbert of Gainesville
sent some pages from a book she likes very much called ``Simple
Abundance, A Day Book of Comfort and Joy.'' (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-HUNTSVILLE _ Taking the kids to the U.S. Space and
Rocket Center in Huntsville, Ala. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-FESTIVALS _ A calendar. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CHELSEA-CLINTON _ AUSTIN _ People can only guess the impact of
her father's admission. A front-page picture of Chelsea Clinton
recently showed her holding hands with her parents, the young woman
bridging the gap between the president and his wife. And we wonder:
What is this doing to Chelsea? (Gandara, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WIERD-MARRIAGES _ The lesson is old and seemingly hard to learn:
Affairs are dangerous, possibly wrong, professionally destructive
and wrenching to loved ones. Or, they may not be. Peccadilloes
march, stumble and steal hand in hand through history with the
greats, near greats and not-so-greats. ``It's a bawdy planet.''
Shakespeare, The Winter's Tale, Act I, Scene 1.(Reid, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RANDOM-ACT _ If you are one of those people who go around
committing random acts of kindness and senseless acts of beauty out
of sheer anonymous decency, the jig might be up. Somebody might rat
you out. In fact, I keep a file on doers of good deeds, and I
encourage readers to tell on their friends. (Wiggins, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-BOUTIQUE _ ``A Woman's Place'' the ``first''
hospital-based retail boutique in the Southeast, opens on Thursday.
A Woman's Place specializes in women's health-care related products
such as prosthesis, wigs, speciality bras. Their customer profile
is any women between the ages of 20 to 70 or older who has recently
had a health-care experience from childbirth to cancer. (Johnson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RIO-GRANDE-FLOOD _ LAREDO, Texas _ Laredo braced for a
fast-moving flood wave on the Rio Grande that is expected to crest
at levels at least four times about flood stage and could close the
Laredo bridge later this week, forecasters said Monday, August 24.
``It's not historic, but this is very serious flooding,'' said
Daryl Williams, a National Weather Service forecaster. (Copelin,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
