<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STROKE-WOMEN (Houston) _ Women stroke sufferers arrive at the
hospital later and are evaluated more slowly than their male
counterparts, even though their death rate in Texas is higher than
that of men, a University of Texas Medical School researcher says.
By RUTH SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MASSAGE (San Francisco) _ Just a week after giving initial
approval to legislation that would ban new massage parlors in the
Tenderloin, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors put the brakes
on the proposal amid emerging opposition from the targeted business
owners and the women who work for them. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   PHONY-COLLECTION (San Francisco) _ A mysterious letter dunning
hundreds of people for money they don't owe to a company that
evidently doesn't exist has triggered a U.S. Postal Service
investigation. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   MAD-COW-CLONES (Undated) _ Texas A&AMP;M University scientists are
trying to clone cattle resistant to mad cow disease, the mysterious
brain ailment that has killed thousands of cattle in Britain and 30
people who ate beef infected with it. The project was begun in
response to requests from Texas cattle industry leaders. By TODD
ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-ENGLISH (San Francisco) _ Waves of immigrants don't
threaten the dominance of English as America's main language
because most youthful newcomers prefer speaking it rather than
their native tongue, research shows. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-RESEARCH (San Francisco) _ How are Americans coping with
this high-speed, high-tech age, when ``all that is solid melts into
air''? National Geographic magazine and social scientists are
planning to find out by using the ultimate engine of mobility _ the
World Wide Web, by which humans ``navigate'' global databases, chat
rooms and stock markets at the speed of light. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-SCHOOL (Albany, N.Y.) _ A controversial national survey
has rated the University at Albany the top party school in the
country. But there were no chants of ``We're Number One'' from
administrators or students. By MIKE HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NLRB-CHAIRMAN (San Francisco) _ Bill Gould IV, great-grandson of
a slave, has been chairman of the National Labor Relations Board
since 1994, which is another way of saying he was a punching bag
for the House GOP for 4 1/2 years. But this punching bag punched
back. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GIFT-CERTIFICATES (San Francisco) _ Paper or plastic? No, not
your grocery bag _ your gift certificate. Retailers in growing
numbers are starting to replace those seemingly unchanging paper
gift vouchers that look like oversized checks with plastic, credit
card-sized gift certificates that function much like debit cards.
By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-VACCINATION (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's a growing movement of
parents across the nation, in opposition to the medical
establishment and in many cases, state law, that opposes childhood
vaccinations. Their frustration comes as the list of recommended
and required vaccines for children grows beyond the standard polio,
mumps, measles and rubella vaccines. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
