   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Civilization supposedly may crash
because of the ``Y2K problem.'' ``Y2K'' stands for ``the year
2000.'' The problem, also known as ``the millennium bug,'' is that
when big mainframe computers were built in the '60s and '70s,
engineers saved valuable storage space by giving them clocks with
years recorded only by their last two digits. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The escape of murderer Gary Evans
raises the question of whether the U.S. Marshal's Service is
composed of people who, by comparison, make the late and utterly
unlamented Gary Evans seem like a Rhodes scholar. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Before he released the conveyor
belt that would pull me and my 12-year-old Honda Civic through the
one-minute automatic car wash, the man who owns a Ford Motor Co.
car and I talked about the price of new cars today. We agreed that,
barring some unforeseen shift in our finances, both of us had
bought our last new car. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
