<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIC LESSON AT THE CAR WASH: IT RUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The man who runs the last drive-through car wash
on Earth gently scraped at the roof of my Honda with a rag mop.
</P>
<P>
   (OK. Maybe it's not really the last drive-through car wash on
Earth, but it's the last one I can find in San Francisco or
anywhere else around here, so it might as well be the last.)
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the spot that had drawn his attention, I rolled down my
window and yelled, ``It's falling apart! That's rust!''
</P>
<P>
   The man, who is about my dad's age and often wears Bermuda
shorts on the job, stopped scraping. He walked around to my open
window and flashed a mischievous but genteel smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was bird doodie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I replied that I wished that was all it was.
</P>
<P>
   The man who runs the last drive-through car wash on Earth fixed
me with a stern look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it run?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Touche. I nodded and grinned.
</P>
<P>
   The man squirted special cleaner on my tires and pointed to his
own automobile parked behind the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought that new in '77,'' he said of a large, two-toned
luxury model from the Ford Motor Co. ``It's just about gone. But it
runs. And I drive it to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he released the conveyor belt that would pull me and my
12-year-old Civic through the one-minute automatic car wash, the
man and I talked about the price of new cars today. We agreed that,
barring some unforeseen shift in our finances, both of us had
bought our last new car.
</P>
<P>
   Which was maybe a little sad but not the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in here with a $40,000 car, and I look _ they've
got dings and dents all over or they've been keyed all the way from
one end to the other,'' the man said. ``I don't know how you could
stand that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the conveyor began to pull me into the car wash, I waved
goodbye and settled back to listen to the prelude to Richard
Wagner's ``Parsifal'' on my radio. While soap suds covered the
windshield, I thought about how much pleasure this one-person
enterprise had given me over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   On the practical level, for the price of a glass of ordinary
wine, I got the soot-covered, plum-spotted, bird-doodied exterior
of my old, rust-marked car washed and dried. And I got it done in
less time than it takes to brush my teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But on another level, I got something much more important.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the $40,000 cars have dings, dents and key lines, they
always look pretty darn nice. When the people who drive such cars
turn them over to a valet parker, they never see his lip curl in
disgust or hear him say, ``Oh, uhhh-huh,'' because they've informed
him that there's a little trick to turning off the headlights.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have to watch at a regular car wash while a
half-dozen guys with drying rags avoid their cars and look all over
for any other car they can possibly find to wipe down. If someone
scrapes at a spot with a rag mop on the roof of their cars, the
only thing that comes off is the spot, not part of the roof.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, such people are accustomed to having their cars
treated with respect, admiration even. To them, the man who runs
the last drive-through car wash on Earth is probably just a nice
guy who gets them in and out for a quick, cheap wash.
</P>
<P>
   To me, though, he is a man of vision. He looks at a faded
hatchback that came over on the boat the same year the Iran-contra
scandal broke and Ivan Boesky was indicted for insider trading, and
he sees a great little car. A car worthy of washing. A car that
runs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
