<HEADER>
A0940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE27-COX     08-25 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Tuppers' Hop Pocket Pils a bit of domestic nobility
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Driving through the German Rhineland, you see a vertically oval
green sign in every village and town you come to. On the sign you
read, in spare but elegant script, the word ``Pils.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign is the logo for Bitburger, from the town of Bitburg,
and ``Pils'' is a diminutive of pilsener, the lager style that
takes its name from Pilsen in the Czech republic. To most
Americans, ``pilsener'' (or ``pilsner'') is synonymous with cheap
six-pack beer poured from an aluminum pop-top can. A majority of
the beers throughout the world, in fact, are distant derivatives of
the style _ so distant that all resemblance has been lost. The term
has been bastardized to mean any golden lager. A parallel
circumstance in the United States used to be California ``chablis''
in those strawbound jugs. The real thing, originating from the
Burgundian town of Chablis, was a different wine altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, a real pils is among beer's nobility, assertive
and delicate at the same time. But few Americans have ever tasted
one.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is to introduce what might be the best domestic
example of the style. Tuppers' Hop Pocket Pils, brewed by Old
Dominion, arrived in the Atlanta market only a month after the gold
medal-winning Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale sold out almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The two beers could hardly be more different. Where Hop Pocket
Ale is aromatic and bracingly bitter, with a long, lingering
finish, Hop Pocket Pils is crisp and dry, firm on the palate and
softly floral to the nose. Both are beers to be savored, not
guzzled. But savoring the one is a different experience from
savoring the other, just as a superior white wine is different from
a superior red.
</P>
<P>
   For the person unacquainted with ales, Hop Pocket Pils is the
more accessible of the two. At 35 to 40 International Bitterness
Units, Tuppers' is three times as assertive as Budweiser, but only
two-thirds the hopping rate of Hop Pocket Ale.
</P>
<P>
   But the flavor profile more than the IBUs defines a beer _ the
nature of the yeast, the quality of the barley, the interplay of
malt and hop. Tuppers' is a model of pils perfection. It pours into
the glass golden and slightly hazy, forming a rich, foamy head. The
Saaz hops, a trademark of the best pilseners, create a bouquet
that's detectable but not emphatic. On the palate, it's soft at the
outset, with a malty firmness in the middle and a satisfying
crispness at the finish. This is what a good German pils tastes
like.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, you won't find many in Germany as complex as
this. The more familiar imported brands _ notably Beck's,
Warsteiner, Veltin's, St. Pauli Girl _ come nowhere close. The much
overrated Heineken, brewed in the Netherlands and loosely in the
pilsener style, is even further removed.
</P>
<P>
   Bitburger is among the better German pilseners, but not as
assertive as some and not as characterful as Tuppers'. The one
German pils I'm familiar with that's comparable _ though not
identical _ is Jever, and I've never seen that beer in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Czech pilseners tend to be softer, less dry than the German
style. But for an American consumer the important consideration has
to be freshness. Pilsner Urquell, the original, is justly
celebrated, but it does not travel well. (In my experience, the
chances of getting a Pilsner Urquell that has oxidized approach 50
percent.)
</P>
<P>
   With any true pils _ German, Czech or domestic _ you look for an
almost perfect balance of malt and hops, and a finish that subtly
accentuates the latter. It is a beer best enjoyed alone or with
mild to moderately strong cheeses. But it also, like a fine
Chablis, accompanies white-meat fish well.
</P>
<P>
   ``An elderly emigre in Canada,'' Michael Jackson writes in the
``Beer Companion,'' ``once told me that his most evocative memory
from his homeland was of buying on the streets of Prague live carp
from the lakes near Trebon, and cooking the fish like schnitzels to
be served with Pilsner beer for Christmas dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've not had carp for Christmas, you've probably not missed
much. But when you taste a pils like Tuppers', you realize there's
a world of beer you knew nothing about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
