<HEADER>
A0941 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLT-RECIPES-COX     08-25 2384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLT-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enjoy the taste of the classic combo in sandwiches, salads and
even pizza
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making the perfect BLT can be as simple as assembling the
ingredients. Of course, it can be more complex than that, as well.
Take a few extra minutes to make a garlic-pesto mayonnaise to add
even more layers of flavor. Or use grilled green tomatoes instead
of red ones just off the vine.
</P>
<P>
   This combination that works so well for sandwiches can work for
other dishes, too, like salads, canapes and even pizza. With all,
the key is to assemble the freshest ingredients possible.
</P>
<P>
   A word about preparing the bacon. The tried-and-true way is to
fry it in a skillet, preferably a cast-iron one. But cooking it in
the microwave is popular too and certainly does the trick.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more option you may try _ baking it. Now, this
method takes more time but leaves your stovetop free and doesn't
require constant supervision. Simply place the bacon strips on a
broiler or cookie sheet and bake at 300 degrees for about 25
minutes or until crisp. You may want to turn the bacon once during
the process.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit in this technique is that you can dredge the bacon
in a coating first. Try pouring cornmeal or flour or a mixture of
flour and brown sugar onto a plate and simply coat each strip with
the dry ingredients, then place on the pan and bake. This method
adds texture, flavor and fun to an old favorite.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Our Best BLT Chicken and Pasta Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a favorite recipe, originally from Woman's Day Magazine,
that's a good dish to take along to a potluck. Use multicolor
rotini for extra flair.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup mayonnaise or salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup water
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon bottled barbecue or chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons freeze-dried chives, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1pound skinless boneless chicken breast halves
</P>
<P>
   2cups pasta twists (rotini)
</P>
<P>
   6slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   2cups Boston, romaine or iceberg lettuce, torn in bite-size
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1large tomato, seeded and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Mix mayonnaise or salad dressing with water, barbecue sauce,
chives, garlic powder and pepper in a large salad bowl until
blended. Put chicken breast halves in 6-quart pot. Add just enough
water to cover. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat to low and simmer for
8-10 minutes until chicken is no longer pink in center. Remove with
tongs or a slotted spoon to cutting board and cool. Add enough
water to poaching liquid in pot to cook pasta (4 quarts total).
Bring to boil and add pasta. In a skillet over medium heat, cook
bacon until crisp. Drain on paper towel. Cut in small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Add hot pasta to dressing in salad bowl. Toss to coat. Cut
chicken into bite-size pieces and add to salad bowl along with
bacon, lettuce and tomato. Toss gently to mix. Serve at room
temperature or chill.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 647 calories, 39 grams protein, 33 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 47 grams carbohydrates, 101
milligrams cholesterol, 459 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Double Decker BLT
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When one stack won't do, try two. This double-decker version of
the classic BLT comes with a tasty condiment _ Garlic-Basil
Mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   1(16-ounce) French bread loaf
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   Garlic-Basil Mayonnaise (recipe, this page)
</P>
<P>
   8lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   4tomatoes, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   16 bacon slices, cooked
</P>
<P>
   Tomato slices
</P>
<P>
   Fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Cut bread into 12 slices. Coat 1 side of each slice with cooking
spray. Grill or toast coated sides until golden. Spread
Garlic-Basil Mayonnaise on untoasted side of each bread slice;
layer 4 slices with half of lettuce leaves, tomato slices and
bacon. Top each with a second bread slice, remaining lettuce
leaves, tomato slices and bacon. Top with remaining bread slices.
Garnish with tomato slices and parsley, if desired. _ From Southern
Living
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with Garlic-Basil Mayonnaise): 756 calories, 23
grams protein, 45 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 53), 66
grams carbohydrates, 49 milligrams cholesterol, 1,594 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without Garlic-Basil Mayonaise): 555 calories, 23
grams protein, 23 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 37), 65
grams carbohydrates, 32 milligrams cholesterol, 1,307 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Garlic-Basil
</P>
<P>
   Mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/2 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon chopped fresh or 1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients. Cover and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-tablespoon serving: 89 calories, 0 grams protein, 10 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 99), 0 grams carbohydrates, 7
milligrams cholesterol, 127 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Bread Salad With Bacon
</P>
<P>
   and Tomato
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-course servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   What a delicious way to give new life to stale bread! Grilling
it first adds a slightly smoky flavor, though if you're not
planning to fire up the grill, you wouldn't lose much by toasting
it. (Not surprisingly, this is adapted from a recipe from the Weber
grill folks.) Serve it as a main course or as a side dish at a
picnic buffet.
</P>
<P>
   6strips bacon
</P>
<P>
   Scant 2/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lemon
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Half loaf of day-old French bread, sliced lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2cups cherry tomatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   1small red onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   4cups mixed salad greens
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet over medium heat, fry bacon until crispy; transfer
to paper towels to drain. In a glass measuring cup, combine 2
tablespoons bacon fat and enough olive oil to make 2/3 cup.
</P>
<P>
   In a small mixing bowl, combine vinegar, lemon juice, mustard
and garlic. Whisk in olive oil/bacon fat mixture. Taste the
dressing and season with salt and pepper. Place bread in center of
cooking grate to toast. Be careful _ the bread will blacken
quickly. Cut the toasted bread into 1-inch cubes. In a large mixing
bowl, combine bread with all but about 1/4 cup of the dressing. Let
bread sit for 30 minutes. To serve, toss the bread with the
tomatoes, red onion and parsley. Spread the salad greens on a
serving platter, drizzle with reserved dressing and top with the
bread salad. Crumble reserved bacon on top of bread and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 561 calories, 11 grams protein, 41 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 66), 38 grams carbohydrates, 12
milligrams cholesterol, 605 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   BLT Canapes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 canapes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These delicious morsels are among the treats that Carol Parks
Caterering in Atlanta offers. They would be perfect starters for an
early-fall porch dinner.
</P>
<P>
   6to 8 slices dense white bread or brioche
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon basil pesto, drained of excess oil
</P>
<P>
   1piece romaine lettuce, rib only, chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   2pieces bacon, cooked crisp and chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   1or 2 Roma tomatoes, seeded, finely diced and drained
</P>
<P>
   Using a 1 1/2-inch round biscuit cutter, cut 2 or 3 circles from
each slice of bread to make 18 pieces. Discard trimmings and set
aside. Toast circles lightly. In a bowl, combine mayonnaise, pesto,
romaine, bacon and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon some onto each bread circle and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (1 canape): 38 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 5 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 74 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Green
</P>
<P>
   Tomato BLT
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 sandwich
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is Kudzu Cafe's popular interpretation of the classic. The
grilled green tomatoes are more sour than sweet, and the Boursin
Cheese Spread holds up well to the bold flavors.
</P>
<P>
   4strips hickory-smoked bacon
</P>
<P>
   3to 4 slices grilled green tomatoes, sliced 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2large slices whole-wheat bread, toasted
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons Boursin Cheese Spread (see recipe, this page)
</P>
<P>
   Leaf lettuce
</P>
<P>
   In large skillet over medium heat, cook bacon to desired
crispness and drain on paper towels. Drain most of the grease from
skillet and add tomato slices. Cook about 2 minutes per side until
lightly browned. Reserve slices on a plate. Spread each slice of
bread with 1 tablespoon cheese spread. Place tomatoes on one slice
of bread, then top with bacon, lettuce and remaining slice of
bread. Serve with pickle slice.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with 2 tablespoons cheese spread): 583 calories, 23
grams protein, 35 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 53), 45
grams carbohydrates, 79 milligrams cholesterol, 1,172 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Boursin Cheese Spread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2/3cup, enough for 4-6 sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2ounces Boursin cheese with garlic and herbs (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2ounces soft cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, mix Boursin cheese, cream cheese, cream, salt and
pepper until smooth. Set aside or cover and refrigerate until ready
to use. Refrigerate leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Boursin _ a brand of soft, spreadable cheese in a tub _ is
found in the gourmet cheese section of most grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1-tablespoon serving: 69 calories, 2 grams protein, 7 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 23), 0 grams carbohydrates, 23
milligrams cholesterol, 50 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   BLT (and O) Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Damon Lee Fowler's visits to the lunch counter for BLTs with his
grandmother inspired this creation. We love it because it includes
another Georgia favorite _ the Vidalia onion. Sweet, crunchy,
juicy, yummy.
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2cups 1/2-inch crusty bread cubes
</P>
<P>
   4medium ripe tomatoes, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1medium Vidalia or other sweet onion, cut in 2-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   8to 12 romaine lettuce leaves, washed, well-drained and torn in
bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon chopped fresh chives or parsley
</P>
<P>
   8slices bacon, fried crisp and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees with rack in upper position. Put
butter in a 9-by-13-by-2-inch pan and place in oven briefly to melt
butter. Add bread cubes and stir to coat with butter, then spread
cubes in a single layer. Bake for about 20 minutes, stirring
frequently, until bread is toasted. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, mix tomatoes, onion, lettuce, chives and bacon.
Add mayonnaise and toss to coat salad evenly. Add salt and pepper.
Place salad on individual plates and top with bread cubes. Serve
immediately. _ From ``Beans, Greens and Sweet Georgia Peaches'' by
Damon Lee Fowler (Broadway Books, $17.50)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 503 calories, 9 grams protein, 44 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 79), 19 grams carbohydrates,64
milligrams cholesterol, 577 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   BLT Pizza
</P>
<P>
   With Peppers
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We wanted to try our hand at a BLT pizza but found the lettuce
to be a bit of a problem. So we fudged, substituting other greens.
In this one, collards make the perfect bed for the bacon and
cheese. Collard greens on a pizza? Trust us and try it.
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1medium onion, halved and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2medium red bell pepper, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2medium yellow bell pepper, sliced
</P>
<P>
   8to 10 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon bacon drippings
</P>
<P>
   8cups chopped collard greens (about 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   110-inch pizza crust (prepared or homemade)
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups mozzarella cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1cup provolone cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Heat 2 tablespoons olive oil in a
skillet and saute onion, red pepper and yellow pepper until tender,
about 15 minutes. Fry the bacon in a skillet and let drain on a
paper towel. Save 1 tablespoon of the bacon drippings and combine
with 1 tablespoon olive oil in a Dutch oven or saute pan. Add the
chopped collard greens and saute until tender, about 20 minutes.
(Don't overcook.) Spread the tomato sauce on the pizza crust. Put
the collard greens on top of sauce, then layer the onions and
peppers, bacon and basil. Top with the shredded mozzarella and
provolone cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 20-25 minutes, until bubbly and browned. Let stand for
5 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 341 calories, 14 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 22 grams carbohydrates, 36
milligrams cholesterol, 625 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   HOLDING THIS RECIPE
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   BLT Pizza with Gorgonzola
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   I'll sound the salt alert right now. The bacon, the cheese and
the olives all have their share. But the overall flavors blend
nicely here and this is fairly quick to assemble. Again, we cheated
on the ``L'', using spinach instead of lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup mozarella, shredded
</P>
<P>
   110-inch pizza crust (prepared or homemade)
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup spinach, cleaned and torn in strips (about 1/2 pound)
</P>
<P>
   8to 10 slices of bacon, cooked and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   4Roma tomatoes, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup olives, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons or fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1cup gorgonzola cheese, broken into small chunks
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Sprinkle mozarella cheese on
prepared pizza crust. Then layer the spinach on top. Then sprinkle
with the bacon, tomatoes, olives and oregano. Sprinkle the
gorgonzola cheese over the top. Bake for 20-25 minutes, until
bubbly and browned. Let stand for 5 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 292 calories, 10 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 58), 20 grams carbohydrates, 26
milligrams cholesterol, 613 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
