<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BLT-COX     08-25 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BLT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classic combination is sandwich of the season when its
ingredients are in perfect balance
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, the best things come in threes.
</P>
<P>
   Curly, Larry and Moe were the trinity of slapstick comedy.
Peter, Paul and Mary sang in perfect three-part harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The supreme trio of summer has to be bacon, lettuce and tomato.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of another combination that really does the
trick like BLT,'' says Damon Lee Fowler, author of ``Beans, Greens
and Sweet Georgia Peaches'' and ``Classic Southern Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler remembers as a child getting dressed up in Sunday best
and going downtown with his grandmother to the Woolworth lunch
counter. While the crowd and conversation varied with each visit,
his lunch selection was always the same: the BLT.
</P>
<P>
   The trio has been the darling of the diner for decades because
it's so simple and inexpensive. And the diner tradition of creating
slang names for foods is probably how we came to know the sandwich
by its initials, according to John Mariani's ``Dictionary of
American Food and Drink.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to a good BLT, according to Fowler, is to have all three
ingredients in perfect balance. ``You want as much bacon as the
sandwich will hold, but it shouldn't overpower the tomato,'' he
advises.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that balance, let's break the triumvirate down:
</P>
<P>
   B: The bacon is the meat of the matter, providing not only
robust pork (usually) flavor but also a good shot of salt to the
formula.
</P>
<P>
   To get the lowdown on bacon, we turned to Sean Daniels,
organizer of Atlanta's annual Baconfest, which started as a reason
to have a party in college and now serves as a fund-raiser for
Dad's Garage Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that in the late '90s we can admit, without fear,
that there are people out there who love bacon,'' said Daniels,
noting they went through 170 pounds of bacon at this month's event.
``We served bacon in piles, where bars normally have bowls of
peanuts. And we had a place where folks can make their own BLTs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some like it crisp, some chewy. Some folks have a high tolerance
for fat; others want only lean, center-cut bacon. And that's just
the beginning of the choices out there: applewood-smoked,
hickory-smoked, maple-flavored, turkey, veggie, low-sodium and
precooked. (For comparisons, see our handy chart inside.)
</P>
<P>
   To bacon lovers, of course, many of the options are not an
option. ``Healthy bacon is an oxymoron,'' Fowler says, showing
particular disdain for low-sodium, which he said often has too much
sugar. Daniels calls veggie bacon ``facon'' and wouldn't allow
little at a time, and whisk until of spreading consistency.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Arrange one layer on a cake plate. Carefully peel
off the wax paper. Spread 2/3 of the marmalade over the top,
smoothing it into an even layer. Invert the remaining layer onto
the top of the first layer, peel off the wax paper and spoon the
remaining marmalade onto the center of it, leaving a 1 1/4-inch
border around the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Frost the sides and top border area with the frosting, leaving
the marmalade on top of the cake exposed. Or, if you prefer, frost
the entire cake, adding the marmalade as a garnish atop. Chill for
at least 2 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 581 calories, 6 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 84 grams carbohydrates, 149
milligrams cholesterol, 199 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from Victoria magazine
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to e-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
