<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP27-COX     08-25 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A really, really serious orange marmalade cake
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 27: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We weren't optimistic last month when Margarett Kinton of
Roswell, Georgia asked for the prize-winning orange marmalade cake
recipe referred to in Jan Karon's Mitford novels. They are, after
all, novels, and that presumably means the recipe would be
fictional, too.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. At about the same time, in its July edition, Victoria
magazine published a recipe it called ``Esther's Orange-Marmalade
Layer Cake.'' The magazine had commissioned Atlanta chef Scott
Peacock to create a cake in the fashion of the fiction. Many
readers saw the recipe and sent it along.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, others dug into their cookbooks and recipe boxes and
came up with a dozen marmalade cakes or breads. The chef-created
one given below is fairly complicated, so we'll follow it up with
one of the easier ones next week in the Mitford Cakes, Chapter 2.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Esther's
</P>
<P>
   Orange-Marmalade Layer Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   CAKE:
</P>
<P>
   3cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3large eggs, at room temperature, beaten lightly
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1cup buttermilk, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE SYRUP:
</P>
<P>
   1cup freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   FILLING:
</P>
<P>
   1cup orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   FROSTING:
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup well-chilled heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup well-chilled sour cream
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Butter two 9-inch
round cake pans and line them with parchment or wax paper. Butter
and flour the paper, shaking out the excess.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, sift the flour, baking soda and salt. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat butter with an electric mixer until
creamed. Add the sugar, a little at a time, and beat until light
and fluffy. Beat in the eggs, orange zest and vanilla. Beat in 1/3
of the dry ingredients, then 1/2 of the buttermilk, until combined
well. Add half the remaining dry ingredients, then the remaining
buttermilk and then the last of the dry ingredients, beating until
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the batter evenly into the pans, smoothing the surface.
Rap each pan on the counter to expel any air pockets or bubbles,
then place in the oven. Bake for 45 minutes or until a cake tester
inserted into the center comes out clean. Place pans on wire racks
to cool for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the orange syrup: In a bowl, stir together the orange juice
and sugar until sugar is dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   With a toothpick or wooden skewer, poke holes at 1/2-inch
intervals in the cake layers and spoon the syrup over each layer,
allowing the syrup to be completely absorbed before adding any
remaining syrup. Let layers cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: In a small saucepan set over moderate heat,
heat the marmalade until just melted. Let cool 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: In a bowl, whisk the heavy cream with the
sugar until it forms firm peaks. Add the sour cream, a little at a
time, and whisk until of spreading consistency.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Arrange one layer on a cake plate. Carefully peel
off the wax paper. Spread 2/3 of the marmalade over the top,
smoothing it into an even layer. Invert the remaining layer onto
the top of the first layer, peel off the wax paper and spoon the
remaining marmalade onto the center of it, leaving a 1 1/4-inch
border around the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Frost the sides and top border area with the frosting, leaving
the marmalade on top of the cake exposed. Or, if you prefer, frost
the entire cake, adding the marmalade as a garnish atop. Chill for
at least 2 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 581 calories, 6 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 84 grams carbohydrates, 149
milligrams cholesterol, 199 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from Victoria magazine
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to e-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
