u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-UNMARRIED-BOS &LR;      08-25 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-UNMARRIED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JAPANESE WOMEN, ATTITUDES CHANGE AT HOME, WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TOKYO -- Not long ago, unmarried women in Japan were referred
to only half-jokingly as ``Christmas Cake'' _ as in, no good after
their 25th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Even educated women were expected to get a job in order to find
a husband, and quit to rear children. Women who did have jobs
outside the home were still expected to carry the full burden of
housework.
</P>
<P>
   But like many attitudes in Japan, that is changing. A government
report released last month revealed that Japanese women are
marrying later (average age 26.6), staying single in record numbers
(5.1 percent), divorcing more (last year, 222,650), and having
fewer children, in large part because of a desire to pursue
careers. A record number _ 78.5 percent _ now want to continue
working after marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're coming out of a top university with the right degree
and qualifications, whether you're a man or a woman matters very
little today,'' said Mariko Fujiwara, research director at the
Hakuhodo Institute of Life and Living, a Tokyo think tank. ``If
anything, women are becoming more like men,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deepest recession in 23 years in Japan is helping to speed
that change. As more men lose jobs to the worst labor market since
World War II, more wives are re-entering or staying in the
workplace as a matter of economic necessity.
</P>
<P>
   The economic downturn is also paving the way for shifts in
attitudes among employers and voters frustrated with old ways of
doing business and running government. Executives are starting to
revise the traditional Japanese management model now that it is no
longer seen as infallible, and with that overhaul, traditional
prejudices against hiring women are diminishing.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, citizens fed up with old-style politics are
turning to new parties _ and women candidates _ as alternatives. In
July's Upper House parliamentary elections, the long-ruling and
male-dominated Liberal Democratic Party got trounced, while women
won almost one in every five seats _ a record.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, women remain a minority in office _ just 4.8
percent of the powerful Lower House _ far below most European
countries and even lower than the relatively paltry 12.6 percent of
women in the US House. Japan ranks 84th out of 179 nations in terms
of the number of women in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic advances for women have been in the workplace,
and in the way that values are changing to accommodate, or promote,
women pursuing careers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the number of Japanese working women has risen more
than 22 percent, according to the Ministry of Labor, with four of
every 10 workers female. Sixty-three percent of working-age women
are employed outside the home today. (In the United States the
figure is a little more than 70 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, because of societal pressures against women working
after marriage, only one in three women employees were married;
today, nearly 60 percent are.
</P>
<P>
   Age is perhaps the biggest factor in attitudes here, and the
more progressive views of the younger generation suggest that a
change that was long incremental will snowball. Numerous Japanese
twentysomethings interviewed for this report say they reject the
``samurai capitalism'' of their parents' era that forced men to
devote themselves to work and ignore family, while wives served at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Sayaka Iwai, 23, is a television reporter whose mother didn't
work and whose father worked so much that he hardly was at home.
Still, her parents encouraged her to pursue a high-powered career,
and both they and her boyfriend support her plans to work after
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   She loves her job, but is unsure if it will pay off with a happy
life. ``I'll never be sure if my choice is right. I could be posted
in Okinawa for a year, in Hokkaido for three years. What man will
want to marry me then?''
</P>
<P>
   There may be more than she thinks. Societal mores have shifted
dramatically this decade. In 1990, 43 percent of women and 34
percent of men disagreed with the statement that ``men should work
and women should stay at home,'' according to a survey by the prime
minister's office. Five years later, 54 percent of women and 40
percent of men rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Daisuke Nishikawa, 27, who works in personnel for a Japanese
trading company, says not only would he have no problem with his
wife working outside the home, but he thinks that ``raising
children and having families'' is just as important for men as a
successful career. ``Somebody has to take that role, and it doesn't
matter whether it's the husband or the wife,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nishikawa is by no means alone. Goro Hokari, 26, who works at an
advertising agency, said he wants to marry a career woman ``because
I work till midnight, so if my wife is only housekeeping, she may
feel alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariko Bando, 51, vice-governor of Saitama Prefecture and the
highest-ranking woman in local government, recalls years of
sleeping just three hours a night when she had children, a husband,
and a government career to nuture. She criticizes Japan's lifelong
seniority system that grants promotions based on years of service _
excluding women who take time off for families.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, she says the prolonged economic slump this
decade proves the traditional Japanese management model is
outmoded. ``People are valued not for their achievement, but for
how much they sacrifice their private lives,'' she said. That
``must change through drastic upheaval of the economic system.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujiwara adds that as Japanese firms lose business to other
countries, they realize they can't afford ``not to hire the best
and the brightest women.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies will also be forced to hire more women because Japan's
birthrate is so low and its population aging so rapidly that there
won't be enough men to fill all jobs. By 2007, the population will
start declining.
</P>
<P>
   The already low birthrate of 1.39 children per woman is expected
to dip even further as more women defer marriage and avoid having
children, because husbands don't help at home and employers don't
allow flexible schedules. Working wives spend 4.2 hours a day on
housework, while their working husbands spend only 21 minutes,
according to a government survey released last month.
</P>
<P>
   That has meant that until now, most women could only make it to
the top by sacrificing family life. Only 8.2 percent of Japanese
managers are women, compared with 43 percent in the United States.
Sixty percent of female managers here are unmarried and only 25
percent have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government should enact laws to help women, but they don't
because they are influenced by employers'' who prefer to hire women
at lower cost, said Ikuro Takagi, professor of social policy at
Japan Women's University.
</P>
<P>
   The average women's wage here is 63 percent of men's, compared
with the United States, where it is 80 percent. Women are not
unionized or politically organized, and that hasn't helped either.
</P>
<P>
   The 1985 Equal Opportunity Law recommended hiring without bias,
but imposed no penalties on employers who didn't. The law was
amended recently to ban discrimination and remove limits on women
working the same overtime hours as men, but there are still no
sanctions for noncompliance, said Jay Siegel, a lecturer at the
John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University who
specializes in Japanese workplace practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are bumping up against the bamboo ceiling,'' he said.
The old anti-discrimination law was ``a toothless tiger... and it
remains toothless'' with no penalties. In the 10 years after the
1985 law took effect, only 11 cases went to mediation under the
law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some landmark cases fought under different laws,
such as a ruling in which a municipal government was ordered to
reinstate a woman with back pay after firing her for refusing to
report to work early to serve tea 10 times a day, in addition to
her secretarial duties.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more importantly, more women are trying to have
both careers and families today and are finding men to cooperate.
``People of both sexes need to have options. That's the ideal
society,'' said personnel manager Nishikawa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
