<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MCGOVERN-2TAKES-AR     08-25 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MCGOVERN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICIA MCGOVERN DRIVEN TO DEFY NAYSAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was Patricia McGovern, outfitted in her Bermuda shorts,
sneakers, and baseball cap, running around in the wilds of North
Carolina. About a dozen women of all ages were there to test their
mettle as they rappelled down mountains, climbed ropes, crossed
rivers, and camped out in a steady rain.
</P>
<P>
   The Outward Bound program had one rule: No one could say what
she did for a living. By the end of eight days, it was McGovern _
with little to no camping experience but plenty of problem-solving
ability as former chairwoman of the Senate Ways and Means Committee
_ who had emerged as the undisputed leader of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned home, McGovern and her friend Wendie
Gershengorn were greeted by Gershengorn's husband, Ken, at Logan
Airport. The two women were exhausted. But McGovern, 57, was also
beaming triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked like she could turn around and start again,'' Ken
Gershengorn recalled. ``I've never seen her with a lack of energy
or enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McGovern's indomitable spirit is her hallmark. She went
to law school when few women did such a thing. She ran for the
state Senate against a Democratic incumbent when she was told she
would lose. (She won.) She became the first woman to chair the
budget-shaping Ways and Means Committee, and she helped steer
Massachusetts through its worst economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she is facing perhaps her greatest challenge of all in
the Democratic primary for governor. Naysayers have suggested that
she get out of the race. (She won't.) They say she got in too late,
can't raise enough money, and doesn't have the statewide
organization necessary to win.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern remains optimistic, another trademark. She says
predictions of a low turnout at the polls mean ``it's anybody's
guess who's going to win anything.'' She has $602,000 in cash on
hand, and she's hoping that an expected debate with John Silber,
head of the state Board of Education, ``could give me momentum or
spark.''
</P>
<P>
   In the event that she prevails in the primary Sept. 15,
McGovern's rich history of public service as a former state senator
may either haunt her or help her. To some, she was among the first
to warn of the economic storm about to pound Massachusetts in the
late '80s, and among the first to take the requisite action. To
others, she is a tax-happy liberal, unable to resist raising taxes
and levying new ones _ to the tune of about $2 billion dollars
during her tenure as chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I thought was right,'' McGovern says, comfortably
discussing her record. ``I really believed with all my heart in
what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Joe Walsh, the former Democratic senator from Dorchester, used to
call her ``the little girl from Lawrence'' on the floor of the
Senate chamber. McGovern took it as high praise, a term of
endearment from the old-time lawmakers she used to cajole into
doing this or that deal.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, few could have predicted McGovern would grow up not
only to join the most inside of men's clubs, but to help lead it.
Neither of her two sisters, Gayle Miller and Kathy Stella, was
driven academically or professionally the way that Patricia was.
And neither of McGovern's sisters had any interest in politics.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up in a triple-decker, working class and Irish
Catholic in a town where people knew each other well. Their father
was a health inspector for the city; their mother worked for the
Lawrence Housing Authority as a bookkeeper. There were no lawyer
role models in the family, and certainly no women lawyers. Two
uncles were politically active; one served three governors as
commissioner of labor and industries.
</P>
<P>
   She briefly showed interest in journalism, but soon McGovern
became hooked on Perry Mason and expressed a desire to study law,
Miller recalls. ``She was just very assertive from the moment she
was born,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern became the first in the family to complete college,
graduating from Suffolk University. She stayed there to receive her
law degree in 1966. And when her youngest sister considered ending
her formal education with high school, it was McGovern who urged
her on to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `You have to go, you have to get an education,'''
recalls Stella, a social worker. ``I'm glad I went to college. It
took me a while, but I made it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, who has never married, is ``Auntie Pat'' to her niece
and four nephews. She talks about them often, displays their
photographs around her North Andover home, and takes them on some
of her travels. When her niece was 11, McGovern took her along on a
trip to China. When a nephew reached eighth grade, she took him and
his sister to Paris and London.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that trip that Patti and Phillip Stella insisted on
visiting the rocker Jim Morrison's grave. Phillip urged McGovern to
hang back so as not to embarrass the teen-agers. But McGovern
wanted to see the grave, too, and pretended not to know them as she
inched forward in the queue of devotees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smell of pot through the air,'' she exclaims now, waving
her arms as if churning up the odor. ``It was amazing!''
</P>
<P>
   She describes herself as ``a funny duck,'' and wants people to
know she has a sense of humor. Showing off a silver-framed
photograph of herself, her niece, and her nephews with President
Clinton, she refers jokingly to the leader of the free world as
``Mr. DNA.'' She is a gin rummy addict and she treasures weekends
in New Hampshire on Webster Lake.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a rare eye condition that has left her with little
sight since birth, she has traveled on safari in Africa and hot-air
ballooning over the Serengeti Plain; double- and triple-checked the
fine print of multiple state budgets; and read voraciously over the
years. The only thing she can't do is drive.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m., before she's even had a cup of coffee, McGovern is
already moving rapidly throughout her colonial home, chattering
nonstop, as she is pressed to slow down and reflect on her
political career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  There was no particular issue or personal story that galvanized
Patricia McGovern and served as a catalyst for her arrival on the
political scene. But she knew she wanted in. Never mind that women
were rarely included in Massachusetts politics back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to run for office, all my life,'' she says,
describing herself as a creature of the Kennedy era, wanting to do
good. ``Government could be used in a positive way for social
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she always thought that if she ran, it would be for a
House seat. But eventually she settled on a target: state Senator
William X. Wall, a Democratic relic, in office for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, it was a lot to squinch up my courage and run
for office,'' says McGovern, who had so far spent her career
working as a public defender for juveniles and then running a state
criminal justice office.
</P>
<P>
   Though the party leaders tried to wave her away from Wall,
McGovern persisted. She won that race by 2,000 votes and arrived on
Beacon Hill in 1981 with an agenda favoring the environment,
education, and abortion rights, as well as economic development.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MCGOVERN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-25 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MCGOVERN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... economic development.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon after she was elected, McGovern found herself at the center
of national attention, assigned a task that would prove her
organizational abilities and propel her up the leadership ladder.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``60 Minutes'' had broadcast a gruesome story about the
murder of 9-year-old Arnold Zeleznik, and the failure of the
Commonwealth of Massachusetts to prevent his death. Vernal Walford
had been committed to Northampton State Hospital for 10 days in
1974 by a psychiatrist who called him ``the craziest man I ever
saw.'' An illegal alien from Jamaica, Walford was released 40 hours
after he was admitted, despite his hallucinations, screams, assault
on a nurse, and fights with two attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Three-and-a-half weeks later, he snatched Zeleznik from the
corridor of a Miami hotel and slit his throat.
</P>
<P>
   Carter Zeleznik, Arnold's father, wanted to know why someone
like Walford was out walking around free. He got no answers from
the Massachusetts Department of Mental Health.
</P>
<P>
   After the ``60 Minutes'' report, then-Senate President William
M. Bulger asked McGovern to chair a special commission to
investigate just what had gone wrong. In the glare of the national
spotlight, McGovern discovered that Walford had tried to turn
himself in to the Immigration and Naturalization Service just two
weeks before the murder, but was turned away.
</P>
<P>
   The committee ultimately concluded that the hospital was guilty
of gross institutional negligence and should never have released
Walford. It also found that an investigation by the state
Department of Mental Health was ``thoroughly deficient and
extremely misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's committee asked the Legislature to award the Zeleznik
family $50,000 in a public admission of error, and to establish the
Arnold Zeleznik Chair at the University of Massachusetts Medical
School in Worcester. Later, McGovern inserted language into the
budget to restructure the state's mental health system, following
the progress for years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, McGovern's political career was given
another boost. Bulger asked her to chair the Ways and Means
Committee, the panel responsible for writing the state's budget,
monitoring its economic health, and awarding lawmakers projects for
their districts. After the Senate president, the Ways and Means
chairman is the most important person in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were shocked when I was chosen,'' says McGovern, who
was still a relative newcomer to the crusty upper chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Her colleagues' shock was like a red-hot cattle prod as she
organized the committee and hired a staff, preparing to write her
first budget. ``You know everything you're going to do is going to
be looked at critically,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern thinks of herself as a problem-solver, a negotiator,
and a consensus-builder. She's also a policy wonk with a serious
penchant for fine print. And as she took over the committee, she
made sure to know every detail, dollar, and line in her budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Torres, her former staff director, remembers spending long
Saturday and Sunday sessions reviewing every one of the 1,300 line
items and every one of the line items' 14 subsidiary accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She literally digested the state budget,'' he remembers. ``She
knew every line of it in the first year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say that McGovern can get bogged down in details
_ a trait that might be more tolerable in a Ways and Means chairman
than in a governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fair comment,'' McGovern acknowledges. ``But I don't
think it's true now.''
</P>
<P>
   When she first took over, she says, ``I wanted to know every
detail and I wanted to know them all.'' Eventually, she realized
that what she was doing was not about the numbers, but about the
policy. ``In the end, I stopped worrying about the details, but I
knew the big picture,'' says McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   On the policy front, McGovern's tenure as chairman is perhaps
best remembered for her effort to provide universal health care to
every uninsured person in Massachusetts, assembling a fragile
coalition of hospitals, insurance companies, businesses, and
consumer groups. Though she pushed the legislation through, the
employer mandate _ the piece de resistance _ was never put into
place and the major component of the plan has gone largely
unrealized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work she did on universal health care was as important as
anything we did,'' says former governor Michael S. Dukakis. ``That
was Pat at her best. She just worked it and worked it and worked
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1989, McGovern began to notice signs of a faltering
economy. Dukakis had been off campaigning for president, uninvolved
in the state's affairs. Revenue was dwindling and certain programs
were costing more and more money.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern launched her war on the ``budget busters,'' reining in
the five items in the state budget that were on their way to
ballooning out of control: Medicaid, pensions and health insurance
for state workers, debt service, and the Massachusetts Bay Transit
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, she pushed to cut programs and raise taxes to deal
with the negative cash flow into the Treasury's coffers. Relations
with the Dukakis administration became strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found ourselves in the worst recession since the Great
Depression,'' McGovern remembers. ``Unemployment was in the double
digits. We had to cope with that or things would grow worse.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern began calling for tax increases. And soon after,
taxpayers were faced with a 15 percent hike in their income taxes
in 1989, a 10-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax increase in 1990, as
well as a new and unprecedented tax on services such as
long-distance phone calls, fitness center memberships, and legal
and financial work.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was determined to raise taxes,'' remembers Barbara
Anderson, co-director of Citizens for Limited Taxation and
Government. ``I thought that was a real problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pezzella, the deputy legislative director for Dukakis at
the time, sees it differently. His boss, the governor, had little
clout with the Legislature as he returned from a humiliating
defeat, Pezzella says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was the person who kept the state prudent and
fiscally sound,'' he says. ``She was the person who basically kept
the state together, more so than the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, McGovern is calling for tax cuts. Back then, she raised
taxes. ``I don't regret doing it,'' she says matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   If she has a regret, it is her previous enthusiasm for the
services tax, which caused an uproar among the law firms and mutual
fund businesses that populate the state. Former Governor William F.
Weld rescinded it as soon as he took office and before the tax
could take effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been much easier for my life if I hadn't gone
down that road. We were a little too cutting-edge,'' McGovern says
now. ``It was not right for the times, nor is it right for the
times now. It was not right for the economy. ... You learn from
experience and you go back and do things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, McGovern continued her work on the Ways and
Means Committee, attending to the needs of her colleagues and
addressing the issues of the day. Then, at the pinnacle of her
power, McGovern decided to give it all up. The decision shocked her
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she had tried to give herself a term limit as soon as
she got the job, writing down a deadline on a slip of paper. By the
time she left in 1992, she had surpassed the date she had set for
herself by two years. ``I wanted to stay through the fiscal
difficulties,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As she left, says McGovern, she thought about returning to
Beacon Hill, perhaps as treasurer, or maybe even as governor. After
a stint in private practice, she worked as a lobbyist for the firm
of Goulston &AMP; Storrs, which had clients such as Blue Cross and Blue
Shield and Malden Mills, and she served on several corporate
boards, including that of Massachusetts Electric Company.
</P>
<P>
   She says she still believes government can be a force for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the end game,'' she says of the primary
race's final days.
</P>
<P>
   And win or lose, there's always Rome. She's already planning a
trip with her niece and two of her nephews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
