<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PARODY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONG PARODY ONLY ADDS TO THE `MESS WITH BILL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He's lying low on Martha's Vineyard. The Republicans
want his head. He's political road kill on editorial pages from
coast to coast. And now one of President Clinton's diminishing
oases _ oldies radio _ has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   In a blistering parody of a tune that he doubtless thought very
cool as an undergraduate at Georgetown University in 1966 _ ``Don't
Mess with Bill'' _ the president is skewered with his own finely
cut versions of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   A week after his prime-time, nationally televised expiation
about a sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
S. Lewinsky, a doctored version of the old Marvelettes hit is the
hottest summertime song on WROR-FM in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the number-one requested song on the radio station
without any doubt,'' said Harry Nelson, the station's program
director. ``I hope things will get straightened out and the country
can get back to a more normal pace.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton struggles to achieve a personal form of domestic
tranquility, prepares his legal case for possible hearings in the
House, and attempts to relax during his island vacation, he finds
himself where no politician wants to be: the object of stinging
ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   The public's embrace of the song suggests that, a week after
Clinton's testimony before a grand jury in Washington, people still
simmer over his deceits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the `McLaughlin Group' or anything like that,'' said
Gordon McAdams, WROR's production director. ``We're the fun button.
That's our thing. And in this case it's at someone else's expense.
We certainly didn't open the door. We just rushed right through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Clinton's partly contrite, partly defiant address
to the nation, McAdams and Nelson spent seven hours in a radio
station editing room piecing together the president's own words
from its well-stocked audio archive of Clinton cuts over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The result? The Marvelettes song, about a jealous girlfriend,
that rose to 7th on pop charts 32 years ago, portrays the president
as a gleeful philanderer and the first lady as the oblivious woman
done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I misled people, including even my wife,'' Clinton is heard
saying from his confessional speech. To which the station has
spliced this out-of-context Hillary Rodham Clinton retort: ``At
this point, I don't pay much attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great,'' Nelson said. ``We've received a ton of
phone calls. We did it for a laugh and with no intention to be mean
to anybody. We were running out of jokes because they were being
recirculated. We were looking for something that was a little more
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   The song is played at least six times a day. ``We might slip it
in an extra time or two if the request lines start to get really,
really hot,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the radio station's signal can be heard as far
north as southern Maine, as far west as Worcester County, and as
far south as, well, Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yup, it comes in loud and clear down there,'' the program
director said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
