<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO SPLITSVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks of British dictionary makers as stuffy
conservatives has got another think coming, now that Oxford
University Press has put out its latest blockbuster, the New Oxford
Dictionary of English.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the contents of the dictionary that shock, though some
of its judgments will rattle conservatives' teeth. It's the
publicity that verges on shamelessness, showing that when it comes
to selling, overstatement is a lingua franca.
</P>
<P>
   NODE, as the new dictionary is acronymically called, is not yet
available in the United States. But according to the publisher's
press release, the new dictionary ``reveals that the battle to
prevent us splitting infinitives has been based on a fallacy all
along.'' The Star Trek slogan _ ``to boldly go where no man has
gone before'' _ is a standard English construction, the publishers
say, ``broadly accepted as both normal and useful.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this stop-the-presses hype is the verb
``reveal.''
</P>
<P>
   True, there are still many people who were taught that splitting
infinitives _ that is, inserting a word between the two parts of
the infinitive form of the verb, as in to boldly go _ is bad form.
In fact, though, the split infinitive has never been universally
condemned; it wasn't even noticed, let alone named, till the 19th
century. Some grammarians of the time condemned it, arguing that
split infinitives aren't used (in fact, they aren't possible) in
Greek and Latin, the ideal tongues of the educated classes.
</P>
<P>
   But 20th-century usage writers have consistently rejected this
analogy, pointing out that adverb placement in English is crucial
to the emphasis of a sentence. Here are a few of the usage arbiters
who scooped NODE on the news from Splitsville:
</P>
<P>
   ``The objection to the split infinitive has never had a rational
basis'' (Merriam-Webster, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   ``The split infinitive, in actuality, is another pedantic bogey,
carried over from the Latinate prescriptions of the nineteenth
century'' (William and Mary Morris, 1985).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every good literary craftsman splits his infinitives when the
sense demands it'' (George Bernard Shaw, quoted in Follett, 1966).
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that it is a grammatical mistake to place a word
between to and the simple form of a verb ... is responsible for a
great deal of bad writing'' (Evans and Evans, 1957).
</P>
<P>
   NODE does offer some newsy language tidbits. The most often
misspelled words in English, the editors found, are restaurateur,
rendered as restauranteur 20 percent of the time, and millennium,
which is missing an n one time in 10. Snuck is gaining on sneaked,
thanks to American casualness, and will soon be standard, they
predict. Perhaps most controversially, NODE's editors endorse they
in reference to a singular antecedent _ ``ask a friend if they
could help'' _ as a way of avoiding the clunkiness of he or she and
the sexism of he alone.
</P>
<P>
   But the split infinitive's respectability is not only old news,
it's old news published and republished by Oxford University Press
itself _ in perhaps the most famous usage guide of all, H.W.
Fowler's 1926 Modern English Usage.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler would have gone green around the gills at snuck in, but
he preferred infinitive-splitting to being ``ambiguous or
artificial''; and though he conceded that rewriting could eliminate
any split infinitive, he reserved to writers ``the right of
deciding in each case whether recasting is worth it.'' Surely the
Oxford University Press still owns a copy of Fowler, but apparently
it's not on the shelf at the publicity office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Life in Latin
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maud Chaplin of Wellesley College and William Neenan of Boston
College zipped off e-mails noting the Latin error in The Word's
Aug. 9 &UR;  &LR; headline, which used the phrase curriculum vita. ``The
correct form is curriculum vitae _ literally the `course or run of
life,''' wrote Neenan; without the genitive case, it becomes the
nonsensical course life. A fancy word for resume, curriculum vitae
is common in academia; it's often abbreviated c.v., which is easier
to spell and fits nicely into headlines, too. But it can also be
shortened to vita, or ``life'' _ ``His vita is filled with
second-rate publications'' _ and in that case the nominative is
correct. In fact, my dictionary calls vita an English word, while
curriculum vitae remains Latin. Life is strange, and language
sometimes more so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
