<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PREVIEW-DIARY-HNS &LR;      08-25 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEW-DIARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN'S `DESMOND PFEIFFER' PROMISES TO OFFEND EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' is one
of the most inclusive shows on television. It will anger everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the overall theme, which is basically the lighter
side of slavery. There is no truth to the rumor that UPN is
secretly working on a project tentatively titled: ``Holocaust: The
Merry Musical.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the humor of this show in which Pfeiffer, a black
English nobleman with his own (white) valet is indentured as a
butler/confidant in the Lincoln White House at the onset of the
Civil War. Pfeiffer is not a slave, per se, but it is made clear he
is not free to leave.
</P>
<P>
   So what fuels this half-hour comedy? Oh, the usual.
</P>
<P>
   Like a sexually frustrated Mary Lincoln. And Abe Lincoln making
gay and pedophilia overtures. Clinton sex gags. (Actually, those do
seem to be mandatory for all fall shows.) Racial put-downs? Why not
some incest jokes? Suuuuuuuure. They are all there.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is based in fact, of course, (and even in the show
the Abe Lincoln sexual remarks are made under the influence of
alcohol spiked with an aphrodisiac). And despite his subservient
station on the kitchen staff, Pfeiffer is clearly the smartest man
in the White House, an homage to Robert Guillaume's erudite
character Benson the butler on ``Soap.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while there is some contemporary political satire
involved in the period piece (Lincoln laughs off as absurd the
possibility of any president sleeping with a female staff member),
this show set its sights squarely, if not solely, on attacking
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desmond Pfeiffer,'' (the P is not silent, as the character
must remind everyone), may be the most politically incorrect sitcom
since ``Married ... with Children.'' Many critics have gleefully
panned it, stating it is merely offensive.
</P>
<P>
   This show is in fact not that bad especially by UPN standards
but hardly qualifies as quality television. So why am I futilely
rooting for the doomed ``Desmond Pfeiffer?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's look at what's going for it:
</P>
<P>
   _ It's not about some single twentysomethings living in New York
City apartments they couldn't afford even if they tripled their
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ In an age of network timidity the show tries to be different
and succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ It actually has some flashes of humor.
</P>
<P>
   _ No wacky neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   It's different. It may not work, but at least it earns a nod for
being apart from the standard, cookie-cutter, demographically
targeted yuppified pablum normally churned out by the network
conveyor belt.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering of television critics in Pasadena in July,
creator and executive producer Barry Fanaro was asked if this show
could have aired on any network other than UPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Not a chance. Not a prayer,'' he said. ``You would have
been laughed out of any other network, pitching this show.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Valentine, president and chief executive of UPN, told
critics he had sound reasoning for putting ``Pfeiffer'' on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about what show would (tick) you guys off the
most,'' he said. ``And the computer spit out that show and, you
know, we put it on.''
</P>
<P>
   In a more serious vein, Valentine added: ``There is room on
television for sometimes offensive, sometimes silly, sometimes
brilliant political satire. Our shows are kind of like pretty bland
compared to stuff like that. We wanted to try something and push
the envelope of comedy a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Chi McBride, late of the ``John Larroquette Show'' (he played
the janitor), stars as Pfeiffer. McBride has a message for anyone
who gets truly angry at the show, a group will undoubtedly include
fellow African Americans: Lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fine something to be offended about in everything,''
McBride said. ``That's why I don't play pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Pool? ``That's where the white ball chases the black ball off
the green table, which represents the Earth. See, that's why I like
bowling.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to ask: Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``The black ball knocks down the white pins with the red
necks,'' he said. ``I mean, c'mon man.''
</P>
<P>
   The show premieres Oct. 5. New shows on UPN are starting later
in the season than other networks. The sitcom is going to air
Mondays at 9 p.m. Eastern, against ``Monday Night Football,''
``Ally McBeal,'' ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' and ``Caroline in the
City.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any dispute over quality aside, the competition makes
``Pfeiffer'' roadkill before it even gets on the air.
</P>
<P>
   So what? UPN is last in a six-horse field of networks. (A
seventh one, Pax TV, joins the field come next Monday.) Why not
take chances?
</P>
<P>
   While fellow newcomer WB has been able to carve a strong niche
market with youths, UPN has struggled to find its core. Executives
have said instead of trying to be a ``narrowcaster'' targeting a
particular market, UPN will strive to be a broadcaster, meaning
putting on a variety of shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' certainly constitutes
variety, even if it will not have broad appeal. On that basis alone
it deserves our praise, even as we bury it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
