<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TITANIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SCORE FOR `TITANIC' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent full-page ad in Billboard trumpets the new ``Back to
Titanic'' as the ``most anticipated soundtrack sequel in history.''
Crass commercialism, right? If that's the slant, then you might as
well call it the ``Titanic'' cash-in, since its release is timed to
the ``Titanic'' home video, which is out Sept. 1 and has had
pre-orders of 22 million copies in the United States alone _ second
only to 30 million for ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the hype subsides, however, let it be said that the ``Back
to Titanic'' album is every bit as captivating as the first
soundtrack, which has sold a staggering 25 million copies
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The sequel comes out Tuesday (Aug. 25) and is going to be
drubbed by many cynics who feel the ``Titanic'' tentacles have gone
too far. I was ready to feel that way as well, but then heard the
record and was smitten again. All the raw emotionalism from the
original record surged back _ and, to the credit of ``Titanic''
composer James Horner, there's a lot of previously unreleased
material that helps flesh out the ``Titanic'' saga.
</P>
<P>
   Pop diva Celine Dion reappears with ``My Heart Will Go On,'' the
humongous hit destined to win song-of-the-year honors at the next
Grammy awards. This version, which includes interspersed dialogue
from Jack (Leonardo DiCaprio) and Rose (Kate Winslet), the
star-crossed lovers in the film, originally was only available to
radio programmers.
</P>
<P>
   But composer Horner has really outdone himself elsewhere. He has
fashioned two long suites _ the 19-minute ``Titanic Suite'' and
nearly 13-minute ``Epilogue: The Deep and Timeless Sea,'' which
take some of the original movie theme music and weave it around
previously unissued music that is stunning. The merging of a
classical viola section (of 22 players, versus the normal six or
eight), together with the ghostly, world-music strains of uillean
pipes and pennywhistle, lends a fresh, cathartic magic to the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   More of Norwegian singer Sissel's wordless, ambient vocals
course through the sequel. Included for the first time are the
lively Celtic dance tunes played when Jack and Kate attend a party
in the ship's third-class section. The collection of jigs and reels
is nimbly played by Celtic group Gaelic Storm.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights are a new version of the hymn ``Nearer My God
to Thee,'' played solo by ``Riverdance'' fiddler Eileen Ivers; and
a new version of ``Come Josephina in My Flying Machine,'' sung by
ethereal Irish chanteuse Maire Brennan of Clannad. The song was
popular during the ``Titanic'' era and was briefly sung by Jack to
Rose in the film.
</P>
<P>
   So cynics, take note: It may be easy to slam this sequel purely
on the grounds of ``Titanic'' overkill, but give it a serious
listen and you'll be impressed by how much new material is here.
The dramatic power of the music is too much to deny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
