<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it takes a designer with the stature of a Calvin Klein
to prove the obvious: There is nothing new in fashion anymore.
(itals)Everything(unitals) is recycled.
</P>
<P>
   Even clothes you thought you'd never see again, like the famous
1978 ``original'' Calvin Klein jeans, the skintight numbers Brooke
Shields put on the map.
</P>
<P>
   The originals are back in stores all right _ just in time for
school bells _ with their dark denim fabric, loop design on the
back pocket, and white and red label. The one key modernization
this time around is that they're looser (guess we're a fatter
population).
</P>
<P>
   But don't think that because Klein is pushing straight jeans
that the 1970s bell-bottom fad is over.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are two schools of thought on back-to-class
fashions this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It's still cool to go 1970s retro, with super-flared jeans and
platform shoes (or sneakers).
</P>
<P>
   But high school kids are embracing a new image as well, a
``cleaned-up, collegiate-school look,'' says Robert Rutkauskas,
Filene's fashion director. For girls, that means plaid pleated
skirts, crisp white shirts, and a cardigan, worn as an accessory.
It sounds private-schoolish, but kids make it chic with platform
shoes. ``It's almost like the uniform from years ago,'' says
Rutkauskas. ``All you need is an apple and a ruler and you're ready
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys are choosing a less conservative but still mainstream look:
khakis or cordoroy cargo pants and plaid shirts, worn open and
untucked, over a plain T-shirt. We've seen it on college kids and
now many high school students want to wear it too, rather than the
overalls and baggy jeans they wore last year.
</P>
<P>
   They're also continuing the athletic trend that started last
year: nylon sweat pants with white stripes down the sides. Instead
of a matching top, they're wearing ``hoodies,'' zip-up sweatshirts
with hoods.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)The(unitals) accessory this season is the messenger bag,
those square bags real messengers carry on their bikes. And of
course, pagers, cellular phones, laptop computers, and portable CD
players will be back on campus.
</P>
<P>
   MTV is hoping to capitalize on the electronic trend. It's now
offering a $69 MTV pager, which comes in colors like neon yellow
and is adorned with an MTV logo. Kids who buy the pager and
subscribe to an about $11 monthly service (from Nationwide Network
Services of Florida) will be paged twice a week. When they respond
to a toll-free number, they have the chance to win prizes, trips,
and (no surprise here) MTV merchandise and programming news.
</P>
<P>
   Even Calvin Klein has jumped on this. Kids who spend $55 on his
jeans can buy the pager for about $20. During September, network
users can win new clothes or a ticket to attend a Klein fashion
show in New York.
</P>
<P>
   So who knows? If you're lucky, maybe you won't have to actually
pay for too many ``original'' Calvins yourself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
