<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE-I-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     08-25 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-I-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... Boston University.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No one would believe it was true. There was tremendous denial
and pressure on us when investigating it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross rejects the justification of investigators who say they are
acting out of loyalty to fellow officers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a coverup,'' he said. ``What is the message you are
sending to junior officers when you cover up? We don't do this for
lawyers or insurance salesmen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Death remains a mystery
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Galvin's closest friends paid little attention to the
actions of investigators the night of her death. They were too
stunned by what had just happened.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-foot-2-inch bundle of energy, Galvin was unceasingly
cheerful and the first to offer a smile for a downcast colleague.
When she patrolled highways around Worcester, she was teased for
her South Boston accent and her frequent expressions of ``Southie
pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin was constantly busy, working full-time, attending school,
and baby sitting during off-hours for her sister's children. Even
with this hectic schedule, she found time to maintain an active
social life, often traveling to the Cape or Berkshires when not
working. It was not surprising that at the State Police academy,
Galvin was the best endurance runner in her class.
</P>
<P>
   Running was one of the few things that came easily to Galvin
when she attended the academy, friends say. Her small hands made
handling a gun difficult, and she constantly fretted over exams.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin would later tell friends she hoped to one day return to
the academy as a drill instructor.
</P>
<P>
   She was drawn to police work, friends say, by a simple desire to
help people. Galvin grew up only a block from the Old Colony
housing development, and was a member of one of the poorest
Catholic parishes in the city.
</P>
<P>
   She was a frequent volunteer at homeless shelters and elderly
housing complexes.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the police academy in 1992, Galvin was
assigned to highway patrol in central Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that her idealism gave way to the reality of
midnight shifts, office politics, and gruesome accident scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some things that bothered her,'' said Jane Kennedy,
an academy classmate and close friend of Galvin's. ``Anything
involving children bothered her. She had a lot of compassion for
people and didn't get any pleasure from arresting people. It could
bother her.''
</P>
<P>
   The night Galvin died began with a celebration, a fund-raiser
for the Boston Police Gaelic Column that had had the trooper
excited for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The tickets were relatively cheap _ $20 a person _ and the
fund-raiser, which was really more of a party for cops from many
different departments, was being held less than a mile from her
home at the Boston Teachers Union hall, just over the South Boston
line in Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin had a lot of friends who were Boston officers. One of her
best friends was a piper in the bagpipe unit. She told her State
Police colleagues that it was important to show support for the
unit, which frequently played at the funerals of officers from
other departments and only weeks earlier participated in the
service for Trooper Mark Charbonnier, who was gunned down during a
highway stop on Route 3 in Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called me and made me promise to set aside two tables for
her,'' said James Barry, the president of the Gaelic column and a
Boston police officer. ``We had a real good showing from the State
Police.''
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser, Galvin worked the room of 300 people. ``If I
knew 10 people at an event, she knew 100,'' said Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Futile efforts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But something was wrong with Galvin that night.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharacteristically, she began sobbing toward the end of the
evening. And then she said something to another female trooper that
alarmed her friends. No one will repeat what she said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about her well-being, another trooper drove Galvin to
her nearby home on the other side of Columbia Park.
</P>
<P>
   The same unidentified trooper also took Galvin's .9mm Sig Sauer
service weapon from her as a precaution, sources said, unaware that
she had another handgun at home. The friend stayed with Galvin for
a few minutes, but left after a smiling Galvin assured her she was
no longer upset.
</P>
<P>
   A carload of other troopers, meanwhile, was on its way to
Galvin's house. Their purpose was two-fold: They were worried about
their friend, and she had previously invited people to stop by
after the fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   As they drove, Kennedy called Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we were on our way over and I asked if everything was
all right,'' Kennedy said. ``She said she was fine. She was
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the troopers arrived, the door to Galvin's apartment was
locked. Kennedy ran down the street to Sullivan's, a bar Galvin
frequented. She wasn't there. At the same time, the other troopers
went upstairs to Galvin's sister's apartment and asked her to let
them in.
</P>
<P>
   The sister unlocked the door. Her screams led the troopers to
Galvin's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to be found,'' said a trooper at the home that
night. ``She invited her friends to the fund-raiser and to her
house later.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy agreed. ``She knew we were coming.''
</P>
<P>
   In the investigation of Catherine Galvin's death, the detective
writing the report for the Boston Police Department was careful to
note a gun cleaning kit was nearby. However, several people
interviewed by the Globe who were at Galvin's home that night said
it was obvious she was not cleaning the weapon. The cleaning kit
was nearby only because it was in the same box that stored the gun,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, the Gaelic column , whose fund-raiser Cathy
Galvin had helped make such a success, played the bagpipes at her
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A wall of silence
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who were at Galvin's home the night of the suicide
are not talking.
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk County assistant district attorney at the scene,
Mary Ames, is now in private practice, but said she would not
discuss the case without the approval of her former boss, Suffolk
District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II. Martin's office refused to
give her that permission.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Police Department also refused to allow the detective
who prepared the report of the incident to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor who performed the autopsy and labeled the death a
suicide agreed to discuss her findings, but was denied permission
to do so by her boss, Dr. Richard Evans, the state's chief medical
examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Galvin's friends on the State Police also declined to
talk about her death. Some said they were being pressured by other
classmates, the group of troopers who trained with Galvin at the
police academy, to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   For Jane Kennedy, who was one of Galvin's closest friends, it
doesn't matter what her death was labeled, only that her friend is
gone. Four years later, Kennedy is no closer to understanding what
her friend was thinking that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you,'' said Kennedy. ``Because you are on
the job, you are apart. It is hard to reach out to anyone else. The
culture can make it tough. I don't have as many civilian friends as
I once had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
