<HEADLINE>
POLICY SUICIDES RELY ON TOOLS OF GUNS, ALCOHOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
And when you watch a person die 
And hear a battered baby cry 
Then do you think that you can be 
All these things that you ask of me? 
 
THE POLICE OFFICER'S LIFE 
AUTHOR UNKNOWN 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Gary Windsor didn't leave a suicide note when he killed
himself in his police cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   His grieving widow searched their home for clues, for anything
that would help explain why the 28-year veteran of the Metro Dade
Police Department took his own life.
</P>
<P>
   All she discovered was an empty bottle of Absolut vodka hidden
in a backyard shed.
</P>
<P>
   The decorated officer was drunk when he shot himself in the head
with his department-issued 9mm Beretta handgun on March 4, 1997.
His blood alcohol level was three times the legal limit for
driving.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Windsor's suicide is a familiar one in the nation's
law enforcement ranks. Not only are police officers killing
themselves at a disturbing rate, but they accomplish it with
haunting uniformity: In nearly every case, the officer uses his or
her police-issued handgun, and alcohol is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Police veterans call alcohol ``an officer's worst friend,'' an
oft-used crutch for dealing with inexplicable violence on the
street and stress inside the station house.
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day policing, which calls for officers to do more in a
society that affords them less respect, and the old-school habit of
burying a bad day with a beer and a shot, can combine to deepen
depression. Depression can spiral into suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Today's officers are one and one half times more likely to
commit suicide than their predecessors only a decade ago, according
to John Violanti, a leading police suicide expert and former New
York state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   So many law enforcement officers are committing suicide that
Violanti calls the situation an epidemic in need of radical action
_ such as requiring officers to leave their guns at the station
after a shift.
</P>
<P>
   The roll of officers who have died by their own hand includes
those who worked in wealthy suburbs and rural towns as well as big
cities. Police suicide is as prevalent in Massachusetts as in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a 25-year veteran of the Holyoke Police Department
killed himself with his police handgun only days after being passed
over for a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, a sergeant on the Municipal Police Department,
which patrols city-owned properties in Boston, killed himself at a
Braintree cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, a Wilmington police officer shot himself in a
wooded area off the Massachusetts Turnpike. He was the second
Wilmington officer in five years to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an uncommon thing in our profession,'' said
Wilmington Police Chief Bobby N. Stewart. ``You see so much of it
over a career that it becomes an accepted way to go.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `You find releases'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Barry, a 10-year veteran of the Boston Police Department
and vice president of the patrolmen's union, can recount every
detail of the day eight years ago when he discovered a young woman
on the floor of a Huntington Avenue apartment.
</P>
<P>
   How it was a Sunday morning and he was drinking a cup of coffee
when he was approached by the woman's worried mother. How he found
the 19-year-old woman in her apartment, a knife sticking from her
chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see that room and the girl's face just as if it happened
yesterday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers recount similar stories from the job. For some,
it was shooting a violent suspect. For others, it was responding to
a gruesome accident scene or finding a dead child.
</P>
<P>
   These traumatic events often produce a common gut reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inclination is to go right over to Doyle's'' pub, Barry
said. ``It's not a war tale you go home and sit over Sunday dinner
and talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You find releases,'' he continued, ``whether it be a half a
case of beer or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Some turn to alcohol to remedy problems on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcoholism is a huge problem in the police community,'' said
Rory Gilbert, a psychologist who operates an eight-bed home for
alcoholic police officers in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Police work always has been difficult and subject to intense
stress. More than a hundred years ago, Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan penned
the famous line that ``a policeman's lot is not a happy one.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's police officers, however, have a job that is arguably
more difficult and stressful than at any time in history.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers encounter more violence and more dangerous
criminals, are given more responsibility and receive more scrutiny
than police officers just a generation ago, according to a 1997
report by the National Institute of Justice, the research arm of
the US Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Community policing, a concept that has swept the country, adds
to the tension by forcing police officers not only to enforce the
law, but to assume different roles, from social worker to referee
to minister to psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Television and the proliferation of videocameras, meanwhile,
have led to more scrutiny and the potential that almost any act
will be caught by an electronic eye and dissected by the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police work is getting more risky,'' said Violanti, who is a
professor at the Rochester Institute of Technology. ``The demands
on police officers have increased tremendously. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A common denominator'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In moments of personal anguish, police officers find themselves
in the company of a dangerous tool: the gun they are given by the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Guns are used in about 60 percent of all suicides among
Americans, according to the National Center for Injury Prevention
and Control. Police officers, according to research by Violanti,
use their guns to kill themselves 95 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The use of handguns is so prevalent in police suicides that
Violanti argues police agencies should require officers to leave
their guns at the station when their shift is finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would save lives,'' he said. ``If they have to go somewhere
to get a gun, they might change their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Violanti points to a study of London police, who are generally
unarmed, that found the suicide rate for officers was lower than
the rest of the population. He concedes, however, his proposal is
one that few police forces in the United States would seriously
consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police wouldn't like that because the gun is an integral part
of their being,'' he said. ``If you took the gun away, they will
tell you they would feel naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Police Sergeant Richard Ross, who studied the suicides of
the 12 fellow officers who killed themselves in the past 10 years,
said guns were used in every case _ and alcohol usually was a
factor as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol is a big-time factor, a common denominator,'' Ross
said. ``Alcohol is a crutch and key to social life in the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross became interested in the problem of police suicides after
some of his closest friends on the department took their own lives.
He was an usher in their weddings, and a pall bearer at their
funerals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE-II-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     08-25 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-II-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MIAMI: ... at their funerals.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I know a cop who very methodically left one round in his
semi-automatic, and wrote a beautiful note,'' Ross said. ``I'd
known him for 23 years and he shot himself in the chest. There were
a bunch of beer cans next to him. I was devastated when he killed
himself. I never saw it coming. He was the first cop I ever worked
with in 1970. I knew him very well. I thought, `How did I miss
it?''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucracy that can kill
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Douglas was disturbed by many of the things he saw on the
street during his 23-year career as a Baltimore Police officer. But
as he sat in his study at home one night, staring at the barrel of
his service handgun, it was not a grizzly murder scene or the
senseless shooting of a fellow officer that was gnawing at him.
</P>
<P>
   For Douglas, it was the realization that after 15 years on the
force, he was failing to realize his goal of moving through the
ranks and some day becoming chief. Douglas was still a patrolman
and felt victimized by an unfair promotional system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a hot shot, boy,'' he says now. ``I wanted to be a
police commissioner. But I had to wait five years just to take the
sergeant's exam and then affirmative action came in. It got worse,
not better. I got frustrated to the point where I got depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said his life was saved when his wife opened the door to
his study and asked what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas told his story to 120 police chaplains who came from
around the world to a conference in Duluth, Minn., last year. The
former officer is now a minister, and on a mission to stop police
officers in the United States from killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing 250 to 300 cops a year to suicide. It may be 500
a year, but we can document 250 to 300,'' Douglas told the
chaplains. ``There is a terrible, terrible problem with police
officers and suicide. This number is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   What is suprising about police suicides is how many stem from
frustrations like those experienced by Douglas. For many officers,
it is not the blood on the streets, but the politics and conflicts
in the station house that can make life miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband came home more screwed up with department problems
than with anything he ever encountered on the streets,'' the wife
of a police officer told a US Justice Department panel studying
police stress in 1997 .
</P>
<P>
   The perception of unfair promotional systems and arbitrary
disciplinary procedures, the rigid requirements of a military-like
hierarchy, midnight shifts, and long hours are just some of the
sources of stress cited by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   A 1981 FBI study of what makes police work stressful found that
being passed over for a promotion was more difficult for police
officers to deal with than pursuing an armed suspect or responding
to a hostage situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police departments are notorious for being not necessarily a
healthy place to work,'' said Sergeant William Garrison, who runs
the Metro Dade Police Department's wellness center in Miami.
``There are a lot of stresses and anxiety that go on
organizationally. Most police officers will tell you the pressure
doesn't come from street, but the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison works for the same police agency as Gary Windsor, the
Dade County police officer who killed himself last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before his death, Windsor was anxious about changes
in his unit. The senior officer was retiring, leaving the
51-year-old Windsor with the most seniority in the office.
Ordinarily that would mean a promotion for Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   But his supervisor warned him ``not to bank on getting'' the
job, according to Windsor's wife of 26 years, Natalie. The senior
man retired on a Friday. The following Monday and Tuesday, Windsor
called in sick to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he told me on Monday that he wasn't going in, I said to
him, `If you don't get that position, don't be all upset about
it,''' Natalie Windsor recalled. ``He said, `Don't worry about it,
Nat. I have it covered.'''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he drove his green and white cruiser to the edge
of a canal near his home, and shot himself in the head. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the line of duty?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Banuelos realized there was something different about her
husband's death when she was told the police department would not
provide a traditional gun salute at his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-year veteran of the Orange County Sheriff's Department
in southern California, Ernie Banuelos shot himself in his car in
March, 1997. Much of the traditional ceremony of police funerals
was missing from his service. The sheriff didn't even attend; a
spokesman said he was at a conference in Los Angeles at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Banuelos' colleagues wore black cloth over their badges
in tribute, but even that gesture was made over the objections of
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff's department did nothing for me,'' said Sylvia
Banuelos, who blamed her husband's death on his long-standing
frustration at being unable to win a promotion while junior
deputies he believed were less qualified rose above him.
</P>
<P>
   Although the reaction of police departments varies, many suicide
survivors quickly find themselves cut off from the law enforcement
community and the blue wall of support extended to the families of
police officers killed in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   An officer killed in the line of duty is praised for his work by
colleagues and public officials. The death of an officer by suicide
often goes unnoticed by the public, hidden from view because of
shame and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The families of officers killed in the line of duty are entitled
to a $100,000 federal payment, maximum pension benefits and
programs to pay for other expenses, including the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   For suicide survivors, there may be some pension benefits and
perhaps some money from life insurance, although some policies may
be voided if the death was a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits for police officers who kill themselves are so
meager that the Boston Police Patrolmen's Association is trying to
win approval of a special bill filed at the State House that would
provide $5,000 to the daughter of Jose Martinez, an officer who
killed himself in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, filed in 1995, is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Many families of police officers who commit suicide find
themselves angry, isolated, broke and stigmatized.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a law enforcement officer takes the oath and wears the
badge, you are told that you are part of a family for life,'' said
Sylvia Banuelos, who was left with four sons. ``There is no little
paragraph that says that if you take your own life that you are no
longer family, but that's the way it is because that is what
happened to my boys and me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an extensive support network for families of those
killed in the line of duty, but nothing similar for suicide
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The spouses of police suicide victims argue their husbands and
wives were killed in the line of duty; it's just that they were the
victims of the strains and conflicts of police work instead of a
violent criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Since her husband's suicide earlier this year, Natalie Windsor
has been dwelling on an incident in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was part of a team evicting people from an apartment
building. He was the first one in the building, and when he turned
inside the doorway, he saw a man pointing an Uzi automatic weapon
at him. Gary Windsor was not wearing a bulletproof vest. Before he
could draw his weapon, the man pulled the trigger. The weapon
misfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so sad,'' she said, ``is had I lost him eight or nine
years ago, he would have been considered a great American hero.
Now, he is remembered as the guy who committed suicide. It's sad,
because he gave so much time to the department, and on roll call
day his name won't be called.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
