<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNSOLVED-MURDER-BOS &LR;      08-25 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNSOLVED-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TEST MAY REVEAL IDENTITY OF THE `LADY OF THE DUNES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN, Mass. _ She had come to be known as ``the lady of
the dunes,'' her mystery a grisly slice of town lore still clinging
to memory at the tip of Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Her body was found in 1974 amid the green pines and dry sand at
Race Point Beach. Her skull was crushed, by someone evidently
intent on taking not just her life but her identity: The killer had
also cut off her hands, leaving no fingerprints and rendering her
forever anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, perhaps. After 24 years in which the victim's name
has remained as elusive as the killer's, police believe they may
finally have a means of confirming her identity.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a decade, they have speculated that the victim may
have been Rory Gene Kesinger, a woman with her own history of
run-ins with the law who had disappeared after escaping from jail
the year before the murder. Recently, they used a private
investigator to track down Kesinger's mother, in the hopes of
verifying whether the victim was her daughter, using DNA testing
unheard of when the case began.
</P>
<P>
   Provincetown Police Detective Warren Tobias, the lead
investigator on the case, would not talk about the latest
developments. ``There are people with feelings in their lives we
have to consider,'' Tobias said. ``Although the case is 24 years
old, it doesn't make it any less painful for the people involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But the private investigator, Phillip E. White Jr., confirmed he
had located Kesinger's mother, and that she agreed to submit to a
blood test that could link her DNA to the victim's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind,'' said White, ``the ultimate solution to this case
is at hand in the very foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman's badly decomposed body was found on July 26, 1974, by
a 13-year-old girl walking her dog. Pathologists thought she had
been dead for a few days, and blamed heat and dune flies for the
decomposition of her body.
</P>
<P>
   Police, searching for clues to the woman's identity, described
her to the media in detail: She was between 25 and 35 years old,
5-foot-6 to 5-foot-8, 140 to 150 pounds, with a long,
reddish-blonde ponytail. She had a size 34 waist, as shown by the
Wrangler jeans left folded beside her naked body. She had a blue
print bandana and was found lying on one side of her beach towel,
looking eerily as if she had been sharing it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their rich depiction, investigators had few clues to
chase. There was no sign of a struggle, leading police to believe
that the woman knew her attacker, and that she may even have been
killed somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   In a gruesome act, her killer tried to sever her head and
succeeded in cutting off her hands, replacing them with small piles
of pine needles gathered at the ends of her arms. Police believe
the mutilation was more crafty than perverse: The victim must have
had a criminal record, they reasoned, and her killer must have
feared that the fingerprints would pave an easy path for police to
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she was a poor innocent,'' Tobias added. ``I
think she was a bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rory Gene Kesinger, by police accounts, would have fit that
profile.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, she ran away from home _ police won't say where that home
was _ and already had a record in several states when she landed in
Massachusetts. She was allegedly a drug user involved in running
guns and drugs, tied in with bank-robbing accomplices, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was wanted all across the country at that time,'' said
Tobias.
</P>
<P>
   She was only 24, an attractive young woman, when Pembroke Police
Lieutenant Willard Boulter came upon her in January 1973. Boulter
was assisting Stoughton Police in delivering notice of a traffic
violation to a home in Pembroke, when Kesinger and several others
scurried out the back door into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   He caught Kesinger when she tripped and fell. The woman, wearing
only lingerie, claimed she had just been raped, but when Boulter
took her back to the house, she tried to steal his gun.
</P>
<P>
   He pushed her away and led her in the house, and as he called
for help, Kesinger turned off the lights and slipped into another
room. Boulter flicked on the lights to find Kesinger with a gun in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, but I have to kill you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He dove for her, pushed the gun to the side, threw her on the
floor, and handcuffed her. ``You would just not think that a
nice-looking girl like that would kill you in a heartbeat,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police took Kesinger to the hospital, where she ended up
stealing another officer's weapon. ``Die, you (expletive) pig,''
she hollered, aiming at the officer. Again, she was thwarted: He
flung up his hand and was able to keep the gun from firing.
</P>
<P>
   She was charged with two counts of assault with intent to murder
and sent to Plymouth County jail, said Sheriff Peter Forman.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't wait for trial. Sometime between the night of May 26,
1973, and the following morning, she escaped, using a hacksaw blade
that someone had smuggled into the jail for her. She went to the
window of the laundry room, tied together sheet after sheet, and
hacked the bar of the window until she could squeeze herself
through. Then she lowered herself to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Someone must have been waiting for her nearby in a car, Forman
said. She was never seen again, but her mark was indelible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old prison, which is still up, you can still see the
cut marks on the bars where she cut out,'' Forman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was back in 1989 that former police chief James Meads, who
had been dogging the case for 15 years, began theorizing that
Kesinger could be the lady of the dunes.
</P>
<P>
   By then, so many false starts had gone nowhere. There was an
armed robbery convict in a Maine prison who kept drawing women
without hands, but he died without offering insight. There was the
psychic who told Meads where to find the victim's hands, but the
tip led to a recently excavated site, its potential evidence swept
away. There were the people who would call Meads over the years,
reporting a missing daughter or niece who would later return.
</P>
<P>
   Police had little to go on; there was no DNA testing at the
time, so they had to rely on dental records.
</P>
<P>
   The victim had unusually expensive dental work _ $5,000 to
$7,000 worth of gold crowns. Police had distributed a description
to every dentist in Massachusetts, and contacted another 50 dental
societies, the FBI, the Canadian police, and Interpol for help.
They got nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found so many dentists had passed away or their records
were destroyed,'' Meads added. ``It was extremely frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he learned of Kesinger, who would have been 25 when she
disappeared from prison. Her photographs bore a remarkable
resemblance to a forensic artist's rendering of the victim, her
profile otherwise fit, and she had a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   For years, though, police have been unable to prove or disprove
that theory. After the latest hope of a DNA link was reported
recently in the Cape Cod Times, investigators have been
tightlipped, saying that they must confirm the victim fits the
general profile before pursuing a costly DNA test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process now is to go back and do some background,'' said
State Police Sergeant Richard Nagle, of the Cold Case Unit, where
the Provincetown murder is the oldest unsolved case.
</P>
<P>
   Before the DNA test, anthropologists are conducting a more
thorough analysis of the victim's remains to verify the age, sex,
and racial makeup. If the information proves consistent with
Kesinger's profile, police will move forward with a DNA test of the
mother. If not, the only real lead in a 24-year-old mystery may
vanish as completely as Kesinger did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor, unfortunate young lady,'' said Meads, the former
chief. ``We put her in the Catholic cemetery as the unknown female.
Maybe if there's some closure, she'll be able to be removed and
brought home someplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
