<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MARSHALS COULD LEARN A LESSON FROM THE LOCALS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The woman wants no more trouble than is
absolutely necessary, so I won't give you her name. But she has
been following this strange, disturbing business with Gary Evans.
She had a story for me.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Evans was the career criminal who'd confessed to five
murders and was facing either life imprisonment or the death
penalty. The district attorney was still mulling over which
alternative seemed more alluring when Evans took the decision out
of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Evans was being transported in a van by the
U.S. Marshals Service between a courtroom in Albany and his jail
cell. As the van crossed the Troy-Menands Bridge, some 60 feet
above the Hudson River, one or more of these three thoughts popped
into Gary Evans' tiny mind:
</P>
<P>
   _ I can escape.
</P>
<P>
   _ I can save the overburdened taxpayers a ton of money by
killing myself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Duh.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever thought motivated him at the moment, Evans sailed
through the van window onto the bridge roadway. He scrambled up off
the pavement and took a spectacular swan dive off the bridge and
into the Hudson. Unfortunately for Evans, he landed in what turned
out to be less than a foot of water.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of the body showed that Evans had a handcuff key
stuffed up his nose and some other metal gear stashed on his person
that might have been used in an escape attempt. All of which raised
some intriguing questions _ not the least of which was whether the
U.S. Marshals Service is composed of people who, by comparison,
make the late and utterly unlamented Gary Evans seem like a Rhodes
scholar.
</P>
<P>
   For example, why was a guy this deadly in the back seat of a van
all by himself? Why wasn't a screen covering the van window? Why
wasn't somebody with a gun watching Evans, up close and personal?
Finally, is this the way serial killers are always transported? Is
security always so shoddy?
</P>
<P>
   Local and state authorities say it isn't _ that they're much
more careful with evil guys like Evans than the U.S. marshals
apparently were that day. The problem is that we have to take their
word for that. Who would have guessed that the feds would have been
so slipshod with so grim a character as Gary Evans?
</P>
<P>
   To reassure you, I thought you might like to hear the story the
woman told me the other day: She said, ``I'm a spiritual adviser
for young men who are incarcerated. I'm currently dealing with two
young men who are down at Greene County Correctional. A few months
ago, their grandfather had passed away. And they were transported
from Greene County up to Syracuse to attend the wake for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you could have seen the security involved in that van.
There were two correctional officers in the front seat _ the driver
and a passenger. The boys were then behind them, shackled at the
feet, at the wrists. The wrist shackles were connected to the feet
shackles. And then there was a bar that went through not only the
shackles on the feet but also the handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind them, in the same van, was an armed correctional
officer. Now, these guys are doing four-to-12 on a possession and
sale charge _ certainly a lesser degree of crime than Evans.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Marshal David Demmit, who supervises the U.S.
Marshals Service in the Albany area, says that changes in the way
the service does business are likely. Just a thought, but they
might consider doing what the state corrections department was
doing with those drug dealers. They also could attach inmates to
the old ball and chain.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least a boat anchor or two.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
