<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ELEPHANTS-BOS &LR;      08-25 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ELEPHANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK AMONG THE ELEPHANTS: THEY'RE ALL EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SILENT THUNDER 
In the Presence of Elephants 
By Katy Payne 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 288 pp., Illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Katy Payne listens to elephants.
</P>
<P>
   An acoustic biologist at Cornell University, Payne had studied
whale songs for 20 years when she turned her attention from the
largest sea animals to the largest land animals.
</P>
<P>
   Interested in elephant calls, Payne visited the Metro Washington
Park Zoo in Portland, Ore., and unearthed something unexpected.
While spending time near the elephants, she experienced ``a kind of
thrill in the air.'' Remembering the same sensation from a pipe
organ playing in a chapel, she realized she was feeling what she
could not hear. It was a moment of scientific discovery. Payne
concluded that the animals may have been communicating at
frequencies far below the detection of human ears.
</P>
<P>
   And that would make sense. Infrasound's long waves can travel
huge distances and are less diminished than high sounds by
obstacles such as trees. Infrasound is employed by blue whales. If
elephants used it, it would explain something that had puzzled
field biologists for years _ how elephants are able to coordinate
movement, to organize ``silently,'' even when physically far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, Payne was back at the zoo, armed with
recording equipment and heading down a path of scientific inquiry.
The strength of ``Silent Thunder: In the Presence of Elephants'' is
that there are two journeys. One is an action-packed,
anecdote-rich, fact-filled research safari in which we camp out and
study elephants in Kenya, Namibia, and Zimbabwe. The other is a
sort of pilgrimage during which Payne weaves together her magical
farmland upbringing, a Quaker sensibility, the philosophy of the
Shona people she works with in Africa, and her own spiritual
leanings to form a philosophy of wise conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water tastes of the pipes,'' Payne quotes the Quakers as
saying, ``so you may as well know a few things about the pipes.''
Because no observer is indifferent, she says, she gives us the full
picture of her life.
</P>
<P>
   We come to love the human characters and elephants alike. The
stories of her mother, who ``played the piano modestly and loved
the music of Bach immodestly,'' mingle with those of elephants: the
big strong bull who holds out his tentlike ear to shade a younger
companion from the searing sun; the female so desperate to mother
another's calf that she uses her trunk to steal milk from the
lactating female's teats to daub on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Payne braves the dangers of Africa: She drives down dangerously
steep grades, gets caught in a wild moment of elephant pandemonium,
and spends a night holding still inside a sleeping bag in a
stare-down contest with a drooling lion called Yellow Mane.
</P>
<P>
   But she is driven by this exciting research, which is opening a
new door into the world of elephants. Her projects, using recorded
elephant infrasound to examine reactions in other elephants, and
also radio collars to try to determine whether communications are
between family members appear to confirm that elephants use
infrasound to communicate, particularly with those closest
genetically to them.
</P>
<P>
   But as with all great projects, this one has raised even more
questions about this complex phenomenon. Do elephants employ
infrasound more at the times of day when temperature and other
conditions make the sound waves travel farther _ something like our
long-distance rates going down after 5 p.m.? Is there an elephant
dictionary?
</P>
<P>
   There is still much to study. But amid all this, Payne learns
that several bull elephants from a group she studied in Kenya have
been killed by hunters when they crossed the Tanzanian border, and
that many of her test subjects have been culled in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what she does of the complex tapestry of elephant
society, the dependence of a group on its experienced matriarch,
and the large presence of elephants in the web of life, Payne makes
an emotional plea and a reasoned argument for new ways of elephant
management.
</P>
<P>
   The Shona people, whom Payne grows to know and love, have a
greeting that illustrates their philosophy: I am well if you are
well. Just like the author's recollection of her tight-knit family,
and like the Shona people who groaned in pain when she was injured
as though they had been struck, her memories of the elephants are
about the connections of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are memories of living elephants who were not dissected
into parts for analysis, but were so deeply a part of their larger
families, and the families so deeply a part of their societies, and
each society so fully embedded in its own land, and each land so
defined by the journeys and bonding calls of elephants, that
nothing less than the whole is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Next of Kin,'' Roger Fouts's deeply moving book about
chimpanzees, ``Silent Thunder'' challenges the reader to think
about these majestic animals in fresh ways by covering emotional
and philosophical terrain along with the scientific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1324EDT &QL; 
