<HEADLINE>
`AIR RAGE' NO LONGER TOLERATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   British Airways, a very civilized way to fly across the
Atlantic, is giving notice it will no longer tolerate ``air rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sept. 1, the airline is warning potential offenders
that they face arrest on landing unless they cease their
unacceptable behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown is triggered by a 400 percent rise in ``air rage''
incidents globally the last three years, and is specifically
targeted at drunk and abusive passengers and those breaking the
airline's worldwide smoking ban.
</P>
<P>
   While the airline said disruptive behavior is still rare among
the 40 million passengers who take 300,000 British Airways flights
every year, the company is standing firmly behind its cabin crews
in dealing with the problem. Last year, there were some 200
incidents, most related to the airline's smoking ban, a policy
British Airways said it has no plans to change.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also noted that disruptive passengers will be liable
for costs if the airline has to divert the flight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Foliage stays
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With foliage season just around the corner, less than a month
away, where to stay becomes an issue for many. Upcountry foliage
season always means lots of sold-out accommodations along popular
routes, so if you haven't booked a room at a favorite inn, try now.
The colors begin in northern Vermont, New Hampshire, and Maine
around mid-September and continue in southern New England almost to
November. Columbus Day weekend is traditionally the high point for
foliage and the busiest weekend for leaf viewing. The Globe's
Travel section will have a special foliage issue on Sept. 13. While
many accommodations will be sold out for foliage, lodging can still
be found through local chambers of commerce, and especially at ski
resorts throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Click for rewards
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a new way to earn frequent-flier miles on line: Just
shop. ClickRewards gives ClickPoints to consumers making purchases
from Web merchants such as Music Boulevard, SkyMall, 1-800-FLOWERS,
Broderbund, and others. And what are ClickPoints? They're a digital
currency, with each point worth one frequent-flier mile on any of
six major airlines. Netcentives, the company behind ClickRewards,
said its program also offers secure on-line transactions and
protects the privacy and security of consumers' information. In
additon to purchases, rewards are also provided to consumers
registering or taking surveys. Membership in ClickRewards is free,
and you can sign up at www.clickrewards.com. When it comes time to
spend the rewards, just go to the Spend ClickPoints section of the
Web site and the ClickPoints will be transferred to an airline
account or merchandise order.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Icelandair, once known as the ``Hippie Airline,'' has grown up,
marking its 50th birthday of service from America on Aug. 26. To
celebrate, Icelandair is offering all those calling to book a trip
to any of its destinations on Aug. 26-28 an immediate $50 discount.
The airline, which now has five US gateways, including Boston,
offers destinations in Scandinavia, the United Kingdom, and
continental Europe through its hub in Keflavik, Iceland. To get the
discount, call 800-223-5500 Monday through Friday between 8 a.m.
and 7 p.m. and Saturday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia Airlines is offering up to two stopovers on its flights
to Malaysia. The Stopover Program offers accommodations begining at
$11 a night, including breakfast, airport transfers, and taxes.
Tours are also available beginning at $8 and include jungle visits,
museums, and an orangutan rehabilitation center. For information,
call 800-552-9264.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet quiz by the Korea National Tourism Organization
offers a free trip to Korea. To enter, visit www.knto.or.kr and
answer a few questions (the answers can be found elsewhere on the
Web site). A winner is chosen every three months; 20 others receive
a Korean gift.
</P>
<P>
   A Tropical Breeze Getaway is being offered by 16 St. Croix
hotels and resorts through Dec. 15. Visitors will receive
discounted accommodations and a coupon book with $300 in savings
throughout the island. For information, call 800-524-2026.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Santa U opens
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finland, which claims to be the home of the Claus family, is
opening the world's first Santa Claus University this month. The
fact that standards for candidates may not be politically correct
has been defended by Nino de Prado, North American marketing
director of the Finnish Tourist Board, who said, ``The demand that
candidates be size-appropriate, age-appropriate, and sufficiently
multilingual to say at least `Ho, ho, ho' in all major languages,
is dictated by the dreams of children all over the world, not just
by the founders of the world's first university for Santas.'' The
university will be in Rovaniemi, capital of Finish Lapland and the
legendary namesake's hometown. For information on how to arrange a
one-on-one meeting with Santa in Lapland, call the Finnish Tourist
Board at 212-885-9700. Ask also about the opening Nov. 28 of
Santapark along the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meal deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The newest edition of ``America's Best Meal Deals,'' the Zagat
Survey's guide to great dining values in 35 cities, features 1,411
experiences that, according to Zagat, are ``somewhere between fine
dining and fast food.'' The average price of a meal in the book is
$10.11. ``Surveyors give these top-rated pizzerias, soup kitchens,
noodle joints, and the like credit for doing one thing supremely
well,'' says Tim Zagat. ``They offer a genuine peak dining
experience at a bottom-rung price.'' Among restaurants cited is
Boston's Brown Sugar Cafe, a ``tiny storefront'' Thai restaurant.
</P>
