<HEADLINE>
CAPETOWN, MASS.? AND PEPSI-COLA, FLA.? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel agents have been e-mailing tales like these to one
another:
</P>
<P>
   _A caller said she wanted to go to Capetown. The agent started
to explain about passport information when the caller interrupted
with, ``I'm not trying to make you look stupid, but Capetown is in
Massachusetts.'' Without trying to make her look stupid, the agent
explained, ``Cape Cod is in Massachusetts _ Capetown is in
Africa.'' Her response: Click.
</P>
<P>
   _A man phoned his agent to complain that he didn't know which
plane to get on. ``I was told my flight number is 823, but none of
these damn planes have numbers on them!''
</P>
<P>
   _A client asked, ``Would it be cheaper to fly to California and
then take the train to Hawaii?''
</P>
<P>
   _A woman wanted to know: ``Do airlines put your physical
description on your bag so they know whose luggage belongs to
who?'' ``No,'' the agent replied. ``Why?'' She said, ``Well, they
put a tag on my luggage that said FAT, and I'm overweight.'' She
was told the airline code for Fresno is FAT.
</P>
<P>
   _A woman said, ``I need to fly to Pepsi-Cola on one of those
computer planes.'' She was asked if she meant to fly to Pensacola
on a commuter plane. She said, ``Yes, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll have more travel agent tales next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  If it's noon Sunday as you cross the International
Date Line traveling west, what time does it become? (Answer at end
of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  There is a bed-and-breakfast inn in Newport, R.I.,
called the Artful Lodger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable &LR; : ``Why would I want to be president of the United States?
I'm the king of Disneyland!'' _ Walt Disney, when told he could
easily win the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel joke: &LR;  Wilbur Wright's wife had a question for her husband:
``You were only up in the air 12 minutes? How did our luggage end
up in Cleveland?'' (Told by Red Buttons aboard the Grand Princess
cruise ship.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Popular places:  &LR; The big surprise in a survey of popular summer
travel destinations is not that Walt Disney World tops the list but
that Central America is number 13. The complete ranking, in order,
according to the Carlson Wagonlit Travel Agent Poll: Walt Disney
World, Florida, Las Vegas, the Caribbean, Europe, Mexico, Hawaii,
Alaska, California, Canada, Disneyland, Branson, and Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A week to go: &LR;  The winner of our mystery photo contest will be
announced next Sunday. Entries must be received by Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Ole! &LR;  ``Muy Sabrosa,'' meaning ``Very Tasty,'' is a Southwestern
culinary celebration sponsored by the Inn on the Alameda in Santa
Fe. On various dates from November 1998 through February 1999,
Susan Curtis, a chef and founder-director of the Santa Fe School of
Cooking, will give 2 1/2-hour demonstrations. Participants also get
two nights at the Southwest-themed, 68-room hotel and the sumptuous
``Breakfast of Enchantment'' buffet, as well as a 20 percent
discount at a premier Santa Fe restaurant. The cost of the package
ranges from $135 to $175 per person. For more information or
reservations, call 800-289-2122 or 505-984-2121 or e-mail
info(AT)inn-alameda.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Snappy slogan: &LR;  A bar near Rome's fabled Trevi Fountain has a sign
in the window that advises, in English: ``Skip the Trevi, Have a
Bevi!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Moon over Hawaii: &LR;  A brew moon microbrewery is coming to heavenly
Hawaii this fall. The restaurant, with its its many varieties of
beer and ale, will be located in Honolulu's Ward Centre, a pleasant
enclave of shops and eateries. This will be the sixth restaurant
for the Massachusetts-based company. Pineapple-mango ale, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  It becomes noon Monday. (With thanks to Mike
Schuster of Foxborough, Mass. and MailBits.com.)
</P>
