<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MOROCCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING EACH OTHER'S SECRETS ON A TRIP TO MOROCCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV   AND DANIEL CUNNINGHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOLUBILIS, Morocco _ We're still speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Four days into our north African adventure, this doesn't
surprise us. But it's certain to amaze our friends back home. As a
sun the color of hot steel sets between the columns of these
ancient Roman ruins, we recall their worries and warnings and have
to laugh. After all, we are here as much to explore our new
relationship as we are to investigate the unfamiliar landscape.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, we have our first fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going on a trip right after I met my last
boyfriend,'' a female friend had volunteered when she heard of our
plans. ``That's how he became my last boyfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh wow, are you guys really that serious?'' a male friend had
asked. ``I'm not sure I could spend two weeks straight with my
wife, and she already knows every lousy thing about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Our parents wisely withheld comment, except to wish us luck.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are having what we hope is only a fatigue-induced fight _
over whose camera has the better timer and would best capture our
happiness on film. The spat ends in seconds, proving our friends
both wrong and right. We're still glad to have two weeks together
in Morocco; we're also aware for the first time that neither of us
has ever seen the other suffer from serious indigestion.
</P>
<P>
   The olives hit hard in the next town, Meknes. Or maybe it is the
daylong smorgasbord: the Moroccan equivalent of an almond milkshake
for breakfast, the Chicken Tangier and couscous for lunch, and the
afternoon snack of sesame paste and pistacchio nuts washed down
with a liter of Orange Crush _ an eating frenzy accompanied by the
smell of freshly slaughtered camel heads hanging in the market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh oh, I'm going to see Daniel throw up for the first time,''
I think as I grab the bag of green, black, and red olives from him.
Daniel hasn't traveled much, I have, and I can see stomach upset
coming from a mile away. He's going to have it something fierce.
I'm not sure I'm ready for this much closeness after just months of
dating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the first time I got down on my knees for Lynda it
would be to propose,'' I think as another wave of nausea sends me
to the regrettably thin-walled bathroom. ``If she stays with me
through this, she could stay with me through anything. Still, I
wait for an `I told you so' _ or, better yet, for her to get sick,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough we're back on the road, feeling better, looking
worse but hardly caring because our relationship has so obviously
deepened during the last few days. We have our very own inside joke
now. Unfortunately, it concerns vomit, but still it's ours. We
start putting it on postcards home.
</P>
<P>
   By Fez, the jokes are piling up, and we start to wonder what is
missing from our friends' relationships. We're smug with
self-satisfaction, hardly mentioning that one of us talks too much
first thing in the morning and that the other gets grumpy when she
doesn't get enough sleep even though she refuses to go to bed
before midnight. As we wander the mazelike medina, hunting for
rugs, sipping mint tea, mangling our limited Arabic, and fending
off would-be guides, we develop a rhythm so certain that it starts
to seem like we've known each other forever.
</P>
<P>
   We choose our roles carefully, and we stick to them. In a
variation of the good-cop, bad-cop routine, one of us is the
haggler, one of us pretends to hate shopping. By day's end, one of
us actually does. Actual entries from the separate travel journals
we are keeping as documentation of our idyll:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Today a rug merchant offered me a camel in trade for Lynda.
Apparently I'm more annoyed by her inability to choose a carpet
than the Moroccans. For a full 5 seconds, I wondered how I would
get a camel back to the states.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting tomorrow, I'm in charge of carrying the cash. Before
I grabbed the money belt today, Daniel was seriously negotiating
the price of one of those floor-length hooded outfits like Obi-Wan
Kenobi wore in Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day we decide to take a break from the pungent, often
unidentifiable aromas that fill the outdoor markets known as souks.
We've smelled henna by the handful and inhaled more donkey dung
than imaginable. We've seen the rooftops lined with drying leather
and the backstreets blossoming with fig necklaces for sale. Through
most of it we've managed to hold hands and our tongues. Now we need
a change of scenery and some fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   The guidebook makes Ain-leuh, a tiny Berber village set in a
lush green landscape, sound both romantic and easily reachable.
With gas station bathrooms tending toward the hole-in-the-floor
variety, the less time spent in the car the better. The drive takes
about two hours, and we pass it warding off the evil eye from
disappointed Moroccans standing on the roadside hoping for a ride.
According to local lore, the best way to do this is to extend one
arm, palm out, in the direction of the ill-will. As a backup, there
is always the chameleon trick. Toss one in the fire. If it pops,
you're safe. If not, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the hand works pretty well, too. We arrive in
Ain-leuh &UR;  &LR; on what turns out to be market day, but we don't care if
we miss the most amazing bargains. All we want is to walk and talk
and watch them watching us. The only Americans in town, we know we
stick out. Every time we touch _ sometimes out of necessity, so we
don't lose each other in the crowd, mostly out of affection _
schoolgirls giggle, women frown, and men leer. They're just
jealous, we think.
</P>
<P>
   The day is a perfect blend of warm weather, inviting country
air, and a soft blue sky. Berbers in traditional robes and turbans
keep a respectful distance but happily sit for photographs and
endure our attempts to question them in Arabic. ``How much does
that cost?'' can take two minutes to get across. The slow pace is a
pleasure after frantic Fez, and we hop on a stone fence, lean back
to back, and start writing and drawing in our diaries.
</P>
<P>
   The calm doesn't last long. One of us, entranced by the men
walking their sheep like wheelbarrows, wants to stay. One of us,
having had his fill of farm animals, wants to stick to a previously
determined schedule.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Never travel with someone who's only gone on bus tours of
Europe before,'' I think. What I say is, ``Daniel, honey, a
schedule is just a way of keeping track of the things you'll
inevitably miss.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Never go to farm country with someone who grew up in the
city,'' I think. What I say is, ``Lynda, honey, if you wanted to
look at wool, we could have stayed in Fez and spent the day
shopping for rugs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We trudge back to the car, a matchbox-size Peugeot that
redundantly has the word ``Jr.'' embossed on its side. We have too
much fun making fun of it to stay mad when we're inside. Plus, we
can't help smiling each time we pass a checkpoint and have to hand
our passports over to the Moroccan version of the highway patrol.
``Do you know Arnold Schwarzenegger?'' one officer asks. ``Brooke
Shields, a friend?'' asks another. We lie both times, saying lam,
or yes, and are waved through without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway to Fez, we see a stand covered in shiny shawls and
beaded blankets, rugs thrown out in welcome. One of us thinks, ``Oh
yeah, shopping opportunity.'' The other thinks, ``Oh no, shopping
opportunity.'' We're both wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The stand is a portable photography studio, specializing in the
sort of dress-up shots normally associated with Old Tucson Studios
or Western theme parks. Of course, in this case the cowboy hats are
felt fezzes, and the six-shooters are, instead, sabers. Parents pay
about $1 for portraits of their babies painted like little dolls.
Newlywed couples who can't afford personal photographers come by to
don traditional wedding garb and act out the big day for the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   We decide to be one of those couples, if only for an afternoon.
In the photos we take away with us, we are draped in robes and
scarves in colors we would never consider at home. We are wearing
headdresses. The glint from the spangles that are on every surface
is reflected in our eyes. We are looking at each other, and in that
instant we could be any of the other dusk-skinned couples who are
so certain they will stick it out that they record their commitment
for the cameras. We look like we are starting to &UR;  &LR; know each other's
secrets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PATRICIO-BOS &LR;      08-25 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PATRICIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING TO DO, AND ENJOYING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PATRICIO, N.M. _ Sometimes the perfect destination is a
place with nothing to do. There is very little going on in San
Patricio most days. Oh, the occasional polo game on the grassy
field across from the Wyeth-Hurd La Rinconada Gallery will break
the quiet. Sunday Mass. A card game at the Senior Citizens Center.
That's about it.
</P>
<P>
   A small river comes down through the valley here, the Rio
Ruidoso, the Noisy River. It's pretty quiet actually, but this is
so far south and east in New Mexico that any running water is rare.
A river strong enough to make a noise you can hear from a distance
would be very ruidoso indeed, and a pleasant sound, after you
crossed the dry plains that stretch away toward Roswell and off to
the Gulf of Mexico. The Rio Ruidoso doesn't get even to Roswell
before it sinks into the desert and disappears forever.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, if there's a river, there's a mountain to make it,
and the headwaters of the Ruidoso are up in the Mescalero Apache
Reservation on El Capitan mountain. (Most Southwest ranges have an
El Capitan, if there's one peak clearly higher and more
authoritative than any other.) They come up from Texas to Ruidoso
for cold air, horse races, and skiing in the winter. It is natural
air conditioning for the people of the plains.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurd Ranch (home base of the extended family of Hurds
married to Wyeths) has just gone into the guesthouse business,
having a few extra homes on the spread that they could make
available to the traveler. Two are down in the valley, set in
orchards and horse pastures along the Ruidoso, the third is halfway
up the hill with a fine view of absolutely nothing but rangeland,
cottonwoods along the river, and buzzards.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the most exciting thing that happens in San Patricio
on a regular basis is the convention of buzzards that return every
evening from scavenging on the plains down river. They come
silently, first one, then another, and suddenly, on a clear, fair,
evening, a turning gyre, a conical spiral, of wheeling buzzards
that doesn't literally fill the air but does punctuate the
darkening sky with black chevrons of descending birds.
</P>
<P>
   How odd that Hinckley, Ohio, has a buzzard festival, and San
Patricio doesn't. Of course, there isn't much to do in Hinckley,
and the buzzards do arrive on schedule every year on April 19, St.
Joseph's Day. Still, the buzzard roost in Hinckley is just a bunch
of trees a ways off in the distance across some farm fields. Why do
we admire the punctual wild thing, and ignore the more casual
buzzards of San Patricio, who hang around all year? They do return
to roost every day, but not by the clock. They come back when it
gets late enough to make them think about getting home before dark
and before the loss of daylight's sun-heated updrafts of air would
make them flap home instead of soar home.
</P>
<P>
   Plan for the day at the Hurd Ranch: Make breakfast, take a ride
down the highway, come back, crack a beer, light the barbecue
(mesquite and pine logs), watch the buzzards, eat dinner, go to bed
when it gets dark. You could live a long life with a Hurd Ranch
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you could drive to Roswell, less than an hour away, and
visit the UFO Museum and Research Center. It's recently opened in a
new star base on Main Street that's a former movie theater with an
Art Deco canopy that much predates, but eerily resembles, the
flying saucers that brought us the alien beings just after World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   They had the 50th anniversary of the Roswell Incident last
summer. A simple incident: A saucer crashed. Alien bodies were
examined and buried in secret. The government covered it up. You
can believe in flying saucers or you can believe in physics.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, shortly after the Roswell Incident, I had a
memorable high school science teacher whose motto was ``Faith in
Physics.'' He was fond of illustrating simple concepts in dramatic
ways. His best demonstration was of the principle of inertia. He
had a 20-pound lead weight hung on a strand of wire from the center
of the lecture room ceiling. One by one, we would sit in a chair on
one side of the room, the 20 pound weight would be brought to us,
we would press it against our foreheads and let it swing. Those who
could sit still in their chair as the weight returned from the far
wall toward our foreheads would get a passing mark, at minimum,
because we had faith in physics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the UFO Museum does center a small array of Alien Being
gift shops. I particularly liked Star Child, where they had
T-shirts with more humor and less preaching. The newest T-shirt
admonishes you to: ``Fly Alien Airlines, Only One Crash in Fifty
Years.'' I'll stick with Qantas.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Alien Beings, you can visit more plausible historical
sites within a few miles of the Hurd Ranch. Just around the corner
is Lincoln, brief and final home of Billy the Kid. The Lincoln
County Wars were all about cattle _ buying them, stealing them,
selling them to the Army post and the Apache Reservation. Billy the
Kid was a bit player who probably killed a few less people than he
boasted about, but enough to get him killed in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln is a particularly sedate little town, now, with art
galleries and a gourmet restaurant in the old Wortley Hotel. The
Wortley, once owned by Sheriff Pat Garrett (``The dirty little
coward,'' as the old song goes, ``who shot Mr. Howard, and laid our
poor Billy in his grave''), has the ultimate in amenities if you
are tired of the 20th century. Nothing in the rooms but period
furniture. No TV. No phone. Certainly no computer work station and
data line. You could have a good rest in the Wortley, which only
lacks a serious buzzard roost in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they haven't had a good gunfight in Lincoln
for almost a hundred years, which tends to disinterest the
buzzards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
