<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN MUSCLES IN ON LITTLE LEAGUERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's just give ESPN the benefit of the doubt, and say that the
cable sports giant, which arguably has become larger than
professional sports, is suffering from growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, no one would have cared what advertisements the
network ran.
</P>
<P>
   Not so today. Because ESPN owns significant pieces of television
rights to professional football, baseball, hockey, college sports,
X Games, fishing, beach volleyball _ did anyone mention
``SportsCenter''? _ what goes on their air matters.
</P>
<P>
   Beer is one thing, but muscle enhancers?
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's Little League playoff game between teams from
Jenison, Mich., and Greenville, N.C., ESPN ran a 30-second spot
bought by the makers of Creatine, an over-the-counter
muscle-builder.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Federal Drug Administration has approved its use as a
nutritional supplement, no one knows whether their are longterm ill
effects from Creatine, especially when to competitive athletes who
may use a variety of substances to improve their performances.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire, for instance, has acknowledged
using Creatine as well as a legal anabolic steroid called
Androstenedoine for the past year. To some, his use of such
substances diminishes his challenge to Roger Maris's home run
record.
</P>
<P>
   Is he live or the product of better chemistry?
</P>
<P>
   The use of Creatine remains an open question. The substance is
produced naturally in the liver and kidneys and is found in meat.
Some athletes call it ``muscle candy'' and argue that it is safer
than steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Creatine has exploded off the health store shelves.
Sales hit $30 million in 1995, $100 million in 1997, and are
expected to reach $180 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of powder.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the American College of Sports Medicine issued a
statement conceding that little was known about the long-term use
of Creatine, but in short-term studies, ``no negative side effects
have been documented in scientific literature.'' But the report
also stated that the ``verdict is still out on the safety of
Creatine supplementation, especially over long periods of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing anecdotal evidence, the ACSM and the American Dietetic
Association reported some health problems, including stomach
cramps, nausea, and higher blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Without any clear answers, individuals are left to make up their
own minds, and in that gray area, the airing of Creatine
commercials by ESPN amounts to tacit approval.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear. Airing the commercial during the Little
League World Series, presumably when young athletes are watching,
is pretty shameful.
</P>
<P>
   There's some money that is just not worth having, and while the
product is legal, showing sculpted bodies enhanced by Creatine is
not the way to encourage the young _ or old _ about sweat equity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hitting the roof
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The History Channel will have an interesting special on domed
stadiums Thursday from 10-11 p.m. The documentary begins with the
Houston Astrodome and runs through Toronto's SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Dietrich, supervising producer of ``Modern Marvels,'' said
one of the fascinating aspects of the Toronto stadium is its
retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based very loosely on the lobster shell,'' she said. ``If
you look at the different sections, like the lobster tail, one can
see how it hinges together.''
</P>
<P>
   The show details how the designers of Montreal's domed stadium
did not take into account the weight of snow, which caused its roof
to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Dietrich said that, to some, domed stadiums are shrines, almost
like cathedrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the true sports fans, these domed stadiums are every bit
important as Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Manly is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
