<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-25 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY UP FOR SOME LIGHT WORK AT MONMOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks as if Skip Away, the leading candidate to be Horse of
the Year, will have the closest thing possible to a walkover in
Sunday's $500,000 Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Park. As soon as it
was announced that Skip Away would carry 131 pounds, two
predictable things happened. Trainer Sonny Hine complained about
the weights, and all of Skip Away's legitimate opponents ran away
as fast as they could.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Skip Away was assigned just 1 more pound than he
carried to an easy, track-record victory in the Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk Downs May 30, Hine was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they're just trying to be fair,'' said Hine. ``I said
a long time ago, if you have the fastest car, they give you the
pole. They don't put lead weights on Michael Jordan. Horse racing
is the only sport that tries to get the big champions beat. But we
accept the weight. Sometimes, I question the spread, but I see what
the racing secretary is trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the connections of Silver Charm, Awesome Again, and
Frisk Me Now, the next three highweights, took the first bus out of
town. Bob Baffert, the master of the bob-and-weave who trains
Silver Charm, assigned 125 pounds, has no intention of taking on
Skip Away until he must. Pat Byrne, who trains Awesome Again, given
120, talked bravely until the weights came out; now it looks as if
he'll stay at Saratoga. And Bob Durso, whose Frisk Me Now was
assessed 118, will hold his charge out because of a cough.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, who has been beaten in his last two starts, worked
6 furlongs in a rapid 1:12 1/5 at Del Mar Sunday. However, Baffert
has not set a schedule for the big gray, who was 3-year-old
champion last year and won the $4 million Dubai World Cup this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea yet where I'm going to run him, but I'm
starting to get him cranked up again,'' said Baffert. ``This was a
really good move for him. He's starting to look a lot better, a lot
fitter. He's getting closer to a race. We might shoot for something
in September or October. I'm playing it by ear. He's coming around
and going forward and that's all I can ask. I'm not ruling out the
Breeders' Cup Classic (Nov. 7 at Churchill Downs) if I can get him
back into top form.''
</P>
<P>
   Awesome Again looked sensational winning the Whitney Handicap at
Saratoga Aug. 8, but Byrne feels an 11-pound weight concession from
Skip Away is not enough. It appears he will race instead in the
$300,000 Saratoga Breeders' Cup, run the same day as the Iselin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feeling is to go back to Saratoga because I know
the horse likes the track,'' said Byrne. ``But owner Frank Stronach
is in Austria, and he will make the final decision. We only got 11
pounds from Skip Away. I think we should have gotten 13 or 14, and
I told them that if we got that much, we would definitely come.''
</P>
<P>
   Frisk Me Now is a horse who has danced often, gliding from track
to track, but he'll be a wallflower for the Iselin, even though
he's based in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been coughing since he came back from Saratoga,'' said
Durso. ``I thought he was over it last week, but we had him out on
the track and he started coughing again when he came back. I'm
really disappointed about missing the Iselin. I had planned to give
him some time off but not right now. But I'll give him a rest and
point for the Meadowlands Cup (Oct. 16).''
</P>
<P>
   All of these maneuvers leave lightweights _ literally and
figuratively _ Testafly, at 114 pounds, and Stormin Fever, at 113,
as the main competition in the Iselin for last year's handicap
champion.
</P>
<P>
   So only accident or injury can stop Skip Away from winning his
sixth straight race of the year and remaining undefeated. After the
Iselin, though, come the Woodward Stakes (Sept. 19 at Belmont), the
Jockey Club Gold Cup (Oct. 10, also at Belmont), and the Breeders'
Cup Classic. Those are the races in which Skip Away must prove his
greatness. The Iselin, no matter how worried Sonny Hine claims to
be, is merely a public workout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A bust in 'Bama
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manistique, who won her first three races in California by a
combined 31 lengths, came into last Saturday's $250,000 Alabama
Stakes at Saratoga touted as perhaps the next Ruffian. Ruffian was
the great, undefeated 3-year-old filly who broke down in a match
race with Kentucky Derby winner Foolish Pleasure at Belmont in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   Bet down to 3-5 by the bedazzled New York crowd even though she
had never run the 1 1/4-mile Alabama distance, Manistique failed,
finishing third behind Banshee Breeze and Lu Ravi, although it was
not all her fault. The big daughter of 1990 Kentucky Derby winner
Unbridled, too large to race at age 2, displaced her palate during
the running of the race, something that was immediately noticed by
jockey Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``She relaxed well but then she started making funny noises,''
said Stevens immediately after he dismounted. ``I felt she
displaced something. She just started wilting underneath me. She
came home on class alone. My race was over at the three-eighths
pole. She has all the tools and the talents to do it. Something
went wrong today.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspicions of Stevens were confirmed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Monday``She displaced a little,'' said trainer John Shirreffs.
``Sometimes you can correct the problem with an equipment change,
like a figure-8 bit or a tongue tie; other times it requires
surgery. It's still too early to see which way we're going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Banshee Breeze, also a daughter of Unbridled, is a top filly who
was coming off of a win in the demanding 1 1/2-mile Coaching Club
American Oaks at Belmont. Ridden by Jerry Bailey, Banshee Breeze
won by 6 lengths in the time of 2:03 2/5 and returned $6.70 to win.
Banshee Breeze, who has won five of nine starts (9-5-1-2), is owned
by James Tafel and is the first important horse trainer Carl
Nafzger has had since Unbridled.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was strong at every point,'' said Bailey. ``We tucked in
behind Manistique and then Banshee Breeze really exploded at the
head of the stretch. I didn't have a lot to overcome at any time. I
had a lot of horse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been doing fantastic; I can't say enough about her,''
said Nafzger, who is pointing Banshee Breeze toward the Spinster at
Keeneland (Oct. 17), and then the Breeders' Cup Distaff. ``She's
just a really good filly. She'll close from anywhere. She's learned
to finish, she's matured. She does a lot of things like Unbridled.
They are a lot alike.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Down time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero, an import from Chile who ran a strong second to
Skip Away in both the MassCap and the Hollywood Gold Cup, will be
rested for the remainder of the year after running sixth in the
Pacific Classic at Del Mar Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Richard Mandella reported that the 4-year-old, who is a
stout closer, was stiff and sore after the Pacific Classic and may
have wrenched his back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was
used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
