   Minutes before the announcement, I happened to walk in to the
American Express bank and cashed a U.S. check in order to pay my
telephone bill and other work expenses. They handed over $1,000 in
rubles and $2,000 in U.S. currency without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, the government devalued the ruble. Twenty
minutes later, an American colleague went to AmEx to pick up $8,000
wired to him by his editors. All banking services were closed. He
is still waiting for his money.
</P>
<P>
   Well-salaried expatriates are cash-starved. An American woman in
search of a working ATM posted a message on a computerized bulletin
board last week. Where can I go to get dollars, she asked. Someone
replied: Try the corner of 52nd and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   It is no joke. Some Americans are contemplating trips to
Helsinki or Warsaw simply to get dollars wired from America and
bring them back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   As for Russians, most of whom receive their pay in rubles, they
spend what they need to survive and convert the rest to dollars as
a form of cookie-jar savings account.
</P>
<P>
   That's why there are almost as many currency-exchange booths in
Russia as there are places to buy vodka, in other words, on just
about every other street corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar is in fact our national currency,'' quipped the
newspaper Sevodnya about last week's ruble devaluation, ``so let it
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the ruble dropping, the price of dollars is going up.
Nervous banks and people are hoarding. Large Western companies
doing business in Russia are getting their dollars for now, but
they fear their corporate wire-transfers eventually could be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Komsomolskaya Pravda newspaper offered a clip-and-save guide for
Russians to cope with the crisis, including tips such as: if you
were waiting to buy that TV or fridge, do it now. And don't
needlessly rush to exchange rubles for dollars as that will only
weaken rubles further.
</P>
<P>
   The advice concluded: ``If your savings are in a strong, hard
currency, you have just wasted your time reading this list.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
