<SLUG> BC-DC-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON SECURITY SIGNALS RISING US WARINESS OF TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Security measures have tightened so considerably in
the nation's capital that tourists and area residents are taking
the threat of a terrorist attack seriously in a way they never have
before.
</P>
<P>
   At the Washington Monument, where concrete barriers, more
police, and a new security checkpoint were added this weekend,
Kenny Horseman admitted he felt afraid, especially when his
10-year-old daughter Abby asked if she was going to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to convince her she would be OK,'' said Horseman, a
registered nurse from Herlock, Md. ``It makes you wonder if they
are going to get us, and it makes you worry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared we'd be bombed,'' said Abby, with an embarrassed
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Since last week's US missile attack on an alleged terrorist
network in Afghanistan and Sudan, which followed twin bombings on
Aug. 7 at US embassies in Africa, fear for basic personal safety is
creeping into the psyche of some visitors, who have long taken
America's geographic isolation as a guarantee of security.
</P>
<P>
   From Union Station and the National Museum of American History
to the Capitol building, more police, more barriers, and more gates
were added as protective measures.
</P>
<P>
   Other monuments, including the Jefferson Memorial, were also
barricaded to prevent a vehicle with explosives from coming within
striking distance. In high-risk areas like CIA headquarters, a
mobile command unit the size of a truck roamed the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Security has been tightened at places like the CIA, the State
Department, and the Pentagon in the wake of the strikes, as the FBI
has sent warnings to all law enforcement agencies, and airports
around the nation took added precautions.
</P>
<P>
   It is slowly dawning on people here that the first salvos in
this war on terrorism may not be the last and the uncertainty of
waging a battle with no clear targets and no clear end seems to be
provoking anxiety, especially among children.
</P>
<P>
   Another fear articulated by psychologists and sociologists is
that this country could become another Ireland or Israel, where
people learn to live with a constant threat of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really jolts Americans because we've been immune to the
day-to-day psychological vigilance that other countries have
adopted,'' said Robert Butterworth, a Los Angeles psychologist who
specializes in trauma and examined the Gulf War's affect on
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's worse for kids, who either exaggerate the threat or
deny it completely and ignore reality,'' he said. ``My son, for
example, asked me the other day if a package that arrived in the
mail had a bomb in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials acknowledged that last week's decision
to launch the air strikes courted the danger of possible reprisals.
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright warned that what ``is very
important for the American people to understand is that there may
in fact be retaliatory actions. We are very concerned about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the embassy bombings, Osama bin Laden, the wealthy
Saudi believed to be the mastermind behind those attacks, had
announced: ``We do not differentiate between those dressed in
military uniforms and civilians; they are all targets in this
fatwa.''
</P>
<P>
   And people, who last week had no idea what ``fatwa,'' a death
edict, meant, now appear to be paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things feel out of control, but you can't live in constant
fear,'' said Ream Hasan, a mother and part-time teacher in Fairfax,
Va., touring the Washington Monument. ``These people want to stifle
your sense of security, but if you let them, they've won.''
</P>
<P>
   Another tourist, Mike Cahoon, a roofer from Manchester, N.H.,
said, ``I'm thinking retaliation. Hit and you get hit back. It
could be anybody, anytime. It could be somebody walks by you, and
boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahoon, however, said he doubted terrorists would reach into his
corner of New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to do, blow up the granite? They'll hit
here, New York, or California.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaz Jadallah, a physician visiting from Lansing, Mich., simply
said: ``I'm not afraid, just more aware.''
</P>
<P>
   Rona Fields, a Washington-area psychologist and author of
several books on terrorist organizations, who has studied violent
groups such as the Khmer Rouge, said a slow psychological
transformation is under way in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike some of the previous fear syndromes that have
circulated through the populace, this is based in reality,'' said
Fields. ``We're not talking about a neurotic anxiety, but a
response to warnings and the need to mobilize security.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields added: ``These are people who see men, women, and
children as symbolic targets to be snuffed out. Members of
organizations committed to symbolic goals, like bin Laden's total
destruction of the US and everything it represents, are not at all
afraid of taking risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Several experts said education and preparation are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give people an expectation that there will be reprisals
and you heighten awareness, then there won't be a shock when
something occurs, and that minimizes fear,'' said a government
behavioral scientist, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
