<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE GOES BACK TO THE DRAWING BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe's preseason efforts to master Ernie Zampese's
Swiss-watch offense reminds me of watching Rich Gedman and friends
trying to hit under the tutelage of Red Sox hitting coach Walter
Hriniak in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hriniak was a relentless worker and perfectionist who
recommended (some would say insisted) that hitters swing level
(some would say downward) and release their top hand from the bat
after passing through the hitting zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Hriniak style was awkward. Sox batters sometimes appeared to
be chopping wood. But it made Dwight Evans an offensive star in the
second half of his career, and the Sox annually led the league in
batting when Walter worked the cage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some players never succeeded with the technique and had
to junk it. Who can forget the sight of rookie Mike Greenwell
taking one-handed cuts at curveballs in the dirt during the 1986
World Series? Ellis Burks took the simple route and rejected the
theory from the start.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was poor Gedman, who had his career aborted
because he insisted on sticking with something that didn't work.
Initially, the Hriniak system was magic for Gedman. He hit the ball
as hard as any major leaguer when he was a two-time All-Star. But
then he slumped, and never got his swing back. The harder Gedman
tried, the more he struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it looks bad a lot of times,'' Gedman would say. ``But
when you do it right, it's the best way to hit. It works great.''
</P>
<P>
   So now we have the enormously gifted Bledsoe trying to learn the
Zampese system in five exhibition games. Folks in Dallas will tell
you that Troy Aikman struggled to learn the system, hated it at
first, but eventaully found a comfortable groove.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe's performance in Washington Saturday night showed
progress (15 for 26, 153 yards, including one play of 47 yards),
but he still missed badly on a couple of throws, including a sure
touchdown when Terry Glenn faked veteran cornerback Cris Dishman
into the Potomac River. The same thing happened against the Vikings
when Bledsoe overthrew a wide-open Vincent Brisby. Patriot fans are
not a patient lot, and those kinds of mistakes won't fly once the
season starts in (gulp) Denver on Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has not thrown a touchdown pass in any of the four
exhibition games. Does this bother anyone? It's seems like 10 years
ago, but just last summer Bledsoe threw eight touchdown passes (to
eight different receivers) in the first two regular-season games.
It was then that owner Bob Kraft spoke of Drew being more
``comfortable'' playing for Pete Carroll rather than Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of last season, it looked like New England would
have a monster air attack into the next century. But the Patriots'
passing game has eroded, and even though Bledsoe is in his
(itals)sixth(unitals) season, we're watching him take baby steps
again as he learns a new system.
</P>
<P>
   In four exhibition games, Bledsoe is 34 of 64 for 319 yards, no
touchdowns, and two interceptions. He has been accurate on sideline
passes and throws over the middle but can't connect on the long
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe hasn't made excuses about the overthrows. He never does.
He said he's made poor throws and that he has to do a better job.
On the Glenn overthrow, he actually pulled the trigger too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi said it's tough to hit and think at the same time, which is
precisely why Bledsoe won't be able to faithfully execute the new
offense until he's able to stop thinking so much.
</P>
<P>
   Watching QB-11 in these games makes me long for the days of the
hurry-up offense and ``everybody go long.'' Hasn't Bledsoe always
been most effective when he's working out of the no-huddle, calling
his own plays? Was there ever a better day than Nov. 13, 1994, when
he went 45 of 70 for 426 yards and three touchdowns in a
second-half comeback win against the Vikings?
</P>
<P>
   The guy is a natural quarterback, just as Gedman was a natural
hitter. But now he's working on the timing-oriented offense,
missing Glenn by 15 feet and getting the ball to his receivers too
late.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the ball too long is brave, but it's deadly in a Zampese
offense. And if the Patriots fail to establish a running game,
Bledsoe is going to spend a lot of time picking himself up off the
ground and pulling pieces of turf out of his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember what Geddy said. When you do it right, it works
great.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
