<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANTY TURNS THE CORNER AFTER A SEASON OF ROOKIE MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Chris Canty can smile and joke about it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more doughnuts,'' he said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   No sir. Canty used to leave a little time in the morning to pick
up a dozen doughnuts at the local coffee shop for the defensive
backs at the morning meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Those duties are over. Canty apparently has arrived. Respect is
finally his.
</P>
<P>
   After a season of being called too short, too slow, too cocky,
too cool, too this, and too that, Canty got the message. He left
behind his Kansas State swagger for life in the big leagues. With
that comes responsibilities and maturity. Canty, a No. 1 draft pick
in 1997 (the 29th player taken), had to take it one step further
this season. He had to go from washout to starter at right
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe he has pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   Being insulted in the media probably helped. Also motivating him
was the team's drafting of a projected cornerback in the first
round this year. Tebucky Jones might have been Canty's biggest
incentive to get his act together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helped me a little bit,'' said Canty. ``Last year
everybody was on my back, I was the washout player of the year. It
was great to come in and get better. Drafting Tebucky told me,
`You've got to pick up your play.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want competition. There was a lot of competition at
that position in training camp and in the preseason and I just
wanted to step up and prove that I could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest thing: You always want to prove people
wrong and win the respect of your teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   He apparently has done that. Coach Pete Carroll, an expert on
defensive backs, says nothing but good things about the cornerback
now. Canty's last two games have been very good. Each week, he
seems to rise in status. He has taken no steps backward, but then
again, the regular season has not begun.
</P>
<P>
   When the games are for real, quarterbacks are going to try to
beat Canty deep every week. It's been done to every Patriot
cornerback who has played the right side since Ty Law came into the
league four years ago. Ask Jimmy Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the confidence factor,'' said Canty. ``If you can go
out there and feel like you can cover anybody and have the
confidence and the skills and knowhow to do it, it's going to get
done. It's a just a matter of executing _ go out and take care of
the deep ball and make some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems to mean it now. He admittedly walked onto this team
last year and acted as if he could rest on his collegiate laurels.
As Robert Edwards and Jones have found out, there's a big
difference between being a conditioned athlete in a big-time
college program and being one at the pro level. The body is
stretched to incredible limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard coming in as a No. 1,'' said Canty. ``You have a lot
of factors that you have to get used to. You have to deal with the
media, you have to deal with financial aspects, and you have to
deal with the football at the pro level. Once you go through it,
man, you see how hard it is and try to get used to everything. It
took me a year to adjust. I know what I want to do and I've set my
goals. Last year I set goals but they weren't anything to write
home about. This year, I'm really going to push myself to get those
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of pressures as a No. 1 pick. If you're not
able to handle them, they can get to you early. You can fall into a
rookie rut where you want to go home and be with your mom and those
types of things. You have to fight through it. It was tough and I
fought through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt, because of what I did in college, that would get me
through my rookie year. Obviously, that didn't get me close to what
I wanted to accomplish. Now I have a year's experience and I'm
watching more film. The coaches are working with me more, giving me
more technique and that type of thing. Now I can go out there and
be comfortable and play my type of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which used to be a bump-and-run style. Canty got away from that
last year, as Carroll wanted him to learn all phases of the game.
Now he is slowly getting back to it.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie, he knew he didn't have the respect of his teammates
all the time. But he has gradually won them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, as a rookie, they want to see what you got and see
why you got drafted No. 1,'' he said. ``Now guys are trying to help
you fit in, trying to get you adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Canty says he will never again take his career for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try and take each and every game and each and every practice
to get better,'' he said. ``I'm trying to win the respect of my
teammates, coaches, and the entire organization. If I can start,
that's great. If I'm unable to start, I'm still going to do what I
can for special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Canty may be on the field more than any other Patriot. In
addition to his starting corner spot, he's a kickoff returner and
plays on cover teams. In camp, the wear and tear was starting to
show, but he has been rejuvenated lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you feel wanted,'' said Canty of his many jobs.
``Special teams is a place for special guys who can do a little bit
more than other guys. It's great to be able to make a play on
special teams on kickoff returns, punt returns. You might get a
block or a big tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year he made a few big plays blitzing out of nickel
coverage but didn't show a great ability to cover. So far in this
exhibition season, he has been covering well and not getting beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to keep it up,'' he said. ``Keep getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he can leave his house a little later in the morning,
knowing the doughnuts will be waiting for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
