<HEADLINE>
MAKING MONEY FROM STOCK-MARKET SLAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If good investors like volatility, this should be heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't it feel that way? The Dow and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 are both off about 8.3 percent since their July peaks, but it
has been much, much worse. The Russell 2000, which tracks small
stocks, offers a better glimpse of reality, down 20 percent. That
is bear market territory.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in that slaughter, there's money to be made. Using
some basic value measures, we went prospecting through the 350
Massachusetts stocks we monitor daily. Our credo: Cheap is good.
</P>
<P>
   We ran the numbers three ways. We looked at price-to-book
ratios, a measure of a company's net worth vs. its share price. We
also ran the price-to-earnings ratio, which shows how much we would
have to pay for a company's profits. And we considered the
price-to-sales ratio, which shows how much we would pay per dollar
of annual sales. There's no fancy footwork here.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of companies popped out of our screens, but we were really
picky. We tossed out any firm with a market capitalization of less
than $250 million and any that is not making money. All our
companies are selling far below the benchmarks for the broad
market.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what looks cheap by the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   _Neiman Marcus Group. The high-end retailer has seen its stock
sag from 43 and change at the start of July to 30 5/16 Monday. But
run the numbers and consider its name and you have to wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   First the basics: Chestnut Hill-based Neiman is selling at a
price-to-book ratio of 2.3, a multiple of 14 times recent earnings
and just 0.64 times sales. The S&AMP;P 500, by comparison, is trading
at a price-to-book ratio of 4.1, a price-earnings multiple of
nearly 26, and a price-to-sales ratio of 1.68.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lodewick, research director of Boston Partners Asset
Management, says Neiman is generating lots of free cash and is
growing earnings at 10 percent a year or more. In addition, Neiman
Marcus and Bergdorf Goodman are marque names, and chief executive
Richard Smith and his team are proven winners.
</P>
<P>
   _Thermo Electron Corp. The ingenious mouse trap that the
brothers Hatsopoulos, George and John, built in Waltham is getting
killed. The stock has been crushed from 44 at the start of the year
to 19 7/8 today.
</P>
<P>
   A whole slew of Thermo spinoffs show up on our value screen, but
Thermo Electron remains the center of the universe. This used to be
a pricey tech stock, but no longer: It is selling at 12 times
recent earnings and 1.4 times book value. Its price-to-sales ratio
is 0.83.
</P>
<P>
   The retrenchment has forced the Hatsopouloses to admit, tacitly
at least, something they have always denied: There are limits to
the strategy of forever spinning out Thermo babies. Just this month
Thermo Electron announced it would reorganize, cutting the number
of subsidiaries to 15 from 23.
</P>
<P>
   This could be a rare opportunity to buy the Hatsopoulos vision
on sale.
</P>
<P>
   _Allmerica Financial Corp. The Worcester insurer went public in
October 1995 at 21 and has been on a run ever since, closing Monday
at 70 5/8. But it remains cheap by many measures. The company sells
at 1.7 times book value, an earnings multiple of 15 times earnings
and 1.2 times sales.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Partners's Lodewick says Allmerica's variable annuity
business is growing fast and it is expecting to cut more costs out
of its property and casualty side. He also thinks Allmerica is a
takeover target in the wake of American International Group's
purchase of SunAmerica. Buyout price: north of $90.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything that looks like a bargain is, of course. Reebok
International, for instance, turned up on lots of people's value
screens, ours included. But a lot of very good investors have been
growing old waiting for Paul Fireman to fix his Stoughton shoe
company.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Whitridge, one of Boston's best investors, is among them.
David L. Babson &AMP; Co., where Whitridge runs the highly successful
Babson Value fund, is among Reebok's largest holders, with about
1.8 million shares. Whit-ridge, a patient sort, hasn't given up,
but admits: ``I'm highly disappointed in Reebok.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
