<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTI-VACCINATION-HNS &LR;      08-25 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-VACCINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PARENTS QUESTION THE PROLIFERATION OF VACCINES FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Byron Nilsson took vaccinations for granted until
his daughter was born in January 1997 in the rural upstate New York
home he shares with his wife, Susan.
</P>
<P>
   He had been doing research on home births when he came across
articles on the Internet and in magazines about the potential
dangers associated with childhood immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he and his wife have opted against getting their
daughter vaccinated against most childhood diseases, arguing that
the shots pose a greater medical risk than the chance of getting
the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Consider polio. Today, the only documented cases of polio in the
Western Hemisphere come from the weakened live virus in the oral
polio vaccine, the same vaccine credited for eradicating wild polio
as an epidemic health crisis in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all cases, you're rolling the dice,'' said Nilsson, a
free-lance writer and full-time father. ``What's worse, getting the
disease or getting the vaccine?''
</P>
<P>
   The decision not to fully immunize their daughter puts this
family, and a growing movement of parents across the state and
country, in opposition to the medical establishment and in many
cases, state law.
</P>
<P>
   Their frustration comes as the list of recommended and required
vaccines for children grows beyond the standard polio, mumps,
measles and rubella vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, for example, all kindergarteners entering New York
public schools must be vaccinated against hepatitis B, a viral
disease spread primarily through sexual contact and intravenous
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents, upset because they don't view their children at
risk of contracting the disease, question why such a vaccine is
routinely given to all newborns before they leave the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents who have never questioned vaccines are in increasing
numbers calling up and complaining bitterly about having to
vaccinate their children against hepatitis B,'' said Barbara Loe
Fisher, co-founder and executive director of the Virginia-based
National Vaccine Information Center, a group of parents and
advocates concerned about vaccine safety.
</P>
<P>
   Many states also are considering adding the chicken pox vaccine
to the list, even though some people question whether that
childhood illness is serious enough to merit another mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Vaccines are the only required medical treatment in this
country. Exemptions for medical or religious reasons are rare in
most states. Those who fail to comply can be denied access to many
schools, colleges, the military and even some jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt pretty alone in this,'' Nilsson said. ``It does feel
like we're dropping through a trap door and becoming part of the
underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians and public health officials blame a small group of
parents and skeptics whose children have had a severe reaction to
vaccines for overstating the medical risks.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, vaccinated children are fine, underscoring the
fact that vaccines save millions of children across the world from
potentially debilitating and deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts credit a mandatory vaccination program for
eradicating some of the most dangerous childhood diseases,
including smallpox. In addition, there has been a dramatic drop in
the incidence of diseases for which vaccines have been developed.
</P>
<P>
   That change is evident is statistics compiled by the National
Vaccine Information Center, comparing reported cases of disease in
1945 to 1997. Those numbers show:
</P>
<P>
   _ There were more than 18,000 reported cases of diphtheria in
1945, compared to less than 5 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 13,000 reported cases of polio compared to about 10
last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 133,000 reported cases of pertussis or whooping
cough compared to less than 10,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ And 346 reported cases of smallpox compared to none today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not immunizing everybody, you're not doing your
job,'' said Dr. Elaine Schulte, a pediatrician at the Albany
Medical Center. She said the problem with making vaccines optional
is that a large pool of unvaccinated children can set the stage for
another outbreak of disease.
</P>
<P>
   A national measles outbreak in from 1989 to 1991 sickened 55,000
children across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for parents to understand,'' Schulte said. ``Fifteen
or 20 years ago, it was easier to push immunizations because people
were more familiar with the diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The issue goes beyond science, with some parents making the case
that they, and not lawmakers and public health officials, have the
right to decide what's best for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do live in America and people do have an attachment to
personal freedom,'' said Joseph L. Hayes, a physician in Glenville,
N.Y., who says he is hearing from more parents questioning the
safety of vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the concern is new research, published in journals and
magazines such as Epidemiology, Science News, and the New Zealand
Medical Journal, that link vaccines to a host of chronic childhood
illnesses, including asthma, allergies and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Until the recent widespread use of the Internet, most parents
would not have come across these controversial studies. Today, a
few parents are going to their pediatricians' offices armed with
evidence they believe supports a case against all vaccinations or
more often, only some vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are personal and private decisions. I don't think
government has a role for making carte blanche decisions for an
entire population,'' said Monica Miller of Kinderhook, N.Y., a
private lobbyist and patient activist who decided against getting
her two children, now 19 and 13, vaccinated against pertussis,
rubella, mumps and measles.
</P>
<P>
   She ended up having to take significant time off from work on
two occasions when they each came down with whooping cough _ an
option she acknowledges most working parents don't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a second thought,'' she said, explaining how she
believes the illness strengthened her children's immune system and
aided their emotional and physical growth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the federal government acknowledged that vaccines
aren't 100 percent safe when it set up its National Vaccine Injury
Compensation Program. The intent was to compensate families whose
children suffered death or a severe reaction to vaccines, using
money collected through a 75-cent excise tax on the childhood
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, the program has received 5,274 claims from
parents and paid out an estimated $925.7 million in awards to
injured children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot say to give a vaccination is absolutely safe, but I
think there are a lot of times when we forget that everything we
do, including getting out of bed in the morning, is a risk,'' Hayes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hayes acknowledges, it's a tough pill for some parents to
swallow. ``It's very difficult to tell people with small children
that there are certain risks society demands that you take whether
you think it's worthwhile or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson and his wife are still weighing the risks of the polio
vaccine. Although they've agreed to have their daughter vaccinated
against tetanus and diphtheria because they live on a farm where
her risk of exposure is greater, they've opted against measles,
mumps, rubella and pertussis.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they haven't felt the consequences of their decision.
Lily, now 18 months, is healthy and stays at home with her dad,
rather than go to day care, where vaccinations would be required.
</P>
<P>
   School is also more than three years away, and the family
already is a considering other alternatives, including private
school, to protect their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm perfectly willing to fight the state,'' Nilsson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
