<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NLRB-CHAIRMAN-HNS &LR;      08-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NLRB-CHAIRMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NLRB CHIEF LEAVES THE FIRING LINE WITH HIS LOVE OF LABOR INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill Gould IV, great-grandson of a slave, is
returning to Palo Alto, and not a moment too soon. Gould has been
chairman of the National Labor Relations Board since 1994, which is
another way of saying he was a punching bag for House Republicans.
But this punching bag punched back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't accommodate myself to the enemies of my agency and
the National Labor Relations Act,'' Gould, 62, said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes keeping the faith is hard to do while maintaining
one's composure. A onetime autoworkers' union attorney who went on
to become a nationally known arbitrator, Gould is a distinguished
Stanford University law professor who has been named repeatedly to
Ebony magazine's list of the most influential black Americans.
Nevertheless, a few congressmen treated him and his five-member
board as if they were shills for organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to speak of the `Imperial Presidency,' but there are
a number of congressmen who are imperious and swelled up,'' Gould
said. ``This comes through in their conversation with you. You are
in many senses a supplicant _ they control the purse strings.''
</P>
<P>
   There also were Democrats who had problems with Gould. Among
them was Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, a powerful party figure and
ranking minority member of the House Appropriations Committee and
labor subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fall of 1997, he said to me, in a very pugnacious and
bellicose tone, `You don't really know how things are done in
Washington. Perhaps you'd like me to give you less money than what
even the Republicans want to give you. How would you like that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been talked to like that since I was a laborer in
Longbranch, New Jersey,'' Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd chalk it up to his arrogance and megalomania more than to
racism _ although I think many in Congress were more hostile to me
because of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Obey's office had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite President Clinton's support, the NLRB's authority has
eroded. The agency's $175 million budget hasn't kept pace with
inflation and staff is down from about 3,000 to some 1,800. This
translates into a backlog of unresolved disputes, including the
fate of strikers at the Detroit News and Detroit Free-Press trying
to reclaim jobs and a dispute between a Reno, Nev., contractors'
group and electrical workers.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Congress, Gould said, never have accepted the fact that
the National Labor Relations Act is intended to promote collective
bargaining and freedom of association for workers. Why don't they
repeal the law?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they don't have the votes. They'd rather pursue this
avenue of character assassination. They're reduced to guerrilla
warfare, which takes place through the appropriations process and
oversight hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould's foes, on the other hand, say their problem with him
arose from his abandonment of any pretense of neutrality. And
there's no question Gould has been bold. The U.S. Chamber of
Commerce won't soon forget his vocal opposition to Proposition 226,
the initiative on the California ballot in June that would have
denied unions the right to spend dues on political causes without
the consent of union members. The measure lost.
</P>
<P>
   The picture of Gould that finally emerges, however, is of a man
of ideology too thoughtful and too flexible to be called an
ideologue. ``Bill Gould came in like a lion and went out like a
somewhat older and wiser lion,'' said Frederick Baron, head of the
employment and labor group in the Palo Alto office of the Cooley
Godward law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was concern when he came in heralded as a pro-union
activist. But if you look at his record, he showed a willingness to
make significant decisions in favor of management. In that sense,
he seemed more like a professor than a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould may be speaking out again this fall, as the gubernatorial
race in California moves into high gear. He supports Lt. Gov. Gray
Davis, a Democrat, and says he has an interest in serving in state
government.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans two books _ one about government (``I've kept good
notes'') and one about his great-grandfather, also named Bill, who
escaped slavery in North Carolina and served in the Union Army.
That Bill Gould also had a good memory, kept notes and was
determined to speak his mind. It runs in the family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
