u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN27-COX     08-25 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Confessions of a bleeding-heart liberal
 &HT;    By Harley Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Since I challenged the right-wing hate mongers a
few years ago concerning their character assassinations of all who
disagree with them, I have been deemed by some a ``bleeding-heart
liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   How did I get this way?
</P>
<P>
   When I removed all the ``teaching of men'' as instructed by
Jesus's teaching, and revisited his words, it was obvious. My
social liberalism has developed from the fundamental teaching of
Jesus. Fundamental Christianity, that's what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus taught that we should give to those in need. He did not
qualify their worthiness nor did he qualify or limit the amount or
the frequency of giving and forgiving. He said that there should be
no limits on either.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus said that we should not store up treasures on earth, for
one cannot serve both God and wealth or money. He went on to
emphasize this teaching by adding that it would be easier for a
camel to pass through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to go
to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus forgave the Samaritan woman who had been married several
times and was living in adultery, even when she did not feel
worthy. He was criticized for socializing and associating with
sinners and tax collectors. He said that they were the ones who
need help, not the righteous. He did not play politics with either
the religious or the political power sources of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus said of marriage, ``... a man will leave his father and
mother and be united to his wife, and the two will become one
flesh. ... So they are no longer two but one.'' This fundamental
Christian teaching, in my opinion, put them on equal terms.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus's simple, unadulterated teachings are hard for most
Americans to accept. We have to find a ``church'' or denomination
that will alter them to suit our money- and power-driven society.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus said to be meek, merciful, peacemakers, to give to the
poor. He said do not condemn, do not judge, that all would have to
give account for every careless word spoken. He said to pay taxes
without complaining, and, he said to preach the good news and to
stay out of politics.
</P>
<P>
   If Jesus were on earth today, which church would he attend?
Probably, as in his days on earth, he would go to a synagogue and
teach. After all, he was a Jew, you know.
</P>
<P>
   He would, otherwise, be among ``sinners and tax collectors''
teaching wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
   For macho ``Christians'' who condemn bleeding-heart liberals who
are compassionate, loving and caring, I quote the shortest verse in
the Bible: ``Jesus wept.''
</P>
<P>
   (Harley Johnson, a retired school administrator, is a member of
the Board of Contributors of the Waco Tribune-Herald.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
