<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLERBULLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGEROUS, BLUE-CHIP BULLS IN DEMAND ON MULTIMILLION-DOLLAR PRO
RODEO CIRCUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Cody Hart drew a notorious bull named Red
Wolf at a rodeo last year in Alexandria, La. Some 2 1/2 years
before, Red Wolf had fatally stomped Brent Thurman at the 1994
National Finals Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was, fresh out of high school, just a kid, and I draw
this bull that has a death list,'' said Hart, who was 18 when he
faced the red-horned animal that was named the 1996 Professional
Rodeo Cowboys Association's top bull. ``I was a little scared, but
I knew that nothing tragic would happen to me if I just stayed in
the middle of his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart, a nationally ranked cowboy who lives in Thackerville,
Okla., stayed on Red Wolf for the mandatory eight seconds that day
and posted a score of 94 out of a possible 100. He survived an
encounter with a growing, flesh-and-blood reality of the sport:
Crowd-pleasing bulls with feisty reputations have become the
marquee attractions on today's multimillion-dollar pro rodeo
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls have become so powerful, and dangerous, that cowboys now
wear flak jackets and helmets. And powerful bulls have become so
valuable that when producer Chris Woodruff put together ``The
Battle of the Bulls'' last weekend in Weatherford, just west of
Fort Worth, he said that he budgeted up to $20,000 to hire six
livestock contractors to bring about 75 top bulls to the
Professional Bull Riders event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make stars out of these bulls,'' Woodruff said.
``They're athletes. They may not understand fan applause or what is
being said. But they have adrenaline, and I know they must feel the
intensity of the bright lights and the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   A BULL MARKET: The growth of bull riding _ the Professional
Rodeo Cowboys Association and Professional Bull Riders each have
year-round schedules _ has created a demand for more blue-chip
bulls than ever before. And it's not as if there's a Red Wolf
waiting in every cow pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Like a pro baseball scout scouring the farm leagues to beef up
his pitching staff, Sammy Andrews is on a constant watch for
blue-chip bucking bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding great bulls is a lot like recruiting baseball
players,'' said Andrews, who raises rodeo livestock. ``We have the
equivalent of Double-A and Triple-A farm systems with junior and
amateur rodeos. When I hear of a potentially great bull, I usually
rely on amateur producers to test them. But like baseball, there's
a few rodeo bulls that immediately are ready for the pros.''
</P>
<P>
   For Andrews, a northeast Texan who trucked his top stock to
Weatherford last weekend, recruiting a blue-chip herd requires
continual consultation with minor-league producers, bidding at
auctions and formulating a breeding program. Only about one bull in
10 becomes a keeper, Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip herds are a mainstay on the Professional Bull Riders
circuit, which awards more than $4 million a year in purses,
including $100,000 to the overall winner at the world championships
in Las Vegas each November.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 40 animals in Andrews' stock pen, including Skat
Kat Skoal, a former top bull at the National Finals Rodeo. Andrews
also owns Bodacious, a two-time PRCA bucking bull of the year who
was retired in 1995 after injuring too many cowboys. Many
competitors sustained facial injuries from colliding with the
massive white beast as they were thrown from his back.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious is now a breeder.
</P>
<P>
   Just as owning a Triple Crown winner in thoroughbred horse
racing can bring notoriety, producing top bulls such as Bodacious
can earn contracts to high-profile shows and big bucks. This year,
the bull of the year on the Professional Bull Riders circuit is
expected to receive a $25,000 prize, said Cody Lambert, the
association's livestock director.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a top bull can mean instant success.
</P>
<P>
   Stock producer Terry Williams of Carthage spent $31,000 last
year for a prime-time bull named Panhandle Slim. Williams soon
wound up with a $10,000 payoff after Panhandle Slim, a fast
spinner, was named bull of the year at last year's Professional
Bull Riders World Finals in Las Vegas. Williams split the $20,000
prize with the breeder who sold him the bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a job,'' said Williams, who also owns Red Wolf. ``I see
stock contractors form a herd of great bulls and then they think
they're set and they quit looking hard. But then after a while, the
quality of their herd goes down. You have to be on the lookout all
of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   A RARE BREED: With the increasing popularity of bull riding,
producers say the odds of acquiring a star bull are the same as
recruiting a Michael Jordan or a Troy Aikman. Bulls, it seems, can
lose confidence when ever-improving riders defeat them in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when the world's top bull riders competed in PRCA
events, they might face a blue-chip bull four times a month. Today,
with the Professional Bull Riders circuit and its nationally
televised, 24-city Bud Light Cup Tour, riders face and conquer
rampaging bulls two to three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a bull, being ridden for eight seconds is a defeat, the
equivalent of a rider getting thrown off,'' said Morgan Mill's Tuff
Hedeman, president of the Professional Bull Riders and a former
world champion. ``If I were a bull and someone stayed on me nine of
10 times, I probably would lose confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these bulls like Red Wolf are smart. If riders start
staying on them when they spin to the right, after a while they
will get smarter and spin the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to facing top riders more often, a rodeo bull must
endure challenging road conditions on 1,000-mile trips and
different feed and water in varying parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you put a bull in a truck and blow black smoke on him,
you don't really know how good he is,'' Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, creating top bulls has become more scientific
in recent years. For example, Andrews' Bodacious and Skat Kat Skoal
are registered in a thriving breeding program called Buckers Inc.
that was begun two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said that he is banking on producing meaner and tougher
animals.
</P>
<P>
   In Weatherford last weekend, only two of 16 finalists in the
two-day event stayed on for the full eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate challenge when you have man vs. beast, which
is the way our world began, and now we still have the same
challenge,'' said Woodruff, the Weatherford producer. ``It's
thrilling to me to see an athlete who weighs in at only 120 pounds
take control of a 2,000-pound bull, then get off and wave his hand
in victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart, now 19, understands the thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an auto racing driver,'' he said. ``If you're really
serious about it you'll want to drive the highest level of cars,
the NASCARs and Indy cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting on Red Wolf was like racing at Daytona: You know you
have your hands full. And staying on him was like winning Daytona.
You have something to brag about.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
