A1179 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-MASSAGE-HNS &LR;      08-25 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MASSAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKLASH DELAYS SAN FRANCISCO'S MASSAGE PARLOR BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The city's Board of Supervisors has cast aside a
proposal that would ban new massage parlors in the Tenderloin
neighborhood amid opposition from targeted business owners and the
women who work for them.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision to delay a deciding vote on the proposal and
return it to a board committee for consideration came a week after
the supervisors gave initial approval to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the proposed ban say it will help clean up the
Tenderloin, long a hangout for prostitutes, criminals, drug addicts
and drunks. They say the massage parlors help attract the unsavory
elements. But foes say the businesses are legitimate operations
that have a right to exist and provide jobs for mostly poor women.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the board's latest action will doom the
proposal, which has been more than a year in the making. Supervisor
Leland Yee, chief sponsor of the proposed prohibition, said he was
hopeful it eventually would become law. The plan earlier this year
underwent two public hearings where public testimony was
overwhelmingly supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Yee said opponents had lobbied hard over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there was a lot of pressure on the board members from
the sex workers caucus and massage parlor owners who felt they were
not heard before,'' Yee said. ``I feel differently about that, but
I'm going to fight like a dickens to preserve the legislation. I
think the community support is still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yee reluctantly agreed to support the delay on a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the debate is a heavy dose of old-fashioned City Hall
politics. Monday's action can be seen as a hard slap at Yee, who is
often at odds with the board majority and Mayor Willie Brown. It
was board President Barbara Kaufman who requested that the
legislation be sent back to committee for further review. The
animosity between the two supervisors is no secret.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he thought the board's vote was aimed at him,
Yee said, ``I think there's a tinge of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, however, said her intention was to give people with
concerns another chance to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a month's delay is going to make a difference,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal targets adult-oriented businesses in the
Tenderloin, which the police say often serve as fronts for
prostitution and other criminal activity, such as drug dealing and
extortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they want to do is take away a lot of people's property
rights, their livelihood,'' said Candice Nguyen, an attorney
working with the massage parlor proprietors. ``It's also
discriminatory because it's targeting these businesses, and not
others, like liquor stores and strip clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners presented the board with a petition opposing the ban,
signed by more than 100 people who work and live in the Tenderloin
district. But those who favor the ban say they have many more
merchants, residents, social service agencies and the police on
their side _ and public hearing testimony up to this point backs up
that contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is widespread support for this ban,'' said Susan
Phillips, a social worker and Tenderloin resident who serves as
secretary of the North of Market Planning Coalition. ``They bring
in criminal elements, and that's something this neighborhood
doesn't need any more of. Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood, with some 22 city-sanctioned massage parlors,
has the highest concentration of such enterprises in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
