 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of WEDNESDAY, Aug.
26.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NAPOLEONS (Undated) _ What you get from today's restaurant chefs
can resemble the conversation at a cocktail party: some of it is
smart and a lot of it is showing off. Consider the ostentatious
trend toward greater and greater height on the plate, food
sculpture that looks impressive until you try to eat it, and it
falls apart. And the trend, which virtually begs restaurant cooks
to build things ever higher, is seen perfectly in the proliferation
of dishes named after the napoleon, the classic dessert that has
become just about anything you can imagine, as long as it comes
stacked high. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   HOW-TO-EAT-A-NAPOLEON (Undated) _ The napoleon, however
beautiful, poses a serious challenge to the diner: how to attack?
There is a trick to getting a taste of each layer without squishing
the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   NAPOLEON-CHEF (Undated) _ When I was just learning about fine
cooking as a 14-year-old apprentice in an inn in upstate New York,
I was completely fascinated by the dessert cart. I was particularly
taken with the elaborate pastry cream creations like the napoleon.
And as I learned by the time I got to culinary school, the ability
to create those creamy classics was one of the hallmarks of the
professional. By Charlie Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS-SOMMELIER (New York) _ When Andrea Immer bounds up to a
table at Windows on the World, she faces diners who invariably seem
wary. Dressed in her severe black pantsuit and white blouse, she is
clearly not the waitress. She did not welcome them at the door so
she is neither hostess nor maitre d'. And her greeting is so
relentlessly energetic, there is a fleeting suspicion she might try
recruiting volunteers for the hokey pokey. What almost no one
assumes _ with her brisk demeanor that seems part corporate
executive, part kindergarten teacher _ is that she is the
sommelier, overseeing a cellar that accounts for $5 million in wine
sales per year. Not only that, but she is was judged the best
sommelier in the country last year by the Sommelier Society of
America. By Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PURSLANE (Undated) _ These days I seem to encounter purslane
everywhere I go. If you eat in restaurants with any frequency, the
chances are that you do, too. For American chefs are finally
beginning to appreciate the many qualities of purslane, the juicy
little weed so prized by the French. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SKATE (New York) _ Skate's arrival as a Serious Fish, at
least in New York, can be pinpointed to the day. It was on Jan. 28,
1986, the day Le Bernardin opened: skate was there on the menu,
poached with browned butter. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: fish grilled over fennel.
By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   AVENGER-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ With ``The Wine Avenger''
(Fireside, $11), Willie Gluckstern establishes himself as the
bleacher bum of wine writers. A book review by William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The trouble is that you want to believe.
That the used car you are buying was driven only once a week. That
this will be the year the home team makes it to the Superbowl. That
this diet is going to do the trick. That (fill in the year) is
going to be the vintage of the century in (fill in the country).
Italian wine makers are sure that the 1997 vintage was the best
ever. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ Capsule review of a particular wine.
