<SLUG> BC-PHONY-COLLECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTAL SERVICE PROBES BOGUS LETTER SEEKING PAYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S. Postal Service is investigating a
mysterious letter asking hundreds of people to pay a bill they
didn't owe to a company that evidently doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the anxious backlash of the letter are San
Francisco-based Wells Fargo Bank and a prominent Northern
California law firm. The phone numbers of both the bank and the law
firm are noted in the letter. But officials for both deny prior
knowledge of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Postal Service inspectors and the Mill Valley police are
investigating the origin of the letters, which are addressed to
``Dear Valued Customer'' by a company calling itself ADS Collection
Services. The letter tells recipients ``you have a past due bill in
the amount of $76.''
</P>
<P>
   It says the customer could face a ruined credit rating or legal
action if the money isn't paid promptly. The return address given
is in Mill Valley, though no company by that name exists in that
town north of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Many, but not all, recipients of the letter are Wells Fargo
customers. More than 200 _ confused or angry or both _ called the
bank last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know who sent the letter out or how many were sent
out,'' Wells Fargo spokeswoman Lisa Rossi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that they may have been mailed out across the
nation,'' she said. ``The letter is fraudulent, and we are assuring
our customers who are calling in that it will in no way affect
their accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter also suggests that recipients with questions about
the bill call a phone number that turns out to belong to the law
firm of Nielsen, Merksamer, Parinello, Mueller &AMP; Naylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been advising people who call not to write checks, or to
cancel checks if they've written them and call the U.S. postal
inspector,'' said James Parinello, a partner in the firm. ``It's a
scam and really quite outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters were mailed from Sacramento last week and were
stamped, not put through a postage meter, which makes it impossible
for postal inspectors to determine the identity of the sender. Nor
does the Postal Service know exactly how many letters were mailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking into it to see if there was any attempt to
solicit money through the mail by making false representations,''
which is a federal crime, postal inspector Steve Kline said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1508EDT &QL; 
