<SLUG> BC-WEB-RESEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS TO DELVE INTO AMERICAN LIVES VIA THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Americans are far more mobile than their
ancestors were a century ago, and that mobility exacts a
psychological price: loss of ties to one's family, relatives,
friends and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   How are Americans coping with this high-speed, high-tech age,
when ``all that is solid melts into air'' (to borrow a line from
Karl Marx, who watched the Industrial Revolution similarly derail
the lives of 19th-century Europeans)?
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic magazine and social scientists want to find
out, using the ultimate engine of mobility, the World Wide Web, by
which humans can navigate global databases, chat rooms and stock
markets at the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, described Monday at the American Sociological
Association meeting in San Francisco, is one of a number of
fledgling efforts to gather scientific data via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sept. 20, the magazine is sponsoring ``Survey 2000,''
an on-line sociological survey of the nation. Those who want to can
go on line and fill out a questionnaire to describe who they are,
what they do for a living, where they come from originally, how
well-connected they feel to both their hometowns and new
communities, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   According to the project director, social scientist James Witte
of Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill., the study aims to
answer questions such as, ``How does migration affect our sense of
community? How much are cultural tastes (for example, in food and
music) influenced by migration?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is regional variety giving way to homogenized global culture?
Are people replacing geographic communities (such as their
hometowns) with substitutes such as (their) profession, workplace
or the Internet?''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say gathering scientific information through the
Internet allows researchers to contact far more people than is
feasible with telephone surveys or old-fashioned questionnaires
sent by mail.
</P>
<P>
   It also is much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks, too, Witte acknowledged. For one thing,
those surveyed by the Web aren't likely to be a representative
sample of the U.S. population. But he said scholars can
statistically massage the data to extract useful insights into
modern American society.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie May, managing editor of National Geographic Interactive,
said the magazine hoped to increase participation in the survey by
social groups that don't routinely use the Web. Hence, anyone who
needs assistance in joining the Survey 2000 can phone 800-424-9420,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The questionnaire will be posted from Sept. 20 until Nov. 27 at
the following Web site: http://survey2000.nationalgeographic.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
