A1252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-POWELL-SHORT-VER     08-25 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-POWELL-SHORT-VERSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED JUSTICE LEWIS POWELL, VOICE OF MODERATION ON POLORIZED
COURT, 90  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lewis F. Powell Jr., the retired Supreme Court
justice who brought a voice of moderation and civility to an
increasingly polarized court during his 15-year tenure, died
Tuesday at the age of 90. An announcement from the court reported
that Powell, who retired 11 years ago and had been in failing
health, died of pneumonia at his home in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was one of the country's most prominent corporate
lawyers, with practical legal skills polished by decades of
experience, when his nomination to the court by President Nixon in
1972 gave him an unexpected second career. He was 64 years old, an
age at which he said he had expected to start ``tapering off,''
when he took the seat made vacant by the retirement of Associate
Justice Hugo Black.
</P>
<P>
   His role on the court eventually became so central to the
institution's ideological balance that his retirement in 1987
unleashed a furious political battle over the nomination of the
prominent conservative President Reagan named to replace him,
Robert Bork. The nomination was defeated and the seat eventually
went to the more moderate Anthony Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   First in his native Virginia and then on the national scene,
Powell had long since reached the highest ranks of the legal
profession. He had been president of three major legal
organizations, the American Bar Association, the American Bar
Foundation and the American College of Trial Lawyers. He was a
senior partner of one of Virginia's oldest law firms, a trustee and
general counsel of Colonial Williamsburg and a director of 11 major
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Born into the insularity and rigid stratifications of the
post-Reconstruction South, Powell cherished his roots in Richmond
and at the same time transcended them. From a young age, he was
drawn to the wider world while maintaining his ties to home. His
long life in some respects mirrored the journey of the modern South
from the country's fringe to its mainstream. He described his
initial response to the Supreme Court's ruling in Brown vs. Board
of Education, the 1954 decision that segregation in the public
schools was unconstitutional, as one of shock. Yet as a Virginia
civic leader and later as a Supreme Court justice, he stood for
moderation and consensus-building on matters of race.
</P>
<P>
   He played a key role on a court that was marked by sharp
ideological divisions. He was the balancer and compromiser, a
political moderate with an aversion to heated rhetoric and
doctrinal rigidity. Neither his colleagues nor lawyers practicing
before the court could take his vote for granted. He had to be
persuaded by the weight of argument, and his vote was frequently
the decisive one, whether the subject was state aid to parochial
schools, remedies for racial discrimination or the rights of
illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The most important opinion of his Supreme Court tenure was
probably one in which he wrote only for himself. In the Bakke case,
a landmark affirmative action decision in 1978, he bridged two
competing four-justice blocs to extract a holding that barred the
use of rigid racial quotas but permitted race to be taken into
account in university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   He never lost either his acute sense of the court's great power
or his conviction that the power had to be used sparingly. For him,
judicial restraint was crucial to keeping the balance of power
among the three branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   A concurring opinion he wrote in a 1974 decision, holding that a
taxpayer could not bring a suit challenging the way the Central
Intelligence Agency was financed, expressed as clearly as anything
else Powell's vision of the role of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be ever mindful,'' he wrote in United States vs.
Richardson, ``of the contradictions that would arise if a democracy
were to permit general oversight of the elected branches of
government by a nonrepresentative, and in large measure, insulated
judicial branch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Repeated and essentially head-on confrontations between the
life-tenured branch and the representative branches of government
will not, in the long run, be beneficial to either,'' he said.
``The public confidence essential to the former and the vitality
critical to the latter may well erode if we do not exercise
self-restraint in the utilization of our power.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Powell did not hesitate to place the court's
weight on the side of those who had nowhere else to turn. In 1982,
he joined the court's liberal bloc in providing the crucial fifth
vote for a decision requiring Texas to give a free public education
to the children of illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not unmindful of what must be the exasperation of
responsible citizens and government authorities'' over the influx
of illegal aliens, he wrote in concurring with the majority opinion
in Plyler vs. Doe. But the fact remained, he said, that
``innocent'' children were being denied an education solely because
of their parents' illegal status, and were thereby ``singled out
for a lifelong penalty and stigma.'' He said that ``it can hardly
be argued rationally that anyone benefits from the creation within
our borders of a subclass of illiterate persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Franklin Powell Jr. was born in Suffolk, Va., on Sept. 19,
1907 into a family with deep roots in the region. One of his
father's relatives, although not a direct ancestor, was Nathaniel
Powell, one of the original Jamestown settlers and for a time the
colony's acting governor. Powell's mother, Mary Lewis Gwathmey, was
raised on a Virginia plantation by an uncle who had accompanied
Gen. Robert E. Lee to the surrender of the Confederate forces at
Appomatox.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, when he was 28, Powell married Josephine Pierce Rucker,
the daughter of a prominent Richmond obstetrician. The two had met
years earlier, but Powell first became interested in the doctor's
daughter after hearing that she had set a broad-jump record of 22
feet at Sweet Briar College. Their marriage produced four children:
Josephine Smith; Ann Pendleton Bowen, known as Penny; Molly Sumner;
and Lewis 3d. Mrs. Powell died in 1996. In addition to his
children, Powell is survived by nine grandchildren and one great
grandson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1253 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR &LR;      08-25 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR STRIKES GOLD IN CHRONICLE OF SUNKEN TREASURE SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1989, Gary Kinder received a mysterious
invitation to visit a Victorian house in Columbus, Ohio, that was
the headquarters of a business partnership called Columbus-America
Discovery Group.
</P>
<P>
   When Kinder arrived, he was met by the head of the partnership,
Tommy Thompson, who ushered him into an office and closed the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have something to show you,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinder saw that Thompson held a bundle in his hands, something
small but weighty, and wrapped in cloth. Slowly, Thompson pulled
away the material so that Kinder could see what was inside.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bar of solid gold. Kinder blinked, and looked again. It
was a (itals) brick (end itals) of gold. A big brick, as shining
and as wondrous as he ever imagined something like that could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hold one of those things in your hands,'' Kinder says
today, ``you realize that gold fever really does exist, and it's
not silly, not silly at all. Gold is so beautiful. It is (itals) so
beautiful. (end itals) He showed me some gold coins, too, and, let
me tell you, it was pretty magnificent stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ship of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea'' (Atlantic, $27.50) is
Kinder's bestselling book about that magnificent stuff, and about
the visionary man who found it. At the time of their meeting,
Kinder already had spent two years following Thompson's efforts to
locate the wreck of the Central America, a paddle steamer that sank
in the Atlantic Ocean in 1857, taking with it hundreds of
passengers and a fortune in gold. Even so, Thompson was secretive,
and wanted to bring Kinder into his confidence slowly. That day in
his office, he told Kinder only that he and his crew had found the
bar and a few coins, and were searching for the rest of the gold.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was that they'd found it all _ hundreds of millions of
dollars' worth of sunken treasure _ and by the end of the summer
would be bringing much of it to the surface. Here, from ``Ship of
Gold,'' is how Thompson described his first glimpse of what lay in
the skeleton of the Central America:
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom was carpeted with gold. Gold everywhere, like a
garden. The more you looked, the more you saw gold growing out of
everything, embedded in all the wood and beams. It was amazing,
clear back in the far distance, bars stacked on the bottom like
brownies, bars stacked like loaves of bread, bars that appear to
have slid into the corner of a room. Some of the bars formed a
bridge, all gold bars spanning one area of treasure over here and
another over here, water underneath, and the decks collapsed
through on both sides. There was a beam with coins stacked on it,
just covered, couldn't see the top of the beam it had so many coins
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a heady image, but it is only a small part of ``Ship of
Gold in the Deep Blue Sea.'' The book begins with a narrative
account of the sinking of the Central America, the tense and
poignant story of a brave captain, his terrified passengers and
crew, and their efforts to survive a raging storm at sea. From
there, the book leaps ahead more than 100 years to the odd group of
men who went searching for the wreck under 8,000 feet of water off
the coast of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the group was Tommy Thompson, a young marine
engineer from Ohio who was insatiably curious, had a genius for
experimentation, and took an eccentric approach to nearly
everything he did. Later, Thompson would show how persuasive he
could be when he convinced a group of Ohio businessmen to finance
his search for a ship that even the most savvy treasure hunters had
been unable to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy was a techno-nerd in many ways, but he had more steel in
him than anyone you can imagine,'' Kinder says. ``People look at
what he did at various stages of this thing and they say, `Boy, was
he ever lucky on that one.' But it wasn't luck. Tommy never sleeps.
He's too busy asking himself what can possibly go wrong, and then
he comes up with six solutions for every problem. Then he asks
himself what could go (itals) right, (end itals) and if it does,
how can he enhance it and make it go even better? He is constantly
thinking in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My challenge was to tell the truth but still make Tommy
Thompson believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinder, 51, first read about the Central America in a 1987
magazine article on lost treasures. Kinder had a law degree but did
not practice. As a young man he had read Tom Wolfe's 1973
anthology, ``The New Journalism,'' and had wanted ever since to
make his living as a writer. He already had published two books
(``Victim,'' about a Utah crime and its aftermath, and ``Light
Years,'' on UFO contacts). On the lookout for a new subject, he
stumbled onto the search for the Central America.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, there were at least five ``treasure hunters'' (a
term Thompson abhorred, Kinder later learned) looking for the ship
and its gold. Kinder met with a few of them before he heard about
Thompson. He made contact through Thompson's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reception was warm,'' he says. ``I was a legitimate author
and I had a law degree, so I could talk their language. I kept in
touch through the lawyers while Tommy was at sea. By the time I met
him, I had already narrowed it down. I liked those other guys, but
they were cowboys. They were treasure hunters. Tommy saw the gold
as a means to an end, a way to entice investors so that he could
develop technology to work at the bottom of the deep ocean. The
treasure was secondary to him. I was sure that if anybody could
find that ship, he was the one.''
</P>
<P>
   It would take two more years of searching and several trips back
to Thompson's investors for more money. Then, in 1989, Kinder was
summoned to the house in Columbus to hold a bar of gold. A few
months later, he was with Thompson at sea when he announced to the
world that he had found the gold.
</P>
<P>
   With Thompson's triumph, Kinder's work began. He drew from
survivors' accounts for chapters on the sinking of the Central
America, and from Thompson's sonar and at-sea logs for passages on
the search and on confrontations at sea with other men who wanted
the gold for themselves. Kinder also had to describe the
cutting-edge technology Thompson used to recover the gold, and the
legal maneuvers through which he claimed the right to salvage it.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling it all into a readable narrative was a grueling task
that dragged on for years. Publication was delayed again and again.
Kinder's advance _ said to be in excess of $100,000 _ ran out, and
he supported his family by giving writing seminars for other
lawyers. Thompson himself asked for another delay because of legal
battles over the recovered gold. And there were personal problems.
Kinder's father died, his mother suffered a series of strokes, and
he was spending too much time away from his wife and daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I really wondered if I was doing the right thing,''
he says. ``There was a long stretch when I was just exhausted. I
felt like I had hit a wall, like a marathon runner. I was on my
knees crawling to the finish line and I just couldn't keep going.
It was a humbling experience, trying to pull together so many
disparate pieces of the story and still keep a job and be a father
and a husband.''
</P>
<P>
   With the project finally finished, there are still questions
Kinder can't or won't answer. Exactly how much gold did Thompson
find on the Central America and what is it worth? And what will
Thompson do with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy refers to it as the `up' gold and the `down' gold,''
Kinder says. ``The `up' gold is at least 3 tons, and it is in a
vault somewhere in Virginia. I don't have a clue where. And the
`down' gold is still unrecovered or is piled somewhere else or
maybe some of each. I really don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy's been trying to find the very best way to handle the
treasure. He has thought of everything possible and then some, and
he's driving everybody crazy. I don't know what he's going to do
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinder's not sure yet what he'll do with his own success either,
with his place on the bestseller lists and his pile of good
reviews. He says he will keep his day job teaching other lawyers
how to write, but he's not sure he'll ever want to do another book.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all I went through, the good reviews have been
comforting more than anything,'' he says. ``It's relief rather than
exhilaration. That after all those years, we really do have a good
book. That I was up to telling this the way it should be told. I
can stop worrying that the first review is going to say, `This is a
great story. If only Norman Mailer had gotten to it first.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
