<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STROKE-WOMEN-HNS &LR;      08-25 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN EVALUATED MORE SLOWLY THAN MEN FOR STROKE TREATMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Women stroke sufferers arrive at the hospital later
and are evaluated more slowly than their male counterparts _ even
though their death rate in Texas is higher than that of men, a
University of Texas Medical School at Houston researcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in getting women to the hospital means that fewer of
them are candidates for treatment with tissue plasminogen
activator, a clot-busting drug that reduces the injury that strokes
can cause, said Dr. Lewis Morgenstern, an UT assistant professor of
neurology.
</P>
<P>
   He published his study in the current issue of Neurology, the
scientific journal of the American Academy of Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment with tissue plasminogen activator, or TPA, must start
within three hours of the onset of stroke symptoms, Morgenstern
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern's study of 241 stroke patients admitted to Hermann
Hospital in Houston showed that it took women 46 percent longer to
get to the hospital after stroke symptoms were recognized. Once
they were at the hospital, it took 49 percent longer to be seen by
a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern said he began the study when he discovered that 61
percent of the people who die from stroke in Texas are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you asked physicians and community members who is
more likely to die of stroke, they would say it was men,'' he said.
``Vascular disease is seen as a disease of men. But a clear
majority of the people dying from stroke in Texas is women.''
</P>
<P>
   A stroke is deadly, and it is the No. 1 cause of disability in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing the disabilities associated with stroke is one reason
the TPA treatment is so important, Morgenstern said.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier study at Hermann showed that the No. 1 reason people
do not get the treatment is that they arrive at the hospital too
late, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in getting women to the hospital could have
sociological dimensions, he said. Because women live longer than
men, they are often alone in their older years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay may be that they are alone when they have a stroke
and cannot call 911 quickly,'' Morgenstern said. ``But that doesn't
explain the majority of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As for why doctors see women more slowly, he does not have an
answer. ``The best thing we can do is to get the message out that
it is happening. We should tell people about these numbers and see
if it improves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing you can do when you or a loved one has a stroke
is call 911, Morgenstern said. His study showed that patients who
arrive at the hospital by ambulance are seen more quickly than
those who went by private vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting aspect of the study was whether having a primary
care doctor helped patients get treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found in this study is that having a primary care
physician slowed you from getting to the hospital by 63 percent,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a stroke, if you call your doctor, you have to
wait for him or her to be paged. Then he or she calls you back and
you go to the office or the hospital. If we have only three hours
to treat the patient, that can be catastrophic,'' Morgenstern said.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnicity also can be a factor in speed of getting to the
hospital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four percent of non-Hispanic whites were able to get to
the hospital within three hours of their stroke symptoms, he said.
But only 28 percent of African-Americans and 18 percent of
Hispanics managed to get to the hospital in time to receive
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenstern said more education about the signs and symptoms of
stroke is crucial to increasing the numbers of all people who get
to the hospital on time.
</P>
<P>
   Warning signs for stroke include the sudden onset of the
following:
</P>
<P>
   Weakness, numbness or paralysis on one side of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Blurry vision or loss of vision.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden difficulty speaking or understanding speech.
</P>
<P>
   Dizziness or loss of balance or coordination.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden, severe headache.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
