<HEADER>
A1367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SKATE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-25 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SKATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILD IN TASTE, ELEGANT IN LOOK, SKATE JOINS THE A-LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Skate's arrival as a Serious Fish, at least in New
York, can be pinpointed to the day. It was on Jan. 28, 1986, the
day Le Bernardin opened: skate was there on the menu, poached with
browned butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilbert introduced it as a fancy fish,'' said Eric Ripert, Le
Bernardin's executive chef, referring to the restaurant's founding
chef, the late Gilbert LeCoze. ``In the beginning, customers said:
`What? Skate? It will never work in such a nice restaurant.'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ripert figures he sells at least 30 skate dishes a day.
And while customers may ask about its preparation _ he sautees it
in goose fat and serves it with caramelized onions, artichokes and
fennel with squab broth _ no one is questioning its place on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting hard, in fact, to find a restaurant that doesn't
serve skate in some form. Downtown at Gramercy Tavern, Tom
Colicchio sautees skate, then briefly braises it in a
lemon-rosemary vinaigrette. At Pearl Oyster Bar, a sliver of a
restaurant on Cornelia Street, Rebecca Charles fries skate until it
is crisp and golden and dots it with a tiny dice of fried potato.
It's plainer but no less delicate or sweet, with the springy
texture of lobster.
</P>
<P>
   Skate is actually related to the ray, and is found year-round
and worldwide _ in the Gulf of Maine (the source of much of New
York's skate), as well as the Pacific, the Atlantic, the
Mediterranean and the Arctic Ocean, among other bodies of water.
</P>
<P>
   The fish's flat, diamond shape yields two edible wings.
Fan-shaped, with a ribbed texture, skate fillets look like
pearlescent angel wings, pristinely white with occasional tinges of
pink.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bowman, purchasing director at Browne Trading Co., in
Portland, Maine, a fish distributor, said that in 1996, the company
sold 35,000 pounds of skate, and in 1997, 50,000 pounds. ``It's
getting more exposure in the high-end restaurants,'' he said, ``and
some of the midsize restaurants are using it in Boston, New York,
Atlanta, Chicago and Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, New Yorkers are taking the cue and tossing the wings
into their saute pans as they would flounder, trout or sole. In the
last year, Citarella's two stores have been selling 300 pounds of
skate a week. In 1996, they were selling only 200 pounds. And at
$6.99 a pound, skate is about $3 a pound less than salmon steak or
flounder fillets.
</P>
<P>
   What a customer sees at a fish market is a skinned and cleaned
wing, usually on the cartilage. To cook skate on or off the
cartilage is a question of flavor, just like cooking meat on the
bone. Chefs sometimes cook the fish on the cartilage, and then
serve it as a fillet. Or for the sake of efficiency, they will cook
it already filleted. (Home cooks may prefer it filleted; to remove
it from the cartilage after it is cooked is tricky and often causes
the wing to fall apart.)
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, skate was a culinary gift of the French.
``The French have always eaten it, because it's a good quality
fish,'' said Jacques Pepin, a chef and the dean of studies at the
French Culinary Institute in Manhattan. ``It's very meaty, has a
very mild taste, a nutty taste. It's very soft and gentle to eat,
and it's difficult to overcook it.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled recipes for skate in La Varenne's ``Le Cuisinier
Francais,'' a 17th-century cookbook. ``When I was an apprentice, 50
years ago, we were using it,'' he said. But what the French ate,
and served in French restaurants, the Americans threw away.
</P>
<P>
   Pepin remembers going fishing with other chefs on Long Island
Sound 20 years ago. ``All the fishermen kept was the sole, the
striped bass,'' he said, ``and all the rest, they threw back into
the water. We filled up the basket with sea trout, monkfish, skate,
of course, and even the bluefish _ all that people didn't use.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, people can't use them enough.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Revsin, the author of ``Great Fish, Quick'' (Doubleday,
1997), likes skate as an easy late summer dish with tomatoes and
basil. The trick, she says, is to cook filleted skate just until it
turns white, which is about a minute or two on each side.
</P>
<P>
   But what finally persuades people to try skate may be its own
pretty self. ``If one of them flies by, past one person to another
person,'' Ms. Charles of the Pearl Oyster Bar said, ``they see this
crispy, golden fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapeliness is always a plus _ even in a fish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
