A1381 &Cx1f; tab-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-REMEMBERED-ADVI     08-25 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-REMEMBERED-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONDAY AUG. 31 MARKS THE FIRST ANNIVERSARY OF PRINCESS DIANA'S
DEATH IN A CAR CRASH IN PARIS.
</P>
<P>
   To mark this day, NBC is airing a documentary by British film
veteran Richard Attenborough, Diana's friend for 15 years. In an
interview with New York Times reporter Sarah Lyall, Attenborough
discusses his friend and why he chose to make the movie. The
1200-word feature is available for one-shot purchase from The New
York Times Syndicate. (FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, SEE BELOW.)
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough admits he did not want to present a saint, a martyr
or an icon. For example, he talked to several people who knew her,
including her childhood nanny, who described how Diana had
terrorized earlier nannies by throwing their clothes on the roof or
locking them in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we've demonstrated her ability to laugh at herself,''
he says. ``She wouldn't want to be idolized, she wouldn't want
people to pay homage to her. She would want the people who loved
her to say, `Come on, let's get on with what has to be done.'''
</P>
<P>
   TAKE A LOOK ...
</P>
<P>
   The article, which has been sent to category codes ``e''
entertainment and ``l'' lifestyle, can be found in your system
under the slug: BC-DIANA-ANNIVERSARY-DOCUMENTARY-NYTSF.
</P>
