<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1392 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-ANNIVERSARY-DOC     08-25 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-ANNIVERSARY-DOCUMENTARY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA REMEMBERED: FLESHING OUT A FAIRY TALE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales
Representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or by fax at 816-822-1444. She also has information
on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly package of five
intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: THIS STORY IS EMBARGOED UNTIL AUG. 30.  
 &HT;    
 By SARAH LYALL  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   After the death of Princess Diana, Richard Attenborough found
himself besieged, as so many of her friends and acquaintances were,
by people begging him to speak and write about her.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a brief article in The Times of London, he turned
down all the requests. But about six months after Diana's death, he
was approached by the producer Robert Halmi Sr., who has worked on
several big-budget television films, about making a documentary
about Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough, having had time to reflect on her death, began to
think about how he would depict the life of someone he knew well
for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview, Attenborough said he wanted his
film to reflect the many things he saw in her _ warmth, charisma,
compassion, sense of humor, star quality, intuitiveness, the
crippling lack of confidence that she worked so hard to overcome _
and to explore the effect she had on others.
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't want it to do was present her as a saint, a
martyr or an icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great difficulty in not lionizing her,'' he says.
``We don't stick her on a pedestal saying that she was a goddess.
We say she was a very perceptive, courageous, revolutionary young
woman who used her good looks and her style and her ultimate
confidence to beat paths into areas which the Establishment would,
in large measures, have avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Diana,'' a two-hour program on NBC at 8 p.m. on
Aug. 31, the one-year anniversary of Diana's death. In making the
film, Attenborough sought a new perspective on a well-trod story by
combining his own reminiscences with footage and photographs from
Diana's well-documented life and interviews with four dozen people,
including some of her closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he convinced Lucia Flecha de Lima, the wife
of the Brazilian Ambassador to the United States, and one of
Diana's best friends, to speak publicly about Diana, something she
rarely does.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a nod to his audience _ ``Diana'' was made for NBC _
Attenborough's film relies heavily on interviews with Americans,
including First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and former Washington
Post Publisher Katharine Graham. Attenborough also spoke to a
number of people who were quietly helped by Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Among these were a woman with cystic fibrosis whom Diana
regularly visited in the hospital, and a young woman who is a
quadriplegic and who tells the camera in her soft, labored voice
that Diana ``made me feel that even though I can't use my arms or
my legs, I could do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But other sides of Diana are also presented. Attenborough
interviewed Mary Clarke, who worked as a nanny for Diana and her
siblings when they were little and who described how Diana
regularly terrorized earlier nannies by throwing their clothes on
the roof or locking them in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   He showed Diana returning to her old school and reminiscing
about having to spend Saturdays weeding the grounds as punishment
for various misdeeds. He interviewed the makeup artist who, in the
early days of Diana's marriage, unsuccessfully tried to get her to
stop using blue eyeliner.
</P>
<P>
   And he spoke with Mary Robertson, the American whose son Diana
was looking after when she began dating Prince Charles. There were
times, Robertson related, when Diana would be so daunted by the
journalists camped outside her door that she would stay home,
leaving her without child care and forcing her to stay home from
work, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson's co-workers didn't care, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought it was terribly exciting that my baby sitter was
dating their future king,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough says: ``Diana had a wonderful sense of humor about
herself and I hope we've put that into the program. I hope we've
demonstrated her ability to laugh at herself and the fact that she
was always very conscious of what she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was divorced, for instance, up went the skirt, up
went the heels, and on went the best clothes you've ever seen in
your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough met the princess at the behest of Prince Charles,
whom he knew slightly and who asked him to help his new bride
overcome her crippling stage fright.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that she would have to do a certain amount of public
speaking and that she just dried up and got terrible nerves, and
could I come and talk to her about it,'' Attenborough relates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a question of giving her confidence. She felt that she
was not going to be able to do the job, that she had already made
great bloopers, and that the Establishment didn't seem to be able
to help her and point her in the right direction,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt isolated, and most of the times when there were
problems they emanated from this sense of inadequacy,''
Attenborough says.
</P>
<P>
   The film tries to show how Diana rose above that self-image and
literally reinvented herself. Attenborough says that he and his
wife, Sheila, loved ``this young woman who might have been a very
ordinary young woman, but who because she was gutsy and courageous
knocked down barriers that had been in place for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I wanted to talk to were the people who had
witnessed this,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The film does not dwell on Diana's romantic life, except
peripherally: Attenborough tells the camera that when Diana
telephoned him not long before she died to tell him about her
romance with Dodi al-Fayed, he had ``never heard so much fun and
love and happiness in her voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the focus is on her work with charities, especially
those dealing with AIDS and with land mines, a particular interest
of Attenborough's. He plans to donate the proceeds from the film to
the Princess of Wales Memorial Fund, and NBC is setting up a
toll-free number through which viewers may pledge money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I've done this is in no small measure to support
the work to which she was committed,'' Attenborough says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't want to be idolized, she wouldn't want people to
pay homage to her. She would want the people who loved her to say,
`Come on, let's get on with what has to be done. Let's get on with
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sarah Lyall is a reporter for The New York Times in London.) &LR; 
 &UR; c.1998 The New York Times &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; PLEASE NOTE: THIS STORY IS EMBARGOED UNTIL AUG. 30. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
