A1397 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     08-25 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIST IGNORES NOTED AUTHORS WHO EEKED INTO 20TH CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In selecting both judiciously and capriciously those works that
would be anointed as the 100 best novels published in English in
the 20th century, the editorial board members of the Modern Library
made certain that Henry James would be aboard.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that Henry Junior of the elegant James clan is a
19th-century figure whose greatest works _ ``The Portrait of a
Lady,'' ``The Bostonians,'' ``Washington Square,'' ``Daisy
Miller,'' ``The Spoils of Poynton,'' the novella ``The Turn of the
Screw'' _ all appeared in print before the century's turn. But the
master lived on until 1916; and ``The Wings of the Dove,'' ``The
Ambassadors'' and ``The Golden Bowl'' are authentic 20th-century
productions.
</P>
<P>
   They're good books, too. Certainly they're superior to some of
the entries on the now-rather-infamous list, and the balloteers may
feel cleansed because Henry James wasn't forgotten. But a protest
may be in order because other notable 19th-century folk who wrote
into the 20th century were rudely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain, for one. ``The Man That Corrupted Hadleyburg'' was
published in 1900; and whether that was the last year of one
century or the first year in another, it's the same year that saw
publication of Theodore Dreiser's ``Sister Carrie,'' which made the
list.
</P>
<P>
   There's also ``The Mysterious Stranger,'' issued in 1916, six
years after Twain's death. It's an abrasive fable, and like
``Hadleyburg'' is a product of the pessimism that darkened Sam
Clemens' later years. Perhaps they weren't considered because they
fell short of what may be deemed standard length for a novel. (That
line of thought may also have deprived Edith Wharton's ``Ethan
Frome'' of residence on the list.)
</P>
<P>
   Herman Melville died in 1891, but regardless of when ``Billy
Budd'' was actually written, it was not published until 1924; and
the Modern Library people specified ``published in'' rather than
``written in.'' ``Billy Budd'' is a supreme ironic tragedy at full
length. One wonders whether it was considered at all.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Crane died in 1900 at age 28. Frank Norris died in 1902
at age 32. Crane's ``Maggie: A Girl of the Streets'' and ``The Red
Badge of Courage'' belong to the 19th century's final decade, and
Norris' great novel ``McTeague'' _ the source of Erich von
Stroheim's silent-film classic ``Greed'' _ arrived in the fall of
1899, six months ahead of ``Sister Carrie.'' Yet both Crane and
Norris could have made the 20th-century roll call, and I would have
had them on it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Crane's ``Whilomville Stories,'' published in the late
spring of 1900, only a few days before the author's death on June
5. It's a collection of short stories _ united, however, by setting
and characters, in the manner of Sherwood Anderson's ``Winesburg,
Ohio,'' which made the list and now has fragile identity as a
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Norris has the better claim. His ambitious ``Epic of the
Wheat'' was projected as a trilogy. The first installment, ``The
Octopus,'' arrived in 1901 as a subject for critical acclaim; even
today, some rate it above ``McTeague.'' Norris completed ``The
Pit'' before his death, and in 1903 it was a resounding success
both critically and commercially. But ``The Wolf'' was only
outlined and left unwritten; had the trilogy been completed, Norris
would be a household name today. No matter, ``The Octopus'' should
be on that infernal list.
</P>
<P>
   Both Crane and Norris received early encouragement from Mark
Twain's great champion, who was William Dean Howells. Living long
enough (1837-1920) to become a has-been in his own lifetime,
Howells nonetheless is the prophet of realism and a figure of
lasting historical importance in American literature. I would
include his last novel _ ``The Leatherwood God'' (1916) _ among the
century's great novels, just to get him on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Have I read it? No. That doesn't deter the Modern Library gang,
so let me be as whimsical.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
