<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A WAY TO GET YOUR GROOVE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, everybody is talking about Ms. Stella and her
missing groove. Stella is the main character in Terry McMillan's
bestseller ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.'' The book, which was
published in 1996, was made into a recently released movie produced
by the author and starring the phenomenal actress Angela Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, for the terminally uncool, your ``groove'' is like
your joie de vivre: a delight in being alive or carefree enjoyment
of living.
</P>
<P>
   The movie synopsis: Stella Payne is 42, divorced, a high-powered
investment analyst, mother of 11-year-old Quincy _ and she does it
all. In fact, if she doesn't do it, it doesn't get done, from
Little League car-pool duty to analyzing portfolios to folding the
laundry and bringing home the bacon. She does it all well, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Stella is tired and stressed out so she takes an impromptu
trip to Jamaica, where she meets Winston Shakespeare, a ``tall,
lean, soft-spoken, Jamaican, (who) smells of citrus and the ocean -
and is half her age.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just the introduction to the book. Now, toss in a big
movie screen, a 40-year-old superstar actress with the body of a
25-year-old and a young, virile actor with a megawatt smile and a
body so chiseled that you could play jacks on it. Honey child, if
you're still wondering why women are flocking to see this movie,
you might need to check on your own groove.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, I'm not a movie critic so I am under no
obligation to evaluate the artistic merits of this screenplay. I
loved it and I'm going to see it again because Stella's best
friend, played by Whoopi Goldberg, was so funny that I missed half
of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's sort of nice to see the tables turned for a
change. All summer long, we've been bombarded with movies starring
middle-aged men with women who could be their daughters. Where are
Sally Field and Meryl Streep, anyway? Was I the only one who
enjoyed ``The Bridges of Madison County''?
</P>
<P>
   One critic I read said that Stella was ``unrealistic.'' Hello!
That's why I go to the movies, to escape reality. If I want the
real world, I'll go over to my cousin's house and listen to her
sweet, but colicky baby scream for two hours while she cooks chili
with too many beans in it. As for my movies, I want beautiful
people, in beautiful places, doing incredible things that will
never happen to me in a million years.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Stella was happy, the audience applauded, and all
the women rushed home to work out so that they could have a body
like Angela Bassett. Yeah, I know, fat chance, but what did we say
about reality?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
