<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-25 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY'S ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Naturally we noticed the deliberate way that Hillary Clinton
avoided body contact with her husband as they got on the plane for
Martha's Vineyard. And how when they arrived she took off in a
different direction and he seemed to momentarily misplace her.
</P>
<P>
   She was as gracious as ever to the crowd but still allowed a
hint of cold shoulder to the man who did her wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In that way she didn't disappoint. We wanted her to show at
least a trace of legitimate anger.
</P>
<P>
   But what else was going on behind those dark glasses?
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson said Hillary Clinton felt humiliated. Spokeswoman
Marsha Berry suggested she was angry.
</P>
<P>
   But was she furious? Was she feeling like a chump? Did she wince
when greeted with open arms by Vernon Jordan, the friend who helped
the other woman get a job? Was she wishing she could back up the
ramp and fly on to Nantucket?
</P>
<P>
   And what are we hard-core Hillary fans, who wavered on Bill
through these tawdry times but remained steadfast to Hillary,
supposed to think now?
</P>
<P>
   We said if it's okay with Hillary, it's okay with us. Maybe they
had an arrangement. But at the same time we got mad on her behalf
and felt sick for her. Even before he went on TV and admitted to
the relationship with Monica Lewinsky, we wondered how Hillary
could stand all the snickering. As much as she's protested her
husband's innocence we wished she had a lamp to throw or a string
of lovers to give her comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night Hillary fans, like everyone else, tuned into every
breathless update on late night TV. We railed at Bill Clinton for
being so stupid and wished Hillary could be doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   She has lots of friends and fans, but who is her confidante? At
a time like this you need more than the ghost of Eleanor Roosevelt
to confide in. You need a friend who will pour you a glass of
brandy, pass you a box of Kleenex and let you rip.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton has made a lot of sacrifices for the sake of the
presidency. At times it seemed she was the greater patriot,
considering what she is willing to give up for her country.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy public opinion and presidential advisers she's been
remodeled, re-coiffed, muffled and silenced. She's had to edit her
opinions, reign in her intelligence, quiet her influence and stifle
her emotions.
</P>
<P>
   She's been mocked and burned in effigy and told to butt out of
public life. At the same time her personal life has been dragged
through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   She has willingly changed her image to keep her husband popular.
She's worn warm colors and pushed her hair into a headband and
refrained from being uppity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she hasn't backed off to the point of being ineffectual and
has continued to speak out on women's rights. In all the advances
to women credited to the Clinton presidency no one doubts her
significance. Fans enjoyed the romance of the Clinton marriage,
too. For all the skepticism that theirs was a political
arrangement, the two came across as a couple very much in love.
Here was a modern marriage between two equals, who respected each
other and cuddled too. Then he had to wreck it.
</P>
<P>
   So what role does Hillary play now? She has been the adoring
wife and the loyal wife but she's never played the sappy
long-suffering wife.
</P>
<P>
   It must gall her to know that some people who didn't like her
when she was strong now give her high approval because they feel
sorry for her.
</P>
<P>
   The other night a TV commentator said Bill Clinton must now
realize how much his forgiving wife loves him and you wanted to
shout back, ``That isn't the question.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even a loyalist has to wonder if Hillary really was the
last to know.
</P>
<P>
   How do you find out one day that your husband has been lying to
you and over the weekend help him write his apology?
</P>
<P>
   For how long has she been walking across the White House lawn,
holding the presidential hand and looking cozy while digging her
fingernails in deep?
</P>
<P>
   She's an intelligent and savvy woman and has known her husband
from past infidelities. Would she have let him lie this long to
her? And continue to lie to the country?
</P>
<P>
   With all that's happened, we don't want to be disappointed by
Hillary, too. We don't want to hear her say some day that she knew
about it all along, and she lied to us to protect her husband and
her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   We want to stick by her, share the pain, withhold the pity and
hope she finds an isolated beach where she can kick sand and scream
into the wind.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for the Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
