A1474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-SCHOOL-HNS &LR;      08-25 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-SCHOOL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S TOP PARTY SCHOOL ISN'T TOASTING DESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A national survey released Monday has rated the
State University of New York at Albany the top party school in the
country. But there were no chants of ``We're Number One'' from
administrators or students.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 edition of the Princeton Review Guide awarded the
dubious honor in its seventh annual ``unscientific index of campus
life and customer satisfaction'' based on responses to
questionnaires by 56,000 students at 311 of the nation's top
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Many at the school felt it was getting a bum rap, as they did
last year when the review _ which has no connection to Princeton
University _ had the school ranked No. 3 in the nation. Last year's
No. 1 party school, according to the guide, was West Virginia
University, which is now ranked No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think we're the number-one party school,'' said
Albany spokeswoman Mary Fiess. ``We think our students and parents
of our students know about our quality academic programs, but we
are concerned about prospective students who might be misled by
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiess conceded the school has problems with alcohol abuse, but
they are no different than the widely reported problems of binge
drinking on campuses throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   She said the institution has a ``zero-tolerance policy''
regarding substance abuse and strict policies for violations by
campus organizations. In the last year, for example, the university
severely sanctioned a fraternity found guilty of hazing.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Custard, author of the guide, said the party list always
sparks the most controversy but said it shouldn't be taken
seriously. He said it is based on an unscientific survey of several
hundred students at each campus and makes no claims to be
statistically accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing this mostly for fun,'' Custard said. ``We
strongly encourage people not to jump to conclusions about things
like a party-school list. For example, if you look at the schools
on the top of that list _ Albany, Wisconsin, the University of
Florida _ those are great schools, there's no question about that.
All we're pointing out is these are places where they are having a
lot of pretty exuberant fun. Hopefully, they are doing it
responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the spirit in which Albany senior Katie Martyn took the
findings. The 22-year-old human-biology major works as a waitress
at The Washington Tavern, itself rated in a magazine survey last
summer as one of the top 100 college bars in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a party school, because I know that people who
come to visit me from other schools cannot get over how late the
bars are open or how many people are out or how many parties are
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   She has spent so much time partying that it will take her
another year to get her degree, she said, but she has both enjoyed
her time at school and is getting a good education. But she
recognizes that some people will be uncomfortable with a
party-school label.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was almost universally glum from the students
interviewed for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Shatz, a senior and political-science major, said the
reputation is not at all accurate and the designation is harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's detrimental to the reputation of the students when they
come out of here,'' Shatz, 20, said.
</P>
<P>
   She worked for telemarketing efforts by the school and said last
year's survey label hampered fund-raising. ``Every time you call
and ask for money, parents or people in the community say, `I'm not
going to contribute to a school like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Franzoso, 21, a senior and psychology major, said when her
parents heard about the ranking last year they expressed their
concern that their tuition money was being wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Another student said she got a call from her grandmother in
Ohio, who learned about last year's ranking from news media.
</P>
<P>
   Brigid Bergin, 20, a senior and vice president of the Student
Association, said the label is unjustified and a result of flawed
methodology.
</P>
<P>
   And then she offered some rankings of her own: ``We're here for
academics. We're here because we have the number-five public policy
department in the nation, because we have the number-one criminal
justice department ... because our business school is competitive
with business schools at Ivy Leagues. We're just smarter because
we're saving a lot of money in our education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
