<HEADER>
A1489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDOWS-SOMMELIER-ART     08-25 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOWS-SOMMELIER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING MATCHMAKER FOR FOOD AND WINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Andrea Immer bounds up to a table at Windows on
the World, she faces diners who invariably seem wary. Dressed in
her severe black pants suit and white blouse, she is clearly not
the waitress. She did not welcome them at the door, so she is
neither hostess nor maitre d'. And her greeting is so relentlessly
energetic, there is a fleeting suspicion that she might try
recruiting volunteers for the hokeypokey.
</P>
<P>
   What almost no one assumes _ with her brisk demeanor that seems
part corporate executive, part kindergarten teacher _ is that she
is the sommelier, overseeing one of the city's most respected
cellars, one that accounts for $5 million in wine sales a year. Not
only that, but she holds the title of BEST sommelier in the
country, as she was judged last year by the Sommelier Society of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Immer, who is 31 and stands all of 5 feet 2 inches, looks as
if she couldn't buy a beer without being carded. But make no
mistake. She not only is intimately acquainted with all 870 wines
in the restaurant's cellar, but also spent a year studying
thousands more to represent the United States in the Sommelier
World Championship, held earlier this summer in Vienna. Though she
did not win (the representative from Germany did), she was one of
only two women among 30 contestants.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening at Windows, she approached a table of four _
three women and a man. ``We're going to defer to the gentleman,''
one of the women said, when asked about wine. ``That's nice for a
change of pace,'' Ms. Immer shot back. They all laughed. The man
did not. Instead, he began a rapid-fire quiz of vineyards and
vintages, all of which she parried expertly.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he asked sulkily, ``How's the Araujo drinking?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' she said. He nodded, as she took off for the cellar to
retrieve the $140 bottle of cabernet sauvignon, one of the most
sought-after boutique wines from the Napa Valley. ``Awesome
choice,'' she concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Her next stop was a private dining room where four men in
suspenders barely acknowledged her. One managed to break away from
the conversation long enough to bark, ``White.''
</P>
<P>
   She surveyed their food order. ``They're having steak and
lobster,'' she said, ``so we'll do something big and brawny. The
Girard chardonnay is drinking so great now. I know they'll be super
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   How can she muster so much perkiness in the face of so much
rudeness?
</P>
<P>
   She shrugged. ``It's a great challenge particularly with men,''
she said. ``You need a different game face. There's a huge
clientele that wants to play around with you, but that's part of
what the restaurant business is. What's nice about it is that the
business is also extremely personal, an opportunity to try to
share, to make the experience much more than a drink. If you get
people in the right frame of mind, you can get them in this sharing
thing with wine that's so personal. It's why chefs cook for people.
It's a total thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   The job description for a sommelier, Ms. Immer said, is someone
who needs ``an encyclopedic palate, a keen sense of diplomacy and
empathy table-side _ hopefully also a sense of humor.'' All of
which is at odds with the caricature of the traditional sommelier,
a portly, older gentleman bearing a silver tasting cup and a
permanent air of condescension.
</P>
<P>
   She decanted the bottle of Araujo, holding it over a candle to
illuminate the sediment, then pinched out the flame with her
fingers. ``You can't blow in the dining room, it's like sneezing,''
she explained. She poured a tiny bit into a glass, swirled it and
sniffed. ``Mmm, pretty,'' she said, adding, ``We don't use doilies
and coasters here because we want to reduce the paraphernalia
table-side. It's less imposing.''
</P>
<P>
   She darted from one table to another like a firefly. Not all
customers had the expertise of the man at the first table, and
after Ms. Immer gently guided them _ asking about their food and
the wines they liked _ they seemed to leave having learned a new
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter went by with a tray holding a bright green drink. It is
the restaurant's version of iced tea, which in her dual capacity as
beverage director, Ms. Immer created. ``It's brewed green tea and
spearmint leaves, sweetened with kiwi syrup and pineapple juice,''
she said. ``Delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   How does she have the time to run such an enormous cellar and
invent cocktails as well? ``Cocktails are job security,'' she said.
``People drink a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Glancing at her watch, she took off for her office to call her
4-year-old son, Lucas, to say goodnight. Then it was back to the
restaurant, where she had a few more hours to go to meet her
regular 11-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 22 years of great wine and great wine history
here,'' she said. ``I don't want to blow it.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Grand Forks, N.D., as Andrea McKinster, she said: ``I'm
Scotch-Irish with a little Cherokee Indian thrown in. It's the only
exotic thing I can lay claim to.'' She and her older brother grew
up in Florida, Texas and Indiana; her father was a much-transferred
manager for Pillsbury. ``We ate a lot of slice-and-bake cookies
when we were little,'' Ms. Immer said.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Southern Methodist University in 1988 and
spent a year in the financial analyst program at Morgan Stanley.
``I could see all too clearly the proscribed path of that career
track,'' she said. ``I didn't like the idea that life could be so
pedestrian. I tried to think of a new way to spin it.''
</P>
<P>
   While still employed there, she volunteered at the International
Wine Center and the Windows on the World Wine School, pouring for
wine classes. ``At first it was learning for fun,'' she said. ``But
the more I did it, it became a different type of learning _ like
opera or orchids, a culture. I was intrigued by the sheer hedonism
of the experience combined with the absolute certainty that I could
never master it. I could go on forever and always have the thrill
of a neophyte.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She moved on to an importing company to do public relations,
then called Kevin Zraly, the director of the wine school at
Windows, who advised her to spend time in Europe. She bought a
Eurailpass and a youth hostel card and took off, alone, for five
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I left, typical me, I sent faxes, letters or postcards
to every place listed in the Wine Spectator,'' she said.
``Sometimes when I showed up, people said, `Who the hell are you?'
but most of the time they showed me the vineyards _ as soon as they
saw how absolutely gung-ho I was. Wine people are so incredibly
giving and sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the States in the fall of '90, she returned to the
International Wine Center, where she ran tastings, taught some
introductory classes and honed her abiding passion for pinot noirs,
especially those from the Russian River Valley in Northern
California. ``To me it's the perfect grape,'' she said. ``The
flavor is intense, but it has a silky almost ethereal texture, so
it goes great with almost any food.''
</P>
<P>
   The following January, Zraly hired her to run the wine school at
Windows. At night she worked in the cellar to learn the wines, and
gradually she trained in the restaurant with the sommelier before
working her own shifts. Two years later when the cellar master
left, she got the job, the first woman at Windows to do so.
</P>
<P>
   She was thrilled. ``The cellar master buys the wine, works the
floor, trains the staff,'' she said. Three months later the World
Trade Center was bombed, and she was out of a job. She became
pregnant that spring, and after her son was born she worked as the
maitre d'hotel and sommelier in the dining room at the Hilton Hotel
in Short Hills, N.J. Less than a year later she became the beverage
director at Restaurant Associates, but once Windows on the World
was scheduled to reopen, she returned.
</P>
<P>
   Her career ascension has been dizzying, to say the least. Last
year she became a co-host of ``Quench,'' a talk show on the Food
Network. She seems to do it all. ``I've always been the kind of
person who could think about a fantasy in a rather calculated
way,'' she said, ``which is strange sounding, but when I saw the
possibilities about the industry I had fallen in love with, I could
see what I needed to do to gain a mastery of the field. It became
obvious I had to immerse myself, make a serious commitment of time
to taste and read and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other wine professionals applaud her despite her unorthodox
background. The traditional route to becoming a sommelier is either
through spending a longer time in a restaurant setting or working
for a wine retailer or buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has excellent taste and an excellent comprehension of
wine,'' said Daniel Johnnes, the wine director for Montrachet and
the Myriad Restaurant Group. ``She's doing a great service for
people who want to get into the industry, especially women. She
changed careers to follow a passion and reached a pinnacle.''
</P>
<P>
   The support is not unanimous, however. There is some sniping
within the industry about what is perceived as Ms. Immer's talent
for self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Zraly insisted. ``Andrea has a tremendous passion for
wine,'' he said. ``She tastes like 20 wines a day, and I think she
deserves all the credit she gets. It bothers me to hear a charge of
self-promotion. But it must be part of being on top. People go
after you.''
</P>
<P>
   Later this fall, Ms. Immer will help reopen Cellar in the Sky,
the wine restaurant at Windows on the World, which closed in
February. Its original concept of a $125 prix-fixe tasting menu
paired with wines dating to 1977 did not succeed. ``More people
know what they want now,'' she said. ``The Cellar will be an a la
carte restaurant with a simple market-driven menu heavily reliant
on wine.''
</P>
<P>
   When she's not working, she is at home in Glen Rock, N.J., with
Lucas and her husband, Bob Immer, who consults on wine for
educational programs and corporate events.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Immer's parents, who have settled in Charlotte, N.C.,
did not drink wine when she was growing up, they do now. Like many
Americans, she says, they drink bag-in-box wine. ``It's a five- or
eight-liter container with a plastic spigot you keep in the fridge
so it disperses into the glass,'' she said. ``Gallo, Inglenook,
Almaden all make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Can she say they are good with a straight face? She nodded
earnestly. ``Generally, I would say the table wine standard in this
country is decent,'' she said. ``I would like it if they traded up,
because they would enjoy it. But for heaven's sake, they're
drinking wine. They don't expect to be judged on their selection.
That would be mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Her democracy extends past wine, to the tequila tasting she ran
recently at Windows as part of a series that included sessions on
Cognac and Armagnac. More than 50 people crammed behind place
settings boasting three types of tequila. The room smelled like a
bad headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``I included tequila in the seminars on a dare,'' she told her
class. ``I guess anytime you drink tequila it's on a dare.'' They
laughed appreciatively.
</P>
<P>
   As the progression of tastings went on, Ms. Immer held up the
bottle the class was savoring, a Sauza Tres Generaciones. ``See
that the shape is the same as a Cognac bottle,'' she said, ``which
means `Compare me to Cognac, the bottles are the same.'''
</P>
<P>
   Someone groaned out loud. Ms. Immer drew herself up to her full
height, and her smile dimmed. ``Don't be a snob,'' she instructed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
