<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEATGUIDE-TEX     08-25 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEATGUIDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUIDE TO PERSPIRATION, FROM ECCRINE GLANDS TO LOVE APPLES TO
OZONE HOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably a fair assumption that you're sweating more than
usual this summer. In honor of this much-maligned physical
function, we offer the following information as our Ode to Sweat.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCIENCE OF SWEAT: Sweating is good for you! Sweating
regulates body temperature by cooling the blood. Human skin houses
up to 4 million sweat glands; backs, chests and foreheads have the
highest concentration, but the glands in the armpits are the most
active. Eccrine glands _ in the palms and soles, for instance _
respond to raised body temperature by secreting a colorless sweat
that is mostly water. Apocrine glands _ most numerous in the
armpits, groin and nipple area _ produce the stinky sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat doesn't inherently smell. It takes an hour for bacteria on
the skin's surface to break down the sugars and fats in apocrine
sweat before people are asking you to leave the room. Deodorants
kill the bacteria; antiperspirants work by preventing sweat from
reaching the skin's surface.
</P>
<P>
   The other downside of sweating is dehydration. Sweat contains
sodium, chloride and potassium _ the much-ballyhooed
``electrolytes'' lost along with water when we perspire.
Electrolytes function as the electric currents that allow nerves
and muscles to talk to one another. Lose too much sweat, and you're
in for muscle spasms, cramping and fatigue, says Craig Horswill, a
research scientist with Gatorade's Sports Science Institute in
Barrington, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   At room temperature, most of us produce 200 milligrams of
underarm sweat an hour. Multiply that by three when you're sitting
in 100-degree temps. And Horswill reports that a quart of sweat
(try not to picture that) contains from 460 to 1,380 milligrams of
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   A HISTORY OF DEODORANTS: Prior to the 19th century, Westerners
disguised body odor with perfumes or not at all; they didn't really
care much. Then scientists discovered sweat glands, and women began
rubbing their underarms with ammonia and water.
</P>
<P>
   In 1888, the first trademarked commercial deodorant _ Mum _
appeared in cream form. An early 20th-century product, Everdry, not
only stung the skin but also ate right through clothing. Roll-ons
debuted in the middle of the century, according to Proctor &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   The first aerosol hit the shelves in 1959, and by the early '70s
aerosols accounted for more than 80 percent of the market. But a
mid-'70s ban on CFCs and on the use of aluminum zirconium in
aerosols put the kibosh on those sprays. Dress shields also became
a popular method among women for absorbing sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the companies say their most effective products are the
clear gels and ``soft solid'' antiperspirants _ the ones that don't
leave those annoying white marks on your clothes.
</P>
<P>
   DRY, GOOD. WET, BAD: Americans don't like to sweat. That's
evident in the $1.6 billion we spend a year on sticks, roll-ons,
powders, creams and sprays. Men generally sweat more than women,
but women have more apocrine glands (the ones that produce body
odor) and use more antiperspirants or deodorants than men (95
percent compared with 91 percent), according to the Gillette Co.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy business people have developed all sorts of products to
combat sweat: sprays for hat rims and shirts, and clothing that
wicks sweat away from the body or absorbs it. Scientists have yet
to conclusively link the aluminum in deodorants to Alzheimer's
disease, but alternative, ``natural'' products abound.
</P>
<P>
   THE CULTURE OF SWEAT: Not everyone in the world is as
embarrassed by sweat as Americans are. Members of a New Guinea
tribe take leave of one another by placing their hands under each
other's arm pits and rubbing themselves with the other's scent.
</P>
<P>
   Smelling au naturel was de rigueur in Elizabethan times, when
women would present their beaus with ``love apples,'' notes a 1996
National Geographic article. The women held peeled apples under
their arms long enough to absorb their odor, then gave the fruit to
their lovers to inhale while they were apart.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat as an aphrodisiac has some scientific backing. Through our
underarm sweat, we emit pheromones. Humans can't smell these
chemicals, but our bodies register and react to them. Researchers
have determined that women's ovulation cycles are lengthened and
shortened by exposure to different pheromones.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a shvitz for health has a long history. In Native
American cultures, sweat lodges have long been places of physical
and spiritual purification. Indians compare lodges to a mother's
womb and say they emerge ``feeling like a newborn baby.'' In
Finland, saunas are nearly as universal as bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   HOW NOT TO SWEAT: For people afflicted with hyperhidrosis
(excessive sweating), everyday social and professional duties can
be a nightmare. But science has developed several treatments for
the sweatiest among us. Doctors often prescribe Drysol, a roll-on
product, to staunch underarm sweating, says Dr. Raymond Garcia, an
Irving, Texas, dermatologist.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new procedure involves making a small incision
under each armpit and inserting an instrument and fiber-optic
camera into the chest cavity. The surgeons then sever the nerve
that controls sweating.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, mainly to control profuse sweating of the palms,
has a ``99 percent immediate success rate,'' says Dr. David Sekons,
a general surgeon at Beth Israel Hospital in New York City who
regularly performs the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The traditional approach
</P>
<P>
   Aerosols: The mid-'70s saw a couple of crises for aerosol
deodorants, which had captured 80 percent of the market. The
government banned the use of CFCs in reaction to ozone depletion.
Safety concerns about aluminum zirconium led to a ban of that
ingredient in aerosols.
</P>
<P>
   Roll-ons: Ultra-popular substitute for the aerosol. Debuted in
the '40s when, finally, customers could discreetly choose their
deodorants from store shelves instead of having to ask the grocer
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Clear gels: Consumers assume their deodorant will work these
days; now they're concerned about how it looks when it goes on.
Enter the clear category. Clear antiperspirants promise no annoying
white stains on clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Soft solids: Look opaque but go on clear. Tres cutting-edge.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The organic approach
</P>
<P>
   If you're more concerned about chemicals than perspiration, an
alternative deodorant might be up your alley. Your
``Star-Telegram'' tester tried four, and they all worked equally
well at keeping said tester smelling perfectly unoffensive (at
least, no one complained to my face).
</P>
<P>
   Remember, these are not antiperspirants; be prepared to sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally Fresh Deodorant Crystal: Our favorite of the
alternatives. Looks like a big crystal and goes on like a roll-on.
You have to wet it to use it, but it dries immediately. The company
claims the crystal will last up to a year. No scent. $6.95.
</P>
<P>
   Now Long-Lasting Deodorant Cream: Has to be smeared on, which is
pretty messy. Also, smelled strongly medicinal. $5.95.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Crystal Deodorant Spray: Went on uncomfortably wet and
stayed that way for a while. No scent. $4.35.
</P>
<P>
   Tom's of Maine Natural Gentle Deodorant: Also went on wet and
sort of sticky, but the earthy Woodspice scent was pleasant enough.
$5.55.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
