</P>
<P>
   HBO-WEBMD _ HBO &AMP; Co. has bought 5 percent of WebMD Inc. for $10
million. Story will address why deal was made, benefit to both
firms and comment from analyst. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GA-Y2K _ ATLANTA _ Public services' Y2K fixes are being
monitored by a Y2K users group consisting of volunteers from
Atlanta area companies. (Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CST-SOFTWARE _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based CST's software brings
mainframe dinosaurs into graphical point-and-click modern age.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MERGERS _A Wall Street analyst last week talked to a
roomful of telecommunications executives, lawyers and researchers
about the massive rash of mergers and acquisitions in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ferency of Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. said federal telecom
deregulation, an until-recently surging stockmarket and low
interest rates are fueling the urge to merge. The combined value of
newly wed U.S companies in 1985 was $241 billion. In the first two
quarters of this 1998 alone, the combined value of merged U.S.
companies was $907 billion. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COMPOSER _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech's first
composer-in-residence is a man who loves to talk music and
technology, and that's why he's so right for his job. He has
accumulated a wealth of musical experience and credits in Hollywood
and with his stand alone pieces, such as his Concerto No. 1 for
Orchestra and Timpani. But he is also comfortably at home with his
colleagues in the Interactive Media Technology Center at Tech,
where he employs electronics to extend the musical palette.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PORTALS _ A look a the portal craze among Web sites not
traditionally thought of as portals. How they are trying to keep
Web surfers from surfing by providing a variety of goods and
services and features. Also incudes plans of CNNfn to become
something of a portal for the financial world. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SYNQUEST _ ATLANTA _ Your company is expanding rapidly but where
do you put a new plant? It's a big decision that has wrecked many
an expanding company. But what's dangerous for many companies is a
marketing opportunity for Joe Trino and his Atlanta-based SynQuest.
His company makes industrial strength software that helps chief
executives make big decisions about such things as new plant
openings. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDTREK _ DULUTH, Ga. _ Soundtrek is a company with only four
employees, but it has a global reach and an idea that just might
set the 21st century to rocking. Soundtrek makes the Jammer, the
most sophisticated of several programs that use computers as a tool
for composing music. Select the instruments, a style, from Tex-Mex
to techno, plug in chords and other musical data, and the Jammer
will compose away endlessly. For jingle-writers, arrangers and,
yes, those who only dream of being the next Quincy Jones, it's a
godsend. With more on how the Jammer works, its possibilities and
how the small company works. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ Newt Gingrich makes more supportive comments about
Microsoft than in the past at a fundraiser in Seattle. (Sherman,
Cox News Service) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-DELPHI _ Delphi Automotive's Vandalia airbag plant has
landed three major business contracts to manufacture door inserts
for General Motors Corp. and Navistar Int. The contracts could
create as many as 175 jobs at the plant that was on the brink of
losing more than half of its work force earlier this year. Delphi
officials credit the union's willingness to accept a new local
contract agreement as the main reason for winning the new business.
That contract enhanced the plant's tiered-wage scale that already
paid new workers about $8 an hour. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CATTLE-CANADA _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Western beef producers
are organizing and raising money to pursue an international trade
complaint against Canada. They allege that subsidized Canadian beef
imports _ boxed and on the hoof _ are driving down domestic calf
prices by $100 to $250 a head. (McGregor, Grand Junction Daily
Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CATTLE-CANADA-RANCHER _ NEW CASTLE, Colo. _ Barton Porter
supported the North American Free Trade Agreement, but now he feels
that U.S. beef packers are taking advantage of the open border to
buy cheap Canadian cattle. Since early 1997 the price of meat has
stuck below $60 a hundredweight, said Porter, 74, a rancher and
feeder. (McGregor, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-METRO _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Capital Metro, which has been
without a general manager since December, is getting a new boss
from Buffalo, N.Y. The board of directors voted recently to begin
negotiating with Karen Rae, acting director of surface
transportation for the Niagara Frontier Transportation Authority in
Buffalo, to take over Capital Metro's top job. (Hiott, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-TECH _ AUSTIN -- It's official: nerds and geeks outnumber
wildcatters and roughnecks in the Lone Star state. That trend is
sure to continue, said Comptroller John Sharp. ``High technology
has emerged as one of the main engines of economic growth in the
state,'' said Comptroller John Sharp. ``There are strong signals
that our high-tech industry will become even more dominant in the
next century.'' (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BANKS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ After three years of record
profits, Texas banks may be headed for some turbulence. Earnings
were still good for the state's 855 banks in the first quarter
1998, according to the latest figures from Austin-based bank
research company Sheshunoff Information Services Inc. (Golz, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-NEW-SYSTEMS _ ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. and
other personal computer makers announced several new systems
recently that incorporate the newest processors from Intel Corp.,
including a new and improved chip for the sub-$1,000 market.
(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Sunbeam Corp.'s latest turnaround
strategy calls for abandoning cost-cutting plans former Chairman Al
Dunlap put in place before he was fired. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
