<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDALS26-CO     08-25 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDALS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE PUBLIC WEARINESS, SCANDALS WILL CONTINUE, EXPERTS SAY
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Polls show Americans are weary of White House
scandals and wish investigations of President Clinton would just go
away, but that's not going to happen during his presidency,
political and legal analysts predicted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``will remain a presidential litigant for his remaining
time in office,'' said Jonathan Turley, a George Washington
University law professor and frequent legal commentator on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it's not going to end as quickly as the public
would like,'' agreed Thomas Mann, director of government studies
for the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the stories of scandal probably wouldn't end even if
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr were to unexpectedly report to
Congress that he found no wrongdoing in his investigations into
Whitewater and Clinton's relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   There are other headlines on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno is considering whether to call for a
new independent counsel to investigate allegations of illegal
campaign finance abuses in the 1996 presidential race. If she does
so, that probe could last into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   And an appeals court is considering reinstating Paula Jones'
sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton that was dismissed
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion surveys indicate most Americans will not welcome
this news. A Los Angeles Times Poll conducted Aug. 22 found that 63
percent of respondents wished the whole Starr investigation could
simply be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   However, the independent counsel is required by federal law to
report any evidence of impeachable offenses to Congress and all
findings to the three-judge panel that appointed him. With an
election looming in November and a busy legislative agenda to
complete before the scheduled Oct. 9 adjournment, Congress is
unlikely to act quickly on any report from Starr or even to decide
if impeachment hearings are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all sure that you can get to that this year, and
I'm not at all sure that it's a smart idea to try to get to that
this year,'' House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., told The
Washington Post this week.
</P>
<P>
   The process is complex, Mann explained. First, Starr must
complete what is expected to be a massive report to Congress and
submit it to Gingrich. Even when the report has been sent, Starr
may continue to investigate or indict other people and ``chip away
at Clinton through surrogates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress has the report, the House Judiciary Committee
could deal with it in executive session, with leaks keeping the
scandal alive. If formal impeachment hearings convene, they could
last many months. And if the House voted for impeachment, there
would be a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With this long road to travel, amid uncertainty how impeachment
proceedings would play politically, ``we're unlikely to have any
action before the election,'' said Mann.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton acceded to critics' demand that he resign and
spare the country more turmoil, the scandal headlines are unlikely
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reasonably likely'' that Reno will appoint an
independent counsel to investigate campaign finance charges, said
William Schneider, a political analyst for CNN and the American
Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans are demanding the appointment after it
was recommended by both FBI Director Louis Freeh and federal
prosecutor Charles La Bella, whom Reno had appointed to lead the
Justice Department investigation of the charges. And last week, a
1995 White House memo surfaced raising new questions about the role
of Vice President Al Gore in the fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   A new independent counsel would pose problems for both Clinton
and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A probe of campaign fund-raising abuses ``would have what
critics say Starr is missing in the Lewinsky investigation'' _
substance, said Turley. It would deal with charges of official
misconduct, an illegal cover-up and illegal foreign contributions
that affect national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could occupy the remainder of the president's term,''
said Turley.
</P>
<P>
   It would also affect the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``it would hang over Al Gore immediately,'' said Schneider.
``It's hard to run for president with independent counsel
investigating you. It would instantly tie him into Clinton's
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters would be asked, ``Do you want to elect another president
with an independent counsel already there?'' said Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any independent counsel investigation into 1996 campaign
finances is virtually guaranteed to last into the 2000 campaign
season,'' said Mann. ``That would be a disaster for Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Paula Jones case may also come back to haunt
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There was a ``shaky legal foundation for dismissal,'' said
Turley. A conservative Arkansas judge applied a narrow
interpretation of the law _ ruling that even if Clinton did
everything he was accused of doing, it would not amount to sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that ruling were to stand up, it would be a setback for
women in the workplace,'' said Turley. He said a Supreme Court
ruling since the Jones case dismissal creates a much broader
concept of sexual harassment and could apply on the appeal by
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
