<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAPOLEANS-ART-900&AMP;ADD     08-25 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPOLEANS-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINING: INVASION OF THE WOULD-BE NAPOLEONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (nk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What you get from chefs in restaurants today can resemble the
conversation at a cocktail party: some of it smart and a lot of it
showing off. Consider the ostentatious trend toward greater and
greater height on the plate, food sculpture that looks impressive
until you try to eat it, and it falls to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   This trend, which drives chefs to build dishes ever higher, can
be seen perfectly in the proliferation of dishes named after the
napoleon, the classic dessert that has become just about anything
you can imagine, as long as it comes stacked high.
</P>
<P>
   It took pastry chefs more than a century of toiling in the
kitchen to perfect and popularize the napoleon, a prim rectangle of
alternating layers of flaky, buttery puff pastry and
vanilla-scented pastry cream.
</P>
<P>
   Then today's aspiring Napoleons of cuisine got hold of it. Some
of them saw an opportunity to juxtapose contrasting flavors and
textures in imaginative ways; others approached the task like
construction workers, brick and mortar layered ever higher. In
little more than a decade, they have completely changed the
napoleon, often disastrously, sometimes triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, Alfred Portale, the chef at Gotham Bar and Grill,
who is often credited with changing food presentation in New York
restaurants by making things like lamb chops stand up straight on a
plate, is critical of the modern napoleon. ``I don't think it's
neat or fun to build,'' he said. ``There's too much attention paid
to presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick for the diner is to develop an eye for the triumphs
from a mere menu description: the eggplant napoleon at Gramercy
Tavern qualifies. Thin crisp disks of fried eggplant sandwich a
silky eggplant caviar, which melts like butter on the palate.
</P>
<P>
   The clue here is a crisp layer and a soft, creamy layer. If you
can imagine the ingredients coming together to form a layered,
texturally contrasting dish, in the spirit of the original
napoleon, you will probably have found a good variation on the
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Versions in which similar textures are layered together, like
the tiresome roasted vegetable napoleon, should raise suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Without the contrast of textures, and a subtle interplay of
flavors, the napoleon becomes something slightly crude _ a prosaic
stack of raw materials. Why not just add bread and make a sandwich?
</P>
<P>
   Assembling a great napoleon has to be much more than just
slapping ingredients on top of one another. ``You want diners to
feel the contrast,'' said Eric Ripert, the chef at Le Bernardin.
``You want to build different layers with different flavors, but at
the same time you want to keep the dish in harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   The crab napoleon at Le Bernardin may be utterly wild-looking,
but it succeeds in doing just that. It is a postmodern design with
long jagged chards of rice flour wafers, which alternate with
levels of curried peekytoe crab and apple salad. Each bite is
tender, crunchy, moist and dry. Oh, and by the way, intensely
flavored.
</P>
<P>
   Another remarkable version is the smoked salmon and mango
napoleon at La Caravelle. Delicately thin slices of sweet mango and
salmon are tightly layered with creme fraiche, so that the texture
is uniformly silky and unctuous. The dish drips with elegance.
</P>
<P>
   But a pork-and-eggplant napoleon at 27 Standard is the kind of
mess you made as a child when you piled together meat loaf, mashed
potatoes and peas. You get a taste of pork, potato and eggplant in
every mushy bite. Others have structural problems, with ingredients
peeling off like bricks from a Manhattan building.
</P>
<P>
   At Nougatine, paper-thin chocolate disks droop under the weight
of bland raspberries, causing a few to plunge into a bed of diced
raspberry jello. (Remember Lesson 1: If it doesn't sound like a
napoleon, there's no telling what it will taste like.)
</P>
<P>
   With so many interpretations, the word itself is on the verge of
dissolving into meaninglessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like risottos that have nothing to do with arborio rice
or lasagnas that are made with vegetables and no pasta,'' said
Leslie Brennan, a culinary historian from Brooklyn. Which is the
only way to explain why a napoleon can be a pile of yellow, green
and red tomatoes with a green goddess dressing at Lobster Club, a
buttery potato puree braced between thick potato chips and a
truffle sauce at Park Avenue Cafe or a short square of roasted
shrimp sandwiched between thin strips of zucchini at San Domenico.
</P>
<P>
   Where the napoleon is going, as it turns out, is easier to pin
down than its origin. The word ``napoleon'' appears to be a
corruption of ``napolitain'' (Neapolitan), the name of an old
French dessert, which is a layering of butter cookies and jam iced
with fondant. The napoleon dessert as Americans know it, however,
more closely resembles the French pastry called a millefeuille
(thousand-leaf) _ the familiar layering of puff pastry and pastry
cream _ which was created sometime in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The millefeuillelike pastry was introduced to the United States
around the turn of this century. But the word ``millefeuille''
never stuck. Napoleon did.
</P>
<P>
   Designing dishes that use the napoleon construction, Ms. Brennan
said, is a way for chefs to anchor their creative zest to some form
of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them a safe place to experiment in a more measured
way,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even dessert napoleons are rarely left in peace. At Chanterelle,
Michael Klug, the pastry chef, has created a huckleberry napoleon
with such gorgeous shades of purple that it could make Martha
Stewart weep. Each layer is a variation on the fruit: a compote, a
creamy mousse and a tangy sorbet scented with lavender. Neat
triangles of phyllo dough, lacquered with sugar, separate the
layers and are angled so that they form a star.
</P>
<P>
   The strawberry napoleon at Windows on the World is _ naturally
enough in the current craziness _ filled with layers of coconut
creme brulee and towers above a pool of Thai basil sauce and muscat
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the traditional version? Is it gone? Not quite. The
grand old napoleon, whose fragile pastry explodes at the touch of a
fork, may be down, but it is not yet out. It still lurks _ and
often sags _ in the pastry cases of French and Italian pastry shops
across the city. Payard Patisserie offers a lovely plain one with
pastry cream, or one with raspberries. The traditional Argentine
napoleon, called mil hojas, is served at Chimichurri Grill. The
puff pastry, a fat, flaky pillow, sandwiches a thick smear of dulce
de leche, the rich, Latin version of caramel, which is
``lightened'' with whipped cream. There are also chefs who wander
only a few steps from tradition, like Terrance Brennan, the chef at
Picholine, who makes a napoleon with lemon curd.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether the napoleon succeeds or fails, it almost
always presents one obstacle: it is devilishly hard to eat. It is
inclined to flatten on contact _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the thing is too hard, if it really requires a solid blow,
if it flies off the table,'' said Wayne Nish, the chef at March,
``obviously it hasn't been successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
