<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, hurricane warnings were issued from the Carolinas to
Middle Atlantic coast, even as Hurricane Bonnie was still located
nearly 400 miles from shore. Wednesday, tropical storm force winds
exceeding 39 miles an hour along the North Carolina coast will
increase to hurricane force Wednesday morning as Hurricane Bonnie
nears the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusting past 100 miles an hour will buffet a large area
exposed to the eastern side of the hurricane, though the strongest
winds will likely stay offshore. However, hurricane force winds
will only occur in a very narrow band to the west of the
hurricane's center. Tropical squalls will penetrate 75 to 100 miles
inland, though winds will struggle to reach 50 miles an hour away
from the coast. Winds and squalls will increase over the Delmarva
Peninsula and lower Chesapeake Bay Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Outer rainbands from the hurricane will spread up the coast
during the day. Large swells will continue to build from the New
Jersey coast to southern New England, though wind speeds will
remain below 20 miles an hour through Wednesday evening. Hurricane
Bonnie will make its closest approach to these areas late Wednesday
night and on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the remnants moisture from Tropical Storm Charley
will continue to sponsor downpours over parts of central and
southern Texas. Another disturbance will prompt some thundershowers
in the southern Plains near a stalled front. Scattered storms are
expected elsewhere in the Plains and Rocky mountain states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: East Side, West Side &LR;
</P>
<P>
   All sides of a hurricane are not created equal. Given that most
of the hurricanes that affect the East Coast move parallel to the
shoreline, it is the eastern side of the storm that becomes most
dangerous. Here, winds from the south couple with a northward bound
hurricane's forward velocity to produce an enhancement of the
surface wind speed. On the hurricane's western flank, where the
wind blows from the northeast, the opposite occurs. The storm's
northward motion reduces the effective surface wind speed, thereby
sparing the coast from the brunt of an offshore hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
