<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORE-BOUGHT HOMEMADE COOKIES; WORK IN PROGRESS; FOOD MAGAZINE
DEBUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you know your New York bakeries, you might guess
that the Maury of Maury's All-Natural Cookie Dough, now making its
debut at D'Agostino's stores in Manhattan, is Maury Rubin, owner of
City Bakery, 22 E. 17th St. Unlike other chilled slice-and-bake
cookie doughs, the flour and many of the other ingredients are
organic, and it's made with things a home cook might use. In other
words, no preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The dough comes in three classic flavors: chocolate chip,
oatmeal-raisin and peanut butter. All make very good cookies. But
it's important to use a heavy knife to slice through those
chocolate chips, and to allow the somewhat fragile peanut butter
cookies to cool completely before trying to remove them from the
pan. And be sure to use a nonstick pan as directed on the package.
The 18-ounce roll of dough, which sells for $4.99, makes 15 to 24
cookies, depending on the thickness.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who live outside New York, the dough is also
available at Kings Super Markets in New Jersey and Fresh Fields
markets in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding Delicacies
</P>
<P>
   For months, the expansion of Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Ave.
(79th Street), has been a work in progress. It's now virtually
complete, with the new design allowing for more generous displays
of produce, cheese, bread, pastry, meat, smoked fish, and hot and
cold prepared foods. The enlarged seafood counter, which has a
lobster tank, offers a somewhat limited but high-quality selection
of fish and shellfish, including such hard-to-find items as sea
scallops with roe ($17.95 a pound) and langoustines ($18.95 a
pound).
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley, in Type
</P>
<P>
   The Valley Table, a quarterly magazine covering the food and
wine scene in the Hudson Valley, has made its debut with a 36-page
issue. Featured are an article about farmers' markets, with a
directory of them; an interview with John Novi of the DePuy Canal
House, and a useful essay, with recipes, about locally grown
hard-neck garlic, which is often preferred by chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Contributors include Peter Rose, a food historian, and Steven
Kolpan, a wine expert. The Valley Table is distributed free in many
shops and restaurants in the region, some locations in Westchester
County and at the Union Square Greenmarket. Subscriptions are $20 a
year. Information: (914) 361-2436.
</P>
</TEXT>
