<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SUN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-25 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTO THE RISING SUN': SAILING IN THE WAKE OF PORTUGAL'S
NAVIGATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 15th-century voyages of Portuguese navigators and crews,
among the greatest exploits of Europe's great age of exploration,
stir more appreciation than excitement in the four-part documentary
that begins Wednesday night on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The hero among heroes of ``Into the Rising Sun'' is Vasco da
Gama, whose journey to India is being celebrated on its 500th
anniversary, but he does not make an appearance until the third
week. First comes an introduction that combines dashes of
15th-century history with a present-day travelogue of stops along
the sea route from Lisbon to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's opener, ``The Barrier of Fear,'' begins with
the religious and commercial zeal of Prince Henry the Navigator
(who never raised a sail or handled a tiller) and the pressures on
a country squeezed between Spain and the sea. From Lisbon, the
sailing ships ventured across the Strait of Gibraltar to Ceuta in
North Africa for the first Christian attack on the Moors. It seemed
to one chronicler of the time that ``God and greed worked in
perfect harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding Cape Bojador on the northwestern African coast, dreaded
by sailors for its heavy seas populated by fearsome monsters, the
explorers found evidence of life and ventured further down the West
African coast. By the end of the first hour, they have touched on
the Western Sahara, Senegal and the Bijagos Islands, where they
made their first contacts with the native peoples.
</P>
<P>
   In the second hour, next Wednesday, the exploring continues
around the southern tip of Africa, renamed by the upbeat Henry from
the dire Cape of Storms to the Cape of Good Hope. But European
hyperbole did not improve the lot of Africans who were thrown into
the developing slave trade. Then comes da Gama.
</P>
<P>
   The summary is more exciting than the pictures, which fall into
a routine travelogue mode, featuring the faces of Portuguese
commuters and crews on shiny sailing ships and ferry boats and
glimpses of African villages.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the series, you can travel the Malay Peninsula
from Singapore to Bangkok aboard the Eastern &AMP; Oriental Express,
catch a look at Macau and watch a re-enactment of the Portuguese
arrival in Japan, with guns.
</P>
<P>
   It's a respectfully conventional documentary, stocked with
information and scenery, but the daring Portuguese deserve
something more exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   INTO THE RISING SUN
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 10)
</P>
<P>
   John Potthast, executive producer; M. Melanie Pefinis, Alice
Milheiro and Kaye Gustafson, producers; Luc Cuyvers, director and
writer; Guy Cuyvers, composer. An international co-production of
Maryland Public Television, Radio Televisao Portuguesa and Mare
Nostrum Productions in association with Studio Hamburg-Fernseh
Allianz.
</P>
</TEXT>
