<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER RECIPES ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By SHELLY BELZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FLAVORS OF THE CARIBBEAN IN THE AIR (AND ON THE WEB) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the summertime, when the tropics try to migrate to Hudson
Bay, the Caribbean seems awfully close to these northern latitudes.
And just now the flavors of the West Indies _ a medley of fruits,
spices, grains, roots and tubers _ are much in the air. If the
motto ``When in the tropics, cook like the tropics'' appeals to
you, help is at hand on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   An extremely well-stocked site is Recipes From Guyana and the
Caribbean, run by Wayne Moses of Guyana
(www3.nbnet.nb.ca/wmoses/recipes.html). He offers recipes for
island classics like callaloo jumble (salt fish, bacon, beef or
pork, shrimp, the spinachlike callaloo and a few other good things,
all served on rice); mango fly (a drink); banana fritters, and
curried hassars a la Courantyne, which calls for four wirri-wirri
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Moses thoughtfully supplies a great deal of necessary
information: Just click on Frequently Asked Questions. You can
learn there that a hassar is a black catfish about six to eight
inches long with a tough shell, and that wirri-wirri peppers are
edible cherry bombs, like habaneros but less incendiary.
</P>
<P>
   Spiciness is a fact of Caribbean cookery, with its curried
dishes and the omnipresent habanero, or Scotch bonnet, the world's
hottest pepper, which is native to the region. But why do hot
countries favor hot foods? The most widely accepted answer is that
they set off the body's own refrigeration system: A curry
legendarily isn't hot enough until it makes you break out in a cold
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, West Indian Recipes
(www.chrisevelyn.com/WIrecipes.htm), is part of the unofficial
Internet voice of St. Kitts and Nevis and was founded last year by
Christopher Evelyn. The recipes section has a grilled jerk chicken
that calls for 10 pureed Scotch bonnets (serves four); curried
goat, but also a vegetarian curry; banana bread, and black cake, a
Christmas specialty, made with a cup of rum. (``For best results,''
the directions say, ``let the cake remain in the pan while you are
sprinkling it with rum for three days.'')
</P>
<P>
   Windows on Haiti (www.geocities.com/Heartland/Pointe/5200), run
by Guy Antoine, is the hub of an online Haitian cultural center,
with pages on art, books and songs of Haiti. Click on recipes for
dishes like Ti-Malice sauce, a hot sauce that accompanies many
Haitian fish and meat dishes, and pain patate, a potato bread made
from sweet potatoes. There are also chicken with peas (poulet pois
France), and beans and rice, both staples of the Haitian diet.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes on these sites come from many experienced cooks, who
are by and large not professional cookbook writers. They usually
assume that anyone who will cook from their recipes knows in
advance what the dishes are. Some of the directions can be sketchy
or might reflect the conditions of island life. For instance, a
recipe might ask you to grate a coconut for coconut milk, instead
of suggesting you buy a can.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEARY OF SUMMER? THINK COLD SOUP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Soup of the Evening, Beautiful Soup is a Web site that owes its
mellifluous name to the Mock Turtle's song in ``Alice's Adventures
in Wonderland'' (www.geocities.com/NapaValley/6188/hpsoup.html).
Nor do its literary associations end there; at this site, it's
possible by clicking on Food Tales to learn, for instance, what
Samuel Johnson thought of cucumbers (not much).
</P>
<P>
   But for the main reason to know about this site as summer
clings, click on Cold Soups. The menu of tempting recipes includes
vichyssoise, of course, but also Czech blueberry soup (it calls for
1{ cups sour cream, but substituting yogurt would make it lighter);
lime-cucumber soup with a kick (from tequila); golden gazpacho
(made with cantaloupe, yellow peppers and yogurt), and strawberry
balsamic soup (it includes a quart of strawberries, orange and
lemon zest, Grand Marnier and balsamic vinegar).
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when you call up this site with Netscape, a pesky
rectangular window of advertisements pops up with it. Just swat it
on the X in its upper right-hand corner. Whatever you do, don't
minimize it, or it will fall to your tool bar and multiply.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SPA CAN BE CREATIVE, TOO  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many people who try the spa experience find it transformative,
teaching them to slow down, appreciate nature and eat more
healthfully. The Web site of Spa Finders magazine
(www.spafinders.com) makes the immodest claim that spa chefs have
changed the way Americans eat (click on magazine) by bringing
dishes low in both fat and calories into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   To see what all the crowing is about, there's a recipe section
compiled by the International Spa and Fitness Association (click on
spa cuisine and then recipes). The bill of fare includes pesto
risotto di mare; red lentil chili, and grilled mahi-mahi with
herbed couscous and three-bean salad with orange vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating these recipes, Margaret Pierpont, the co-author with
Diane Tegmeyer of ``The Spa Life at Home'' (Longstreet Press,
1997), commented by e-mail: ``Spa chefs create meals that are
highly nutritious, which is why there are many creative ways of
serving fruit and vegetables, beans and whole grains in this
collection.'' She also noted that when meat, fish or poultry is
included, the amounts are small.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are generally for tablefuls of diners and need to be
scaled down. Ms. Pierpont, who collected and tested recipes from
spas all over the country for her book, also faced this problem.
For soups, chilis and breads particularly, she recommends making
the amount called for and refrigerating or freezing the rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
