<HEADER>
A1584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAPOLEAN-CHEF-NYT &LR;      08-25 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPOLEAN-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHEF: FROM SCRATCH (ALMOST), A PASTRY CLASSIC MADE SIMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHARLIE PALMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was just learning about fine cooking as a 14-year-old
apprentice at an inn in upstate New York, I was fascinated by the
dessert cart, as any kid (prospective cook or not) would be. I was
particularly taken with the elaborate pastry cream creations like
the napoleon. And as I learned by the time I got to culinary
school, the ability to create those creamy classics was a hallmark
of the professional.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as rich desserts fell out of favor, I began
experimenting, like many of my contemporaries, with savory
alternatives: doing crisp potato or other vegetable napoleons as
side dishes to accompany meat or game. All of them were fine, as
far as they went, but I missed the old ways.
</P>
<P>
   And just recently, I had the urge to revisit the tantalizing
traditional French dessert cart. But this time I could see no
reason at all to make the napoleon some kind of test of chefhood.
Experience brings with it the confidence to take it easy every now
and then. So I made a few changes, the most significant being the
replacement of the time-consuming, delicate puff pastry with
easy-to-use frozen strudel dough, a more than adequate commercial
product.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the most obvious benefit _ avoiding the
make-it-from-scratch madness of puff pastry _ frozen strudel dough
adds character to the dessert. It is, for instance, much richer in
taste than the also frozen phyllo dough. Once baked, the strudel
dough has a nutty taste that I like a lot. And working with the
frozen dough, you don't have to make a sheet-pan full of desserts,
as I was trained to do; it's much easier to make individual
napoleons.
</P>
<P>
   Then for the cream: I added a bit of gelatin, which gives extra
body. The touch of gelatin insures that the cream will stay set and
not ooze out of the edges of the napoleon. It's more attractive
that way, I think.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, instead of the top glaze, I use a dusting of
confectioners' sugar and a refreshing raspberry-citrus sauce.
Although I chose raspberries in this recipe, there is no reason
that any other ripe berry, fruit or even toasted nuts couldn't be
used as well. (Just remember that with fruits, seasonal is best,
and if you do choose a juicy fruit like peaches or very ripe
strawberries, make sure you allow them to drain well on a triple
layer of paper towels so that they don't make the cream runny.)
</P>
<P>
   The light dusting of confectioners' sugar that replaces the
traditional fondant glaze not only allows the crisp golden dough to
shine through, but also adds an accent to the flavors of the dough,
cream and fruit. To me, the sweetness of the usual glaze often
detracts from these flavors and makes the dessert too heavy.
</P>
<P>
   I know, it sounds as if I've done a lot of cheating here. But I
haven't, really, if the test is in the results. This is a terrific
dessert. It's a direct descendant of the classic napoleon, if
somewhat lighter, and it's in my restaurant repertory now.
Actually, its preparation is so lacking in intimidation that it can
be in anybody's repertory. But if you try it, just don't let on how
easy it is. It still looks difficult.
</P>
<P>
   RED RASPBERRY NAPOLEON
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 4 hours for chilling
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon gelatin
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup Wondra flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half, or whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chilled unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 package frozen strudel dough, thawed according to directions
on package
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 1 cup superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup melted unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 cups fresh raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 3 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Raspberry-Citrus Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh mint, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small pan combine gelatin with \ cup cold water. Place
over low heat, and stir until gelatin has softened, about 1 minute.
Remove from heat, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium mixing bowl, combine egg yolks, egg, salt and
sugar. Whisk to blend. Add flour, and whisk until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large saucepan over medium heat, combine the
half-and-half and remaining \ cup of sugar. Split vanilla bean
lengthwise, scrape pulp into pan, then add the bean. Stir to
dissolve sugar, bring to a boil, and immediately remove from the
heat. Whisk about 1 cup of the hot half-and-half into the egg
mixture, then immediately pour the egg mixture back into saucepan.
Return pan to medium heat, and whisk constantly until thickened,
about 2 to 3 minutes. Add reserved gelatin, reduce heat to low, and
whisk 2 minutes more. Remove from heat, and whisk in the chilled
butter. Pour mixture into a shallow container, and place a piece of
plastic film over the surface. Refrigerate until well chilled,
about four hours.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cut a 2-by-4-inch rectangle of cardboard. Line two baking
sheets with parchment paper. Preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   5. Spread dough on a dry counter, covered by a slightly dampened
kitchen towel. Remove one sheet, and brush lightly with melted
butter. Sprinkle with superfine sugar. Repeat with three more
sheets, and stack them one atop another. Repeat with four more
sheets, to make another stack. Cut sixteen 2-by-4-inch rectangles
from the layered dough by placing the cardboard rectangle on the
top sheet and cutting around it. (Twelve pieces will be needed,
with extra allowed for breakage.) Place dough rectangles on the
baking sheets, and cover them with parchment paper and another
baking sheet to weigh them down. Bake until lightly golden, about 5
minutes; do not overcook. Remove from oven, uncover the baked
dough, and allow to cool. Place rectangles on wire racks and
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   6. Remove vanilla bean from pastry cream. Set aside 20
raspberries. Place four rectangles on each of four plates. Spoon a
heaping tablespoon of cream onto the pastry, and top with a few
raspberries. Add a small spoonful of cream, and top with another
rectangle of pastry. Repeat to make another layer, topped by
pastry. Lightly sift confectioners' sugar over the top. Serve in a
pool of Raspberry-Citrus Sauce, garnished with 5 raspberries, and a
sprig of mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   RASPBERRY-CITRUS SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups fresh raspberries
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan over low heat, combine the raspberries,
orange juice, zest and sugar. Cook, stirring, until raspberries are
soft, about 5 minutes. Remove from heat, and transfer to a blender.
Process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour the raspberry sauce through a very fine sieve, pressing
to extract all of the puree. Discard the seeds. Pour the sauce into
a nonreactive container, and refrigerate until it is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
