<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1586 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIVERSITY-PROGRAMS-KA     08-25 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-PROGRAMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERSITY PROGRAMS MISSING IN ACTION AT MANY COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) One-fourth of America's Fortune 500 companies and
two-thirds of smaller U.S. companies have no diversity program in
place.
</P>
<P>
   In a decade of heightened attention to sexual, racial, age and
religious discrimination, a survey by the Society for Human
Resource Management found that many workplaces had no formal
employee training program to encourage diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons given for not having diversity programs were ``lack of
time,'' ``no need'' or ``low priority level.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies also said they didn't need such a program
because of their size or because they dealt with diversity issues
on an informal basis.
</P>
<P>
   Formal diversity programs typically include staff education
about anti-discrimination and anti-harassment laws plus exercises
that build mutual understanding and respect among workers of varied
backgrounds and values.
</P>
<P>
   Such programs frequently include hiring, promotion and retention
goals to help managers build and keep a diverse staff.
</P>
<P>
   In companies with formal programs, three-fourths of the human
resource officers rated their diversity efforts as very effective,
effective or somewhat effective.
</P>
<P>
   The human resource society noted in its workplace diversity
newsletter that diversity was not a universally accepted goal.
</P>
<P>
   In a Q &AMP; A column by Lee Gardenswartz and Anita Rowe, the
authors wrote that there were ``inevitable demands'' from
``employees who object to homosexuality on religious and personal
grounds,'' for example.
</P>
<P>
   Gardenswartz and Rowe said companies needed to know about and
explain to employees what legal protections are granted certain
groups. Companies also should focus training on tolerance, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees need to be assured that dealing with diversity will
not require them to change their beliefs and values,'' they wrote.
``History shows us that people fight and die to hold on to deeply
held beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, employees do need to be held accountable for
following guidelines regarding nondiscriminatory and respectful
treatment of others on the job. Jokes and slurs about any group,
whether gay-bashing or religion-bashing (or gender, race,
ethnicity, or any other group bashing), are off limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Good diversity programs, they said, make it clear that work
colleagues often have widely different values but can work well
together when everyone shows mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   Complete diversity survey results cost $30 for Society for Human
Resource Management members and $40 for nonmembers. Copies are
available by calling the society at {800-444-5006}.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter listed several other publications dealing with
diversity issues, such as recruiting and retaining older workers,
dealing with religion in the workplace, and providing
domestic-partner benefits. All publications may be purchased by
calling the above phone number.
</P>
<P>
   The society is sponsoring a seminar on workplace diversity Oct.
26-28 in Washington, D.C. Information on the seminar is available
by calling {800-283-SHRM (800-283-7476)}.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1587 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN &LR;      08-25 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Women must take responsibility for promoting themselves in the
workplace  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Businesses are beginning to recognize the value of diversity,
but the task of hiring and retaining talented women and minorities
isn't as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Good intentions aren't enough. It takes time, money and
commitment to build and retain a diverse work force. It also
requires women to take responsibility by making ourselves more
visible.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is GE Appliances in Louisville, Ky. Top
management is committed to diversity. They know it's not just the
right thing to do, it makes economic sense because 80 percent of
purchase decisions are made by women.
</P>
<P>
   So this summer GE began an effort to recruit several hundred
women to fill entry- and midlevel engineering positions in
Louisville. The prospect sounds thrilling but it's a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are lots of women with the right credentials, but
reaching them and persuading them to relocate isn't that easy. To
its credit, GE has done many of the right things, according to
Linda Cooper Kee, president of LGC &AMP; Associates, a Kansas City,
Mo., firm that specializes in diversity management training,
consulting and recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   GE is advertising in publications, visiting schools and hiring
external recruiters who specialize in attracting women.
</P>
<P>
   But even before a firm begins to interview prospective
candidates, it should evaluate its corporate culture to ensure that
it values diversity, said Kee. Employees may not express problems
until they are directly asked.
</P>
<P>
   Managers, Kee said, need to understand why diversity is valuable
to their company. If new hires don't feel comfortable and valued,
they will leave and your time and money spent recruiting them will
be wasted.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, women need to take greater responsibility for
their careers. Many of us naively believe that if we work hard and
do a good job, employers will recognize our hard work.
</P>
<P>
   As impossible as it sounds, it's crucial that women take the
time to network and belong to professional organizations, said
Andrea Hall, the first woman senior vice president at the Midwest
Research Institute in Kansas City, a position she still holds.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's career exemplifies the importance of networking. She said
she found all her jobs through contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also encouraged other women to speak with a headhunter if
one calls. Explain your short- and long-term goals because even if
you're not interested in the current opening, something might turn
up a few years from now.
</P>
<P>
   And in the meantime, you might be able to help a company like GE
by telling the headhunter about a friend who would make a fantastic
engineer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
