<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-SYMPHONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$7.3 MILLION GIFT RESCUES HOUSTON SYMPHONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In a philanthropic gesture unusual in its size and
purpose, two local foundations have come to the rescue of the
Houston Symphony Orchestra, donating a total of $7.3 million, which
will wipe out its accumulated budget deficit, the symphony
announced today.
</P>
<P>
   The two donors, the Wortham Foundation, which has been the
symphony's most significant benefactor, and the Houston Endowment,
the largest grant-making foundation in the state, each gave $3.65
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I endorsed one of the checks yesterday,'' said symphony
executive director David Wax in an interview with a relieved laugh.
``It's a big hunk of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The gifts, which will save the symphony some $500,000 in annual
interest payments, testify to the straits into which the symphony
had fallen. In a report to the orchestra's board in May, Henry
Fogel, the president of the Chicago Symphony, who has served as a
consultant here for the last year, wrote that optimism was in
order, but added: ``To be fair, recent history of the orchestra
would be able to make even the most optimistic person a
pessimist.''
</P>
<P>
   Wortham Foundation spokeswoman Barbara Snyder said the
foundation would have no comment on the gift. But asked if the
donations amounted to a bailout, Houston Endowment president H. Joe
Nelson III said, ``You could call it that, yes.'' He added that the
symphony was `` too important to this city for it to be allowed to
lose its prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifts to arts institutions for deficit reduction _ ``paying for
the sins of the past,'' in Wax's phrase _ are the rarest sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foundations certainly don't like to give for this purpose,''
said Stacy Palmer, the editor of the Chronicle of Philanthropy.
``They'd much rather create new programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation Center, a New York-based organization that tracks
gift-giving by private and corporate foundations, reports that in
1996, the last year for which figures are available, just $14.5
million of the $900 million in arts grants awarded by 1,000
American foundations was earmarked for debt reduction. And that
$14.5 million was the total for 25 separate grants.
</P>
<P>
   The symphony gifts, said Steven Lawrence, the Center's director
of research, ``will rank among the largest arts grants of any kind
for 1998, and they are certainly among the largest we've ever seen
in this field, particularly for debt reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra, founded in 1913, has been on unsound financial
footing for many years, relying on deficit spending almost annually
since 1971 and using fund-raising to try to close the gap. The
shortfall has increased over the past 11 years, as the symphony,
under the musical direction of Christoph Eschenbach, embarked on an
ambitious program to raise its quality and visibility, increasing
its recording and, for the first time, touring in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, no one questions the orchestra's quality. ``It is
one of America's finest and most important orchestras,'' Fogel
wrote. But fund-raising, particularly among individual donors, has
lagged, and marketing has been lackadaisical, resulting in poor
renewal rates for all of its subscription series.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Eschenbach spoke angrily of the financing problems
and threatened to leave if they did not improve; late last year he
said the next season would be his last, and the orchestra is
seeking a replacement, although Eschenbach will make occasional
appearances. The resident conductor, Stephen Stein, resigned
recently to attend rabbinical school.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising and ticket sales have been particularly hindered in
the last two years by long and sometimes bitter negotiations with
the musicians' union over a new contract. The airing of that
dispute, along with the finances, were cited specifically in
Fogel's report. Having spoken to corporate, foundation and
individual donors, he wrote that `` ``one of the things that is
keeping support down is the belief that the organization does not
operate in a fiscally sound manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundations made their gift contingent on ending the salary
dispute, which was resolved last week. The new contract calls for
modest salary increases and improvements in pension and health
insurance. Most important for management, it runs through Oct. 5,
2002, which management hopes will be enough time to institute a
sound fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
   The gift was also contingent on a promise to maintain a balanced
budget. The foundations placed restrictions on the orchestra's
short-term borrowing and on drawing from its endowment, which is
just over $40 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
