<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECUADOR-CHEATS-HNS &LR;      08-25 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-CHEATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX EVASION A WAY OF LIFE IN POOR ECUADOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over second n in El Nino) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ When the Finance Ministry recently compiled a
list of the 200 Ecuadorean corporations with the highest earnings,
hard-working citizens were startled to learn that half of these
firms paid no income taxes last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador needs all the tax revenues it can get from the affluent.
Nearly 60 percent of the country's 12 million people live in
poverty. The nation lacks schools, health clinics, roads and
housing. And this year, it faces huge cleanup bills from damage
caused by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts say Ecuador may have the highest rate of tax
evasion in Latin America. You are considered foolish if you don't
evade taxes, said an investigator with Ecuador's independent
Anti-Corruption Commission.
</P>
<P>
   That's no small feat, because for many wealthy Latin Americans,
cheating on taxes is a time-honored tradition. Annual tax revenues
in Latin America amount to just 16 percent of gross domestic
product, according to the Washington-based Inter-American
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the average tax revenues as a percent of the total
goods and services produced in economies in the United States and
Europe are between 30 and 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is especially alarming in Ecuador, where taxes
make up just 6.6 percent of the GDP, according to the Finance
Ministry. For decades, Latin American governments backed off tough
tax enforcement because they feared rigid taxation would hurt the
private sector and drive away foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   They relied on state-run oil firms, airlines and utilities as
cash cows. Now, however, they are starting to crack down.
</P>
<P>
   They've had to.
</P>
<P>
   Industries have been privatized _ so the government no longer
can claim their profits. As prices for many of the region's exports
stagnate or fall, and the number of people living in poverty rises,
better tax collection is one of the only ways to cover budget
deficits and fund desperately needed social welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can be done in Latin America without a major overhaul
of the tax system,'' writes Mexican political analyst Jorge
Castaneda in his book ``Utopia Unarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fundamental,'' added Manuel Castilla, a tax expert at
the development bank in Washington. ``The only alternative (to more
tax revenues) is more loans, but then the foreign debt gets
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the development bank, the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund have a mutual understanding with Latin
American governments that they must improve tax collection to
remain eligible for assistance, Castilla said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Ecuador has shown no sign of falling in line. Recent
tax-reform bills in Ecuador have foundered because many congressmen
and their supporters run businesses that benefit from tax shields.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts say that newly elected President Jamil Mahuad,
who campaigned on an anti-corruption platform and promised to
attract billions of dollars in foreign investment, also will be
forced to increase tax revenues now that he's in office.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad will inherit a 5 percent fiscal deficit. What's more,
fresh income is needed to rebuild roads, housing and other
infrastructure on the Pacific coast that were washed away by the El
Nino weather pattern. Total damage is estimated at nearly $2
billion. But increasing tax revenues requires a reputable tax
collector, which Ecuador lacks. A branch of Ecuador's tax
collection agency was disbanded earlier this year following
accusations of bribe-taking.
</P>
<P>
   And the few tax cheats who are actually caught pay a small fine
and are never sent to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States, there is no accepted covenant between
citizens and government of contributing through taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., most people believe that (taxes) are the price
that you pay for the benefits of citizenship,'' said one
Quito-based diplomat. ``Here ... there is no sense of civic duty.
People say: `Why should I pay if no one else does?'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of forking over taxes so the government can repair the
streets, the rich would rather buy sport utility vehicles to drive
over the potholes, said Santiago Espinosa, a journalist with
Vistazo, a weekly newsmagazine in Quito.
</P>
<P>
   The poor, as well as workers in Ecuador's substantial informal
economy, contribute no income taxes, but everyone pays a 10 percent
value-added tax as well as a handful of other consumer tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that there is little incentive to pay taxes because
the government squanders the money. The corruption often starts at
the top. Exiled former President Abdala Bucaram, who was ousted by
the Congress last year, was charged by the Supreme Court with
stealing $88 million during his abbreviated term.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows where the tax money goes,'' said Xavier
Ribadeneira, a partner at the Quito office of the international
accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche. ``People never see any public
works. Conditions don't improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations, in turn, take advantage of myriad tax shields put
into place decades ago to protect local industries from foreign
competition. The purchase of government bonds or machinery, for
example, is tax deductible
</P>
<P>
   As a result, oil companies, shrimp exporters, textile firms and
more than two dozen banks legally paid no income taxes last year,
according to Finance Ministry records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fiscal shields are subsidies for big business,'' said
Fabian Corral, a Quito lawyer who advises foreign investors.
``Unless the laws are changed, there is no way to increase tax
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Peru is proof that tax reform is possible. In the past seven
years, President Alberto Fujimori's government has raised tax
revenues from 4.9 percent of GDP to 14 percent. It did so by
simplifying the tax code and reducing the number of taxes from 180
to five. Salaries for tax collectors were increased to discourage
corruption, and mobile taxpayer assistance centers were set up in
cities and villages.
</P>
<P>
   More than 11,000 businesses were closed for tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, where the influx of contraband liquor, appliances
and clothing is a huge problem, economists estimate that the
treasury loses about $3 billion annually in unpaid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The incoming government of President-elect Andres Pastrana in
Colombia would like to collect some of that money to pay for
agrarian reform and other costly social projects to help left-wing
guerrillas integrate into civilian life should they eventually sign
a peace treaty to end the 34-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want peace, you should begin by complying with your tax
obligations,'' said Juan Camilo Restrepo, who became Finance
Minister when Pastrana took office earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the peace accords that ended Guatemala's 36-year-old
civil war in 1996, the government pledged to increase tax revenues
by 50 percent by 2000 to pay for social programs and to reform the
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
