<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-COLLEGE _ WASHINGTON _ Decades of desegregation and
affirmative action have failed to bring college enrollment by black
students in line with the percentage of blacks in the general
population, suggesting that money may be the biggest barrier to
higher education, according to a report released Tuesday.
``Contrary to popular belief, the gap between blacks and whites for
opportunity and achievement is not being closed,'' said Elridge W.
McMillan, president of the Atlanta-based Southern Education
Foundation Inc., which produced the report, ``Miles to Go: A Report
on Black Students and Postsecondary Education in the South.''The
report examines enrollment, graduation and family income in 19
mostly Southern states that previously segregated blacks and whites
in colleges and universities. (Harlan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Separate versions will move for Texas, Ohio, Florida and
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's favorable
ratings in the polls depend on how the questions are asked,
according to pollsters. Two recent testings by ABC-News illustrate
that, as the president's favorable rating went from 54 percent down
to 39 percent in three days, after the order of questions was
changed. So what do the polls really mean? (Malone, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDALS _ WASHINGTON _ To Americans who are weary of
endless stories about White House scandals and wish the topic would
just go away, experts offer this prediction: fat chance. House
Speaker Newt Gingrich's statement this week that Congress must look
beyond sexual misconduct to other allegations of wrongdoing is a
sign that hearings _ and perhaps further independent probes and
private lawsuits _ will likely be making headlines for years to
come. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE _ WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Mandatory evacuation orders were
issued along the North Carolina coast Tuesday morning as Hurricane
Bonnie picked up speed and continued toward the coast. The latest
forecast has Bonnie hitting the coast sometime around dawn
Wednesday. In South Carolina, Gov. David Beasley issued a voluntary
evacuation order for Conway and Horry counties. The National Park
Service has evacuated 200 campsites on Ocracoke Island. Landfall is
expected late Wednesday, with the first rain bands expected Tuesday
night (Burritt/Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
WITH GRAPHIC locating Bonnie from KRT on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-WTHRCHANNEL _ MARIETTA, Ga. _ You can tell a hurricane's
coming at the Weather Channel. Catered barbecue for the staff is
picked over on a table in the newsroom, and a meteorologist is
being literally pulled out the door by a producer to hop a plane to
North Carolina, where Bonnie is expected to land. Behind the scenes
at the Marietta-based channel, ncluding interviews with Dr. Steve
Lyons, the new hurricane specialist, CEO Mike Eckert, and a look at
the cable channel's expanding reach. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-WTHRCHANNEL-FACTS _ Fact box about the Channel. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-STORMWEB _ Weather fans and those with friends and family
along the East Coast can watch Hurricane Bonnie's progress 24 hours
a day via several nifty Web sites. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-FLORIDA _ Update on hurricanes Bonnie and Danielle. A
hurricane Bonnie watch is issued from the north carolina/Virginia
border to cape henlopen delaware, including the chesapeake bay
southward from windmill point. Hurricane warnings remain in effect
from murrells inlet south carolina to the North Carolina/Virginia
border. A watch remains in effect from Savannah, Ga., to Murrell's
Inlet, S.C. We're checking surf, riptides, erosion, local disaster
response, insurance problems, etc. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-FAGAN (DEVELOPING) _ BOSTON _ Coverage of the Stephen Fagan
hearing in Boston. (Holland, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BABBITT-FALCON _ STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Interior Sec. Bruce
Babbitt will be atop Stone Mountain Tuesday to release two
peregrine falcons to highlight their delisting from the endangered
species list. Babbitt ceremoniously announced in June the delisting
of 34 other species to show that the Endangered Species Act is
working. An update on the endangered species act, possibly a Q&AMP;A
with Babbitt. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CARPOOL-SCOFFLAWS _ ATLANTA _ Single-driver scofflaws who
violate carpool-lane restrictions might be faced with a high-tech
version of ``Candid Camera.'' Frustrated by virtual waves of
single-occupancy HOV violators, the state Department of
Transportation and the Federal Highway Administration asked Georgia
Tech scientists to focus on the problem. They are experimenting
with an infrared camera that can shoot a picture of your vehicle's
interior even if you have highly tinted glass. Such a device is
years away from being used to enforce the law, but it certainly
shows promise. (Ledford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-BEATING _ ATLANTA _ DeKalb District Attorney J. Tom
Morgan expressed outrage Tuesday at a judge for sentencing a
Dunwoody dad to probation for striking a Little League coach with a
metal bat. Morgan, himself a youth sports coach, said the man
deserved jail time. The sentence by Judge Clarence Seeliger sets a
bad example for parents who lose control at sports activities,
Morgan said. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-UT-LAW-SCHOOL _ ATLANTA _ UT Law School is expected to
release enrollment data today showing its racial breakdowns in this
second year of Hopwood. Texas Tech figures surprised officials
there. They show that their outreach programs helped raise minority
enrollment above what it was in 1996, the year of the Hopwood
decision. Am checking to see if SMU or Univ. of Houston have
figures as well. Also will mention Berkeley data. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTALEGION _ ATLANTA _ A generous gift made more than 70
years ago by a grateful city to its battle-weary sons may cost
Atlanta nearly $1 million. In 1926, Atlanta officials sold a parcel
of land adjacent to Piedmont Park to the American Legion's Post No.
1 as a site for a meeting hall. The nearly two-thirds acre at 1071
Piedmont Ave. went for the token price of $100, but the deed
restricted use of the land for ``the purpose of erecting a home''
for the Argonne Post of the American Legion, as Post No. 1 was
known at the time. In 1939, for an additional $1, the city
relinquished all restrictions on the property and turned it over to
the veterans' group by ``unrestricted title.'' Today that land is
on the block. The American Legion is negotiating with Piedmont Park
Conservancy to sell the property. (Saunders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKLAG _ ATLANTA _ While attempts have been made over the past
20 years to close the gap between blacks and whites in higher
education, a report released Tuesday says little has been done to
actually desegregate public schools in 19 Southern states. The
Southern Education Foundation, a private nonprofit agency concerned
with equity in public education, stated that while piecemeal
efforts are being offered by states, efforts to desegregate higher
education in the South has made little, if any progress, since the
1970s. Georgia, however, was listed, along with Maryland, as two
states that have made some progress. (Suggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
