<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOODFELLAS' ON CBS: FOR MATURE AUDIENCES  
 CONAN O'BRIEN'S ANNIVERSARY SPECIAL IS BUMPED 
</HEADLINE>
   `THAT '70s SHOW' HAVING A NICE START  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cleaner Act for Wise Guys
</P>
<P>
   For nearly six years, Warner Brothers has been trying to get
Martin Scorsese's Oscar-winning film ``Goodfellas'' onto network
television screens. But the film's graphic violence and profanity,
even after Scorsese had edited it for television, made that seem
impossible _ especially in the last few years, with the national
debate over sex and violence on television and the need for a
content ratings system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, ABC bought the rights to the film, based on Nicholas
Pileggi's true story about a gangster named Henry Hill, and owned
it for three years, but never showed it. Since 1996, Warner
Brothers has been trying to sell it again.
</P>
<P>
   Now CBS is taking a chance. And, as Steven Spielberg's
``Schindler's List'' did last February, ``Goodfellas'' will carry a
TV-MA rating (for mature audiences only) when it finally makes its
broadcast television debut on Sunday night, Sept. 13 _ opposite the
annual Emmy Awards show on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this really much different from NBC running `Schindler's
List'?'' asked Edward Bleier, president of pay-television, cable
and network features for Warner Brothers. ``And Marty made far more
changes in this than Spielberg did in `Schindler's List,''' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Scorsese has also recorded a prologue running about 45 seconds
that will caution viewers that even though the film has been edited
for television, it is still a violent story. Enough violence
remains, he says in the prologue, ``so that viewers will not
misinterpret the underlying brutality of the mobsters as
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Scorsese continues, ``I did not want to remove all the violence
because I did not want to give the impression that this film
depicts a remotely glamorous life style.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the scheduling, on a night when other networks by
tradition try not to detract from the Emmy broadcast, a CBS
spokeswoman pointed out that relatively few men watch the Emmys,
and CBS only hopes to attract ``an audience that is available and
has decided not to watch the Emmys.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien Bumped
</P>
<P>
   Television executives spend endless hours examining coming
prime-time schedules; they apparently spend almost no time
examining upcoming political schedules.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, that prime-time special to celebrate Conan
O'Brien's fifth-year as host of NBC's ``Late Night'' will not be on
Tuesday, Sept. 15, as previously announced. Instead it will be
moved to Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? NBC suddenly discovered that New York and seven
other states are holding major political primaries on the 15th,
which would lead to numerous big cities' pre-empting at least part
of O'Brien's special Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   This ``discovery'' was only made on Friday; the O'Brien special
had been announced in July. NBC's top entertainment executives in
Los Angeles, Don Ohlmeyer and Warren Littlefield, told Jeff Ross,
the executive producer of ``Late Night,'' that he had the option of
moving the special to Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross discussed the situation with Mr. O'Brien and they decided
that with a significant number of areas likely to be cutting into
the show on Tuesday, Wednesday night would be the better option.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the gap on Tuesday, NBC will, as usual, turn to
``Dateline NBC,'' whose executive producer, Neal Shapiro, said
Tuesday he would have no trouble adding one more edition of that
series on short notice. O'Brien's special will still be taped Sept.
10. ``At least we get an extra day to edit the show,'' Ross joked.
This will be the first time O'Brien's show appears in prime time.
For the special only, it will move to the larger NBC studio 8-H,
which is the regular home for ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   No guests have yet been booked for the special, Mr. Ross said,
which will mainly consist of taped clip highlights from the last
five years of ``Late Night.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Is It the Bell Bottoms?
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives are celebrating the ratings news from Sunday,
when a new comedy, ``That '70s Show,'' got off to an especially
promising start.
</P>
<P>
   The show wound up the highest-rated show last week among the
audience Fox covets most, viewers between the ages of 18 and 49. No
premiere of any Fox show had ever before finished in first place in
that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' even managed to beat the rating for its
lead-in ``The Simpsons,'' which broadcast a new episode last
Sunday. No new Fox series slotted after ``The Simpsons'' had ever
done better than that animated hit.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason for the early success of ``That '70s Show'' was
its appeal to men. It finished first across the board with men in
every age group.
</P>
<P>
   It also did well with teen-agers, who might have seemed its
natural constituency because the show is about a group of Wisconsin
teens in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
