<SLUG> BC-POP-LIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP LIFE: BLACK BOX RECORDER, PRINCE, HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``I stopped talking when I was 6 years old. I
didn't want anything more to do with the outside world.'' So begins
one of the most macabre singles of the year, ``Child Psychology,''
by Black Box Recorder, a new English band. The song's verses are
spoken by a disaffected deadpan female vocalist, who chronicles her
privileged upbringing as a series of disillusions and
disappointments in the hands of adults baffled by her complete
apathy.
</P>
<P>
   The song's kicker is the chorus, signaled by a sudden tempo
change attended by a muted drumbeat and sharply strummed guitar. A
male voice joins the woman's, soft and just as jaded, singing the
chorus' only lyric as beautifully and methodically as possible:
``Life is unfair/Kill yourself or get over it.'' Perhaps the
closest comparison to ``Child Psychology'' is Leiber and Stoller's
``Is That All There Is?,'' in which Peggy Lee sang about what life
had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the protagonist's sociopathy in ``Child Psychology''
is answered in the title song of Black Box Recorder's debut album,
``England Made Me.'' The singer, Sarah Nixey, spends the first
verse describing how as a child she captured a spider underneath a
glass and then watched it slowly die. Her motivation, she explains
in the chorus, is simply that ``England made me.''
</P>
<P>
   Black Box Recorder consists of Luke Haines, the morbid mind
behind the group the Auteurs; John Moore, the former drummer for
the Jesus and Mary Chain, and Ms. Nixey, a newcomer. Singing mostly
lyrics written by her male collaborators, Ms. Nixey is the perfect
front woman for this album-length critique of middle-class Britain,
with lyrics approaching the dry wit and incisiveness of Ray Davies
of the Kinks. In fact, the band explores some of the same
microscopic themes as Davies, like the way people take photographs
to prove that they really have done something exciting in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixey has the voice of an angel but delivers the lyrics of a
damned soul (usually those of the tragedy-obsessed Haines). Her
character evokes the innocent-looking but murderous girl with blond
pigtails in the film ``The Bad Seed'' (or, for that matter, any of
the malevolent pre-adolescent girls portrayed in the songs of Nick
Cave and the Bad Seeds).
</P>
<P>
   In various songs on the album, Ms. Nixey sings beautifully of
stealing cars, killing strangers and watching schools burn down.
Backed by crystal-clear production and restrained, well-arranged
chimes, keyboards, guitar and soft percussion, her voice can bring
chills. In a phrase, she can tear apart a relationship (``Every
caress is some cul de sac we've already been down''), her
upbringing (``I traveled all my life, but never got away'') or
existence itself (``It's only the end of the world, not a death in
the family'').
</P>
<P>
   ``England Made Me'' is available as an import on the English
label Chrysalis. The company said it had no current plans to
release the album on an American label.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, Please
</P>
<P>
   On a tour he pledges won't end until the last day of 1999, the
artist formerly known as Prince returns to New York to perform at
Madison Square Garden on Sept. 25. Tickets, from a cleverly priced
$19.99 to a steeply priced $125, will be on sale Monday at 9 a.m.
through Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for Canada's jokey, folky Barenaked Ladies, who are to
perform at the Theater at Madison Square Garden on Oct. 7, go on
sale on Friday at 9 a.m.; all seats are $32.
</P>
<P>
   Words of Love
</P>
<P>
   Hunting for puns that will make you groan? Look no further than
the new Hole record, due out on Geffen Records on Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the record's many references to skin, the makeup
on top of skin and the vulnerability hidden below, the band's
leader, Courtney Love, dreams up a bevy of sly self-references. In
``Reasons to Be Beautiful,'' she begins, ``Love hangs herself,''
and a verse later screams, ``Love hates you.'' In ``Dying,'' she
moans that ``Love is dead.'' And in ``Malibu,'' she shows off her
pun pedigree with the line ``Love will tear you apart,'' a
reference not just to herself but to the Joy Division song ``Love
Will Tear Us Apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the lyric ``My sweet tooth has burned a hole'' is
an allusion to the band's name is open to interpretation, though a
clue supporting that is a similar subsequent line, ``My love burns
through everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
