<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOPE-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WONDERLAND' STAR NO STRANGER TO GOING IT ALONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a wrenching moment near the end of the
wonderful new modern romance, ``Next Stop Wonderland,'' that
signals the emergence of Hope Davis as a film actress to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Davis plays Erin, a single nurse who must endure countless bad
dates because of a personal ad her mother placed in a Boston
newspaper. Erin has just finished her graveyard shift and is
enjoying a meal and a bottle of wine with a handsome Brazilian (not
an ad respondent) who has designs on her heart. When he leaves for
more wine, Erin looks around the restaurant and notices all the
lonely people around her. And she just loses it in a heartbreaking
display of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who spends an unusual amount of time alone playing Erin
in ``Wonderland,'' says the scene still gets to her when she
watches it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my favorite things about the movie,'' the
31-year-old actress says. ``(Writer-director) Brad Anderson so
captures that feeling that you can be content by yourself, but then
you go out in a crowd, look around at couples or maybe see tired,
hurting people by themselves, and this feeling of loneliness just
overwhelms you.''
</P>
<P>
   As for all that screen time by herself, Davis says she loved it,
coming as it did after being relatively under-used in the past in
movies such as ``The Myth of Fingerprints,'' ``Kiss of Death'' and
``Home Alone.'' She's probably best known to audiences who saw her
delightful turn in the modest indie hit ``The Daytrippers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good challenge but kind of a lonely one,'' Davis says
of her ``Wonderland'' solo work. ``I just wanted to make those
scenes interesting and not have Erin slumped by the refrigerator
waiting for the phone to ring. She's melancholy, but she's
comfortable with herself, too. I think single people will be able
to relate to this movie because it embodies that truism of how the
search for love has to start with learning to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says he was looking for an actress who wasn't ditzy or
too cutesy or too much of a glamour girl. Davis, an intelligent and
attractive (but not unrealistically so) blonde with expressive
brown eyes, fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope has this quality where she's a little bit detached yet
also soulful, melancholy but also radiant,'' Anderson says. ``We
also wanted someone a little unconventional. The fact that she had
done a lot of stage work prior to her films helped because I shoot
kind of off-the-cuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson made ``Next Stop Wonderland'' (named for a stop along
the Boston subway line) in 22 days nearly two years ago. If Davis
seems convincing while inhabiting her character's gray-filled
world, it's no accident. Her marriage was coming to an end while
she made the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most unhappy time of my life,'' says Davis, who had
known her ex-husband since she was 18. ``I see myself in the movie,
and I just look terrible. It shows. The movie is hard to watch in a
way because it brings back such a bad time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She's moved on _ personally and professionally. Davis has a new
boyfriend (an actor), starred in Chekhov's ``Ivanov'' with Kevin
Kline on Broadway and landed meaty roles in two upcoming movies.
Davis will co-star with Jeff Bridges in ``Arlington Road,'' a
political thriller about domestic terrorism, and recently wrapped a
part in director Lawrence Kasdan's next film, ``Mumford.'' She also
can be seen this fall in Stanley Tucci's ``Big Night'' follow-up,
``The Impostors.''
</P>
<P>
   For Davis, her resume is going to end there _ for now. She's
going to hole up in her Greenwich Village apartment, which is
devoid of televisions and answering machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just bookcases, food, sea kayaks (she just got back from an
ocean kayaking trip to Mount Desert Island in Maine) and blueberry
pie,'' Davis says dreamily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
