<HEADLINE>
WEB IS PLACE TO BE FOR BROADCASTING NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; One of the last places to find radio industry
news is on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the first stop is Don Barrett's Web site devoted to
local broadcasting. The Internet site (www.laradio.com) was
initially launched last summer to promote Barrett's self-published
book, ``Los Angeles Radio People Vol. 2 (1957-97),'' a useful A to
Z chronicle of City of Angels broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to update the site on a regular basis to keep up with
what was occurring, because there was this whole raft of events
taking place,'' Barrett said of the site's early days.
</P>
<P>
   The site is updated daily and has become a must-read for both
broadcasters and local listeners each morning.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, for example, published the full text of an unusual
late-night on-air apology offered by KFI-AM (640) officials last
week after talk host Tammy Bruce was suspended for comments she
made regarding the Cosby family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a daily radio industry convention on the Web,''
said Barrett, a Burbank motion-picture consultant who spent 10
years in radio and launched now-defunct KIQQ-FM in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the latest news, Barrett's site offers a listing of
e-mail addresses for broadcasters past and present. Saturdays, he
posts letters from the site's many visitors, which Barrett
estimates at an average of about 4,000 daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fans of radio who are just passionate about what
they listen to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NOW HEARD ON CABLE: After three decades at Glendale's KIEV-AM
(870), affable evening host Gregg Hunter has moved to the Cable
Radio Network (CRN), which broadcasts on cable TV systems
throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's ``Nightside L.A.'' can be heard at 10 p.m. Saturdays
and 9 p.m. Sundays on such local systems as Century, TCI and Media
One.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome all of Gregg's listeners, which he calls his
call-in cousins,'' said Paul Stern, CRN's program director. ``We're
very proud to have Gregg on staff.''
</P>
<P>
   CRN, which is based in Sunland, is available in about 13 million
homes worldwide through cable TV, satellite and the Internet, Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
   The local number to call into Hunter's program is (818)
353-1276.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN ROCK SHOW: Members of the KROQ-FM (106.7) staff will be on
hand at 11:30 a.m. Sept. 2 when Latin-rockers Ozomatli perform a
free show at the Sierra Quad on the campus of California State
University, Northridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
