NYT-08-25-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-WTHRCHANNEL-CO     08-25 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-WTHRCHANNEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tracking the storm : The Weather Channel hunkers down
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTAMeteorologist Bill Keneely has been plucked, literally,
from the Weather Channel's newsroom by his producer, Lauren
Chambliss. She's grabbed him by the back of his polo shirt to get
him out of a conversation, then trotted him down a hall to the
company van, dubbed ``White Lightning,'' that would take them to
Hartsfield International Airport for a flight to Hurricane Bonnie's
expected landfall in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the deployment of troops at the Weather Channel, where a
hurricane approaching the East Coast coast gets the same blowout
treatment as CNN gives to a presidential address.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, thousands of metro Atlantans drive right by the
Weather Channel's headquarters next to I-75 near Windy Hill Road,
passing another nondescript concrete-and-smoked-glass Perimeter
office building. No big sign announces its presence.
</P>
<P>
   Its metro location is ``a well-kept secret,'' says CEO Michael
Eckert, because the cable channel is small (about 600 Atlanta
employees) and not set up to handle drop-in visitors and tours. But
that relative anonymity works against it as well, because the world
identifies Atlanta with CNN and the rest of Time Warner and Ted
Turner's TV empire.
</P>
<P>
   With Hurricane Bonnie approaching, interest in the Weather
Channel will spike again, and viewership could explode tenfold,
from 200,000 to more than 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Keneely, who'll be reporting from North Carolina today, is one
of the volunteers who go to where the bad weather is for live
reports. They're not as foolhardy as the storm chasers in the movie
``Twister,'' although the Weather Channel does have a few workers
who stalk tornadoes on their own vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with volunteers,'' says Eckert. ``We do
tell them don't get too close, or you won't go next time.'' Despite
such admonitions, there's still admiring talk in the newsroom about
Dennis Smith, the meteorologist who lashed his belt to a hotel
balcony in Coral Gables, Fla., to keep from being blown away during
a live report on Hurricane Andrew in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   An approaching hurricane sends the Weather Channel into what
Eckert calls ``clear-the-decks mode.'' Catered barbecue is brought
in for the staff working extra hours. The dress code for the
newsroom would probably be relaxed if it could be, but it can't,
because the Weather Channel scarcely has a dress code. Casual
Fridays morphed into casual every day a couple of years ago, and so
Eckert, the big boss, wears a golf shirt and slacks into the
office, and assignment editor Patrick Walsh, who runs the live
coverage, is dressed in khaki shorts and untucked polo shirt. Only
the on-air people _ ``on-camera meteorologists,'' as the cable
network calls them _ wear ties or chic outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude is if the weather is going to keep us here, let's
be comfortable,'' on-camera meteorologist Lisa Mozer says during a
break from the TelePrompTer. On a bulletin board behind her, out of
camera range, someone has posted an article from the supermarket
tabloid The Sun, screaming about a ``Weather Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   But their attitude toward their work is anything but casual or
tongue-in-cheek. ``Our mission is to get the word out and help
people prepare,'' says Joe Conboy, vice president of program
operations.
</P>
<P>
   That's the attitude of Steve Lyons, the channel's ``tropical
specialist'' since May, when he replaced long-time hurricane expert
John Hope. Lyons, bald and authoritative with a Ph.D. in
meteorology from the University of Hawaii, is the Weather Channel's
go-to guy for Hurricane Bonnie, the channel's equivalent of CNN's
Christiane Amanpour when the shooting starts in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just breaking in here,'' says Lyons, who is crisp and calm
on the air even though he admits to worrying about how he will do
if his equipment breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons got started with weather forecasting when he was a surfing
high school student in Southern California. ``I wondered where the
waves came from,'' he says, so he built a small weather hutch to
gather information. He's taught meteorology at Texas A&AMP;M University
and was manager of the Tropical Analysis and Forecast Branch of the
National Hurricane Center in Miami before joining the Weather
Channel three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The cable channel began in 1982, two years after CNN's start-up,
and met with similar derision by so-called experts. ``Who's gonna
watch a 24-hour weather channel?'' is how CEO Eckert, who's been
with the channel since the beginning, recalls the initial reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Weather Channel achieved a recognition level
that amazes even those who work there. A study last year by
advertising firm Young &AMP; Rubicam polled people on their awareness
of, and opinion of, TV channels. Fox finished first, the Discovery
Channel second and the Weather Channel third, ahead of CNN, NBC,
CBS and ABC.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out even the Weather Channel is surprised by who
watches. TV sets at the Vortex restaurant-bars in Little Five
Points and Midtown are frequently tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our owners (Suzanne Benoit) is an avid motorcycle rider
and she always has it on to see what the weather's going to be,''
says Vortex manager Kevin Jones. ``And if it's going to be hot and
humid, there goes my patio (business).''
</P>
<P>
   Also watching, according to the Weather Channel's market
research: gamblers, who want to know if horse racing tracks and
football fields are going to be wet or dry; golfers (the golf
portion of the channel's Web pages is its most popular section);
business travelers, pilots, farmers, commodities traders,
construction workers who won't get to work if it's raining; and
some ``weather enthusiasts,'' as Eckert calls them, who sometimes
have the channel on for four straight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons is the first to admit that predicting the path of a
hurricane is very difficult. Different computer models with
acronyms such as GFDL (for geophysical fluid dynamics) suggest
different tracks. And getting it right is potentially a matter of
life and death, a far cry from the jolly weather forecasts favored
in much of TV news. These days, the atmosphere is anything but
jolly inside the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-HUNTSVILLE-CO     08-25 2079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-HUNTSVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The sky's the limit as rocket center in Huntsville takes
visitors to final frontier
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Ala._In the final seconds before the crash, the
voice from the flight tower shifted from cool military tones to an
urgent warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're coming in too low,'' the controller's voice crackled
over the ground-to-air radio. ``We show you drifting off the flight
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ease back on the stick _ now!''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later the aircraft plunged with explosive force into the
grassy fields just short of the runway. There were no survivors ...
and no casualties either, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops,'' whispered my 4-year-old son, Josh, releasing the
joystick of the ``Land the Shuttle'' flight simulator we had so
cluelessly piloted together. Then, after collecting himself: ``This
is just so cool, Daddy. Wanna try it again?''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, we don't have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's just another day at the U.S. Space &AMP; Rocket Center, in the
Alabama city that produced the rocket boosters that put men on the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   This Huntsville attraction boldly goes where no other science
and history museum has gone before. It's a place where ``Star
Wars'' film fantasy mingles with real-world Star Wars missile
technology. Where kids can take a virtual-reality ride to Jupiter _
and get a close look at the real Apollo 15 module that took men to
the moon, then fell back to Earth in a blaze of heat and glory 26
years ago. And where families can spend the morning walking through
a rocket graveyard of retired NASA boosters, military aircraft and
test missiles, and the afternoon watching an IMAX film shot by
astronauts aboard the Russian Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the rocket center spans the distance between sci-fi
space fantasy and sophisticated NASA reality, with more than 60
interactive exhibits and 1,500 pieces of space hardware.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the center has more to offer than ever: An $800,000
makeover completed in the spring adds a children's play area and
new exhibits, including a full-scale mock-up of Mir's core module
and a meteorite display. In addition, the center is drawing up
plans for an expansion that would cost $50 million to $100 million
and quadruple the size of the north Alabama attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Lofty plans are nothing new for Huntsville, which has been
something of a company town for the space program since the 1950s.
That's when Wernher von Braun arrived with a team of American and
German scientists to test and build the rockets that would hoist
Americans into space.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, the center stands as a terrific monument to von
Braun's vision and America's pioneering instincts. It's also a
family-friendly weekend destination.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Rocket City
</P>
<P>
   Our trip to Rocket City could not have been more tailor-made for
our two sons. Danny, 7, is deep into the ``Star Wars'' trilogy, an
enthusiasm that fuels a pretty sophisticated knowledge of the solar
system, NASA missions and astronomy. Josh, 4, loves anything
involving locomotion _ trains, planes, cars, rockets and other
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Even before we'd pulled into the Rocket Center parking lot, the
two were out of their seat belts and clamoring to get out of the
car. The center's large rocket park is visible from the road, its
retired rockets and aircraft towering into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, pictures and memorabilia from NASA's 40-year history
provide an interesting introduction to the space program. A mock-up
of the space shuttle docking with Mir anchors a corner of the
lobby. And, everywhere, photos and small-scale models of lunar
vehicles, space-suited astronauts and Apollo spacecraft fill
displays.
</P>
<P>
   First stop: a movie theater, where a five-minute film boils down
50 years of space research, rocket testing and Huntsville's role in
NASA's lofty plans. The movie is part nostalgia, part futuristic
vision and hails Huntsville's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fitting warm-up to the series of exhibits and interactive
programs that follow.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo exhibits
</P>
<P>
   For space buffs, the first display, ``Rocket City Legacy,'' is
the most compelling. In a series of interlocking rooms, relics from
the dawn of the space program through NASA's most shining moment _
the Apollo missions to the moon _ are preserved under glass.
</P>
<P>
   They range from the intriguing to the bizarre. Film loops and
black-and-white photographs show sketchy images of the first rocket
tests by 19th-century European scientists Konstantin Tsiolkovsky
and Hermann Oberth. A replica of von Braun's office fills one wall,
complete with personal items and space memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Model replicas of the first monkeys in space _ on display in
their odd uniforms _ stare out perpetually at visitors. The Apollo
artifacts include everything from astronaut training uniforms to
cameras, radio transmitters, diaries, shovels used to scoop up moon
rocks and even the ``purging'' underwear worn by orbiting
astronauts (known in characteristic NASA-speak as the ``Urine
Collection Transfer Assembly'').
</P>
<P>
   Games and gizmos
</P>
<P>
   The center wisely alternates hardware exhibits with areas
featuring children's games and science-museum-style gizmos that
youngsters can manipulate. Once through the Apollo exhibits, for
instance, kids can try their hands at the ``Land the Shuttle''
flight simulator, which is equal parts science and video game, or
pilot a virtual lunar lander's descent to the surface of the moon.
They can find out what it feels like for shuttle astronauts to
operate a remote-controlled cargo arm in space. And they can weigh
themselves on a scale that compares their earthbound weight to
their weights on Mars and the moon.
</P>
<P>
   In a cavernous central lobby, artifacts of the space program
stand side by side with mock-ups and re-created scenes. A test
module and lunar rover used by Apollo astronauts sit atop a
realistic moonscape. A few feet away, visitors can almost touch the
actual scorched Apollo 16 command module _ nicknamed ``Casper'' _
that carried astronauts John Young, Thomas Mattingly and Charles
Duke to the moon and back in April 1972.
</P>
<P>
   A full-scale, walk-through replica of parts of Skylab, the
world's first orbiting space laboratory, sits next to a fragment of
the real Skylab, recovered after the vessel crashed to Earth in the
1970s. Behind it stands the quarantine trailer from which Neil
Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins spoke to President Nixon
after their historic return from the moon in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   There are also artifacts from the earlier Gemini missions,
including a training capsule used by the astronauts, a
3.3-billion-year-old moon rock brought back by Apollo 12, and
engraved champagne bottles commemorating every space shuttle
launching, including that of Challenger, which exploded in 1986
killing all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Journey to Jupiter
</P>
<P>
   Some exhibits use a bit of old-fashioned stagecraft. A science
fiction gallery, featuring replicas of vessels from ``Star Wars,''
``Star Trek'' and sci-fi movies of the 1950s, leads to a
virtual-reality simulator that takes visitors on a fictional trip
to Jupiter, the largest planet. Hardly a mall ride, ``Journey to
Jupiter'' sprinkles in bits of real-world detail about the
International Space Station, now under construction.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at real spaceflight, the center's Spacedome IMAX
theater offers ``Mission to Mir,'' a new film that chronicles
American astronaut Shannon Lucid's historic shuttle mission to the
space station.
</P>
<P>
   After touring the center, visitors can walk the grounds behind
it for a close-up experience with nearly a dozen rockets that dot
the landscape like so many massive memorials. ``Rocket Park,''
which U.S. senator and former (and future) astronaut John Glenn has
called ``the finest rocket collection in the world,'' includes a
363-foot, three-stage Saturn V rocket, a full-scale mock-up of the
space shuttle and its huge booster rockets, and other NASA and
military craft.
</P>
<P>
   New this year is the park's ``Kids' Cosmos Energy-Depletion
Zone,'' a covered play area featuring child-friendly games,
climbing structures and rides, including the popular ``Lunar
Lander,'' which simulates a landing on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   For older children, the ``Space Shot'' ride launches 12
strapped-in riders straight up a 180-foot tower in three seconds _
approximating the 4-G acceleration of a real shuttle launch _ then
free-falls back to Earth, providing several stomach-tingling
seconds of weightlessness. (Hint: Do not try this after a large
lunch. The same goes for the ``Centrifuge,'' which spins visitors
at a velocity three times the force of gravity.)
</P>
<P>
   The museum admission fee also covers the cost of a 90-minute
guided bus trip and tour to NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center,
where engineers and laborers in hangar-sized buildings are busy
building components of the International Space Station. The first
pieces of the station are scheduled to be lofted into orbit later
this year by the space shuttle. The remaining sections are to be
ferried up and assembled in space, like giant Tinkertoys, over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Lasting impressions
</P>
<P>
   For the record, some of the center's exhibits appear not to have
been updated since Armstrong uttered his famous ``one small step
... one giant leap'' quote from the moon in 1969. There's also a
heavy dose of patriotic boosterism that seems to hark back, however
sweetly, to the 1950s. And parents should steady themselves for the
gift shops that beckon at virtually every entrance and exit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is an odd charm to the place, even for visitors who
aren't especially intrigued by science or the space program. Staff
members and tour guides, dressed in orange-and-blue NASA jumpsuits,
are helpful and knowledgable.
</P>
<P>
   As we left the center after a long, exhausting day, it was clear
that the visit had left a lasting impression on my sons. ``Can we
come back here for my birthday?'' Danny asked as we pulled out of
the parking lot. Then, strapping himself into his seat belt with a
flourish: ``Let's pretend we're on the space shuttle. You can be
the pilot, all right?''
</P>
<P>
   No problem, Houston. No problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: A 3.5-hour drive from Atlanta, heading north
on I-75 to Chattanooga, west on I-24, then west on U.S. 72 to I-565
in Huntsville. The center is located at Exit 15 on I-565.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hours, admission: Open 9 a.m.-6 p.m. daily. Center admission
($14.95 adults, $10.95 children 3-12) includes IMAX shows about
space and a guided bus tour of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center.
</P>
<P>
   -- Space Camp: For those children who can't get enough in a
single weekend visit, the center's Space Camp offers a week of
training exercises and education on the rigors of spaceflight.
Participants can strap themselves into rotating chairs like the
Mercury astronauts used to experience G-forces, practice
maneuvering in an underwater training tank, and climb into the
cockpit of a space shuttle model to fly simulated missions.
Five-day camps are geared toward grades four through six; Space
Academy is a five-day program for grades six through eight;
advanced camps are offered for high school students and adults.
Tuition is $675 to $875, including meals and lodging. For
information, call 1-800-637-7223 or visit the center's World Wide
Web site at http://www.ussrc.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lodging: Downtown Huntsville has a variety of moderately
priced hotels close to the center, including the Radisson Suite
Hotel (205-882-9400), several Holiday Inns (1-800-826-9563),
Hilton, Marriott and Ramada. Many offer suites and family specials,
with separate bedrooms for children and parents, for $80 to $120
per night.
</P>
<P>
   -- Food: The center's Galaxy Food Court serves up fine,
moderately priced hamburgers, grilled chicken sandwiches and other
American foods. A family of four can graze for $20 and still have
some change for a couple of cups of ``space dots'' ice cream or ice
slush drinks, served in towering ``green alien'' cups. Downtown
Huntsville is dotted with chain restaurants: Outback makes an extra
effort to welcome families, and the Hilton (205-533-1400) has a
fine Sunday breakfast buffet for $7.95 (half-price for children
under 12; those 4 and under eat free) and a lavish Sunday brunch
($14.95 for adults, $7.95 for children under 8).
</P>
<P>
   -- Space Center information: 256-837-3400.
</P>
<P>
