<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-FESTIVALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lost Civilizations' soon to vanish
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only three weeks remain in the run of ``Ancestors of the Incas:
The Lost Civilizations of Peru,'' another in a series of major
cultural exhibits presented in Memphis by the city-run Wonders
agency. The exhibit, at the Pyramid through Sept. 16, features 300
artifacts including mummies, gold and ceramics, in galleries
modeled after archaeological sites. (Information: 1-800-263-6744.)
Like the previous Wonders blockbuster ``Titanic: The Exhibition,''
the Peruvian show will move to St. Petersburg's Florida
International Museum after its Memphis run. Retitled ``Empires of
Mystery: The Incas, the Andes and Lost Civilizations,'' the exhibit
will open Oct. 23 and continue into spring 1999.
(Call1-800-777-9882.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Waynesville, N.C. _ The Atlanta Ballet, in residence at
Haywood Community College, will present two world premieres during
performances at 7:30 p.m. Saturday and 2 p.m. Sunday at the college
auditorium. Among the works is a premiere of ``Earth,''
choreographed by N.C. resident Laura Dean, and a new work by Val
Caniparoli. 1-800-491-6803.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tuscaloosa, Ala. _ The International CityFest and Weindorf
Friday and Saturday features 50 musical acts on eight stages,
including Mark Chesnutt, Patty Loveless (Friday) and the Guess Who,
Martha Reeves, Kansas and the Spinners (Saturday). Also children's
activities, arts and crafts bazaar, barbecue cookoff, antique cars,
German food and dancing. 1-800-538-8696 or http://www.cityfest.org.
</P>
<P>
   -- Chattanooga _ The African-American Cultural Festival, Friday
and Saturday at Miller Plaza, includes local dancers, music, poets,
writers, drama and an African marketplace with clothing, food,
jewelry and crafts. 423-267-1076.
</P>
<P>
   -- Loudon, Tenn. _ The 16th annual Smoky Mountain Fiddlers
Convention, Friday and Saturday at Liberty Park, features bluegrass
bands, fiddle, banjo, guitar, clogging and buck dancing
competition. Includes the Smoky Mountain Arts &AMP; Crafts Show (both
days) and Memories on Mulberry Antique and Quilt Show (Saturday).
423-458-5956.
</P>
<P>
   -- Braselton, Ga. _ Chateau Elan's annual Vineyard Fest on
Saturday includes tours of the winery, wine tastings, seminars,
food tastings, musical entertainment, fine arts show and grape
stomping. Evening concert with the Swingin' Medallions.
770-932-0900.
</P>
<P>
   -- Manassas, Va. _ Civil War Weekend II in Prince William
Saturday and Sunday features living history, concerts and displays
commemorating the second Manassas battle of the Civil War.
703-368-1873.
</P>
<P>
   -- Louisville, Ky. _ The Kentucky State Fair continues through
Sunday at the Kentucky Fair and Exposition Center. This year's
cultural and educational exhibit is ``The Pioneer Experience in
Kentucky: Life on the Frontier.'' Also, food, music, evening
concerts and a world championship horse show. 502-367-5002.
</P>
<P>
   -- Flat Rock, N.C. _ Flat Rock Playhouse, the State Theatre of
North Carolina, presents the musical ``Annie Get Your Gun'' through
Sunday. 704-693-0731 or online at http://www.flatrockplayhouse.org
</P>
<P>
   -- Morgan City, La. _ The 1998 Louisiana Shrimp &AMP; Petroleum
Festival Sept. 3-7 in Morgan City, Berwick and Patterson includes
Music in the Park (Cajun, zydeco, blues, country, swamp rock), Mass
in the Park and Blessing of the Fleet, the Cajun Culinary Classic,
water parade of shrimp boats and pleasure craft and fireworks over
the Atchafalaya River. 1-800-256-2931 or
http://www.shrimp-petrofest.org.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lake Junaluska, N.C. _ The 27th annual Smoky Mountain Folk
Festival brings traditional Appalachian music and dance to Stuart
Auditorium Sept. 4 and 5. 828-452-0593.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hiawassee, Ga. _ The Fieldstone Inn hosts traditional arts
and crafts shows on the grounds of the inn Sept. 5. Weekend
lakeside cookouts will be available. 1-800-545-3408.
</P>
<P>
   -- Amelia Island, Fla. _ The Festival of Wine and New World
Cuisine Sept. 5-7 at the Ritz Carlton offers tastes of wine and
food from around the world. 904-277-1100.
</P>
<P>
   -- Orkney Springs, Va. _ The Shenandoah Valley Music Festival
features a folk festival with Tom Paxton, Sept. 5; big band
concert, Sept. 6. Orkney Springs Hotel. 1-800-459-3396 or
http://www.musicfest.org
</P>
<P>
   -- Louisville, Ky. _ ``Head, Heart and Hands: Native American
Craft Traditions in a Contemporary World'' at the Kentucky Art and
Craft Gallery features more than 50 pieces in a wide range of
media. Through Oct. 31. 502-589-0102.
</P>
<P>
   -- New Orleans _ The work of four Atlanta artists _ Gail Nathan,
Rocio Rodriquez, Deborah Wian Whithouse and Benjamin Jones _ is
included in the New Orleans Museum of Art's 113-year-old New
Orleans Triennial, the oldest continuing exhibition series of
contemporary art in America. Through Oct. 11. Also at the museum,
``Pressing Matters: American Pressed Glass, 1820-1920'' through
Oct. 18. 504-488-2631.
</P>
<P>
   -- Huntsville, Ala. _ ``The Red Clay Survey,'' a biennial juried
show, features 98 works by 63 Southern artists, from conceptual
pieces to traditional realism. At the Huntsville Museum of Art
through Oct. 25. 256-535-4350.
</P>
<P>
   -- Montgomery, Ala. _ ``Walter Thompson: A Symphony of Animals''
is at the Montgomery Music of Fine Arts through Nov. 15. The
exhibit includes a menagerie of animals depicted in pottery,
paintings and prints. 334-244-5700.
</P>
<P>
   -- St. Augustine, Fla. _ The Atlantic Shakespeare Company
presents ``The Merry Wives of Windsor'' Fridays and Saturdays
through Sept. 5, free admission at St. Augustine Amphitheatre.
904-471-1965.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jackson, Miss. _ ``Splendors of Versailles,'' the treasures
of French kings Louis XIV through Louis XVI, is at the Mississippi
Arts Pavilion through Aug. 31. 1-800-409-9959.
</P>
