<SLUG> BC-GM-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAW LEADERS ASSAIL GM, HINTING THAT TENSIONS PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Leaders of the United Automobile Workers strongly
criticized General Motors Corp. on Tuesday, a sign that this
summer's strikes in Flint, Mich. did not produce a reconciliation
and that next year's national contract talks between GM and the UAW
will be contentious.
</P>
<P>
   UAW president Stephen Yokich condemned GM's Aug. 3 announcement
of plans to spin off its auto parts subsidiary. Asked at a news
conference in Detroit on Tuesday what the UAW planned to do about
GM's plans, Yokich said that another strike was always possible,
although he added that the union might not do anything until Sept.
14, 1999. That is when the UAW's current national agreements with
GM, Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. are all scheduled to expire.
</P>
<P>
   GM and the UAW had also agreed at the end of the nearly
eight-week-long Flint strikes to begin holding regular, top-level
meetings to prevent future confrontations. But Richard Shoemaker,
the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said Tuesday that there had
been few discussions with GM since then.
</P>
<P>
   GM spokesman Gerald Holmes acknowledged that few meetings had
been held since the end of the strike, but attributed it to
vacations. ``We are serious about improving the relationship and
making this process work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives contended during the strike that the company must
reduce its labor costs to start earning a competitive return on its
shareholders' investment.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich and Shoemaker spoke at their first news conference since
they announced July 28 an agreement to end the strikes. Since then,
GM has announced several initiatives to try to make the company
more competitive: spin off the auto parts subsidiary, consolidate
its marketing staffs and build new assembly plants in North America
that would require fewer workers.
</P>
<P>
   Both UAW leaders offered a few small hints Tuesday of a
willingness to compromise. Yokich, for example, was cautious in
discussing GM's plans for new assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   The new factories would employ fewer workers by relying on
outside suppliers to deliver large chunks of vehicles, like
complete dashboards, instead of bolting every part together on the
assembly line. Some union advocates worry about GM's plans because
four out of every five auto supplier factories in the United States
are not unionized.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich said in a conversation with several reporters after the
news conference that the union had already won considerable job
security for its members and that some changes in production
processes were inevitable. The union will put greater emphasis on
outside suppliers being in the United States, than being unionized,
he said, although the union will still try to organize these
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if jobs are created at nonunion supplier factories in the
United States, he said, ``It's still an American job, isn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
