<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND MARKET STABLE AS DOLLAR RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bonds were firm Tuesday as overseas financial markets
stabilized and as the dollar's rise against the Japanese yen and
the German mark gave them a lift.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond was up 16/32, to a price
of 101 3/32, and the yield, which moves in the opposite direction,
ticked lower to 5.43 percent, from 5.46 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in keeping the bond market firm was that consumer
confidence as measured by the Conference Board, a private research
group, fell to an index reading of 133.1 in August from 137.2 in
July. It was the first consecutive decline in the series since
September-October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Chan, a managing director and chief economist at Banc
One Investment Advisors Corp. in Columbus, Ohio, said the reading
implied that the second half of the year would produce a
less-threatening pace of growth in consumption spending.
</P>
<P>
   However, investors' enthusiasm was tempered, he said, by a
second report that existing home sales increased 4 percent in July
to a monthly record 4.93 million units at an annualized rate. That
report provided a snapshot of the resiliency of the United States
economy. ``As a result, many market bulls were forced to admit that
they would need to see an even more extensive global market crisis
to justify significantly lower interest rates,'' Chan said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Treasury will auction $15 billion of a new
two-year note, and in when-issued trading Tuesday, the securities
were being offered at a price to yield 5.14 percent. On Thursday,
the government plans to sell $40 billion of 15-day cash management
bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
