<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-25 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONCERT OF WILLS': THE ART OF COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ah, for the life of the brilliant visionary artist:
the thrill of grand conception, the exhilaration of feverish
creation, the profound satisfaction of realization. Then accolades
and immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast!
</P>
<P>
   If the documentary ``Concert of Wills: Making the Getty Center''
is any guide, the process of creation is prolonged and dogged by
frustration and conflict. In the end, no matter what the visible
result or how heady the plaudits, the art that may have done most
to shape the outcome is the art of compromise and collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concert of Wills,'' opening Wednesday at the Film Forum, 209
W. Houston St., is itself a fine and painstaking work of art. It
tracks the 14 years leading to the realization of the plans
conceived by the architect Richard Meier for the six-building,
million-square-foot hillside complex that is the Getty Center in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Behind ``Concert of Wills'' stand three filmmakers accustomed to
acclaim for their documentaries: Susan Froemke, whose credits
include ``Letting Go: A Hospice Journey''; Bob Eisenhardt, whose
credits include ``Vladimir Horowitz: A Reminiscence'' and
``Soldiers of Music: Rostropovich Returns to Russia,'' and Albert
Maysles, who with his brother David blazed the trail into direct
cinema, the American version of the French cinema verite, with
films like ``Salesman,'' ``Gimme Shelter,'' ``Grey Gardens,''
``Christo's Valley Curtain'' and ``Vladimir Horowitz: The Last
Romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Getty Trust commissioned Maysles Films to document the
process of bringing the billion-dollar project to fruition. And the
filmmakers' access permitted them to record the arduous, often
contentious events that led to the opening of the Getty Center last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Meier, noted for his spare white enameled modernist buildings,
was, from the outset, up against the local residents and a
conditional use permit with more than 100 provisions, including one
that insisted that the exteriors of the center be constructed
primarily of stone.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Meier was also pitted against John Walsh, the
director of the J. Paul Getty Museum, and Walsh's traditionalist
focus on an interior design that would best display the center's
collections. Toward the end, the Getty Trust, with Harold Williams
as its president and chief executive and Stephen Rountree as its
vice president, turned to Thierry Despont, an architect who
concerned himself with the interiors, and Robert Irwin, an artist
charged with landscaping the center's central gardens _ a man who
clearly vexed Meier, usually seen maintaining a rather cheerful if
long-suffering demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concert of Wills'' also records meetings of the center's
design advisory committee and city planning commission sessions,
visits the Italian quarry that produced the travertine used for the
buildings' exteriors, and shows the transformation of the hillside
from scrubland to the glowing site of the completed project.
</P>
<P>
   If the cameras are never quite present when some of the
seemingly ceaseless differences over grand design and tiny detail
are resolved, ``Concert of Wills'' nevertheless conveys the tension
and drama of creation. Throughout, Meier struggles to realize a
conception that no end of meetings and drawings and scale models
seem ever to make visible in full subtlety and glory to anyone but
himself. Ever, that is, until the very end.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CONCERT OF WILLS: MAKING THE GETTY CENTER'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Susan Froemke, Bob Eisenhardt and Albert
Maysles; directors of photography, Maysles, Christophe Lanzenberg,
Christian Blackwood, Robert Richman and Giorgio Urbinelli; edited
by Eisenhardt; music by Joel Goodman; produced by Ms. Froemke;
released by Maysles Films Inc. At the Film Forum, 209 Houston St.,
Manhattan. Running time: 100 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Richard Meier, Harold Williams, Stephen Rountree, Ada
Louise Huxtable, John Walsh, Michael Palladino, Kurt Forster,
Robert Irwin and Thierry Despont.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
