<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANSON-CONCERT-REVIEW     08-25 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANSON-CONCERT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERT REVIEW: IT'S HANSON ALONG WITH EXCITED FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Little girls started screaming as the stage crew set up the
opening act, and they didn't stop until Hanson sang its last encore
on Monday night at the Continental Airlines Arena in East
Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing Hanson T-shirts, they waved homemade signs announcing
``Hanson We Love U'' or singling out one of the three Hanson
brothers _ Zachary, 12, Taylor, 15, and Isaac, 17 _ for particular
devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the pandemonium, the three cute blond brothers pretended
they were playing an ordinary rock concert. They barely flirted
with the audience, and limited their stage banter to lines like
``You guys ready to rock?'' The stage set was minimal; they didn't
surround themselves with special effects. Hanson wants to be a
band, not a novelty act.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson understands that kiddie idols have a short commercial
life span, and it has capitalized on its pop moment. Since the
release in 1997 of its major-label debut album, ``Middle of
Nowhere'' (Mercury), with its irresistible single, ``MMMBop,''
Hanson has reissued its home-recorded second album, ``Three-Car
Garage'' (Mercury), as well as a home video commemorating its first
promotional tour. The band has gone on to play concert tours, and
plans to release a live album in October. At the arena, a man with
a video camera shared the stage with the band, perhaps gathering
material for the next video clip.
</P>
<P>
   But releasing a live album is Hanson's way of saying that it's
not like most groups little girls squeal for, which tend to be
studio confections chosen more for looks than for musicianship. The
brothers write their own songs, though sometimes with adult
collaborators. They all play instruments: Zachary on drums, Taylor
on keyboards, Isaac on guitar. And they trade lead and harmony
vocals, with Taylor and Isaac emoting like younger versions of
Gregg Allman while Zachary pipes up with a touch of Michael
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, they had help: a guitarist, keyboardist and bassist
stood in the shadows behind Zachary's drum setup. But Hanson's own
instruments and voices were in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Hanson's songs are standard-issue pop for teenyboppers.
Little girls use kiddie-pop stars as the romantic equivalent of
training bras; they provide an introduction to adult desires and
abilities before they arrive. Kissing a photo of Leonardo DiCaprio
or screaming ``I want you!'' at a distant Hanson brother is a safe
test run for later relationships.
</P>
<P>
   For their side of the exchange, teenypop songs say the things
that real teen-age boyfriends probably won't: ``No matter what I
do, no matter where I go, I'll be thinking of you,'' Hanson
promises. Other Hanson songs pine for a lost girlfriend or try to
patch things up after a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, Hanson finds another topic: ``Man From
Milwaukee'' is a goofy fantasy, and ``Soldier'' is the kind of
story a child might make up about a favorite toy.
</P>
<P>
   And ``MMMBop,'' Hanson's one genuinely inspired song, is about
something else entirely: impermanence and the fragility of life, as
the brothers joyfully sing, ``In an mmmbop they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Between its own songs, Hanson played 1960s songs hinting at
lustier liaisons, like Cream's ``Sunshine of Your Love'' and the
Young Rascals' ``Good Lovin'.'' And it had one brilliant choice of
an oldie: ``Summertime Blues,'' ideal for a band whose members are
too young to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Hanson onstage made nearly every song sound the
same: a midtempo, steady-strumming three-chord tune that could have
been a Doobie Brothers outtake circa 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary is a sure, solid drummer, but Isaac is better off
playing rhythm guitar than revealing his elementary lead-guitar
skills. To hear Hanson perform live is to appreciate the producers
of ``Middle of Nowhere,'' who gave the songs dynamics, sonic
variety and a gimmick or two; on its own, Hanson rolls out its
songs like so many lengths of shag carpet.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, the band's limitations are drowned out
by the screams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
