u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      08-25 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: DIXIE CARTER'S NEW ROLE; ANNE FRANK DIARY; DOS
PASSOS PAINTINGS; STUDIO 54 POLL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dixie Carter, last seen on Broadway as Maria Callas
in Terrence McNally's Tony Award-winning play ``Master Class,'' is
headed for Washington. She will lead a cast of 17 in the
Shakespeare Theater production of the Oscar Wilde comedy ``A Woman
of No Importance,'' directed by Michael Kahn, the theater's
artistic director. Carter plays the title character, Mrs.
Arbuthnot, who seeks to protect her illegitimate son from the
corrupting influence of dandies and social climbers. The show opens
Tuesday and runs through Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ANNE FRANK DIARY
</P>
<P>
   A former employee of the Anne Frank Foundation says he will
return five missing pages from Anne Frank's original diary only if
his fellow Dutch scholars promote his Holocaust research in the
United States. The demand of the former employee, Cor Suijk,
prompted the Netherlands State Institute for War Documentation to
say yesterday that a lawyer may be needed to resolve the matter.
Suijk maintains that Otto Frank, Anne's father, gave him the pages
before his death in 1980 on condition that they would not be
published until the entire family had died. The institute, hoping
to include the pages in the next edition of the diary, maintains
that Otto Frank never intended them to be a gift to Suijk. The
pages are said to contain Anne's severe assessment of her parents'
marriage. Suijk said their contents would be disclosed on Sept. 14
in a Dutch documentary about Anne's years of hiding during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   DOS PASSOS PAINTINGS
</P>
<P>
   To mention John Dos Passos is to bring to mind fiction like
``Three Soldiers,'' ``Manhattan Transfer'' and the ``U.S.A.''
trilogy. But Dos Passos was also an artist of another sort _ a
modernist whose earliest works were drawn in the trenches during
World War I, when he drove ambulances in Italy for the Red Cross.
In the 1920s, his watercolors were shown in New York with works by
Matisse and Picasso, and he painted sets in Paris for the Ballets
Russe with Leger and Natalia Gontcharova. In the '30s, George Grosz
was a friend and influence. Over more than half a century, Dos
Passos created more than 600 works. Beginning on Sept. 9, under the
curatorship of Richard Layman, a Dos Passos scholar, 32 works will
be exhibited through Oct. 8 under the title ``Colors That Will Not
Fade'' at Century Association in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   STUDIO 54 POLL
</P>
<P>
   Virtually on the eve of Friday's opening of ``54,'' a film
revisiting the heyday of Studio 54, Miramax and MTV have released
the results of a poll that ranked the ``Top 54 Dance Songs of the
Disco Era.'' The Top Five are: ``I Will Survive,'' by Gloria
Gaynor; ``Stayin' Alive,'' by the Bee Gees; ``We Are Family,'' by
Sister Sledge; ``Bad Girls,'' by Donna Summer, and ``Good Times,''
by Chic.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1674 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-POLL-HNS &LR;      08-25 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS GROWING SUPPORT FOR PUBLIC AID FOR PRIVATE EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is growing public support for the use of tax
money to pay for private school education but no consensus on how
much tax money should be used, according to a poll released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted by the Gallup Organization, was sponsored by
Phi Delta Kappa International, a Bloomington, Ind.-based
professional group promoting public education, and by the Center on
Education Policy, a Washington-based organization that advocates
public education. The survey of 1,500 adults was conducted in June.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell C. Rose, executive director emeritus of Phi Delta Kappa
and co-author of a report summarizing the polls, said 44 percent of
the poll respondents supported using tax funds to send students to
private schools. A similar poll in 1993 showed only 24 percent of
respondents favored that concept.
</P>
<P>
   While the poll shows growing support for the use of tax money to
pay for private education, the survey also found that respondents
were divided over how much tax money should go to private
education, Rose told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed more support for government funding that only
paid part of private tuition than programs that would pay full
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also asked people about two different kinds of
funding. One approach, the voucher system, would give parents
government-issued notes that pay for tuition. The other approach
would reimburse parents for tuition payments through tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   For tax credits, the partial reimbursement plan won more favor
among poll respondents, regardless of the answer about public
funding for private education. Partial reimbursement won support
from 66 percent of respondents, while a full refund was approved by
56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For vouchers, government help for part of the tuition was also
favored over full tuition, with 52 percent of people in support of
partial vouchers; 48 percent said they would favor full vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents could indicate support of either option or both
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The findings appear to guarantee that the issue of public
funding for church-related schools will be a battleground for the
foreseeable future,'' Rose noted.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that the public wants private schools that
accept any public funding to be held accountable to the state just
as public schools are. This idea ``may be unacceptable to private
school advocates,'' the report warned.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's main conclusion was criticized by the National
Education Association _ the largest teachers union in the nation
and a leading advocate of public schools. The NEA issued a
statement saying Americans ``demand accountability for their public
education dollars, and that's impossible if we give public tax
dollars to private and religious schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Congress approved legislation that would
create tax-free savings accounts capped at $2,000 per year if used
for elementary and secondary education expenses including private
schools. The measure, sponsored by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., was
vetoed by President Clinton on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings from the report:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty percent of those polled believe that any state budget
surplus should be used for public schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ More parents fear for their child's safety at school.
Thirty-six percent say they are afraid in 1998 compared to 25
percent in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   _ More people think it is important to improve inner-city
school, with 86 percent of those polled supporting that goal, up
from 74 percent in 1989. Sixty-six percent said they would be
willing to pay more taxes to help improve those schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ The biggest problem facing local schools is
fighting/violence/gangs, according to 15 percent of the poll
respondents. Lack of discipline comes in second at 14 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
