<HEADLINE>
LEWIS F. POWELL JR., 90; CONSERVATIVE SUPREME COURT JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lewis F. Powell Jr., whose tempered conservatism on the bench
made him a crucial swing vote during his 15 years as a Supreme
Court justice, died in his sleep from pneumonia Tuesday at his home
in Richmond, Va. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the respect shown by liberals and conservatives
alike, President Clinton Tuesday called Powell ``one of our most
thoughtful and consciencious justices,'' and said ``his opinions
were a model of balance and judiciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the greatest tribute to Justice Powell came four
years after he was named to the court. When President Gerald R.
Ford was looking to fill the vacancy created by the retirement of
Justice William O. Douglas, he confined his instructions to
Attorney General Edward Levi to a single sentence: ``Find me
another Lewis Powell.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a mark of just how quickly _ and thoroughly _ Justice
Powell had established a reputation for ability, diligence and
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Powell was named to the court by President Richard M.
Nixon and served as an associate justice from 1972 to 1987, a
tenure largely coinciding with that of Chief Justice Warren Burger.
The Burger Court marked a transitional period in US jurisprudence,
coming as it did between the judicial activism of the Warren Court
and the rightward shift of the Rehnquist Court. Lacking a dominant
judicial philosophy, the Burger Court was an opportune setting for
Justice Powell's centrism. Further enhancing his sway with his
colleagues was a personal manner of unfailing civility and
graciousness _ Justice Powell's ``humanizing influence,'' as
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor once termed it. Judicial historian
Bernard Schwartz has gone so far as to suggest that the Burger
Court might be more accurately known as ``the Powell Court,'' as
Justice Powell was ``probably its single most influential member.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Powell considered his most important opinion to be
University of California Regents v. Bakke. Bakke, the landmark 1978
ruling on the constitutionality of affirmative action, was perhaps
the court's most charged racial case since Brown v. Board of
Education, the 1954 decision ending school segregation. It was
Justice Powell who determined its outcome, an outcome exemplifying
his gift for compromise and moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Four justices voted to uphold, and four justices voted to
overturn a California Supreme Court ruling which had banned race as
a factor in admissions to all the state's schools and ordered the
admission of the plaintiff into medical school. (Allan Bakke was
white, and the school that had rejected him reserved 16 percent of
its spaces for minority applicants.)
</P>
<P>
   Justice Powell, in effect, sided with both. He voted to reverse
the quota _ but to affirm the overall principle of taking race into
account. ``Race or ethnic background may be deemed a `plus' in a
particular applicant's file,'' he wrote, ``yet it does not insulate
the individual from comparison with all other candidates for the
available seats.''
</P>
<P>
   That affirmative action should receive its constitutional
justification from an aristocratic Virginian who initially had
mixed feelings (at best) about the Brown ruling was but one of
several ironies attending the career of Lewis Franklin Powell Jr.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Suffolk, Va., on Sept. 19, 1907, the son of Lewis
Franklin Powell and Mary Lewis (Gwathmey) Powell. On his father's
side, Justice Powell was descended from one of the original
Jamestown colonists.
</P>
<P>
   He earned undergraduate and law degrees from Washington and Lee
University in Lexington, Va., and then spent a year getting a
master of laws degree at Harvard University. Among his teachers
there were future Supreme Court Justice Felix Frankfurter and the
legendary Harvard Law School dean Roscoe Pound.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Powell returned to Richmond, where he had grown up and
would practice law for the next 40 years. During World War II, he
served in the US Army Air Force, rising to the rank of colonel.
Justice Powell worked as a US liaison officer with British
intelligence's top-secret Ultra project, which had decrypted German
codes. He was awarded the Legion of Merit, the Bronze Star and the
French Croix de Guerre.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Justice Powell became a leading civic figure in
Richmond and Virginia. He served as chairman of the Colonial
Williamsburg Foundation, the Richmond School Board and Virginia
State Board of Education. In the latter two positions, he worked
behind the scenes to oppose the state's ``massive resistance
policy'' to desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Powell's firm, Hunton, Williams, Gay, Powell &AMP; Gibson,
was one of the region's most prestigious, and he used it as a
springboard to leadership in the legal profession. President
Johnson appointed him to the President's Commission on Law
Enforcement and the Administration of Justice, and he served as
president of the American Bar Association, the American Bar
Foundation, the American College of Trial Lawyers and as vice
president of the National Legal Aid and Defender Association.
</P>
<P>
   As both that last position and his role in desegregating
Virginia schools might have indicated, Justice Powell was not quite
the dyed-in-the-cotton Southern conservative Nixon might have
assumed. By 1969, Justice Powell had earned a national reputation
as a ``lawyer's lawyer,'' and it was only natural that Nixon should
turn to him when the Senate rejected the nomination of Judge
Clement Haynsworth to the court. Justice Powell refused, however,
citing his age and frail health.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, when Justice Hugo Black died, Nixon again
turned to Powell. Again Powell said no. Then, after finally saying
yes, he had second thoughts and tried to withdraw. It was too late.
Within hours Nixon was telling reporters, ``Some said he was told
old, but 10 years of him is worth 30 years of most.''
</P>
<P>
   The reluctant justice soon came to relish his position on the
nation's highest court. Yet the irony of the preface to his court
career was exceeded by that of its postscript. To succeed Justice
Powell, the epitome of consensus and comity, President Ronald
Reagan nominated Judge Robert H. Bork. Naming such an ideologically
charged candidate set off one of the most rancorous confirmation
battles in Senate history. It ended in Bork's rejection _ and
ushered in an era of politicization of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Such politicization stood far removed from what Justice Powell
stood for, and he lamented it. It was one of the few regrets he had
concerning the court. Two others were his having provided the
deciding vote in Bowers v. Hardwick, which in 1986 dismayed civil
libertarians by upholding a Georgia anti-sodomy law, and his
support of the death penalty. In 1991, he said that he now believed
that capital punishment should be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was hospitalized in 1991 for a fainting spell and
irregular heartbeat; he also had hip-replacement surgery that year.
A year earlier, he had said his health was holding up better than
he expected, but added, ``Let's face it, I've outlived my
generation. Most of the friends I have held dear through my life
are dead now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked once to account for his spectacular success, Justice
Powell gave a characteristically modest reply: ``I worked hard,
some others didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's wife, Josephine, died in 1996. He is survived by his
four children, two of whom are lawyers, nine grandchildren and one
great grandson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
