<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK STUDENTS STILL SCARCE AT MAJOR COLLEGES, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite decades of desegregation and affirmative
action, black students continue to fill only a fraction of the
freshman classes at flagship universities in states that once
deliberately segregated black and and white students, according to
a report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most states, there are still two systems'' of higher
education, said Claire V. Handley, co-author of ``Miles to Go: A
Report on Black Students and Postsecondary Education in the
South.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, produced by the Atlanta-based Southern Education
Foundation Inc., examines enrollment, family income and graduation
rates in 19 states that previously operated separate systems of
higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to popular belief, the gap between blacks and whites
for opportunity and achievement is not being closed,'' said
foundation president Elridge W. McMillan. The report ``challenges
the belief that blacks are making real progress'' in higher
education, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 19 states, blacks made up an average of 20 percent of
the college-age population in 1996 and 17 percent of the first-year
students at all universities, including two-year colleges. At
flagship universities, however, blacks represented only 8.6 percent
of the freshman class in 1996, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditionally white universities remain predominantly
white,'' Handley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the misinformation ... blacks do not have an
unfair advantage in admissions policies,'' said Norman C. Francis,
president of Xavier University of Louisiana in New Orleans and a
member of the advisory panel that reviewed the report.
</P>
<P>
   Francis said he is disturbed by the numbers of black students
who do not finish college after starting _ ``this is a devastating
loss of human and economic potential for this nation'' _ and
attributed much of the problem to money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial aid, or the lack thereof, continues to be a major
factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report examined the average tuition of four-year, public
universities in the 19 states and found that tuition consumes a
higher percentage of the income of black families than white
families.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
