<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF DIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A friend who recently returned from London reports
that our British cousins think our national obsession with Monica
Lewinsky and her pathetic sexual interlude with President Clinton
reflects a sorry case of collective sophomoric madness.
</P>
<P>
   Ha. So how do the British explain their own compulsion, as the
first anniversary of Princess Diana's death approaches, to pay
overwrought tribute to her and find exaggerated meaning in her
memory?
</P>
<P>
   During this entire week Great Britain is indulging in an orgy of
emotion with a rash of special events commemorating the life of
beautiful princess of Wales, who died in an automobile crash last
Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The public hysteria and blind adulation that immediately
followed Diana's death are now supplemented by a frenzied rush of
books, television specials, opinion polls, magazine articles,
tourist attractions and public pronouncements. Nexis, the American
computer research system, lists 243 stories about Diana since the
beginning of the month.
</P>
<P>
   This is in addition to the regular Diana stuff available, for a
price, all during the past year, _ magazine cover stories, charity
concerts, tourist gimmicks, small tubs of margarine with her photo
on them, the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Even the French have gotten into the act, scheduling a
candlelight vigil at the Paris site of the fatal car crash and
telling pollsters they want a street to be named after her.
</P>
<P>
   A French survey reported, in all seriousness, that Diana was the
woman who most deeply marked the 20th century, followed only by
Jacqueline Kennedy and Marilyn Monroe. The French apparently never
heard of Queen Elizabeth, Indira Gandhi, Margaret Thatcher, Eleanor
Roosevelt or Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Diana is as controversial in death as she was
in life, despite the flattering fascination with her complicated
personality, her charitable activities, her alienation from the
royal family and even her dresses. British newspapers that
conducted polls to try to assess the impact of her death produced
contradictory, inconclusive results.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the tabloid Mirror found that 77 percent of women and
56 percent of men surveyed were ``still grieving'' for Diana.
Another poll said 52 percent of the people believe that she
inspired the country to become more spiritually aware and giving.
</P>
<P>
   But a poll for the Independent newspaper reported that 80
percent of those surveyed said her death had not permanently
affected them and that 53 percent did not want the anniversary to
be officially observed each year.
</P>
<P>
   According to a poll by the Mail on Sunday, 62 percent of those
surveyed said they would do nothing to commemorate her death and 50
percent said public grieving after the accident had gone overboard.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant development since her death appears to be a
softening of public attitudes toward Prince Charles and the rest of
the royal family. The message here for President Clinton may be
that it is unwise to react too hastily to predictions of doom. The
passage of time and a good public relations campaign, it seems,
lessen public pressure for radical political punishment for bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months have certainly reduced the animosity the British
public felt toward the royals for their rude treatment of Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Before her death Charles was widely seen as a cold-hearted,
foolish adulterer who should never be king. There were even
whispers about getting rid of the monarchy altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But a new Sunday Times poll says 62 percent of those surveyed
now want Queen Elizabeth to remain on the throne for life, 58
percent think Charles is fit to be king and 57 percent say the
monarchy is ``more in touch with the people'' these days. Not total
adoration, but a big improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The real test of the royals' rehabilitation, however, is whether
Charles' longtime mistress Camilla Parker Bowles will become
socially acceptable. Shortly after Diana's death, 55 percent told
the pollsters they disapproved of the idea that Charles would marry
her. Now only 46 percent feel that way, while 42 percent say they
should stay together and publicly admit their relationship and 38
percent believe they should marry.
</P>
<P>
   This growing sense of forgiveness encouraged Charles not long
ago to introduce his elder son William at last to Parker Bowles.
The meeting reportedly went okay.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she will never generate the excitement of the young
bride who married the most eligible bachelor in the world in
Westminster Abbey at a fairy-tale wedding before a television
audience of 8 million viewers. Diana's fame is singular.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean her reputation is secure. Lord Coggan, the
former archbishop of Canterbury, had the bad taste to attack her
last weekend as ``a false goddess'' with ``pretty loose morals.''
Two Sunday school teachers told their pupils that Diana was in hell
because of her sins. A charity-sponsored walk along the route of
her funeral cortege that had expected 15,000 paid participants last
Sunday was a bust. Only 300 people turned out, and the organizers
lost money.
</P>
<P>
   The first anniversary of her death will pass amid tribute and
turmoil. She will always be a commodity, good for sales and
publicity. But the sentimentality is already fading, and so will
the schmaltz. And then everyone will have to discover a new
goddess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
