<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MFSPRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILIE DEFEATS SQUILLARI, 6-4, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Andrew Ilie isn't the hardest player to
recognize on a tennis court. He's the guy wearing the Air Jordans,
usually seen on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his return to the ATP circuit last November, the
Australian's new attire and renewed skills have served him well.
Take Tuesday's first-round victory over Franco Squillari in the MFS
Pro Championships at Longwood Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-4, 6-2 score only begins to suggest Ilie's domination. His
overall court game was excellent, not surprising as he was once
ranked along with countrymate Mark Philippoussis as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Now 22, Ilie thinks there is enough left in his game to compete
with the best. He has recovered from nagging back problems but
knows he has to prove himself again in the eyes of his peers. To
that end, he has played in about 25 tournaments, including
satellite events.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's victory, he is 14-8 on the ATP tour, his lone
tournament victory coming in May at Coral Springs, Fla., where he
breezed through four players and beat Davide Sanguinetti in the
final, 7-5, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Ilie made the third round of the French Open before losing, and
stops in Italy, Washington, Montreal, and Cincinnati reflect his
desire to reach the upper rankings. Since Jan. 19, when he reached
the third round of the Australian Open, Ilie's ranking has moved
from No. 282 to No. 51. Some think he could be a sleeper in the US
Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment,'' said Ilie, ``all the Aussies are playing
good. Pat Rafter has been unbelievable. Philippoussis has been
playing good himself and will probably do well at the US Open.
Right now, I'm ranked about six or seven in Australia. I feel like
I'm playing pretty good tennis. I'm looking forward to the US Open,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Jordans worn by Ilie are low cut and resemble shoes worn
by a boxer or wrestler. ``But they're lighter than tennis shoes and
help my movement,'' said Ilie. ``The only problem I have is that
they're sold out a lot and hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   His shoes are just another reflection of Ilie's ability to put a
little fun in his game. He is superstitious, romances the crowd,
fumes occasionally at umpires, and wears a red bandanna under his
cap.
</P>
<P>
   His reward for winning Tuesdayis a second-round date with No. 3
seed Cedric Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   Ilie, who was born in Romania, has done things a little
differently during most of his brief career. He first caught the
attention of Australian tennis officials in his country's 1994
Junior Open, losing in the finals. Later that year, he won the
Canada and US junior opens and finished No. 8 in the world rankings
at the age of 17.
</P>
<P>
   But then his career took a twist, partially because of his
success. After a Davis Cup apprenticeship in South Africa, Ilie
reportedly went AWOL on a tour sponsored by the Australian
Institute of Sport. According to a May 29 report in the Melbourne
Age, Ilie flew to Bucharest in chase of a sponsorship deal. He had
dealings with a Romanian businessman and he was seen at the
Austrian training camp of coach Gunther Bosch. Ilie appeared on the
verge of a major career change.
</P>
<P>
   But the change was not what he thought. When Ilie returned home
at the end of the 1995 season, it was without promised financial
backing of those who had urged him to jump. Once back, he had
fences to mend with Tennis Australia, and apparently has done so in
recent months. His life because even more complicated by a back
problem in 1996 that took him out of circulation for 18 months.
Now, he'd like a shot at representing Australia in the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was in 1995,'' said Ilie in a recent article,
``was that people got the wrong idea. They sort of waiting for me
to not feel at home. The Romanians didn't like me because I'm
Australian. The Australians tried to pull the Romanian thing on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to cool down. I'm Australian and more than happy to
play for Australia, if I'm needed. But that should be the end of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad can he be? He is fifth in the ATP rankings among
Australians behind Patrick Rafter (3), Philippoussis (21), Richard
Fromberg (30), Jason Stoltenberg (38).
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're all good players,'' said Ilie. ``But I think I
can hold my own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
