<SLUG> BC-BA-PLANE-ORDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING BYPASSED AS BRITISH AIR GIVES BIG CONTRACT TO AIRBUS
INDUSTRIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a setback to Boeing Co., British Airways awarded the European
aircraft consortium Airbus Industrie a major contract Tuesday,
ordering as many as 188 of its short-haul, single-aisle jets, worth
$8.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The order for the planes, which will be outfitted with engines
built by a consortium headed by the Rolls-Royce aviation company of
Britain, is expected to assure jobs for 38,000 people at factories
of Rolls-Royce and British Aerospace, one of the four partners in
the Airbus group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, until now, British Airways, Europe's largest airline, had
relied on Boeing as its supplier. As it ordered the Airbus planes
Tuesday, the carrier announced that it would purchase 16 new Boeing
777-200 jets, with an option for 16 more, at a total list price of
$4.8 billion. The twin-engine planes have a 256-seat capacity. But
British Air said it was canceling previous orders for 5 of 15
larger and more expensive Boeing 747-400s, as well as options to
buy a further seven 747s.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to put the best face on the matter, Ron Woodard,
president of Boeing's commercial airplane group, praised British
Airways as a ``longtime valued Boeing customer and our largest
customer outside the United States.'' He added that Boeing was
delighted that the carrier chose the 777 to meet ``increasing
demand they are experiencing for frequent point-to-point service in
the long-haul market.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, British Air executives said they were seeking
bids from both Airbus and Boeing, for short-haul jets on domestic
British and European routes, to replace Boeing 737s now in service,
as well as for long-haul aircraft on intercontinental routes.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus order was announced at a news conference in Toulouse,
France, the Airbus headquarters, that was attended by British Prime
Minister Tony Blair. Monday, managers at one of the companies had
suggested the Airbus order would be larger than it turned out to
be, with up to 259 firm orders and options.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, however, British Airways is ordering 39 Airbus A319s,
carrying as many as 126 passengers, and 20 A320s, with up to 156
passengers. It has options to order an additional 129 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   By placing the order with Airbus and choosing Rolls-Royce
engines, British Airways insures that much of the work will be done
in Britain. Parts of the new A320 planes, like the wings, are built
by British Aerospace, which holds a 20 percent stake in Airbus.
Also, Rolls-Royce has a one-third stake in International Aero
Engines, the jet engine maker that also includes Pratt &AMP; Whitney
and MTU Motoren- und Turbinen-Union of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways chief executive Robert Ayling insisted that the
choice of Airbus was made on the basis of cost alone. The offer by
Airbus and Rolls-Royce, he said at the news conference, ``was a
better value offer than the competitive offer. If it had not been,
we would not be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayling said Boeing would remain British Airways' sole provider
of long-haul planes. The airline now flies 18 of the twin-engine
777s, equipped with General Electric engines, and the new orders
signaled a clear shift away from the older, larger 747s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
