A1695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLS-CLINTON26-COX     08-25 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLS-CLINTON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON POLLING POINTS TO UNSETTLED PUBLIC
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, buoyed by a good economy but
weighed down by scandal, is testing the skills of pollsters. Does
the public love him or love him not?
</P>
<P>
   In perplexing results from surveys taken by ABC News since
Clinton admitted to having an improper relationship with a former
White House intern, the president's favorable ratings sagged to 39
percent on Aug. 19, roared back to 56 percent two days later, and
then leveled off at 45 percent by last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   What gives?
</P>
<P>
   The order of questions asked during the surveys made the
difference, ABC pollster Gary Langer said in an interview after the
erratic numbers were featured in the electronic daily newsletter,
The Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Langer said that when poll takers ask about Clinton's
professional job performance first, the answers tend to be
positive, leading to higher ratings on the more general
``favorable'' rating, as well. But if the scandal was mentioned
first, the favorable rating dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, there's not a huge difference between job
performance and favorable ratings, so it doesn't much matter,''
Langer said. ``But in this unique case of President Clinton today,
there is an enormous difference between the two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean the polls are wacky or contradictory,'' said
Langer, who instead attributed the results to the public's complex
view of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is looking at two Bill Clintons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That view is echoed by other public opinion experts. ``More than
usual, subtle changes in the questions and the order of questions
may have more of an impact'' on survey results, said Frank Newport,
editor in chief at the Gallup Poll. ``People have complex portraits
of Bill Clinton in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Gallup organization continues to track Clinton's
support, as it has other presidents, by asking first the job
performance question, followed by the more general favorability
question. The results has yielded consistent and relatively high
favorable ratings of between 50 and 53 percent for the president
since mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   But the seesaw results in the ABC poll could be a more accurate
depiction of the unsettled public perception of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it tells me is that the public has not given its final
word on this topic,'' said Darrell West, political science
professor and polling expert at Brown University, ``It just means
that the game is going to go on until we actually get all of the
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Added West: ``The Starr report (expected next month from
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr) is the big shoe waiting to fall,
and when that comes out, it probably will have a major effect on
public opinion, just because it will provide a level of detail that
we haven't heard yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were sitting in the White House, I'd be very nervous
about these surveys and their suggestion of a possible downside in
the public reaction as the public learns more.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
