<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVE THE BODIES AND BRING IN FRESH TOWELS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The brutal Romanian dictator  &UR; Nicolae Ceausescu &LR;  and his wife,
the fur-loving &UR; Elena &LR; , were executed by unfriendly citizens in
1989, but the palaces and villas in which they lived still have
that special glow. Come next spring, the government of Romania will
offer tourists the chance to stay chez Ceausescu for $3,000 to
$4,000 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Sojourns will include the opportunity to sleep in a bed once
occupied by Mr. Big and his Mrs., and to engage in such frolics as
hunting or swimming in their mosaic-lined pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guests will get a really special reception,'' said  &UR; Mihai &LR; 
 &UR; Nica &LR; , a government official. ``They will be able to relax and at
the same time think this belonged to Ceausescu.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Prince Charles &LR;  is having trouble remembering people's names,
says a forthcoming book by his friend  &UR; Anthony Holden &LR; , and is
being treated for ``short-term memory loss.'' ``During his official
engagements, he is introduced to a wide range of people,'' a royal
source told Holden, ``and he has noticed that he later forgets
their names. All the specialist is doing is helping him remember
those names.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Paid product placement in movies _ Ford, Zenith and Schwinn in
``The Truman Show,'' for example _ is an everyday thing, but the
Kentucky Fried Chicken scene in ``Bulworth'' was a freebie, says
the latest Mother Jones.
</P>
<P>
   KFC spokesman  &UR; Michael Tierney  &LR; says the company usually doesn't
try to cut deals to put its delicacies in movies. ``Our core folks
tend to watch more television.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Arion Press is not publishing ``Tales of the City'';  &UR; Wayne &LR; 
 &UR; Thiebaud &LR; 's illustrations will grace  &UR; Italo Calvino &LR; 's ``Invisible
Cities,'' a classic of a very other stripe. Meanwhile, fans of
 &UR; Armistead Maupin &LR; 's work can keep up with current developments at
the new Web site www.talesofthecity.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A TALENT GETS RECOGNIZED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen teenage members of the Crossroads Touring Company of
Santa Monica were in the Bay Area earlier this month, performing
``A Chorus Line'' in drug rehab centers, retirement homes, recovery
facilities and children's centers, all clients of Bread &AMP; Roses.
</P>
<P>
   During a show at The Redwoods, a senior citizens' community in
Mill Valley,  &UR; Marian Winkler &LR; , an 86-year-old woman trained in
Europe as a concert pianist, recognized the special ability of the
group's 21-year-old accompanist and musical director,  &UR; Alpen &LR; 
 &UR; Hong &LR; . When the planned show was over, and Winkler asked Hong for
an individualized concert, he lifted the lid off the grand and gave
a gala performance of selections by Chopin and other classical
composers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he had finished, 30 people had joined a delighted
Winkler. When his ``Chorus Line'' duties are over, Hong will be off
to Russia in a few months to compete in the Tchaikovsky piano
competition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO WRITE A SONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Jimmy Webb &LR; 's forthcoming book, ``Tunesmith,'' the
songwriter describes the process of choosing ``a title or a hook
line,'' in which he looks for a ``key word that offers the greatest
number of rhyming possibilities.'' In the course of writing ``Just
for Now,'' he says, in an excerpt published in Musician magazine,
he considered about 44 rhymes, including:
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow (``usable, but not a very attractive word and definitely
overused''); brow (``nobody really says `brow' anymore, they say
`forehead' ''); dhow (``arcane, perhaps might find a home in
special material''); disallow (``smacks of the IRS''); disavow
(``legalese''); frau (``she's not German''); Hangkow (``in
China''); hoosegow (``it's not a Western either''); plough, plow
(``a rough word, distinctly out of place in a romantic song'');
pow-wow (``unusable''); slough (``a mass of dead tissue separating
from an ulcer''); vow (``Dudley Do-Right, smells moldy'').
</P>
<P>
   When he realized that only five were usable, he decided to call
the song ``Just for Today,'' which had 258 rhyming possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``A sign of a good executive is someone who doesn't return phone
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Terry Semel, co-CEO of Warner Bros., quoted in Los Angeles
magazine.
</P>
