<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-TERROR-275&AMP;AD     08-25 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TERROR-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR TO RECALL PARLIAMENT TO BEEF UP ANTI-TERROR LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair announced Tuesday that he was
calling Parliament back into session from its summer recess next
week to toughen anti-terrorism laws.
</P>
<P>
   Similar measures are being contemplated by the Irish Republic
after the bombing in Omagh, in the British province of Northern
Ireland, that took 28 lives and wounded 220 people.
</P>
<P>
   Blair made the widely expected announcement when he visited
Omagh on Tuesday. British officials said he might ask Parliament
either to tighten existing laws or to seek ``draconian''
legislation to obtain convictions against members of banned
terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Conservative opposition, William Hague, said
he expected Parliament to convene next Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The car bombing in Omagh, the deadliest attack in 29 years of
conflict over Northern Ireland, has brought calls across both
Ireland and Britain for tougher measures against political
violence. The British and Irish governments appear to be moving in
sync to reassure the public that they are serious in their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Republic's Prime Minister Bertie Ahern has already
announced plans to tighten anti-terrorism legislation and has
recalled the Irish Parliament for next week to consider the
measures.
</P>
<P>
   In Omagh om Tuesday, Blair found the town still in shock 10 days
after a 500-pound car bomb tore apart a commercial street, killing
and wounding weekend shoppers. He met relatives of the victims and
medical personnel who cared for them. His next stop was Belfast, to
meet with leaders of Northern Ireland's main political parties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week Blair, who was vacationing in France, signified his
intent by speaking of increased cooperation with the Irish
government so that there would be little opportunity for violent
groups to operate in either country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will bring in similar measures to those proposed by the
Irish government, so we will then have the toughest anti-terrorist
measures for the whole of the island of Ireland, the Republic and
Northern Ireland, that we have ever seen,'' Blair said last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While Blair did not elaborate, the measures are likely to
include a provision for reinstating ``internment'' _ the power to
hold terrorism suspects for several days without bringing charges.
He is also expected to propose tightening bail conditions for those
accused of crimes and narrowing the scope of their right to silence
under questioning.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman in Blair's office confirmed Tuesday that the
objective of any new laws would be to take action against any
terror organizations and their members before they act.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensitive issue expected to be on the agenda would be
internment. The Blair government abolished internment last year,
and Catholics fear the measure could be used arbitrarily to round
up political activists as well as potential terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the British Parliament was recalled was in 1990,
when Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher obtained its agreement to
dispatch British forces to the Persian Gulf after Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait. Parliament has been recalled from summer recess 14 times
since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Whether new laws will in fact be necessary is not clear. Several
British officials said last week that laws to toughen government
measures were already largely in place, needing only refinements in
their application. Officials emphasized, however, that Britain
would do whatever was necessary to enable security forces to act
quickly and decisively.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread support was expected for any new measures enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mackay, who oversees the Northern Ireland policies of the
opposition Conservatives, said Monday that his party would fully
cooperate to bring ``evil psychopaths'' to justice and to insure
swift passage of measures to crack down on terrorist activities.
``I believe our security forces must be able to tackle terrorism
with every tool available,'' Mackay said .
</P>
<P>
   Last week Blair's Northern Ireland minister, Paul Murphy, said
Britain was working hand in hand with Ireland to track down those
responsible for the Omagh attack and to insure that other groups
could be stopped before they act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of all this, of course,'' he said, ``is to catch
these people, to insure they are caught as quickly as possible,
that they are arrested, that they are convicted and put into
prison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
