<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-MASKS-EXHIBIT-     08-25 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MASKS-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: A SPIRIT LIVES ON, AS MAGICAL MASKS GUARD INDIAN
TRADITIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ The European settlers who came to
this region more than a century ago struck up an oddly conflicted
relationship with the native peoples. They suppressed what they saw
as the Indians' backward religious beliefs, but eagerly embraced
the most visible expression of their intensely spiritual culture,
the esthetically powerful masks used in many ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   From the time Capt. James Cook made his famous voyage here in
the 18th century and well into this century, the graphically
sophisticated ceremonial masks of the Pacific Northwest Coast
Indians have been highly prized in the art world, and purchased by
connoisseurs and museums from Canada to Vienna and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The collecting itself has had a fascinating legacy, as a
striking new exhibition here at the Vancouver Art Gallery
demonstrates. While it commercialized this once-sacred art as early
as the 1820s, transforming it into an export industry, it also did
much to preserve the mask-making tradition _ and, by extension, the
vivid imagery of the Indians' spiritual world _ while some other
elements of the native culture withered.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ``Down From the Shimmering Sky: Masks of the
Northwest Coast,'' a huge compilation of pieces from collections in
North America and Europe that runs through Oct. 12, is one of the
most heavily attended shows ever at the Vancouver Art Gallery, the
principal public art museum of Western Canada. It is scheduled to
travel next year to museums in Portland, Ore., and Tulsa, Okla.
Negotiations are under way as well for a show at the end of 1999 at
the National Museum of the American Indian in New York, which owns
some of the masks in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The 179 painted masks on display, representing everything from
killer whales and bears to supernatural beings, the sun and
ancestors, are penetrating and at times emotionally intense
representations of the spiritual world of the Northwest Coast
Indians. But the show is noteworthy as well because it places
150-year-old masterpieces side by side with contemporary masks,
underscoring the sense of an artistic continuum rather than the
melancholy of a lost tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Joseph, a hereditary chief of the Kwakwaka'wakw tribe and
one of the show's curators, emphasized the significance of
exhibiting the masks in the Vancouver, a gallery of the Canadian
establishment normally devoted to contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a statement about our history and our place here,''
Joseph said. ``These masks continue to have meaning and continue to
have a purpose for our communities, and I think that comes across
here very strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   The show has helped open up some of the innermost recesses of
Indian culture to the world, an achievement that has stirred some
controversy within the native communities of British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The opening ceremony for the exhibition last month in the court
in front of the gallery, for example, included a dance that had
previously been performed only on ceremonial occasions before an
Indian audience. Some of the masks in the show, particularly those
of mythical cannibal beings, are regarded as so sacred by some
Indians of the region _ tribes like the Haida, Nuxalk, Tsimshian,
Tlingit and Heiltsuk _ that they argue they should not be put on
public display at all.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph acknowledged the dissent, but said the show served the
important goals of building understanding of Indian culture as it
tries to modernize and function alongside society's mainstream and
of fostering pride within the Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little boy, we got together with the old chief
and closed the door and let no outsiders in the Big House,'' said
Joseph. ``No cameras, no recorders. But those doors have opened
somewhat to outsiders, as long as they are respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``How will people respect us if we don't tell them
about who we are?''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Macnair, another of the show's curators, said the
exhibition was important partly because it returns to their
homeland many masks that were taken away by Indian agents,
collectors and dealers more than a century ago. An enormous amount
of research went into locating and identifying important masks,
including some taken away by Captain Cook and some that were
captured in photographs before they were whisked away to
collections elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a homecoming, Macnair said, strengthened the show
and underscored the sense of a strong and living tradition with
deep roots in the Indian imagination and local trade.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the research done for the show is that it includes
a number of examples of what became known as Jenna Cass masks,
among the first known examples believed to have been carved
specifically for sale. Previously the masks had been made for use
in the dance dramas that are a critical part of the potlatch, a
huge ceremony that is a central part of Northwest Coast Indian
society and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Macnair said that the name used by the Europeans, Jenna Cass,
was probably a vulgarization of Djilakons, the Indian term for the
god on whom the mask is modeled. One of the earliest such examples,
a handsome mask painted in blue and red, was made before 1828.
</P>
<P>
   Later Europeans were fascinated by the native women's practice
of wearing a wooden disk, or labret, inserted into a slot cut into
the lower lip. So Indian artisans began to carve masks in which the
figures wore labrets, apparently to make their masks more
marketable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some tribes, the art had just about faded away, but then
they started making masks again, around 1970 or so, when they
realized how much money could be made,'' said Macnair. ``The
commercial tradition bridged the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   The artistry can be stunning. Carved mostly from cedar, the
masks tend to be roughly realistic, with heavy eyebrows, open
mouths and open eyes. Most were painted with dynamic geometric
patterns in red, blue, turquoise and black.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more powerful exhibits are the transformation masks,
in which folding parts open up to reveal a different character or
being within another. In one example, on loan from a collection in
Stuttgart, a bird opens up into the sun in a sort of panorama.
</P>
<P>
   The mask used as the symbol for the exhibition, on loan from the
American Museum of Natural History in New York, is also a
representation of the sun, a large circular image highlighted with
vermilion paint and surrounded by a pattern of hand prints.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the masks were meant to be worn in dances that were
``owned'' by specific families or clans and that could only be
performed with the masks.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition includes some photographs from the 1940s of
dances held out of sight of the authorities in which Joseph
appears, as just a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potlatch is our central constitution. It emphasizes our
ties to the spirit world,'' Joseph said. ``They had to be done
underground for years. The only thing that kept us really strong
for a while was our art. It maintained a focus for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
