<SLUG> BC-HAM-SCAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE CHARGED WITH ORGANIZED CRIMINAL ACTIVITY IN HAM SCAM  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY KLIEWER 
Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRENHAM, Texas _ This little piggy went to market, or at least
he was supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   But a certain piggy shown at the Washington County fairgrounds
earlier this year never quite made it to market. And therein lies a
twisty tale of swine crime, according to a county grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Charles Sebesta says the grand jury in Brenham
charged five people with third-degree organized criminal activity
after their scheme to beat statewide livestock exhibition rules
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Brenham, a city of 14,000, is about 75 miles northwest of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Freed on bonds Tuesday after being charged in the ham scam are
Cammy Jean Cornelius, 17, a high school senior from Agua Dulce, a
small town west of Corpus Christi, and her father, Scott Warren
Cornelius, 51, of the same address.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged are Hollis Dean Harris, 33, a Cornelius relative
from Friona, in the Panhandle west of Amarillo; Randy Ray Campbell,
46, also from Friona; and Jay Lynn McCormick, 20, a college student
in Canyon, south of Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Corneliuses, they posted $10,000 bonds, Sebesta said. A
third-degree felony is punishable by two to 10 years in prison and
a fine of up to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the teen-ager showed a barrow, a castrated
pig, here in February in the annual swine ``sift'' for the Houston
Livestock Show and Rodeo, but it wound up one of 2,900 animals not
chosen for the big show. The Houston event is one of the largest
livestock shows and rodeos in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Houston show rules call for the also-rans to be taken by the
official slaughter contractor to a local stockyard for sorting and,
shortly thereafter, a quick final trip to the bacon factory.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the contractor bought the hogs at a set
per-pound price somewhere below $100 each and hauled them away, but
that McCormick and Campbell went to the stockyard pens, found the
Cornelius' animal and stole it back.
</P>
<P>
   Sebesta said the hog was the property of the contractor, who had
paid for it, and its theft is the offense central to the case.
</P>
<P>
   He said the elaborate scheme also included multiple drivers and
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, McCormick and Campbell turned the
stolen hog over to Harris, who hauled it to Victoria, where another
man, who wasn't charged, took over for transport back home to Agua
Dulce.
</P>
<P>
   Sebesta said the fugitive hog then was shown two weeks later by
Cammy Jean Cornelius at a San Angelo livestock show, where it
claimed a blue ribbon as grand champion and was sold again, this
time for $4,000. It has since been butchered.
</P>
<P>
   Sebesta said rumors about irregularities in the Cornelius entry
were circulating at the San Angelo show and raised officials'
suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the blue ribbon might have been the worst thing that
could've happened,'' Sebesta observed.
</P>
<P>
   Judges uncovered the alleged ruse by checking registration
numbers required by major Texas shows to be tattooed on the ears of
swine entries.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Eric Perkins of Corpus Christi, who represents the
Corneliuses, said: ``It's our position that no crime was committed
_ or if there was a crime, my clients were unaware of it.'' He
declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a cousin to Cammy Jean Cornelius, teaches high school
agricultural science in Friona, according to investigators. He,
McCormick and Campbell are acquainted from livestock-related
dealings in the Panhandle, Sebesta said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
