A1744 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTONS-VINEYARD-BOS     08-25 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, INTERRUPTING VACATION, TO SPEAK ON SCHOOL SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ President Clinton, interrupting his summer
vacation once again, plans to venture off Martha's Vineyard
tomorrow and travel to Worcester, where he will deliver a speech on
school safety at an event designed to restore a presidential aura
to a president who has appeared shamed since his Monica Lewinsky
confession.
</P>
<P>
   The hastily planned morning trip will mark Clinton's first
significant public appearance since the Aug. 17 address in which he
admitted an inappopriate relationship with Lewinsky, the former
White House intern, and lashed back at independent counsel Kenneth
Starr. The president can reasonably expect to bask in partisan
warmth in Worcester, a city where Democrats outnumber Republicans
by nearly four to one.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was cobbled together so quickly that by late Tuesday
afternoon, White House aides did not know the site or the time of
the event, though spokesman Barry Toiv did say it would be
``important to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   In private, White House officials believed the event could be
crucial to restoring a sense of dignity to Clinton, who has become
the punchline of lewd jokes and the object of some disappointment
and disgust for the last nine days. The officials also wanted to
allow Clinton to shake hands and speak to an admiring public _ a
tonic to him in his most beleaguered times.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Clinton aides said they were responding to a
longstanding invitation to speak in the district from freshmen
Democratic Rep. Jim McGovern, who is involved in a reelection
campaign against Republican state Sen. Matthew Amorello.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, in a telephone interview Tuesday, said the residents
of his congressional district were eager to talk about issues
rather than the president's adulterous ways, and he predicted they
would ``welcome him with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people give him high marks for job performance because
they agree with the policies he is advocating,'' said McGovern.
``People care deeply about job security and Medicare and education.
I've been traveling around my district from Princeton to Dartmouth,
and I hear the same thing from Republicans and Democrats: Enough is
enough. Let's get on to the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked his assessment of Clinton's speech, McGovern replied,
``People don't condone his behavior. They are disappointed and I
was disappointed. But we have to decide if we are going to continue
to dwell on this or talk about other issues. At least people should
call a moratorium on this until Ken Starr issues his report.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his senior advisers seem to agree heartily with that
sentiment. While at least one television network briefly broadcast
a report this week that Clinton might give a second address on the
Lewinsky relationship with an explicit public apology that was
lacking in his first speech, aides have adamantly disputed that
notion, saying Clinton will not likely raise the issue or respond
to questions for at least the remainder of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``No plans,'' Toiv said in response to a question on whether
another address was anticipated. He added: ``We all assume that he
will be getting questions about this in the future, and presumably
he will answer them.''
</P>
<P>
   As poll numbers show the public's trust in Clinton at a
remarkable low, the president set sail Tuesday with former CBS News
anchorman and Vineyard summer resident Walter Cronkite, who, in his
broadcast prime, was often called the most trusted man in America.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite, his wife Betsy, his grandson, Clinton, Mrs. Clinton
and Chelsea Clinton sailed out of Edgartown Harbor Tuesday
afternoon on Cronkite's majestic ketch, the Wyntje, as residents
and tourists lining the shore offered their applause. It marked the
first time during the vacation that the entire first family has
been seen together in public.
</P>
<P>
   As the boat motored through the harbor, Cronkite stood at the
helm beside Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea. Clinton, wearing a blue polo
shirt and sunglasses, stood in the back of the boat, alone, waving
at the gathered crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton relaxed, his aides seemed to be scrambling to put
together his off-island policy event. Quizzed on the specifics of
the site and the speech, Toiv told reporters, ``I don't have those
details. It's two days away. That's a long time for us, for
planning.''
</P>
<P>
   At the event, Clinton will likely be met by a supportive crowd.
He won the Third Congressional District overwhelmingly in 1996,
garnering 60 percent of the vote compared to 29 percent for
Republican Bob Dole and 9 percent for billionaire businessman Ross
Perot. Worcester itself has 37,643 Democrats in 1996, compared to
9,646 Republicans and 29,307 independents.
</P>
<P>
   One possible caveat to the plans: Storm warnings emanating from
Hurricane Bonnie, which could follow a track up the eastern
seaboard and impair Clinton's ability to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter Tuesday if the White House might change the
speech subject from school safety to storm safety, Toiv responded:
``We're flexible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
