</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN RUBLE SHEDS 10 PERCENT OF ITS VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Russian ruble suffered its steepest plunge Tuesday in nearly
four years, shedding 10 percent of its value against the US dollar
and defying the new government's efforts to stave off a burgeoning
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The decline intensifies Moscow's woes, which acquired a
political dimension over the weekend when President Boris N.
Yeltsin unexpectedly reshuffled his reformist cabinet for the
second time in five months and reinstalled Victor S. Chernomyrdin,
a powerful Soviet-era manager, as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The slide brings the battered currency precipitously close to
the lower part of its new trading range, set last week when Moscow
effectively devalued the ruble by 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The drop has also spilled over to Russia's largely insolvent
banking sector. In a sign that banks may finally undergo a
long-needed shakeout, three rivals _ Uneximbank, Menatep, and Most
Bank _ said they would merge to shore up their limited cash.
</P>
<P>
   On the debt front, Chernomyrdin and Yeltsin signed an
anxiously-awaited deal restructuring $40 billion in defaulted
government paper, a quarter of it owned by foreigners. The
agreement sent the Russian Trading System benchmark stock index up
2.3 percent to close at 88.38. Russia's once high-flying stock
market has lost 80 percent of its value so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is battling some its its most serious troubles since the
1991 Soviet collapse. Asia's problems and low world oil prices have
scared investors away and sliced into much-needed hard-currency
export earnings. At home, ailing factories locked in a cycle of
barter and nonpayments have become what some economists
disparagingly term a ``virtual economy.'' The ruble, stable for
nearly four years until recently, has shed nearly one quarter of
its value since Moscow devalued it Aug. 17 in a bid to shore up its
finances.
</P>
<P>
   The events have set alarms ringing among inflation-fearing
citizens. Analysts say Russia's financial quandary is not likely to
be resolved soon.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who visits Moscow next week for a summit with
Kremlin leaders, telephoned Yeltsin to urge him to stick to
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruble slide came after the Central Bank lowered its
minimum reserves requirement for the country's 1,600 commercial
banks. The move sent legions of bankers with freed-up rubles into
the marketplace in search of hard currency, pressuring the ruble
down to 7.86 per US dollar on the local interbank currency exchange
from 7.14. At exchange kiosks across the city, the currency fell as
low as 8.3 to the dollar, Moscow analysts said _ close to its floor
of 9.5.
</P>
<P>
   The drop was the biggest since October 1994, when the ruble lost
more than one quarter of its value as a liquidity crisis, fuelled
by inept Central Bank policies, hit commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's turbulence, coming only two months after the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank signed an additional
$22.6 billion bailout for Moscow, may swell under Chernomyrdin,
whose five-year tenure as prime minister before his sacking in
March was marked by a fondness for helping sick industries with tax
breaks and credits. More such moves, combined with a weak ruble,
could spark inflation, which could lead to social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who had helped Western oil companies working in
Russia but carries few reformist credentials, is likely to alter
some of the reforms attempted by his predecessor, Sergei V.
Kiriyenko. The Komsomolskaya Pravda newspaper quoted Chernomyrdin,
60, as saying social welfare and aid to ailing industries were top
priorities, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   That contrasts with the austerity measures promoted by Kiriyenko
but only half-heartedly implemented by the opposition-dominated
State Duma, the lower parliament house. In search of cash to
support government finances, Kiriyenko, 36, had campaigned against
tax debtors, mostly domestic oil and gas companies close to
Chernomyrdin, and encouraged tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chernomyrdin, now the Kremlin's candidate in the
presidential poll in 2000, Russia's search for cash could take an
inflationary form. ``One scenario being discussed is that the
Central Bank would print rubles,'' said Jeffrey M. Robbins, an
economist at MFK Renaissance in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank sold over $2 billion in hard currency and
precious metals over the second and third weeks of August to defend
the ruble before caving in to devaluation. Its reserves were down
to $15.1 billion as of Aug. 20, Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a loss of a sense of reality in Russia,'' said Joshua
G. Feuerman, head of emerging markets at State Street Global
Advisers in Boston. ``Russia is in danger of falling into the
Indonesian model.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
