<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS' AMBASSADOR HAS HIS EYE ON SAMPRAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ A road less traveled is the circuitous one
from Black Butt in the Queensland Outback to Boston. But here was
an all-time roadie called ``Emmo,'' doing all the right steps that
he learned a half-century ago when his journey began, and showing
them to the kids at the Sportsmen's Tennis Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who he is,'' said Monet Duncan to her friend
Katrina Elderbush _ both transfixed by the gray-thatched
61-year-old pedagogue _ ``but he's, like, really awesome, isn't
he?''
</P>
<P>
   Later they found out, after the morning tutorial that he and
fellow Aussie Owen Davidson presented at the Smith Center. Then the
Sportsmen's gang were shipped to Longwood for an afternoon look at
Emmo's successors in the MFS Pro Championships, courtesy of MFS, a
benefactor of the inner city teach-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Later the kids learned that their teacher-for-a-day, Roy Stanley
``Emmo'' Emerson, had made the same sort of good impression at such
way stations along his road as Wimbledon, the Australian, French,
and US Championships, not to mention almost anyplace else in the
world boasting a tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   They learned that he is a stalked man, threatened by someone
they had heard about: Pete Sampras. Thirty-one years ago in Paris,
Emerson beat Tony Roche to win the French, and celebrated unnoticed
by downing a few beers with Roche, Davidson, and other Aussie
mates. A marvelously fit and nimble 6-footer with coal black hair
and gleaming gold-filled teeth, Emmo was totally unaware of having
achieved a record that Sampras (born four years later) would
fiercely covet.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Emerson's 12th major singles title, his second French
to accompany six Australian and two each at Wimbledon and the US.
Sampras, on the eve of possibly waylaying him at the US Open, has
11.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pete takes the record _ and he will _ he'll get a lot of
publicity. Good on him,'' Emmo smiles. ``He's a great champion. I
didn't know there was such a record. We just played.'' He had
passed Bill Tilden's record 10th of 1930 by winning the Australian
of 1967 _ and basked in a tremendous absence of fanfare. ``Nobody
talked about records then.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary had her little lamb, and little Roy had his little calf
that walked him to school (when he didn't ride horseback) in Nukku.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nukku was near our dairy farm which was outside the big,'' he
laughs, pale green eyes amused, ``the big city, Black Butt. One
store. One pub. Maybe 600 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was first in my class for three years. Also last. Top and
bottom, the only one in that grade. It was a one-teacher school,
first to eighth grades, with 17 students. But we had a tennis
court. Every place in the bush, no matter how small, had a court.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father built ours on the property. I helped a little. Ant
hill court. You knocked over the hills that looked a little like
red traffic cones, spread out the grit. Not a bad surface.
Chicken-wire fences.'
</P>
<P>
   Remnants of that court can be seen, I'm told. Somebody ought put
up a plaque: ``World Champ Emmo Started Here.'' Sampras may seize
his singles record, but superb volleyer Emerson also nailed 16
majors in doubles _ he could have won with R2D2 _ for an
all-rounder mark of 28 that seems as far out of reach as Uranus.
</P>
<P>
   Longwood was first a port of call 44 years ago. ``Ashley Cooper
and I'' _ a pair of 17-year-olds who would wind up in the
International Tennis Hall of Fame _ ``were sent on our first
overseas tour in '54, and played the US Doubles when that was
Longwood's tournament, on grass.''
</P>
<P>
   They were quarterfinalists, but Emmo would win the title in 1959
with Neale Fraser. Alongside Fred Stolle he won again in 1965-66 as
they became local cult figures through the nightly Channel 2
telecasts. It was a thoroughgoing team effort, he recalls. ``We
didn't party together. We alternated. I'd stay in the hotel and
sleep one night, Fred the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was ever a better ambassador for the game or his country.
Emmo was a non-stop player everywhere. ``We played over 40
tournaments a year, singles and doubles. Plus exhibitions all over
Australia for the sporting goods firms that paid us a few dollars
in those amateur days. I reckon we played 46 weeks a year. Left
home in April, played our way through Europe, England, the US until
it was time to go back in October for the Aussie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laughed,'' he emits a typically joyful guffaw, ``when I read
recently that Sampras said he was `flat' after playing three
straight weeks. Just singles. Didn't even get to the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   He feels that if Sampras is to win the elusive French,``Pete
will have to stay in Europe as we did and play the entire clay
season. In '54 I didn't have a clue about playing on clay. At the
French I played an old guy in long pants named Asboth (36-year-old
Hungarian Joszef Asboth, winner of the title seven years before).
He had me running around like a blue-ass fly. I never got close to
him, and Kenny (Rosewall) and the other Aussies who'd been there
laughed their heads off.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, residing in Newport Beach, Calif., relishes teaching
kids, giving clinics to anybody, hopeful heroes and hapless
hackers. His love for the game flows constantly. Black Butt or
Dorchester. Wherever on his road, give him a court, some kids _
whether or not they know him _ and he's an evangelist in short
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Very pleased, too, ``that there weren't any frogs or poisonous
brown snakes wandering the courts at Sportsmen's the way they often
did, getting in the way, in the Outback where I come from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
