<SLUG> BC-PET-CLONING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M SCIENTISTS SEEK TO CLONE MILLIONAIRE FAMILY'S PET DOG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: San Francisco) 
(Sub for minor editing) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
and TODD ACKERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Missy, by all accounts, has been a pretty good dog.
But if Texas A&AMP;M scientists succeed in a bold $2.3 million effort
to clone the beloved pet of a mysterious family of
multimillionaires, Missy could become a very good dog, dog, dog.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in the ``Missyplicity Project'' _ the first
attempt to clone a canine _ say it could provide valuable insights
into replicating genetically superior seeing-eye and search and
rescue dogs. Technological advances also might help save endangered
canines in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan, announced this week by spokesmen for the College
Station university's College of Veterinary Medicine, brought bleats
of dismissal from the Scottish scientists who created Dolly, the
world's first cloned sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned,'' Dr. Harry Griffin of Edinburgh's
Roslin Institute told a London newspaper, ``we disapprove. ... It
perpetuates the myth that you can recreate an individual through
cloning.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Caplin, a bioethicist at the University of Pennsylvania,
added that cloning pets, as opposed to farm animals, can be
problematic because researchers simply cannot guarantee how well
the process will work.
</P>
<P>
   Cloned animals like Dolly, he said, are alive and look as they
should. But scientists have no way of knowing that they will grow
into normal, healthy creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask a lot of pets,'' Caplin said. ``They're friends and
entertainment sources. We don't ask sheep for anything besides
their wool and lamb chops. In short, we love pets for their minds,
we love Dolly for her body.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Missy's owners said the family is well aware that
a genetic duplicate of a pet is not the same as recreating the pet.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Hawthorne, president of San Francisco-based Bio Art and
Research Corp., or BARC _ the company that organized the project
for Missy's owners _ suggested such concerns might be based on only
a partial knowledge of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists have a natural tendency to be skeptical of any
project that has a high profile,'' he said. ``I'm not sure they're
hearing the story accurately. I'm not sure they realize Texas A&AMP;M
is working on the project. That these are their friends and peers
that they see at every world-class scientific gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Westhusin, the A&AMP;M associate professor of veterinary
physiology and pharmacology who heads the Missyplicity Project,
said the undertaking ``goes well beyond cloning a pet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not $2 million to clone an individual's pet,'' he
said. ``This is $2 million to do some great science.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloning Missy, an aging collie-mix, he warned, is ``not
falling-off-the-log technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to say when we'll succeed,'' he said. ``We set
project goals and milestones. It's our goal to produce puppies at
the end of two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Westhusin, who will lead a team of about 10 researchers, said
the cloning process entails removing genetic material from Missy,
then inserting it into an egg from a donor dog. The egg is then
implanted into a surrogate mother for gestation.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, whose background includes an eclectic array of
scientific and media undertakings _ he currently is writing a book
detailing his motorcycle trip across India _ said tissue samples
have been retrieved from Missy's belly and mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a simple, painless process,'' he said. ``While she was
at A&AMP;M, she was treated like royalty. The cadets played with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Missy, though, is accustomed to being treated like royalty. She
even has her own Web page (www.missyplicity.com).
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne declined to identify his millionaire clients, nor even
to divulge the state in which they live other than to deny that
they are Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They value their privacy,'' he said. ``And there also is some
concern for Missy's safety.''
</P>
<P>
   In a touching reminiscence on the dog's web page, Missy's owner
recalled visiting the pound to find a companion for his enfeebled
shepherd-coyote, Liebe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her (Missy's) eyes stared at me and I couldn't look away,''
the owner recalled. ``She poked her nose through the fence, whined,
got her paw through an opening and when I took her paw in my hand
she licked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know if she had a high, ear-shattering bark (which
I don't like), and if she could howl (which I do like). I began
talking to her and she sat there sloppily, one leg loose, cocking
her head, left, right, and I noticed that one erect ear had a dip,
which I found somehow charming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered a howl to her and she raised her nose and howled at
the roof. I barked at her and she barked right back, a low
rich-toned, businesslike bark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I whined, she whined.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
