<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-POLLUTION-CHARGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRE MANUFACTURER INDICTED IN CHEMICAL DUMPING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ James M. Knott Sr., owner of a company that makes steel
wire mesh used in lobster traps and chicken coops, has been
indicted by a federal grand jury for allegedly dumping acidic waste
water into the Northbridge public sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   Knott, 68, president of the Riverdale Mills Corp. in
Northbridge, was charged with two counts of violating the federal
Clean Water Act. The indictment alleges that although Knott knew a
wastewater treament system in his Riverdale Mills factory had
malfunctioned by April or May of 1997, the company failed to repair
or restore it until at least November 1997 _ at which point high
levels of acid had been detected in untreated wastewater going into
the sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Knott could face up to six years in jail; he and
his firm could face fines of between $500,000 to $1 million. The
case is being investigated by the US Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Knott said he was not aware that the company's
water treatment system was not working. Of those who are
prosecuting and investigating him he said: ``I just don't think
these people are very competent.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Knott said the discharged water in question at its
most potent ``is very, very mild acid. It's about like a Coca-Cola
or lemon juice or salad dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Riverdale Mills employs about 150 people.
</P>
<P>
   The company operates production lines in which steel wire is
welded into wire mesh, which is galvanized and then coated with
plastic. The mesh is used in the manufacture of various commercial
products, including lobster and crab traps, chicken coops and
protective fencing.
</P>
<P>
   The galvanizing and coating processes yield acidic industrial
wastewater that is supposed to be neutralized before it is
eventually discharged into the Northridge municipal sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   Knott is known locally as a gadfly who is prone to picking
fights with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   He is ``a hard-driving businessman and a difficult person to
deal with,'' Northbridge Town Manager Bill Williams said.
``Certainly the town has locked horns with him on certain issues
... On the good side, there are a lot of people who probably look
at him as a good-standing member of the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
