<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S FANTASTIC, INCREDIBLE _ IT'S A BLURB! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Book, cover, the rush to judgment _ you know the old
saying.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to propose a corollary: You can't judge a book by its
blurbs, either.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone actually buy a book because of the blurbs? Judging
from some of the quotes you see printed on the covers, every book
published is a classic of its genre, the most
suspenseful/harrowing/funny/sad/moving of its kind that the person
doing the blurb has ever read.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, everything can't be the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a twisted wizard, a genre-busting virtuoso working at
the outer edge of narrative convention.'' That's what Jay McInerney
said of Mark Leyner's ``I Smell Esther Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Leyner? I'll buy that he's an attention-busting hack
working at the outer edge of readability, but that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Just so we're clear on what we're talking about, a blurb is a
quote about a book from a person presumably so well-known that the
jacket usually just lists his name and what he has to say about
it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Classic fodder
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although occasionally they're not so well-known. ``This book is
destined to be a classic,'' Joan Borysenko says on the cover of Dr.
Andrew Weil's ``Spontaneous Healing.'' You're saying, swell, but
who the hell is Joan Borysenko?
</P>
<P>
   Happily, it says right there beside her quote: She's the author
of ``Minding the Body, Mending the Mind.'' Now you know.
</P>
<P>
   What we're (begin ital) not (end ital) talking about are the
pages of snippets from newspaper reviews. You know, ``Wonderful'' _
``USA Today,'' that kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's one word _ `Gripping!' _ from the ``Arkansas
Gazette,'' generally it's taken from a thicket of blisteringly
negative reviews,'' said James Lileks, a Minneapolis columnist and
author.
</P>
<P>
   Lileks knows about blurbs. He has written them, he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blurbed somebody,'' he said. ``And I can't remember what it
was. I felt vaguely soiled doing it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might guess, Lileks doesn't have much use for blurbs
generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``All blurbs are back-scratching and log-rolling,'' he said.
``Except for the blurbs I got from Dave Barry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, those. When it comes to blurbs, Barry is a master; he
has graced two of Lileks' books with them. For ``Fresh Lies,''
Barry wrote: ``Fresh Lies'' is funny as hell, and James Lileks is
the funniest writer I know. For his height.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Awfully kind
</P>
<P>
   And this, for ``Notes of a Nervous Man``: ``James Lileks is a
wonderfully funny writer, and I am not saying this just because he
bought me a lot of beer. Although that certainly is a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   (For my money, Barry's best blurb is for Tony Kornheiser's
``Pumping Irony'': ``Tony Kornheiser is the funniest writer in
world history. And I do not say this because he is my close
personal friend. I say this because I am a pathological liar.'')
</P>
<P>
   The reason I spoke with Lileks is that he once offered, if I
could get a book compiling my columns together, to blurb it. Which
piqued my curiosity _ just what would he say? (Actually, I was
mostly curious if he remembered making the offer. He did. So I've
got that going for me. And since I have yet to compile such a book,
I figured writing about blurbs would be the next best thing.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was really, really awful, I would find some kind way not
to say that,'' Lileks said.
</P>
<P>
   And if it was _ if you can imagine such a thing _ not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would find some trite and hackneyed way to say it was
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Lileks writing a blurb is that the blurb would
be better than the book. I suspect that's often the case.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not:
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rachel Felder knew more about underground guitar bands in
England and America, she'd turn into a Fender Stratocaster and a
Marshall Stack.'' That's what Patrick Fitzgerald, the lead singer
for the band Kitchens of Distinction, said of Felder's ``Manic Pop
Thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's just a shrewd marketing ploy. After all, the book
is (begin ital) bound (end ital) be better than that. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
