<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETSATWORK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETS GO TO THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYTNS clients)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - There's Lady, Maxwell, Happy and Sweeper. Odd names
for co-workers, even by today's standards. But they are regulars at
Phoenix-area businesses where they help to boost employee loyalty
and build customer satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Lady is a shelty, Maxwell and Happy are cockers and Sweeper is a
long-haired dog of unspecified pedigree. Pets such as these are
increasingly finding their way into businesses and offices where
they can relax and motivate stressed workers and help promote
better relations with customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have established policies that allow workers to
bring their pets to work on a regular basis. Employee resource
specialists believe more firms will follow suit to help attract and
retain employees in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If enough people like the concept, it could become a factor in
employment decisions,'' said John Challenger, a vice president at
Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, an outplacement firm in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   To promote the concept, Pet Sitters International, a
2,200-member educational organization for professional pet sitters,
is organizing a national take-your-pet-to-work day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for sponsors and shooting for June 1999, or 2000
for our first event,'' said Cara Haynes, a spokeswoman for the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   At Autodesk Inc., a $680 million-a-year computer software
company in San Rafael, Calif., there are 75 to 100 dogs at work
with their owners on any given day. The company also welcomes cats,
birds, snakes and other pets. They have to stay in their owners'
offices or cubicles and can't bark or display aggressive behavior.
They are not allowed in public areas, and three accidents inside
the building means banishment until the owner can demonstrate their
pets continence.
</P>
<P>
   Autodesk's pets-at-work program dates to the early 1980s when
the company was operated out of a group of condominiums and its
employees worked odd hours and needed a place to bring their pets.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's viewed as an important employee benefit and a plum
in attracting and keeping talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once employees get used to having their pets with them at
work, it's hard to go somewhere else where they'd have to stay at
home,'' company spokeswoman Kathy Tom said.
</P>
<P>
   Another national company that allows employees to bring their
pets to work is Netscape Communications Corp. in Mountain View,
Calif. Netscape adopted a formal policy 18 months ago after an
informal one was suspended when a dog got into a conference room
and scarfed up a buffet that had been set up for clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``People felt so strongly about it that we reinstated it under
more formal terms,'' company spokeswoman Chris Holten said.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape welcomes all pets except cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many people allergic to cat dander, we had to
exclude them,'' Holten said.
</P>
<P>
   At Netscape, the pets need to be licensed and vaccinated, and
their owners must have liability insurance. They are not permitted
in business meetings and can temporarily be banished for only two
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Besides helping attract and retain employees, companies with
pet-friendly policies find the animals reduce stress and increase
productivity among workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more focused and able to work longer hours when
they are not worried about their pets at home,'' Holten said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa, Ariz.'s police and fire dispatch department, it is the
custom for employees to bring in their pets _ particularly if they
have a veterinarian appointment. On those occasions, department
supervisor Robin Bollman said the atmosphere is more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get pretty stressful around here and having an animal
around really seems to help,'' Bollman said. While the Mesa
department does not officially allow employees to bring their pets
to work, Bollman believes her department would be better off it it
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be really beneficial,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Law firm full of cats
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Phoenix law firm of Taylor Associates, clients are
regularly entertained by 16 cats that live in the firm's two
offices. Two more reside at each of the firm's offices in Flagstaff
and Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's principal, Richard Taylor, said the cats are
generally abandoned strays that have been rescued by the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with one cat that my daughter found in a
Dumpster,`` he said. Taylor took the cat to the office and the
employees were so taken with it they went to the Humane Society and
got a companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just took off from there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to taking in strays, Taylor runs a non-profit agency
out of his law firm that will help needy owners pay for life-saving
medical procedures for their pets.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has found that the cats have become unexpected marketing
assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have put cats on our logo and people refer to us the cat
attorneys,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's Hallmark Cards and Gifts in Phoenix also has found the
marketing value of animals. Maxwell, the store's namesake is a
cocker spaniel who regularly shows up in a necktie and name tag
which reads ``manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Store owner Chitty Kang explained that when he bought the
Hallmark franchise three years ago, the agreement required him to
use his first name in the store's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not like Chitty's Hallmark, so I got permission to use
Maxwell's name.
</P>
<P>
   Besides lending his name to the business, Maxwell is featured on
the store's advertising and has proved to be an effective drawing
card for customers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A real `watch dog'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lady, a 13-year-old shelty, holds court at the Alpine Clock &AMP; Watch
Shop in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wears a little pocket watch on her collar and we call her
our watch dog,'' said the shop's co-owner, Erika Meyer-John.
</P>
<P>
   Pets also are a regular fixtures at Community Florist in
Phoenix. Recently, there were three dogs and a bird, Rosie, who
likes to be petted. Owner Tony Dombrowski regularly brings in his
dog, Victor, and encourages other employees to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It relaxes everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Goethe, owner of Uniforms for America in Glendale, Ariz.,
encourages her employees to bring in their pets. They include a rat
named Templeton and a dachshund named Gloria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love animals,'' Goethe said. ``They're so relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   The store's pet-friendly atmosphere also is a hit with
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our customers are nurses and they tend to like
animals,'' she said. Like Taylor, Goethe's business often fronts as
a stray animal adoption service.
</P>
<P>
   ``People bring in strays and if someone takes a shine to them we
tell them `this little guy is looking for a home.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Max Jarman can be reached at max.jarman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
