<SLUG> BC-COLLEGEPLAN-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU AMONG BEST UNIVERSITY BUYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Looking for a blue-light education special? Then head
on over to University and Mill avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University was the only Pac-10 school listed in
``America's 100 Best College Buys 1999,'' a new book that evaluates
higher-education institutions for academic excellence, low costs
and other factors. Grand Canyon University was the only other
Arizona university on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Florida led the rankings with nine schools, followed by
Tennessee with seven and Kansas and Texas with five apiece.
</P>
<P>
   No schools in California or New York made the grade. Nor did any
Ivy League institutions. The University of Iowa was the lone Big 10
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State was cited for having top research facilities, a
highly ranked library and numerous academic honors, among other
features.
</P>
<P>
   ``ASU is on the forefront in integrating new technologies into
the undergraduate curriculum and successfully garnering increased
support for its diverse research projects,'' said the guide
($19.95; John Culler &AMP; Sons; 803-432-2001).
</P>
<P>
   It described the Tempe campus, with its mix of palms, citrus
trees and cactuses, as ``a unique and intriguing environment that
draws students from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon University was cited for ``top academics,'' a
``vibrant'' campus and ``outstanding NCAA athletic competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The rankings were based on a survey conducted in May and June
1997. High marks were given to schools that had below-average costs
as well as freshman classes that scored above average in terms of
grade point averages and SAT/ACT results. The survey was open only
to four-year, accredited institutions that offered financial aid
and full residential facilities.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,430 colleges and universities responded to the survey. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
