<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGEPLAN-AZR &LR;      08-25 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGEPLAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE TAX SHELTERS: NEW PLANS HELP FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Thomas Chilcoat this month became not only the first
person on his block but one of the first in Arizona to open a new
type of college-savings plan.
</P>
<P>
   His investment is in what's known as a 529 plan, after a section
of the federal tax code amended by Congress this year. These plans
allow more generous contributions into tax-sheltered college
accounts than were previously permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Chilcoat, who lives in Kingman and maintains railroad signals
for Burlington Northern Santa Fe, plans to put $1,500 a year into
an account for his 8-year-old daughter, Kendra. He opened the
account with Boston-based Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax deferral is what sold me on the program,'' Chilcoat said.
He also likes the ability to have money debited from his bank
account each month for automatic investing.
</P>
<P>
   As his example shows, times are changing in college planning.
Not only are 529 plans hitting the scene, but Congress recently
made some adjustments to tax-sheltered education individual
retirement accounts, which are really misnamed college-saving
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of arrows in the quiver because of the new
tax law,'' said Tom LaPorte, manager of a Phoenix area branch of
brokerage Piper Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   Even Arizona has a tax-sheltered college plan in the works,
thanks to legislative action last year. Here's a look at some of
the new and upcoming programs:
</P>
<P>
   - 529 plans. Fidelity is among the pioneers in offering these
vehicles, which are enhanced state-tuition savings programs
stemming from the Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997. The plans feature
tax-deferred growth of earnings and high investment ceilings, and
the money can be used to meet education costs at colleges around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings grow tax-sheltered until withdrawn. Assuming a
beneficiary attends college, withdrawals are taxed as ordinary
income at his or her rate, not the parents' rate. Proceeds can be
used for tuition, room and board, books and more.
</P>
<P>
   Cash withdrawn prematurely or not used for education is subject
to a penalty and taxation at the parents' rate. But if a child
decides not to enter college, the account can be transferred to
another beneficiary. No penalty would apply if a beneficiary dies,
becomes disabled or receives a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   A big benefit is that parents, grandparents or friends can sock
away up to $50,000 per child in a single year without triggering
gift taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means you basically can fund an entire college plan all
at once,'' said Mark McPherson, manager of Fidelity's Scottsdale
branch.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity (800-544-1914) requires investors to buy into a
predetermined mix of mutual funds. The mix for young kids starts
out almost entirely in the stock market but shifts into bonds and
money-market instruments as a beneficiary nears college age.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the above description applies to the federal tax
treatment of 529 plans. Arizona has indicated it will exempt
earnings in these accounts from taxes, according to Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   - Education IRAs. For people on a budget and seeking a better
tax break, these accounts may make sense. Unlike 529 plans, cash
withdrawn from education IRAs isn't taxed, provided it's used for
tuition, books and other qualifying expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But education IRAs have their drawbacks. For starters, the
accounts are off-limits to single parents earning more than $95,000
a year or couples making above $150,000. More critical, no more
than $500 can be invested on behalf of a child from all sources
combined _ parents, grandparents and friends. Assuming you invest
$500 each year for 18 years and earn 8 percent annually, the
account would barely top $20,000, says T. Rowe Price Associates of
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Education IRA benefits include the ability to transfer the
account to a younger child if the beneficiary doesn't go to college
or receives a scholarship. Also, the person controlling the account
_ usually a parent _ can exercise control until the beneficiary
turns 30.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage is that education IRAs are widely available.
Many brokerages, banks and mutual-fund groups offer them.
</P>
<P>
   - The Arizona Family College Savings Plan. This program could be
an enticing one, when it finally sees the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   State-savings accounts were signed into law by former Gov. Fife
Symington last year and were supposed to debut in March 1998. But
Arizona officials delayed the program until loose ends could be
tied up with the IRS. Now, a September launch is likely, said Verna
Allen, executive director of the Arizona Commission for
Postsecondary Education.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmarks of this plan are expected to include tax-deferred
growth, a range of investment vehicles and the ability to apply the
cash to meet educational costs at institutions around the country.
</P>
<P>
   As written into state law, the plans would allow unlimited
yearly investments, although that's one point requiring IRS
clarification, Allen said. Another unresolved issue hinges on
whether earnings would accumulate sheltered from both federal and
state taxes until the money is withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Cash not spent on education could be subject to a tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   One possible drawback is that Arizona has chosen just three
investment firms to offer the savings plan. They are the Equitable
of New York; Securities Management &AMP; Research of Galveston, Texas;
and the College Savings Bank of Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these savings methods, parents and grandparents
have other college strategies to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   At one extreme are Hope Scholarship and Lifetime Learning
credits, which offer annual tax refunds of up to $1,500 and $1,000
to cover education costs. They're available to single filers
earning less than $50,000, or couples with incomes below $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to invest in a traditional tax-deferred IRA.
Penalty-free withdrawals can be made from these accounts for
education thanks to the 1997 tax law, although income taxes would
apply on earnings. Tax deductions on traditional IRAs are possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandparents could gift money to their children, with the
provision that they open an IRA for the benefit of the grandkids,''
LaPorte said. ``If the grandkids didn't go to college, the
grandparents would be helping their own kids with retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   At another extreme are simple custodial accounts that allow
parents to retain control of a child's college assets until age 18.
These accounts are widely available and very flexible _ almost any
investment can be used _ but they offer no tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Custodial accounts aren't specifically set up for college, but
they're a convenient way to invest,'' McPherson said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
