<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      08-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FOR KINGS AND PLANETS &QL; 
 &UR; Ethan Canin (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Canin's second novel (following ``Blue River,'' and the story
collections ``Emperor of the Air'' and ``The Palace Thief'') is the
quiet story of two friends whose backgrounds steer them down
dissimilar paths in their adult lives. Orno Tarcher and Marshall
Emerson meet in 1974 as freshmen at Columbia University. Orno,
whose family lives in the farm country of the Midwest, arrives
wide-eyed and embarrassed by his own stolidness _ among his fellow
students, Canin writes, Orno felt ``the word `Missouri' written on
his forehead.'' Marshall is brilliant, worldly and to all
appearances privileged, and Orno is caught up in his exotic and
affected world. There are no special effects in this novel, no
literary pyrotechnics. Instead, Canin watches his characters with
such patience and compassion that the reader is forced to slow down
and acknowledge the gravity of such a story, one that is both
plodding and profound. This is real life _ the small tragedies and
triumphs, betrayals and lucky strokes that shape what becomes of
us. It's also a tribute to New York. Canin pauses often to describe
the city through Orno's eyes, in pages so full of atmosphere that
you'll probably hear Gershwin playing in the background as you
read. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AROUND THE HOUSE &QL; 
 &UR; David Owen (Villard, $21)
</P>
<P>
   The best way to increase the value of your house by $25,000 is
to add a $50,000 kitchen to it. Most home improvement, however, is
futile: You can spend a fortune fixing up your living room, but at
your next dinner party you'll still find guests in the laundry room
resting their drinks on piles of folded underwear. David Owen knows
a lot about home ownership. He's also a funny guy, especially
because he learned how to use a reciprocating saw. This is a
collection of brief essays with titles such as ``Deck Mania,''
``Let There Be Weeds,'' ``Anatomy of a Kitchen'' and, our favorite,
``Drip, Drip, Drip.'' They are reassuring for people who are home
improvement-impaired, especially when he tells us that the best way
to fix a house is one room at a time. Owen, whose previous book was
``The Walls Around Us: The Thinking Person's Guide to How a House
Works,'' is a staff writer for the ``New Yorker.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; REAL BOYS &QL; 
 &UR; William Pollack (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys today are in serious trouble, including many who seem
`normal' and to be doing just fine.'' That's the way to start a
book about kids: Tell their parents not to believe their eyes.
Pollack, a psychiatry professor at Harvard Medical School,
describes problems that many experts have attributed to girls,
including low self-esteem and feelings of loneliness and isolation.
But boys also are forced into independence too early and made to
feel ashamed of vulnerability. Pollack discusses the ``gender
straitjacket'' and ``the Boy Code'' (``the outdated and
constricting assumptions, models and rules about boys that our
society has used since the 19th century'') and their most serious
consequences: depression, violence and even suicide. There is no
specific mention here of the recent shootings in schools across the
country, but the subject is heavy between the lines. ``By teaching
boys how to harness their anger and aggressive energy and redirect
them into healthy outlets,'' Pollack writes, ``we can help them
avoid hurting others or themselves.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE OVERSPENT AMERICAN &QL; 
 &UR; Juliet B. Schor (Basic, $25)
</P>
<P>
   From the author of ``The Overworked American'' comes another
disturbing look in the mirror. This time, we see what Schor calls
``competitive acquisition,'' only now, instead of keeping up with
the Joneses, we are trying to keep up with people who make much
more money than we do. More than a quarter of all families that
make more than $100,000 a year say that they cannot afford to buy
everything they need. Schor looks at the root of America's spending
problems (television does not help _ every additional hour a person
watches per week increases his annual spending by $218 per year)
and at the many ways our quality of life suffers. She also profiles
``downshifters'' who have chosen to make less money in order to
relieve stress and enjoy their lives. Rampant consumerism is
unnecessary, Schor says. ``We remain a creative, resourceful and
caring nation. There's still time left to find our way out of the
mall.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE DAY DIANA DIED &QL; 
 &UR; Christopher Andersen (Morrow, $27)
</P>
<P>
   There is no end to it. We're starting all over again with this
book, which launches the countdown toward the anniversary of
Diana's death. Thanks to Andersen, a former contributing editor of
``Time'' and senior editor of ``People,'' we now know that Queen
Elizabeth behaved badly (and stupidly, for a woman who should know
something about public relations) after she learned that Diana was
dead. We know that Diana's last words were ``My God, what's
happened?'' (and not, as was reported by Mohamed Al Fayed, ``I
would like all my possessions in Dodi's apartment to be given to my
sister Sarah, including my jewelry and my personal clothes, and
please tell her to take care of my boys.''). We know that Prince
Charles wept when told of the accident in Paris, and later bullied
his mother into acknowledging England's grief. If there's anything
new to say about that day, Andersen has tried to find it, but
there's one more thing we know: It won't be the last word on
Diana. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Contact Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
