<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CENSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PANEL LOOKS TO ANDREW JACKSON CENSURE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress prepares to receive the independent
counsel's report on President Clinton that could lead to
impeachment hearings, some lawmakers are studying a little-known
case: the Senate's 1834 censure of President Andrew Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the Constitution explicitly gives Congress the
authority to censure a president, but nothing prohibits it, either,
according to associate Senate historian Don Ritchie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress could do whatever it wished to do,'' said
Representative Bill McCollum of Florida, the third-ranking
Republican on the House Judiciary Committee. ``We pass resolutions
condemning things every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of censuring Clinton has gained favor among some
Republicans and Democrats partly because polls show most Americans
oppose impeachment. An ABC-TV poll found 55 percent of those
surveyed think Clinton should receive a congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
   A censure is a strong statement of disapproval and carries no
specific penalty, other than the condemnation itself.
</P>
<P>
   The idea may be even more appealing to Democrats than to
Republicans. Democratic leaders are concerned that the president's
admission of an inappropriate relationship with former White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky could derail the party's effort to regain
control of the House. (Democrats have long thought there is no
chance to retake the Senate this year). So some Democrats may look
favorably on censuring the president in order to show that the
party is displeased with Clinton's actions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, even before Clinton's admission last week, Senator
Joseph Lieberman, the Connecticut Democrat, told the New Haven
Register: ``That is a distinct possibility, the censure. You can
sense as you listen not just to Democrats but also to Republicans
that there is not a great yearning for an impeachment here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was on vacation Tuesday and unavailable for comment,
an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Congress have made no comment on the question of
censure or impeachment since Clinton's televised confession on Aug.
17. But lawmakers will be under more pressure to declare their
views when Congress returns from vacation starting next week. House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt Tuesday delivered his strongest
rebuke yet to Clinton, saying the president's behavior was
``reprehensible,'' although Gephardt said he would ``reserve
judgment'' on whether Clinton should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the House Judiciary Committee, which would hold an
impeachment investigation and hearings, has already begun studying
possible alternatives to impeachment. Staff members have found that
the House and Senate have applied a number of penalties to members
of Congress, including: reprimand, denunciation, censure,
condemnation, expulsion, disqualification, and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser of these penalties, such as a reprimand or censure,
do not take away any powers from the affected individual, but there
is often a public and political price to pay. Still, some members
have recovered from the punishment. Former Representative Gerry
Studds, a Massachusetts Democrat, was censured in 1983 for his
relationship with teenage male page and went on to be reelected.
Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, was
reprimanded in 1990 for writing a misleading memo in an effort to
end a male prostitute's probation and for allowing his House
privileges to be used for waiving parking tickets. Frank remains in
office and also sits on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi was one of the
first to suggest that Clinton could be censured, mentioning the
idea in March. A senior Democratic official who is studying the
question of various penalties said it would not be surprising if
Democrats supported a censure or some other discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a logical political resolution of all of this,''
said Jim Jordan, the Democratic spokesman of the House Judiciary
Committee. ``At the end of the day, if whatever charges that Starr
makes don't logically dictate removal of the president of the
United States ... the members may be looking for some means to
voice disapproval for the president's behavior without
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   But is censure of a president possible? The Judiciary Committee
staff started researching the issue and was surprised to learn of
one effort to censure a president.
</P>
<P>
   It happened on March 28, 1834. Jackson, a Democrat, had vetoed
legislation that would have extended the life of the Bank of the
United States. Jackson thought the bank catered to Eastern
elitists. When the Whig party asked for documents relating to the
veto, Jackson refused to turn them over.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate then voted to censure Jackson. But Jackson, aware
that he had the support of the Democratic majority in the House,
told the Senate it had no constitutional power to censure him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lived in vain if it be necessary to enter into a formal
vindication of my character,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   After Democrats gained control of the Senate in 1836, the Senate
voted to expunge Jackson's censure from the record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
