<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COPLEY-MARKETPLACE-AR     08-25 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPLEY-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BOARDROOM POWER PLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204
or -1927.) 
(rl) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Agnes Varis was asked to join the board of Copley
Pharmaceutical Inc. in 1992, it was not because she was expected to
hold her tongue. As president of her own chemical company in Little
Falls, N.J., she had more than two decades of industry experience.
And here was a chance to help Copley, a promising maker of generic
drugs, become a major player. ``You get a good rush from all of
that,'' Varis said.
</P>
<P>
   But that all changed when Hoechst AG, the big German
conglomerate, bought a majority stake in Copley, based in Canton,
Mass., the following year. Hoechst did not seem to appreciate
Varis' occasional dissent. ``They look for directors that are
`parsley on the fish,''' she said in an interview, describing what
she regarded as the trivial role Hoechst executives expected the
outside directors on the board to play.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Varis quit. But unlike many frustrated directors, she
did not go quietly. Instead, she publicly accused Hoechst of
mismanaging Copley and not acting in the best interests of all
investors. Hoechst had contributed to ``the steady decline of
shareholders' value,'' she wrote in a two-page resignation letter.
While Hoechst believed that what was good for it was good for
everyone else, she said, ``I cannot remember a single instance
where this turned out to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst, which has headquarters in Frankfurt, declined to
comment specifically on any of Varis' allegations. But it says its
goals are no different from those of other shareholders, and on
Monday Copley named a new chief executive to help revive the stock.
The shares _ which closed on Nasdaq yesterday at $8.6875, down
$1.25 _ are trading at less than a fifth of what Hoechst paid for
them.``We are going to do everything we can to increase shareholder
value,'' said Patricia Munzer, a Hoechst spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Varis' story illustrates just how little power directors often
have. What happened to Copley, it seems, could befall any company
that finds itself out of favor with its majority shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience also provides a fleeting glimpse of what goes on
behind the doors of a corporate boardroom. Directors rarely quit,
and even when they do, they almost never tell shareholders why.
``What goes on in the boardroom is kept in the boardroom,'' said
Julie Daum, a headhunter at Spencer Stuart in New York who
specializes in recruiting directors.
</P>
<P>
   A second Copley director, Judith Fensterer, resigned two days
after Varis did. In keeping with the directors' code of silence,
she did not return phone calls and has made no public comment.
</P>
<P>
   At 68, however, Varis was willing to rock the boat, giving up a
perch that offered both prestige and perks. In exchange for
attending a meeting once a month or so, Varis made about $20,000 a
year in director fees from Copley, not including stock options, and
Copley bought raw materials from her company, Agvar Chemicals,
purchasing about $808,000 worth in one year, much less in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By speaking out, directors are virtually guaranteed that they
will be blackballed from other boards. ``If you are an independent
director, this would be your first and last time on a board,'' said
Corinna Arnold, the director of global shareholder services for the
Investor Responsibility Research Center in Washington. Varis said
she had been approached to sit on other boards since her
resignation, though she is not sure she wants to spend her time
that way.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the world was very different six years ago when Varis
joined Copley's board. The growth of generic drugs _ the unbranded
versions that come out once a pharmaceutical's patent has expired _
``was going to answer all the problems of high-priced
pharmaceuticals,'' Varis recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her arrival, in October 1992, Copley went public,
selling its shares to investors for $12.67 apiece, adjusted for a
3-for-2 split. Analysts had nothing but praise for Jane C.I. Hirsh,
its chief executive at the time, and the stock roughly quadrupled
within its first year. When Hoechst Celanese, a unit of Hoechst,
arrived a year later, offering $546 million, or $55 a share, for a
51 percent interest, Copley did not hesitate: The deal carried an
11 percent premium to the price of the stock in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this would put Copley into another league,'' Varis
said. Hoechst Celanese would provide the much tinier Copley access
to raw materials for its drugs and first call on any of the drugs
coming off patent from Hoechst-Roussel, then its drug subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst was just as excited. As were many pharmaceutical
companies at the time, it was worried about the attacks on high
drug prices coming out of the Clinton White House, so Hoechst
viewed Copley as a way of inoculating itself from the ravages of
cost controls and managed care.
</P>
<P>
   But the honeymoon was brief, and Hoechst had every right to feel
bitterly disappointed. Within a few months, Copley was tarred in a
quality-control scandal that battered its stock. In January 1994,
Copley recalled its albuterol asthma inhalant because of possible
contamination, leading to a series of regulatory and legal
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst stood by the company, and Varis remembers working
closely with the directors originally chosen by Hoechst. They were
``very understanding,'' she said. To demonstrate her support, Varis
bought more stock, which was then trading in the low $30's.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst proceeded to shake up Copley's management. Kenneth N.
Larsen, an industry consultant who sat on Copley's board in the
mid-1980's, was named interim president in November 1994. The next
May, Hirsh was demoted to president of international business, and
Larsen became chairman. Gabriel R. Cipau, a pharmaceutical
executive, was brought in as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Hoechst, like many of its peers, including Merck and
Warner-Lambert, was starting to lose interest in the generic
business. With brutal competition and low and erratic profit
margins, ``no one was making any money,'' said Viren Mehta of Mehta
Partners, a biopharmaceuticals investment firm in New York. With
their profits no longer in danger from a Washington-directed health
care overhaul, most pharmaceutical companies wanted out.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1996, Hoechst told investors and analysts that it
no longer considered generics part of its ``core'' strategy. In
October, Copley hired Oppenheimer &AMP; Company as an investment banker
to look into its options, including a possible sale.
</P>
<P>
   The company was in limbo. Cipau, the chief executive, had
departed in mid-1996. When Larsen, who took over temporarily as
president, stepped down in early 1997 for health reasons, no one
replaced him. Copley would not say who was actually in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst's lack of interest in Copley also displayed itself in
the boardroom, where directors came and went. Under the current
arrangement, Hoechst names three of the nine board members, and it
has chosen 10 different people over the last five years to
represent it. ``There is no continuity,'' Varis complained.
</P>
<P>
   The change in directors simply reflects the upheaval at Hoechst,
said Munzer, the company spokeswoman. All of the choices have been
``high caliber,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the tension among the directors began to build. Varis
said her relationship with the Hoechst directors was ``cordial but
not one of respect.'' Those directors always voted in unison, she
said, apparently following whatever orders came out of Frankfurt.
Only Fensterer seemed to share her goal of representing all the
shareholders, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Varis continued to speak up at board meetings, prompting an
effort by the Hoechst directors last year to force her off the
board, she said. They lobbied the Copley inside directors to drop
her from the renomination slate. Varis demanded that they provide a
specific reason for their opposition. When the Copley directors
decided not to go along, Hoechst backed down, she said. Hoechst
would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, the one thing the board agreed upon was the decision
to sell Copley. ``It was the only time we worked together,'' said
Varis, who was part of the team in charge of finding a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of 1997, just short of settling on a final price
with an undisclosed buyer, Varis began to sense that something was
amiss. She was informed in a telephone call that Hoechst had
changed its mind because of concerns over recognizing a loss of
several hundred million dollars on its investment. ``It was almost
like, `Oops, we just found out,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Varis and the rest of the negotiating team scrambled to
come up with alternatives, Hoechst refused to consider a sale until
at least 1999. At Copley's annual meeting, the company dismissed
its investment banker. Frustrated by what she believed were
Hoechst's missteps, Varis quit on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst officials never considered ``the devastating effect
their actions would have on the value of Copley's shares, the total
demoralization of Copley's employees and the deleterious effect on
Copley's reputation as an ongoing company,'' Varis said in her
resignation letter.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst said its decision was in keeping with its goal of
maximizing shareholder value. ``When the time is right, we will
look for a sale,'' Munzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has lost about 40 percent of its value since Copley
first retained Oppenheimer. The company's 1997 sales, about $121
million, were down from a peak of $142 million in 1995 and were
about what Copley generated in 1994. Without burdensome recall and
legal costs, Copley finally eked out a profit last year of $2.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it's surviving,'' said David Saks, a managing
director at Gruntal &AMP; Company, who says he believes that most of
the company's troubles are behind it but is still not recommending
the stock to investors.
</P>
<P>
   But while some other generic companies have started to prosper,
Copley has struggled without steady management and the capital it
needs, said Steven B. Gerber, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Gene M. Bauer, Copley's general counsel, conceded that Copley
``has been rocked by things.'' He said that the board was actively
looking to replace Varis and Fensterer. He points to four
consecutive quarters of profitability and numerous approvals for
new drugs as evidence of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment this week of Daniel L. Korpolinski as chief
executive is another step. But Korpolinski's record is spotty.
While he was chief executive of Cocensys, a biotechnology company,
the stock fell from its 1993 initial offering price of $9 a share
to around $6.50 by the time he stepped down in late 1996. It now
trades at around $1. ``I don't think he was a great manager,'' said
Jim McMamant, an analyst in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   And Hoechst is under no obligation to consider other interests.
Directors ``are supposed to act in the best interest of
shareholders, writ large,'' but a majority owner has no such duty,
said John Coffee, a securities law professor at Columbia
University. The shareholder, he added, can do what it wants for its
own ``petty, selfish reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Copley, it never informed investors in any of its public
filings that two directors had resigned. Shareholders found out
only because Varis issued her own press release and, in the course
of answering questions, the company said there had been another
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Varis said she left the board only when she decided she could do
more for Copley as an outsider. But she wanted to make sure that
the six years as a director had not been wasted, and she refused to
remain silent. ``How could I ever do that?'' she asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
