<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA TO BE '99 SEASON PLAYER-COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Walter Zenga plans to not only coach the Revolution
through the remainder of the MLS season but to return as
player-coach next season.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga was hired to replace Thomas Rongen after Saturday's 5-1
loss to the Los Angeles Galaxy Saturday in a surprising move that
was announced Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The change was so swift that Zenga, who had arrived for a
halftime tribute, had to return to Italy to gather his possessions
for a move to back to his Newton, Mass. residence. His first
practice as coach will be Friday at Babson College in preparation
for Sunday's visit to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I have to say is that I have the greatest
respect for Thomas Rongen,'' Zenga said Tuesday from Milan. ``He is
one of the best coaches I've know and I respect him very much. So,
then what can I do now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try to find a way to bring my mentality to the players
and develop a team that the fans and the city of Boston, and the
players themselves, will respect. It's very important to say that
no one loses, 5-1, at home; it's a matter of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team has to have the will to win. When we go to Miami, and
if they are the better team and they win, compliments to them. But
we have to have the will to win and to play for pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, whose goalkeeping helped the Revolution qualify for last
year's playoffs before he retired, will leave many of the coaching
decisions to assistant Sid Mazzola, who has been a scout for the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make big changes,'' Zenga said. ``I'm not David
Copperfield. I will be satisfied if we can perform respectably and
put on a good show for the great crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to return to the Revolution, but not so soon. I
wanted to talk to Thomas after the game about what I might be able
to do to help him and the team next year. But it wasn't the right
time after a loss like that. Still, I wasn't thinking anything
about this year for myself, but about what we could do next year.
The way this happened, it's carpe diem.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, nicknamed Spiderman for his goalkeeping style, is
expected to use the connections he developed in nearly 20 years of
playing in Europe. His agent, Giovanni Branchini, represents many
of the world's best players, and has worked closely with MLS deputy
commissioner Sunil Gulati, who is in charge of player acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have six games to do what we can, then we can do more after
the season,'' Zenga, 38, said. ``In the future, we want to have a
competitive team. We need to analyze what to do. We have 30,000
fans coming to the stadium, and these fans are important, and they
need to have a good team to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not coming just for a few months but for a long time. I
am young and I have time. I want to contribute something important
to Boston sports and I hope I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for next year, it is my dream to be a player-coach, and I
need someone next to me to help me do it, and that's Sid Mazzola. I
will use my connections with Inter to help the Revolution, and one
thing I hope to do is to bring Inter here _ I've already had
discussions with them _ for a game.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Brian O'Donovan said Zenga has been hired as
interim coach and his status for next year is undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to check each other out for the last
six games of a fairly dismal season,'' O'Donovan said. ``Walter
intends to maintain a connection to the MLS in the future, and for
us, that includes any and all options, including being
player-coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
