</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE (Morehead City, N.C.) _ Residents and tourists along the
North Caroline coast are ordered to evacuate as Hurricane Bonnie,
packing winds of 115 mph, picks up steam and heads for the coastal
area. At its present pace, the storm could move ashore sometime
Wednesday afternoon. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-TEXAS (Del Rio, Texas) _ In the aftermath of Tropical
Storm Charley, all known missing people have been accounted for in
Del Rio, and authorities lowered the count of local fatalities to
six. Still, the city has plenty of cleaning up to do after the
remnants of the storm dumped nearly 18 inches of rain on the South
Texas town. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   HAM-SCAM (Brenham, Texas) _ Five people, including a 17-year-old
girl, face organized crime charges for an elaborate scheme
involving a hog shown in a livestock contest earlier this year. The
hog, which didn't win anything in the local show, was rescued _
illegally prosecutors say _ from the slaughter truck and shipped
off to San Angelo, Texas, where it took a blue ribbon. By TERRY
KLIEWER. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   PET-CLONING (Houston) _ If other animals can be cloned, what
about pets? If researchers at Texas A&AMP;M University in College
Station and a private biotech firm in San Francisco have their way,
the family dog will never die. By ALLAN TURNER and TODD ACKERMAN.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-POLL (Washington) _ There is growing public support for
the use of tax money to pay for private-school education but no
consensus on how to raise the money, according to a new poll. The
poll was conducted by the Gallup organization and Phi Delta Kappa,
a Bloomington, Ind.-based professional group for educators. By
NICOLE TSONG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-MAYOR (Puerto Asis, Colombia) _ Just hours after Nestor
Hernandez was sworn in as mayor of this jungle town, he was
abducted by leftist guerrillas and held for 11 days. After angering
the army and right-wing paramilitary groups, grenades exploded
outside his home. As Colombia's 34-year-old civil war drags on,
Hernandez and other mayors find themselves in the line of fire. By
JOHN OTIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-CHEATS (Quito, Ecuador) _ When the Finance Ministry
recently compiled a list of the 200 Ecuadorean corporations with
the highest earnings, hard-working citizens were startled to learn
that half of these companies paid no income taxes last year. Tax
evasion is a virtual pastime for the wealthy here, despite
widespread poverty. By JOHN OTIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ As the first anniversary of Princess
Diana's death approaches, the public hysteria has faded but the
fascination with her life remains. The British are indulging in a
whole week of commemoration, trying to find meaning in her memory
while shaking off some of the blind adulation. By MARIANNE MEANS.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-DAVIE (South Bend, Ind.) _ When Bob Davie took over as head
coach at Notre Dame last year, he seemed the perfect fit for the
Fighting Irish. But it has been one long nightmare for Davie ever
since he took over, and the Irish program is engulfed in a series
of controversies both on and off the field. As Davie enters his
second season, the death watch is on. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Fresh off a three-game sweep of the
Chicago Cubs and a 6-2 road trip, the Houston Astros return home to
open a two-game homestand against the Atlanta Braves in what could
be a preview of their first-round playoff series. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
