</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-Y2K-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panel sees itself as information source
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In assessing their own situations, members of the
Atlanta Y2K Users Group began to wonder about their exposure to
potential Y2K breakdowns at such public services as utilities,
hospitals, and water and sewer services.
</P>
<P>
   Out of these concerns sprang a subset of the users group, the
Common Services Committee, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to its current chairman, Paul H. Arne, an attorney
with Morris, Manning &AMP; Martin, the committee was the brainchild of
Atlanta consultant Ted Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   He perceived such a committee could perform a public service of
its own and avoid much duplication of effort by acting in concert.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to Arne, the committee has about 10 to 15 members
in attendance at its regular monthly meetings. They supply
information to 114 companies, at last count _ companies such as
Equifax, BellSouth and The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The committee doesn't plan to use publicity to further its aims.
These include not only the determination of potential problem areas
but also a plan to offer help from the participating companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view our role as providing information to the Year 2000
Users Group, with the idea being that, if you tell over 100 of the
largest companies in Atlanta whether a particular government agency
has a credible Year 2000 program or not, then you can help those
agencies without strong Year 2000 programs get the resources they
need,'' said Arne.
</P>
<P>
   The information the committee gathers will go into computer
spreadsheets and will cover the Year 2000 plans from 125 to 200
city, state, and county organizations and agencies in the Metro
area.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is in the process of sending out letters to these
such common services requesting a contact name. Those that don't
respond will get another letter in about 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   All these organizations, whether or not they answer the letters,
will hear from the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are getting the information eat and breathe
Year 2000, and they know how to separate true information from
assurances without substance,'' Arne said.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the committee's work is available to members
of the Atlanta Year 2000 Users Group. Membership is open and free.
To learn more, visit the group's Web site
(http://www.bytewise.com/atlyear2000/).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
