<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH26-COX     08-25 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich takes stand against government investigation into
Microsoft
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (f) Financial and (w) Washington categories.)
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A month before the Justice Department's antitrust
lawsuit against Microsoft is to be heard in federal court, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich on Tuesday defended the embattled software
giant and questioned the government's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich attributed some of the criticism of the Justice
Department to the Seattle area's congressional delegation, which
has strongly supported Microsoft, based in the Seattle suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But the speaker, in his own words, accused the federal
government of ``trying to destroy jobs at one of America's leading
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Congress would investigate allegations that the
Justice Department had encouraged foreign governments to sue
Microsoft over allegedly monopolistic practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're going to work very hard to get to the
bottom of, because it's entirely inappropriate,'' Gingrich said.
``The purpose of the American government is to strengthen American
companies in the world market ... not undermine American
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gina Talamona, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said the
allegations against the department are ``completely false.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Microsoft executives were on hand for Gingrich's speech
at a fund-raising breakfast for Republican Rep. Rick White, whose
district includes Microsoft's campus and founder Bill Gates'
spectacular home.
</P>
<P>
   In another show of support for Microsoft, Gingrich omitted from
his standard speech an anecdote about a ring made by Sun
Microsystems Inc., a Silicon Valley computer firm, that contains a
tiny computer.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich frequently displays the ring to his audiences to
illustrate the pace of change.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear why Gingrich moved away from the impartial stance
on Microsoft that he adopted in January, when he visited the
company and met with Gates. He refused to answer questions about
his remarks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 20 states filed suit in May, charging
that Microsoft is trying to corner the market on access to the
Internet by tying its Web browser to its already dominant operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denies the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The case is scheduled for trial Sept. 23 in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Microsoft had been virtually absent from the
political arena. But the company has given $200,000 in cash and
computer equipment to Republican groups this year and thousands
more to individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It has gotten a better reception in the House than in the
Senate, where the Senate Judiciary Committee has held hearings on
Microsoft's practices.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, Gingrich is setting aside his campaign activity
for a few days of travel through Washington and Alaska with the
Western States Coalition, a property-rights group that opposes
federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich will travel with the speakers of the Washington and
Alaska Houses of Representatives to environmentally sensitive areas
for what Gingrich said is a chance for ``Easterners to have a
better sense of the scale and complexity of the West and a better
understanding of Western issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brian O'Donnell, spokesman for the Alaska Wilderness League,
said conservation groups have been excluded from the trip. ``It
will be as one-sided as a Cuban election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
