<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYNQUEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SynQuest lets execs weigh pros, cons of various strategies
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Your company is expanding rapidly, but where do you
put a new plant? It's a big decision that has wrecked many an
expanding company.
</P>
<P>
   But what's dangerous for many companies is a marketing
opportunity for Joe Trino and his Atlanta-based SynQuest. His
company makes industrial-strength software that helps chief
executives make big decisions about such things as new plant
openings.
</P>
<P>
   The software is called supply chain optimization, but what that
means is simple. Trino's software analyzes company and market
information in a way that lets top executives weigh the advantages
of various strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, it lets executives identify scenarios with the
highest potential for profit and the lowest costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was doing this, and we saw an opportunity,'' says
Trino. When he began four years ago, the market was small, but it
is now growing rapidly. There were, for example, $420 million in
sales in 1996 _ a figure industry forecasts peg to reach $2.7
billion by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   While SynQuest has competition now, its software is unique, and
competition is limited to a handful of companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very competitive suite of software,'' says Craig
Gustin, a principal of industry consultant CGR Management.
``SynQuest offers what only a few others in the industry do.''
</P>
<P>
   And more and more companies are looking for decision-making
software.
</P>
<P>
   SynQuest is garnering an increasingly big piece of that growing
pie. It had revenue of $20 million for fiscal 1998, which ended
June 30, up 145 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Trino says the company's growth is on track to reach $200
million in revenue by the end of the century. It plans to add 100
employees this year alone, expanding the staff to 300.
</P>
<P>
   If growth continues at this pace, Trino plans to go public
sometime in the first half of 1999. ``We're running now as a public
company,'' says Trino, explaining the release of the sales figure
by his private company.
</P>
<P>
   Trino is no stranger to the market of corporate planning
software. He has been in the business for nearly 20 years,
including a long stint with Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Software.
</P>
<P>
   He jumped ship in the early 1990s to money manager venture
capital firm Warburg Pincus. His assignment was to figure out the
next big market for planning software. After interviewing the top
computer consultants and industrial companies, he reached a
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they saw was software that would orchestrate planning,
marketing and distribution,'' says Trino. ``Our strategy became to
found such a company through acquisitions and internal growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort began in 1994, when Warburg Pincus bought a New
York-based corporate planner. The company was moved to Atlanta.
Eventually four other companies were bought and added to this
original venture.
</P>
<P>
   Today, SynQuest serves some of the country's largest industrial
concerns. Those companies include Ford, golf ball maker Titlelist
and the packaged cereal giant, Kellogg.
</P>
<P>
   While there's one $10 million contract, most of SynQuest's other
deals are in the $550,000 range. It signed up 12 new customers in
the last four months alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is growing, and we are growing with it,'' says
Trino. ``We have significantly raised our visibility and are very
well positioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
