</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MERGERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It'll take a fancy suitor to wed BellSouth, analyst says
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bell Atlantic has done it, so has NYNEX.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications and Ameritech want to do it.
</P>
<P>
   So, when will BellSouth?
</P>
<P>
   A well-known Wall Street analyst says Atlanta-based BellSouth,
the larger of the two baby Bells still unspoken for, was not likely
to merge without a long courtship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know BellSouth pretty well and based on that we feel pretty
confident about their competitive position,'' said Jim Ferency, of
Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. ``But if the right company came along with the
right offer at the right time? They might reconsider. But knowing
BellSouth, I think they are very confident both domestically and
internationally. They have terrific growth on the bottom line and a
highly regarded senior management team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think they look in the mirror every day and feel
pretty good about who they are,'' he said. ``And when you feel
pretty good you're not likely to do anything rash.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferency spoke at the Georgia Center for Advanced
Telecommunications Technology recently, addressing a roomful of
telecommunications executives, lawyers and researchers about the
massive rash of mergers and acquisitions in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   He said the urge to merge is fueled by federal telecom
deregulation, an until-recently surging stockmarket and low
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The combined value of newly wed U.S. companies in 1985 was $241
billion. In the first two quarters of 1998 alone, the combined
value of merged U.S. companies was $907 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ferency said mergers within the domestic telecom industry are
growing as a percentage of overall domestic mergers. Since 1997,
telecom stocks have outperformed the market by 20 percent, Ferency
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the music's going to stop. At some point,
someone's going to be left without a chair.'' he said. ``But for
now, there is still a lot of robust activity. I hate to sound like
a broken record, but if you're in the market place, it's a pretty
good place to be doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
