<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-PORTABILITY     08-25 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PORTABILITY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE NUMBER, TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Those 10 digits follow
</P>
<P>
   you around under a
</P>
<P>
   new plan from BellSouth
</P>
<P>
   By Michael E. Kanell
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   One number, wherever you go and no matter what company carries
the call _ BellSouth says the technology is now ready.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, telecommunications experts have predicted the
advent of ``number portability,'' a world in which customers would
carry their phone numbers with them. Federal and state regulators
have mandated such a system, although they have postponed the
deadlines for making it happen.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is basic for customers, who would seldom change phone
carriers if they got a new number that would have to be passed
along to friends, family and clients. Naturally, the idea is also
critical for competition in local service, since virtually no one
would leave BellSouth _ or go back to it _ if they had to surrender
their number with each shift.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, BellSouth Corp. announced completion of a $425 million
project that permits number portability in metro Atlanta, although
at first it will be limited to when customers make changes in
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the ability to carry a number anywhere _ including to
other parts of the country, signaling the end of area codes as an
indicator of a customer's location _ is only a matter of time,
requiring regulatory oversight and changes in other networks. The
technology is here.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's two-year effort involved several thousand
technicians in eight states, 300 software developers and scores of
engineers and systems analysts, said Doug McDougal, director of
local number portability for the $21 billion-a-year company.
</P>
<P>
   The revision in software and hardware covers millions of access
lines, reshaping the century-old method for routing phone calls, he
said. ``This is the most complex project ever undertaken in the
history of telecommunications.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday, when the new system went into effect in metro
Atlanta, each local phone company would ``own'' a set of numbers.
Rivals to BellSouth have complained the company unfairly hoarded
all the ``designer'' numbers, parsing out less-desirable exchanges
and combinations. But the new system eliminates that notion of
ownership, BellSouth says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, any call in the Southeast made through BellSouth's network
_ or the network of a rival programmed for number portability _
will be passed through a huge database managed by Lockheed Martin.
That database is intended to include all the numbers in the region.
``In this new environment, the numbers don't belong to anyone,''
said BellSouth spokesman John Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth currently faces competition, mostly for the local
service needs of large companies, a market more lucrative to serve
than residents. Only MGC Communications and MediaOne now offer
consumers a choice in local service. Jim Mitchell, general manager
for MGC, said the new system could eliminate confusion among
customers who fret about having a different number.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Baker, public service commissioner, stopped short of saying
portability would be enough to persuade the PSC to endorse
BellSouth's request to offer long-distance but called the
announcement ``a big step in the right direction in opening up the
local market.''
</P>
<P>
   At least until Monday, customers using a competing carrier would
keep their number, but only because their calls were routed from
that number _ which BellSouth continued to ``own'' _ to a number
owned by their new carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
