</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CST-SOFTWARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CST's Jacada software builds bridge to Internet, intranet
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta software-maker CST is in the business of
breathing new life into dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the long-extinct creatures whose massive skeletons and
razor-sharp teeth inspire awe in natural history museums. The
beasts CST stalks are mainframe computers too extensive, too
entrenched or too expensive to be replaced by the networked-PC
setup prevalent in many companies today.
</P>
<P>
   CST's signature product is Jacada, a software package that
transforms a mainframe's utilitarian ``green screen'' into a
graphical display that allows point-and-click operation instead of
tedious and arcane command input in which computer commands are
typed. The software also extends a mainframe's software
applications to the Internet or an intranet.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-year-old company has propelled itself into the No. 2
market share in ``Web-to-host'' integration, a part of the computer
world an International Data Corp. study concludes will be a
billion-dollar-plus business by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Mainframes ``won't be going away in our lifetimes,'' said Mike
Potts, president of CST's North American operations. ``With people
having invested millions in Y2K compliancy, it looks like they'll
be here for perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   The mainframe market is actually growing, Potts said. Last year,
for example, IBM alone sold more than 60,000 AS/400 computers, a
small mainframe intended for small- to medium-size companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacada is a family line with several derivative products which
will give us great market opportunity beyond the year 2000,'' Potts
said. ``The technology takes advantage of all the skills (mainframe
programmers) have as they try to bridge to Internet and intranet
technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Saab Cars USA, which has its headquarters in Norcross, is in the
process of installing Jacada to work with two different mainframes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jacada project gave us a very friendly user interface,''
said John Jacobs, Saab's manager of retailer and field information
systems. The company may be using two mainframes, but with Jacada
the screen view from either is the same for the end user, Jacobs
said. Saab expects to have the system up and running by early
October, Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   CST recently completed an agreement with Gulfstream Aerospace
Corp., a company best known for its corporate-jet business, to
install the Jacada software in its mainframe-based applications.
Gulfstream has offices in Savannah and in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
