<SLUG> BC-HBO-WEBMD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD may cure what ails HBO &AMP; Co.
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ HBO &AMP; Co.'s investment in WebMD Inc. may be just what
the doctor ordered for both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based HBO is a health information systems provider that
racked up more than a billion and a half dollars in revenue last
year. On Monday it said it had acquired a 5 percent stake in WebMD
for $10 million. HBOC Chief Financial Officer Jay Gilbertson will
assume a seat on WebMD's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, founded as Endeavor Technologies in 1994 by Jeff Arnold,
provides Internet access and services to physicians in 32 states.
This week WebMD announced the name change to reflect its focus on
Internet-based services. WebMD offers medical reference, physician
home pages, a national directory of doctors, communication services
and online clinical data.
</P>
<P>
   Each company offered a market the other coveted.
</P>
<P>
   ``WebMD offers a tremendous opportunity to gain access to the
physician desktop by providing superior Internet-based services to
physicians and their patients,'' said Charles McCall, HBO's
chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   HBOC already provides patient test results and and health
information library services as part of WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, WebMD will gain access to HBO's Web-based
applications and its market presence, Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD has embarked on a plan to put 60,000 computers on
physicians' desks around the nation over the next year. ``We're
basically giving the computers away to the doctors at no cost to be
able to help them get on the Net and to seed the market,'' Arnold
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
