</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Earnhardt vs. Earnhartd at Coca-Cola
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Earnhardt and Dale Earnhardt Jr., one of NASCAR's
hottest father-and-son duos, will confirm today that they will
compete for the first time during the Coca-Cola 500, in Motegi,
Japan, on Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Earnhardts will make the announcement at 11 a.m. at
Atlanta's World of Coca-Cola, where they will unveil the special
Coca-Cola-themed Chevrolet Monte Carlos they'll drive during the
post-season exhibition event.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr.'s car, which is black, will feature the Coca-Cola
polar bear, while his father's car, which is red, has Coca-Cola's
red disk icon and Coke's NASCAR-inspired checkered flag contour
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, the cars are expected to be used by Coca-Cola
during promotional events, and both drivers will return to their
usual cars. Earnhardt Jr., who has won five Busch series races and
leads the point standings, drives an AC Delco-sponsored blue Chevy
Monte Carlo; Earnhardt Sr., a seven-time Winston Cup champion and
winner of this year's Daytona 500, drives a Goodwrench-sponsored
black Chevy Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in April, the 23-year-old Earnhardt Jr. credited
his father with being a major influence on his career. ``I feel I
need to prove myself to him more than anybody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get that chance in the Coca-Cola 500, which will feature
other firsts. The race, to be broadcast on TBS, will be the first
sponsored by Coca-Cola Japan and will also be the race's first
running at Motegi's new 1.5-mile track.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico held the NASCAR sponsorship for more than 40 years until
Jan. 1, when Atlanta-based Coca-Cola began a five-year sponsorship
agreement. Coca-Cola is spending an estimated $30 million to
execute its NASCAR strategy.
</P>
<P>
   A key element of that strategy is promoting ``the Coca-Cola
Racing Family,'' whose members include the Earnhardts; Dale, Ned
and Jason Jarrett; and Kyle, Adam and Patty Petty.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the sponsorship plan does not include putting a driver
behind the wheel of a Coca-Cola car for NASCAR's main season. It's
been more than 20 years since that was done, when Bobby Allison
drove for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
