<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-FEATURE26-COX     08-25 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FEATURE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singh, Singh, Singh: Vijay aims for three wins in a row
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He reminds us why it's the name of the game. Why
people do it for dough. Why Dave Pelz is in business.
</P>
<P>
   Putting.
</P>
<P>
   For the average player, it represents about 40 percent of
strokes burned on the golf course. For the average tour pro, it's
the difference between being Vijay Singh over the past two weeks or
getting lost in his exhaust fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Singh's two-week ascension to the top of the PGA Tour money list
with consecutive wins in the PGA Championship and Sprint
International is no mystery. Known for the hundreds of range balls
he hits every day, Singh in the past two months has started making
eagle putts instead of three-putting for pars. Birdie putts that
seldom found the hole for a player who brandished everything but a
Power Pod are now falling with impressive regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, he's mad if he misses a 15-footer,'' says Davis Love III.
``Before, he just felt lucky if he made one every once in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Filled with confidence instead of doubt, Singh, who switched to
a cross-handed putting grip at the suggestion of his wife two
months ago, now has a complete game to play with anyone. His PGA
Tour colleagues always knew that if Singh's putter ever sang, with
such ball-striking skills already established, he had the potential
for a streak like this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always wondered why he hit so many balls,'' Love was
saying Monday at Callaway Gardens, where he attended Media Day as
the Buick Challenge's defending champion. ``He hit it so good and
he hit it so long, you figured he ought to be putting most of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, as the pros know best, it's usually a matter
of mind over technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of it is just getting confidence and getting on a
roll,'' Love said. ``Guys play good in streaks, like David Duval.
All of a sudden he won and got some confidence and had a great
streak there. Now, he's not really doing that much. It's just as
easy to get off it as it is to get on it. Vijay's on it right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a scary thought: Now that Singh is feeling secure with
his putting, imagine how much time he might spend on the range,
where nobody outlasts him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you could if you got there 30 minutes before he's
done,'' Love said, ``or if you stay after dark. It's always a joke
that he wears out caddies because he stays out there so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing this week at the NEC World Series of Golf in Akron,
Ohio, Singh tries for three in a row, which Duval managed last
fall. Assuredly, two in a row, with the second following a major,
was strong enough. Love tied for ninth at the NEC last year, when
the tournament followed his PGA win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to do because you're still on cloud nine,''
Love said. ``But Vijay's a different guy. He's very, very focused
on what he's doing. It's like he says, `My family is very important
to me, but I'm obsessed with golf.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
