<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notebook
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daly dilemmas
</P>
<P>
   People who observe John Daly regularly don't like the signals
he's been sending. Snapped clubs. Failing to sign a scorecard. Big
numbers at the end of a Friday round to miss the cut. Weight out of
control. It doesn't take a cynic to wonder whether Daly is setting
himself up for another fall. If Daly blows his shot with Callaway
Golf, it might be his last. He is scheduled to play in the Dunhill
Cup at St. Andrews in October as the partner of Tiger Woods and
Mark O'Meara, but he might ask to be replaced. ``I wouldn't help
Mark and Tiger right now,'' Daly said. ``I'd only be hurting the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Buick Challenge field
</P>
<P>
   While Daly has said he will play ``only the fun events'' through
the remainder of the year and no more official PGA Tour events,
Buick Challenge officials still are expecting him at Callaway
Gardens Oct. 1-4. Tournament director Bob Berry reports official
commitments from defending champion Davis Love III, David Duval,
Stewart Cink, Scott Hoch, Jeff Sluman, Justin Leonard, Andrew
Magee, Fred Funk and David Frost. The purse has been upped to $1.5
million, with $270,000 to the winner. Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar,
the tournament's Haskins Award winner, has accepted a sponsor's
exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Homeland havoc distracts Els
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els deeply loves his homeland of South Africa and calls
his residence there in the Western Cape Province ``the most
beautiful place on the planet.'' Lately, however, it has been
nothing short of frightening. Earlier this year, after Els' home
was burglarized, the man who stole his jeep was killed in a crash
with the vehicle. Recently, a crazed farmer who used to work for
one of Els' neighbors, ran through Els' house and three others,
killing four people. ``He ripped out the alarm system and just went
berserk,'' Els said. ``Thank God there was nobody in my house.''
Whether the incidents have affected Els' recent play is difficult
to determine. Back problems were probably more of a factor. In any
case, it was a mediocre year for Els in the majors. He tied for
16th in the Masters, tied for 49th in the U.S. Open as defending
champion, tied for 29th in the British Open and tied for 21st at
the PGA. ``I'm a little bit disappointed, but there's always next
year,'' said Els.
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Known for his rigorous exercise regimen, Gary Player had a quick
reply when told he was behind only Mike Fetchick, who won the 1985
Hilton Head Seniors Invitational on his 63rd birthday, in the race
for oldest player to win a Senior PGA Tour event. ``I'll have to do
some more sit-ups, that's all,'' said Player, who will turn 63 on
Nov. 1. . . . LaGrange's Allen Doyle won the Senior Series event
and $15,000 at Stonebridge Golf Club in Albany on Sunday, marking
his first victory since turning 50. Doyle shot rounds of 68-68-66
to win by four shots over Horacio Carbonetti. . . . Atlanta's Billy
Andrade suggests that Mark McGwire occasionally might be able to
knock a ball past Woods. Having seen McGwire's strength with a golf
ball as a former partner at the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am,
Andrade said, ``For length, I think he and Tiger would have a
battle.'' Andrade has seen McGwire hit the 18th green at Pebble
Beach in two _ with a driver and a 5-iron. Two years ago at Pebble
Beach Woods was the only to hit the 18th green in two, with a
3-wood. . . . Love and Leonard, who met head-to-head on the closing
day of the 1997 PGA Championship, will play a ``Shell's Wonderful
World of Golf'' match Sept. 29 at Winged Foot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
