<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VIRGINIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for a Seminole-buster? Try Virginia
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ If there is to be a challenge to Florida
State's supremacy in the Atlantic Coast Conference, many feel its
going to come out of this place known simply as ``Mr. Jefferson's
University.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the usually conservative George Welsh has pronounced this
year's Virginia team as capable. Football success is nothing new to
Welsh: Virginia has won seven or more games for 11 consecutive
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the experience and we have the talent to win
more than seven games,'' Welsh said. ``We project to be a better
team early in the season than we were last year. You've got to have
some luck and some breaks, and you've got to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's for sure that Welsh will find out early just how good his
Cavaliers may be. Auburn and Virginia tangle on national television
Sept. 3 in a game at Jordan-Hare Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for Welsh's optimism are that the Cavaliers might have
their best defensive unit in history and most of the skill
positions are back on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Rick Lantz pronounced this his fastest
team since he's been in Charlottesville, as nine of last year's 11
starters return.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, quarterback Aaron Brooks, who finished the year as
the ACC's leading passer, opens with the confidence he lacked last
season. Tailback Thomas Jones, who rushed for 692 yards in '97, is
the top returning rusher in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jones has had a good pre-season, I must admit,'' Welsh said.
``And Brooks is much more accurate now than he was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a veteran ball club here,'' said the 5-10, 210-pound
Jones. ``With the people we've got coming back, I think we could
win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks concurs. ``We're a very patient offense. We take whatever
a defensve gives us. Auburn is a very big game, because we have to
go and play in front of 80,000 people in a hostile environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Cavs got off to a 1-2 start, dropping their
opener to Auburn 28-17 and getting trounced by North Carolina two
games later 48-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot further along this year than we were last year,''
tight end Casey Crawford said. ``I think opening against Auburn, a
highly regarded team from the SEC, has helped us stay focused. We
know what happened when we played them last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lantz' defense is what might put the Cavs over the FSU hump.
Everyone returns except defensive backs Stephen Phelan and Joe
Williams, but safety Adrian Burnim and corner Antwan Harris saw
extensive action as reserves in '97.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line is intact, with Antonio Dingle and Johnny
Shivers at tackles and senior Patrick Kerney and junior Travis
Griffith at ends.
</P>
<P>
   All-America candidate Anthony Poindexter will keep things
running smoothly from his safety spot, but the 6-1 senior wanted to
talk more offense than defense. ``Aaron shredded us,'' Poindexter
said. ``He's playing with a confidence I've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone question mark about this team is the kicking game.
Welsh hasn't settled on his punter or placekicker, but he says that
he's not worried. ``We don't have enough depth in certain areas, if
you want to talk about things that concern me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia gets by Auburn, the Cavs have all of their tough
games at home except for Florida State on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh, 65, has said he wants to stick around long enough to put
together a serious run at a national title. He was asked if this
could be the start of that run. ``I don't know,'' he said. ``You
got to have a lot of luck, and you've got to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Thursday: Duke
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
