<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-LEGION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corner is pricey parcel
 &HT;    By Tinah Saunders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A generous gift made more than 70 years ago by a
grateful city to its battle-weary sons may cost Atlanta nearly $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, Atlanta officials sold a parcel of land adjacent to
Piedmont Park to the American Legion's Post No. 1 as a site for a
meeting hall. The nearly two-thirds acre at 1071 Piedmont Ave. went
for the token price of $100, but the deed restricted use of the
land for ``the purpose of erecting a home'' for the Argonne Post of
the American Legion, as Post No. 1 was known at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, Mayor William B. Hartsfield removed the restrictions by
signing a quit-claim deed, giving ``complete or unrestricted title
to the post and its heirs and assigns'' for the consideration of $1
more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, that property is valued at nearly $1 million by the
Fulton County Tax Assessor's Office. And it is on the market, now
that aging members of Post No. 1, who find maintaining the property
a burden, have voted to sell the land and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are under way with the Piedmont Park Conservancy,
which is trying to find funding for the purchase. Neither party has
revealed the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   Although the property is located in the heart of Midtown at the
southwest corner of the park, it is ``prohibitively expensive for
commercial development,'' said Tom Walsh, chairman of the post's
property disposition committee, who has done extensive research on
possible uses for the site. Walsh and other members of the post
determined that the conservancy was the primary market for the
land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zoning restricts any buildings to four stories, and there is a
40-foot setback in front and 20 feet on each side,'' he said. ``And
then there is the problem of parking for a building of any size.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Sam Massell explained the city's generosity
after what was called ``the war to end all wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The original purpose was to help the veterans,'' said Massell,
who now heads the Buckhead Coalition. ``Back then, folks would have
done anything for them _ housing, education _ anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
