</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-FALCON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Release of falcon a symbol of removal from endangered list
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and other
dignitaries standing close by, a peregrine falcon erupted from its
cage atop Stone Mountain on Tuesday and sped into the late-morning
sky.
</P>
<P>
   It was an historic flight: Babbitt seized the opportunity to
announce that federal officials are taking steps to remove the
swift-moving raptor from the federal list of endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this bird flies off this mountain today, I hope it carries
this message through Georgia and throughout the land: The
Endangered Species Act is working,'' Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The crow-size falcon, known for its diving speeds that can reach
up to 200 mph, was on the brink of extinction in 1970 when it was
first listed as endangered -- the victim of encroaching
development, hunters and pesticides. By 1975, the population
reached an all time low with 324 nesting pairs in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are 1,600 nesting pairs due to successful restoration
efforts. ``For years, the peregrine falcon has aroused wonder in
men and we must realize how close we came to seeing this bird
eradicated from the face of the Earth,'' said Georgia Lt. Gov.
Pierre Howard.
</P>
<P>
   The official notice to ``delist'' the falcon will be published
in the Federal Register on Wednesday by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. After a public comment period that ends Nov. 23, the
service will remove the bird from the list if there are no strong
public objections.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said he came to Georgia to make the announcement because
of ``the fine spirt of conservation in this state'' and because of
numerous organizations that have helped the bird's recovery in
Georgia, including the Department of Natural Resources, Georgia
Power Co. and the Chattahoochee Nature Center. The falcon released
on Tuesday was rehabilitated at the nature center after it was
found injured in June in a Roswell backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Peregrines nest in the tucks of cliffs, the ledges of tall
buildings or on large bridges. Several of them are now found in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
