<SLUG> BC-FBC-BEAR-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Wanted: People named for The Bear
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: FREELANCE MATERIAL _ not for NYT wires.)
</P>
<P>
   By Gita M. Smith
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TO THE ATLANTA JOURNAL-CONSTITUTION
</P>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM_No one knows for sure how many baby boys were named
for legendary football coach Paul William ``Bear'' Bryant over the
25 years he spurred the Crimson Tide to 323 winning games. But the
University of Alabama in Tuscaloosa already has collected more than
400 names and stories from various Pauls, Bears, Williams and
Bryants across the nation, and it is looking for more.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the university's Paul W. Bryant Museum is sending out
the call: Persons named for coach Bryant who would like to attend
an invitation-only gala namesake reunion before the Tide's season
kickoff on Sept. 5 should let the museum know.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started with Paul Bryant Jr., the Bear's son, after he
got hundreds of letters from people who said they were named for
his dad,'' said Jan Adams, spokeswoman for the Bryant Museum. ``We
decided to try to collect people's stories, and we've started a
database.''
</P>
<P>
   A party held in 1996 for Bryant namesakes appears to be on the
verge of becoming an annual tradition. About 150 people showed up
then, including two girls, and a similar number, including three
namesakes under a year old, attended last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a senior in high school when I attended my first Alabama
football game _ Coach Bryant's 300th win,'' said Claire Chandler of
Collinsville, Ala., who named her son William Bryant. ``I often
hear people call him `Brian,' and I am quick to correct them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another entry in the Bryant database recalls a lonely childhood
of poverty in which Bear Bryant loomed large as a hero and
substitute father figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son Bryant was born on May 14, 1980, and there was never
any question or debate as to whom he would be named for,'' Tony
Smith wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant fever isn't limited to Alabama. The
houndstooth-hatted University of Alabama head coach gathered fans
in dozens of states while winning six national championships.
``Papa knew from the letters he received that children were being
named for him, and it made him proud,'' his son said. To become
part of the namesake registry and attend the reunion, write to Paul
W. Bryant Museum, Box 870385, Tuscaloosa, Ala. 35487-0385, or call:
205-348-4668.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
