<HEADER>
A1828 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-CHANCELLOR-HNS &LR;      08-25 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-CHANCELLOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICHAEL MURPHY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Comets coach Van Chancellor loves to make a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Most any subject is fair game for Chancellor, but his
magnolia-drenched wit usually is directed at one target _ himself.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, just try to get Chancellor to tell you what a great
job he does with the Comets. Chancellor usually will reply with
some self-deprecating, aw-shucks remark to deflect the praise.
Never mind that Chancellor has taken home the only two WNBA Coach
of the Year trophies.
</P>
<P>
   And forget that the Comets are gunning for their second WNBA
championship behind two-time league Most Valuable Player Cynthia
Cooper. Chancellor would rather crack a disarming joke than accept
credit.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one subject about which Chancellor gets serious _
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Chancellor the reason for the Comets' success, and he won't
talk about their league-leading offense or tremendous individual
talents such as Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   No, Chancellor will point to the Comets' defense as the key to
last year's championship and this year's team that will play for
another WNBA title after throttling Charlotte 77-61 on Monday night
to complete a two-game semifinals sweep of the Sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell you, that's what I'm proudest of _ I think
we're the best defensive basketball team I've seen in a long, long
time,'' Chancellor said. ``I've thought all along that every big
basketball game we've won, we've won it with defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won this playoff (against the Sting) because we are so
really good on offense, but we've always been a great defensive
basketball team. We always have been.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Comets so good defensively is the same thing that
makes the Chicago Bulls such a great team. With the Bulls,
superstars Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen are the team's best
defensive players. And with the Comets, superstars Cooper and
Swoopes are defensive stoppers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's amazing,'' Chancellor said. ``When people ask me
why we've been such a good basketball team, I say, `Because our
best players work so hard.' I think Cynthia and Sheryl are the two
best defensive wing players in the league. And I think Kim Perrot
and Tina Thompson give us the two one-four (point guard-power
forward) defenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper just shrugged off the dual role of league-leading scorer
(22.7 points) and top-notch defensive player. Simply part of the
job for herself and Swoopes, who was the league's sixth-leading
scorer at 15.6 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be (good defensive players),'' Cooper said. ``In
order to make our team complete and our franchise a winning
franchise, we have to play both ends of the floor. We actually let
our offense feed off our defense, and if we continue to play good
defense, we feel that we can get it going on offense. We can get
some easy buckets off the fast break, and that's what it's all
about _ playing a complete game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally defend the best two guard on the opposing team. My
goal is to stop them, and whatever I get on offense is a plus. I
set out with that goal. I know that I'm not going to just let her
(the opponent) score 20 points and hope that I score 24. The key is
to hold her to 10 points and me to score 24. I think when my
teammates see me getting out there and getting down on defense,
then they give a little more on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets hunkered down on defense Monday night against
Charlotte, limiting the Sting to 37.9-percent shooting. Vicky
Bullett hit just four of 14 shots, and point guard Tora Suber was
just 3-for-12 from the floor. The key was pushing both just a bit
farther from the basket than they liked, forcing them out of their
respective offensive comfort zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic defensive philosophy is, `Let's get you out of where
you want to be.' That's the simplest terms,'' Chancellor said. ``We
like to get you out of your comfort zone. If you like to be on the
block, we get you out of the block. If you like to score from 15
feet, then we'll get you to 18 feet. And we like to pressure the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And Chancellor has the good fortune to have one of the league's
top defensive point guards in Perrot, who often seems to be a
one-woman press at work. Perrot has her finger on the pulse of the
game, turning up the defensive heat when she thinks the Comets are
lagging or coasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I enjoy doing,'' Perrot said. ``Growing up,
that's something that I took pride in, playing defense, and that's
a big part of my game. I've played on different teams where I had
to score, but on this team I really don't have to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just concentrate more on defense. It's fortunate that we
have other players who also take pride in defense. When they see
how hard I work, they just put extra effort as well into the
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor is quick to credit his players; the players are just
as quick to credit the coaching staff for all the hard work on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give credit to our coaching staff, which has done an
excellent job of getting us in shape, keeping us in shape over the
course of the season and stressing defense,'' Cooper said. ``They
could have put defense on the back burner, saying, `Well, this team
is good enough on offense,' but they didn't. That's why we're so
successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
