<HEADLINE>
AFTER EARLY BUYING SPREE, INVESTORS BALK AT RUSSIA PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ECON, moved in `i' category) 
(bl) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cautious optimism about the outlook for emerging
markets took a turn for the worse Tuesday as investors balked at
the details of a plan by Russia to restructure some
government-backed debt.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' displeasure with the low interest rates offered on
new longer-term securities as part of the Russian bailout package
moved bank shares off their highs and overshadowed earlier euphoria
that pushed stocks strongly higher.
</P>
<P>
   Investors began the day buying shares as the Dow Jones
industrial average climbed more than 122 points. The buying spree
was a sign of confidence that the domestic economy's low interest
rates and moderate rate of growth would buoy profits of U.S.
corporations. Following on the heels of gains in overseas markets,
it also signaled a belief that recent price declines might have
been overdone, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But disappointment with the Russian plan ushered in another wave
of stock selling and buying of Treasuries, pushing the yield on the
30-year bond down to 5.43 percent, a historic low.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries were also bolstered by a stronger dollar, which rose
partly on reports that the Japanese government may not step in soon
to shore up the yen by selling dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Early gains in stocks erased most of Monday's losses. But by
midafternoon, stocks, led by banks, began to stumble as details of
Russia's rescue plan began to trickle into the market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of J.P. Morgan, which had climbed as much as 4 3/16
points, closed at 120~, up 1| points. Citicorp, up as much as 5
3/16 points, closed at 136[, up 2 11/16 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian plan to exchange about $40 billion of short-term,
ruble-denominated debt into longer-term securities calls for the
new debt to carry an interest rate of about 30 percent for
three-year securities. The rate declines to 20 percent in the fifth
year. Investors who redeem the securities prior to maturity will
receive about 5 percent of their par value.
</P>
<P>
   The debt pact reminded investors that the financial woes of
emerging markets would take some time to mend, analysts and traders
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a reason to sell? I guess,'' said Andrew Brooks, vice
president for equity trading at T. Rowe Price Associates. ``It just
highlights some of the skittishness in the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 8,602.65, a
36.04-point gain. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index closed up
4.72 points at 1,092.86. The Nasdaq composite index gained 7.35
points, to 1,798.17.
</P>
<P>
   But smaller shares fared worse. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller- company stocks fell 3.94 points, or 1 percent, to 389.76,
its lowest close in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed to the limited rally and the declines among
small- company shares as indicators the market remained vulnerable
to further declines in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way trading-range corrections proceed,'' said
Alfred Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards Inc. ``When
you look at all the problems the market has had to digest in the
past week, I think we're putting on a good show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
