<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE TO APPEAL RULING ON SAMPLING IN CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, while acknowledging
that a federal court ruling on Monday was a blow to its efforts to
use sampling to supplement the 2000 census, said Tuesday that it
would still press Congress for the money the Census Bureau would
need to plan for sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The administration immediately said it would appeal the ruling,
which was made by a special three-judge panel that said statistical
sampling violated federal law. Late Tuesday afternoon it filed a
notice of appeal asking the Supreme Court to review the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first stop on a long journey of resolution,'' said
Everett Ehrlich, a former Commerce Department official who is now a
Democratic member of an independent board that is monitoring the
Census Bureau's plans.
</P>
<P>
   But any Supreme Court ruling is not expected until next year.
That still leaves plenty of time for the administration and House
Republicans to engage in a knock-down, drag-out fight this fall
over a spending bill to pay for the Census Bureau's plans for the
next census _ plans that still include the use of sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Statistical sampling is expected to provide a more complete
count of the nation's population, which would mean that groups that
analysts say were under-represented in the 1990 census could
benefit from a 2000 census based on sampling. These groups, mostly
the urban and rural poor, tend to live in predominantly Democratic
areas and therefore counting them might benefit that party in
drawing district lines.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans rejoiced in the court ruling. ``The public
perception is that it certainly enhanced our standing,'' said Pete
Jeffries, spokesman for Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., an ardent foe
of sampling. ``This shows that this is just another example of the
Clinton administration trying to run roughshod over the law and the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shapiro, under secretary of Commerce for economic
affairs, the division that oversees the Census Bureau, was just as
vehement a proponent of sampling. ``Regardless of the court
decision, this is going to be a very tough political fight that
will be hard fought on all sides,'' Shapiro said. ``The opponents
of the use of scientific methods will try to use this ruling to try
to make their case, just like the proponents of scientific methods
use the testimony of noted scientists to make their case. This is a
real fight, and people will use whatever is available.''
</P>
<P>
   The court decision and the coming fight in Congress both flow
from an agreement negotiated in November between Speaker Newt
Gingrich and Erskine Bowles, the White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which broke a logjam over a spending bill,
Gingrich was able to proceed with a lawsuit paid for by taxpayers
to have sampling declared unconstitutional or illegal, a suit that
was heard by a special three-judge panel. The agreement also
allowed for any decison to be appealed directly and expeditiously
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, under the agreement the spending bill would not
fully fund the Departments of Commerce _ including the Census
Bureau _ Justice and State in the next fiscal year, though there is
dispute between the parties on just what it would finance. The
administration and the Democrats say the agreement was to fund the
three departments for six months while everyone waited for a
decision on sampling from the Supreme Court. The Republicans assert
that they agreed to fund only the Census Bureau for half a year.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is pushing for funding all of the operations
of the Commerce, Justice and State departments for six months,
figuring that the pressure of a looming government shut-down _ even
a partial one _ will drive the Republicans to resolve the sampling
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans reason that if only the Census Bureau runs out
of funds next spring, the administraton will be so desperate to
gain the rest of the financing it will agree to drop its plans to
use sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over sampling also comes as Clinton's personal
popularity has been brought low by his acknowledgement of his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's political difficulty certainly has to be
factored in,'' said one former administration official familiar
with the census battle. ``It could go either way.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats feel that the possiblity that Kenneth Starr,
the independent counsel, will be submitting a report to Congress
that accuses Clinton of having engaged in illegal activity might
strengthen his resolve in the census fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
