<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSTER-SIBLINGS-ART-8     08-25 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTER-SIBLINGS-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER CARE PROGRAMS AIMED AT KEEPING SIBLINGS TOGETHER ARE
EXPANDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Fla., Ky., Ohio, Mass., N.Y., Minn., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By PAM BELLUCK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Childhood has not been kind to them, these four
brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Their overwhelmed parents smacked them to keep them in line,
counselors say, and the three oldest, now ages 10, 9, and 5, were
sexually molested by their mother's brothers. Now angry and
insecure, the siblings pummel one another, make disturbing sexual
gestures, sometimes wet their beds, and misbehave in school, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   When child welfare authorities decided to remove them from their
parents' home and place them in foster care two years ago, they
stood a good chance of being separated from each other. Child
welfare agencies have historically focused on finding available
foster parents, not on trying to keep sisters and brothers in the
same home. And it is hard to find foster parents with room for
four, let alone the willingness to take care of so many troubled
children at once.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Veronica, Chantel, Jimmy and Jermaine were
steered toward a new program that pays foster parents a premium - a
salary thousands of dollars more than they get from the state,
health benefits, vacation time, pension and sick days - all to
persuade them to take care of a group of brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago program reflects a growing movement in foster care
nationally. Fueled by lawsuits in New York, Chicago and elsewhere,
and by a groundswell of lobbying by child welfare advocates, states
have begun enacting laws and inaugurating programs designed to
encourage foster parents to care for groups of siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't underestimate the trauma children go through when
they're separated from their siblings,'' said Gordon Johnson, a
former director of the Illinois Department of Children and Family
Services, who is now the president of the Jane Addams Hull House
Association, a non-profit agency which runs the sibling program.
``On top of the trauma of being separated from their parents, you
put them in a strange environment where they're mixed with other
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Some child welfare officials point out potential pitfalls of
trying to routinely place siblings together. Special programs like
Chicago's are generally expensive, and the laws and consent decrees
often logistically difficult to enforce, if only because there may
be so many more needy siblings than families willing to take them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some officials and advocates worry that it might
compromise another increasingly supported goal: to get children
with no chance of being reunited with their parents adopted as soon
as possible so they don't remain in the limbo of the foster care
system. It is always easier to find a family to adopt one child,
rather than several.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, most foster care experts agree that trying to
keep brothers and sisters together is at least worth shooting for,
an effort to maintain some thread of consistency for children whose
small worlds are being otherwise ripped apart.
</P>
<P>
   Since the majority of children in foster care have siblings who
are also in foster care, keeping them together is not a small task.
In some states, as many as 80 percent of foster children have
siblings in the system and half or more are scattered among
different foster homes. And anecdotally, many child welfare
agencies report seeing more large sibling groups, possibly because
social workers who find one abused child in a family are more
inclined to quickly remove the other children.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, California passed a law allowing foster homes to take
more than the maximum number of children, 6, if it meant keeping
brothers and sisters together. Ohio, Massachusetts and New York
took up similar measures the year before, and Minnesota and Alabama
recently began requiring siblings to be placed together, whenever
possible, according to the Child Welfare League of America, a
national advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, a small program begun last fall gives foster
parents who take in sibling groups an apartment - rent-free - in a
building in Rego Park, Queens, pays them an extra stipend and gives
them benefits like laundry service and babysitting.
</P>
<P>
   California's Social Services Department is giving social workers
special training in placing siblings together and has recommended
that counties pay prospective foster families to keep their homes
vacant until a sibling group comes along. New Jersey has just begun
heavily recruiting foster parents who will agree to take sibling
groups. Kentucky has an extra stipend for such foster families.
Florida is setting up a pilot program along the lines of the Hull
House program in Chicago. And Illinois also has another program
that pays foster families extra money for rent if they move to a
larger house to take in more brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are talking about it and trying to do
better,'' said Kathy Barbell, director of foster care for the Child
Welfare League. ``It's like a light bulb went off. What is longest
relationship you have with any person? It's your siblings. And
there are more former foster children searching for their siblings
these days than their biological parents.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, these sibling initiatives reflect a broader
national movement to give foster children more stability. New York
City and other systems are championing plans to keep foster
children in their original neighborhoods, and many states, like
Illinois, are trying to place more children with relatives, which
can also lead to more sibling contact.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, the fledgling sibling programs are making incremental
differences, as states try to weigh priorities in foster care
placement. What should social workers do, for example, if a family
takes in one child, but then does not have room for a sibling taken
from the parents later on or a new baby born to the parents after
other children were removed?
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where a class action lawsuit filed by the
Legal Aid Society against the city was settled in 1993 with an
agreement requiring siblings to be placed together unless their
health and safety was compromised, more sibling groups are being
placed together now - 51 percent in 1996 up from 45 percent in
1990, when the suit was filed. Jennifer Folk, a spokeswoman for the
Administration of Children's Services, said the main reason
siblings are separated is that a social worker decides they need
different types of medical or psychological care, or a relative
wants to take one or two children, but not all. Child welfare
advocates believe more sibling groups could be kept together.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the Cook County Public Guardian won a similar
consent decree with a suit against the state, including a provision
that siblings, when separated, should visit each other twice a
month. Still, currently two-thirds of Illinois' 37,762 siblings in
foster care are not placed with all their other siblings, and only
about half of the separated siblings were visiting each other twice
a month, said Mary Sue Morsch, a deputy director of the Illinois
Department of Children and Family Services, adding that her
department was working to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he wanted to expand the Hull House program, called
Neighbor to Neighbor, beyond its 30 foster families. He said that
placing siblings together makes it easier for social workers to
assess whether children should be reunited with their parents, a
goal the program tries to achieve. Even if they are ultimately
split up in adoption, he said, they have at least benefited from
being together for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Very few studies have actually tried to measure the consequences
of sibling placements. One small recent study of preschool foster
children near Syracuse, found that siblings placed together were
more emotionally stable, but did not do as well on cognitive tests,
perhaps because foster parents allowed older siblings to teach the
younger children skills like vocabulary and colors, said the
author, Maureen Smith, an assistant professor of psychology at
Chicago State University. Professor Smith said she concluded that
sibling placements should not be automatic, but should depend on
each child's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that they are plowing new ground, some of the sibling
programs are explicitly designed to react quickly when conflicts
between siblings and other difficulties arise. After problems
cropped up between brothers and sisters in one of the New York
program's foster families, two brothers moved in temporarily with
another family in the same program, trading places with two
sisters, said Sue Goldman, assistant of director of foster home
services for the Jewish Child Care Association, which runs the
program.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Hull House gives its foster parents intensive
training and monitors the families closely, at least once a week.
In exchange for a $16,000 salary (which supplements the regular
state stipend of roughly $415 per child per month), Hull House
treats foster parents like full-time employees. They cannot hold
another job and can be terminated quickly, for cause.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened to the first Hull House foster mother who
took in Veronica, 10, Chantel, 9, Jimmy, 5, and Jermaine, 3. The
woman, Bobbie Luckett, 56, tried hard to establish order and
dependability for the children, who seemed to gorge themselves on
food as if they never had enough and who were often very physical
with each other. Once, Ms. Luckett said, Veronica brandished a
kitchen knife at her. Chantel acted out in school, calling a
substitute teacher profane names and disturbing other children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Luckett repeatedly consulted the program for guidance and
used methods like ``The Good Kid Chart,'' a checklist which listed
goals like ``I did not fight before school'' and ``I did not argue
tonight.'' But in February, about a year after they had been placed
with Ms. Luckett, the two girls locked the two boys in a closet and
Ms. Luckett's adult daughter, who was babysitting, lost her temper
and struck the girls with a belt, said Michael Heard, a Hull House
therapist. Within 24 hours, the children were removed from Ms.
Luckett's home and placed with Mary Hardwick, a 58-year-old woman
who had years of experience as a foster mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hardwick says the siblings are the most troubled children
she has cared for. Besides disciplinary problems at home, the girls
once were kicked out of a church program for fighting with each
other. But Heard says that with Ms. Hardwick's steady approach, he
is seeing gradual progress, Jermaine becoming more verbal, all four
playing together nicely in group therapy sessions. On balance, he
believes, they are gaining stability from staying together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they really love each other,'' Ms. Hardwick said.
``They just don't know how to express it. But all of them together
is better. I wouldn't want to be split up from my sisters and
brothers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
