<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVANGELICAL-EDUC-ART-     08-25 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANGELICAL-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTO THE SHELTERING ARMS OF EVANGELICAL COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ind., Ill., Calif., Tenn., Iowa, Va., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rl) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For her civics class last spring at Lincoln High School in
Portland, Ore., Rebecca Strong had to memorize the names of all the
participants in the White House scandal, including the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tested on that,'' Strong recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But she was uncomfortable with the class discussions and her
friends' reaction to the relationship between President Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them would say, `What's the big deal?''' Strong said.
``They couldn't understand my thinking premarital sex is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, she said, is why she will enter Seattle Pacific
University, a ``Christ-centered'' college of 2,470 students, in
September. In choosing an evangelical _ or born-again _ Christian
college, she is part of a surge in applicants to institutions that
take a strict view of relations between the sexes, and who say the
White House scandal was a focusing event in their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear a lot about that,'' said Bob Andringa, president of
the Coalition for Christian Colleges and Universities, an
association of 93 evangelical Christian colleges that offer
four-year liberal arts programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's troubles and the fact that so many Americans
don't take them seriously,'' Andringa said, ``underscore for the
conservative Christian community that we're in a society that can
look at something morally questionable and not have it make a
difference. That leads many parents to ask, `Do I want my 18- or
19-year-old going to a campus that is so casual?' The answer to
that brings many of them to our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 100 evangelical colleges across the country
(most densely in Indiana, Illinois and Southern California), and
they tend to be nestled on rural campuses with a small number of
students. Total enrollment is about 160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan College, in Dayton, Tenn., has about 470 students, but
there has been an increase in applicants this year of almost 30
percent, and many other small, little-known evangelical colleges
are reporting increases in applicants of 10 percent to 12 percent
over last year. Applications at Dordt College, in Sioux Center,
Iowa, are up 15 percent over last year, and more than 20 percent at
Palm Beach-Atlantic College, in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Double-digit growth is highly unusual, said Vance Grant, a
statistics specialist at the U.S. Department of Education. The
increase in this year's class of high school graduates (about 3
percent over last year, according to the department) explains only
part of that growth. What is more, the evangelical movement has
remained static in recent years, said Kent Hunter, president of the
Church Growth Center, a consulting agency for evangelical churches.
</P>
<P>
   College officials have long been impressed, and baffled, by how
the culture affects applications. In the 1980s, the University of
Chicago's dean of admissions attributed ``an astounding number'' of
applicants to Indiana Jones' being a fictional archaeology
professor there.
</P>
<P>
   The classic example is what admissions officials refer to as
``the Flutie spike.'' A huge increase in applications to Boston
College in the mid-1980s was tied to the heart-stopping performance
of a gifted quarterback named Doug Flutie. The number of
applicants, which had been a steady 10,000 a year, leaped to 16,163
in 1985 when high school boys across the country, after imitating
Flutie's passing technique, also applied for admission to his
college.
</P>
<P>
   Today's ``triggering event,'' said Stephen Balch, president of
the neoconservative National Association of Scholars, is the White
House scandal, which has caused people to realize they ``must build
a fortress to defend their way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Eisenback of Blacksburg, Va., encouraged her son, Brian,
to choose Bryan College to protect him against what she and her
husband saw as growing moral permissiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal, Mrs. Eisenback said, ``goes with abortion, children
being born out of wedlock and morals not being considered `in.' In
that kind of a world, we have a responsibility to make sure our
children learn values, and Bryan College teaches them.''
</P>
<P>
   The evangelical colleges _ as distinct from Bible schools, whose
curriculum is centered on teaching Scripture _ offer a typical
array of liberal arts courses but teach them from a Christian
perspective. For instance, Bryan College, which is named after
William Jennings Bryan, teaches creationism as opposed to Darwinian
evolution. Southern Nazarene University, in Bethany, Okla., will
not teach Nabokov but will teach Milton and Bunyan, who, explained
Gwen Ladd Hackler, a professor of English, ``portray the kind of
struggle that would occur in a spiritual life.'' Psychology at
Calvin College, in Grand Rapids, Mich., emphasizes ``the dignity of
humanity, because people are created in the image of God,'' said
Thomas E. McWhertor, an administrator there.
</P>
<P>
   Dordt College, which has 1,300 students, requires faculty
members and students to sign a pledge that they understand and will
abide by a conservative interpretation of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The colleges benefit from a perception of safety and have strict
rules of conduct. Many ban alcohol and tobacco on campus. Dancing,
where allowed, is carefully regulated. Attendance at chapel
services is usually mandatory, and the colleges teach that
extramarital sex, abortion, co-ed living arrangements and
homosexual and lesbian behavior are contrary to Scriptural
principles.
</P>
<P>
   When an administrative employee at Dordt College was recently
discovered to have had an extramarital relationship, the employee
was summarily dismissed, said Carl Zylstra, president of Dordt.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian colleges have long been weak academically, with
entrance requirements listed in their promotional literature as
moderately to minimally difficult, but a few have made significant
improvements. Wheaton College, in Wheaton, Ill., is sometimes
called the Harvard of the evangelicals because 86 percent of its
faculty members have Ph.D.'s; the National Research Council's 1995
study listed Wheaton as 138th of 2,307 institutions in the number
of graduates going on to receive doctorates.
</P>
<P>
   Some evangelical colleges are deliberately trying to position
themselves in the public consciousness as moral centers. The Boston
Sunday Herald published an opinion piece last February by R. Judson
Carlberg, the president of Gordon College, in Wenham, Mass., on
``our lack of concern for the truth'' in the White House.
Applicants are up about 8 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, The Seattle Times published an op-ed article by Philip
Eaton, the president of Seattle Pacific University, urging readers
to ``pray for our president and for all involved in this sorry
matter.'' In an interview, Eaton pointed to ``issues of cultural
drift, the loss of standards, truthfulness and the tyranny of
tolerance in which people say, `If you think that way, that's your
business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Van Essen, director of admissions at Dordt, said he
sensed such concerns on campus tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents who visit the school with their kids won't come right
out and say what they're thinking,'' Van Essen said, ``but they'll
ask, `What do your faculty think are the important issues?' And
then they'll say, `Are any of the athletic coaches homosexual?' And
then they may come around to making a remark about what's going on
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what's on their minds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
