<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKLAG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern black students are focal point of private studyBy Ernie
Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While blacks continue to lag behind whites in higher
educational opportunities in the South, programs in Georgia may
serve as an example of what can be done to provide greater access
for blacks in higher education, according to an Atlanta-based
education group.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Southern Education Foundation released Tuesday,
focusing on the lack of educational opportunities for blacks in the
South, singled out the University System of Georgia's P-16
Initiative, which connects pre-school and high school with college,
and the HOPE Scholarship, which provides additional college funding
for Georgia high school students to attend college, as examples of
state programs to bridge the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's approach is the right one, said Michael Timpane,
senior advisor for Education Policy at the RAND Corporation, a
non-profit institution that researches public policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our conviction and belief that working on the K-12
system and working on the connection between them an higher
education _ these separate systems working together _ can produce
dramatic changes (in the access that blacks will have to higher
education opportunities),'' said Timpane, former president of
Columbia University's School of Education. ``Colleges have to pay
attention to K-12 or they will never solve their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Timpane's comments, and subsequent praise of Georgia's
direction, came Tuesday after the SEF's release of that states that
on virtually all fronts, efforts to desegregate higher education in
the South have little impact over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Among other indicators, the report lists economics and a lack of
preparation of black students in the lower grades as a direct
correlation on why the gap is still wide.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kronley, project director for the SEF, said even though
the black population has grown and remedies have been developed for
blacks over the last 20 years, opportunities for blacks at colleges
and universities have been at a virtual standstill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is alarming,'' said Kronley. ``Despite an
appearance of progress here and there, blacks lag behind whites.
The gap is not closing, but the gateway to opportunity is
closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kronley added that other efforts, including the implementation
of admissions programs that may be viewed as pro-affirmative
action, would be another way to close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this reports says is that race sensitive remedies are
still relevant, but not by any means the only solution,'' said
Kronley. ``While we are still struggling to cast off the vestiges
of the past, we may need to consider these.''
</P>
<P>
   The report looked at 19 mostly Southern states that currently
have historically black colleges and at one time maintained a dual
system of higher education. Including Georgia, those states include
Alabama, Arkansas, Delaware, Florida, Kentucky, Louisiana,
Maryland, Mississippi, Missouri, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma,
Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Virginia and West
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is unique about these states is the legacy of
segregation,'' said Kronley.
</P>
<P>
   More than 75 percent of black first-time, full-time freshmen at
four-year public schools attend school in one of those 19 states.
All but three of the nation's 103 historically black colleges and
universities are also located in the 19 states and more than half
of them are public. These were included in the study's results.
</P>
<P>
   But while the number of blacks entering higher education has
grown, the percentage of blacks among full-time freshmen is almost
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Kronley said that in nine of the 19 states, the proportion of
first time, full-time black freshmen has actually declined over the
last five years. In Georgia, where blacks represent more than 32
percent of the 18- to 24-year-old population, fewer than 24 percent
of the first-time, full-time freshmen are enrolled at four-year
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flat percentage of blacks who are participating in higher
education reflect the fact that states are shrinking from their
commitment to ensure that all students have access to quality
education,'' Kronley said.
</P>
<P>
   University System of Georgia Chancellor Stephen Portch would not
comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
