<HEADLINE>
RE-EMERGENT CLINTON GOES SAILING, PLANS SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ President Clinton is slowly emerging from his
self-imposed cocoon, venturing out Tuesday into public view with
his wife and daughter for the first time since they arrived here a
week ago after he admitted to an ``inappropriate'' relationship
with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The first family went for an hourlong sail Tuesday afternoon
with Walter Cronkite on the former CBS News anchorman's nearly
60-foot-long ketch, Wyntje, with the Clintons drawing hundreds of
spectators to the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   And the president has decided after much debate among his
advisers to give a speech in Worcester on Thursday, testing the
theory that by changing the national conversation from his sex life
to policy matters Clinton can rebuild his leverage as he heads into
negotiations this fall with Congress over spending issues and as
Congress considers whether to reprimand him in some way, or even to
impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been searching for a venue in which Clinton
could appear presidential. Since he admitted last week on national
television to an affair with the intern, Monica Lewinsky, his aides
have been telephoning Democratic members of Congress to gauge the
public reaction and how the president might help Democrats this
fall _ even if it means staying away from their districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've definitely been reaching out,'' said an aide to one
Democratic member. Such reaching out has included invitations to
join Clinton next week as he visits Russia and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The decision for the president to go to Worcester to speak on
the topic of juvenile crime was made on Monday night. Rep. Jim
McGovern, D-Mass., whose district includes Worcester, said he had a
longstanding invitation to Clinton to visit the district, and the
White House _ to the surprise of McGovern's aides _ suddenly
accepted. The site for the speech had not been determined as of
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Worcester struck some political veterans as
odd. It is a swing district _ an anomaly in heavily Democratic
Massachusetts _ and McGovern, a first-term Democrat, is a top
target for national Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the district offered an easily accessible
destination that would not cut too much into the time that Clinton
is spending here, generally in seclusion with his wife and
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were more cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only district that would have him,'' sneered Marc
DeCourcey, executive director of the Massachusetts Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Marsh, media consultant for McGovern's Republican
challenger, State Sen. Matthew Amorello, said he looked forward to
using film footage of McGovern with Clinton in the campaign this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who care about cultural issues, their
families and the breakdown in values in society, and I wouldn't
think Bill Clinton would be the image that McGovern would want to
project,'' Marsh said. ``Bill Clinton is the poster boy for
everything that's wrong, values-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGovern said he was thrilled with the prospect of Clinton's
visit. ``Having the president come is a big deal, and people are
proud he's coming here,'' the congressman said. ``People here are
hungering for a discussion of the issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
