<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORCESTER HOPES CLINTON WILL HELP PUT IT ON THE MAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Miles off of the state's main highway routes,
Worcester, New England's second-largest city, has long felt
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sat here and told people we're the second-largest city in
New England and had them insist I am wrong,'' Mayor Raymond Mariano
said Tuesday. ``They say, `No, it's Providence,' or, `No, it's
Hartford.' For too long, Worcester hasn't gotten the recognition it
deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   But with President Clinton's planned visit here Thursday,
Mariano and those who make this city an hour west of Boston home
hope that will change _ at least a little. They will be trying to
stretch the media spotlight to showcase some of the Worcester they
know and love as the president goes about unveiling a school safety
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Worcester as the site for one of the
president's excursions from Martha's Vineyard, where he is
vacationing, seems to make sense. A tough program that charges
police officers with bringing truant kids back to school has cut
the dropout rate in half. Student test scores are improving.
</P>
<P>
   And the president, fresh from his embarrassing revelation of his
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky, couldn't hope for a much more
sympathetic audience. In interview after interview Tuesday, the
people of Worcester strongly, sometimes adamantly, declared their
support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``His business is his business,'' Jack Danzilio, a regular
History Channel watcher who cooks at the Boulevard Diner, said
Tuesday of the Lewinsky affair. ``I like everything about him. I
like his personality. I like his policies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nobody's business,'' the diner owner, Debbie Griffin,
interjected, from behind the kitchen counter.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine excitement seemed to greet news of the president's
visit. No one interviewed _ not even the mayor _ could remember the
last time a sitting US president stopped by this city of 170,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever he goes, I'll be there,'' said Brenda Bombard, a
waitress at Porto Bello restaurant, who has a daughter, Ari, in
first grade. ``I'll keep Ari home from school for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll put us on the map,'' Danzilio said.
</P>
<P>
   As they and others eagerly point out, Worcester does have much
to be proud of. It is the economic engine of central Massachusetts
_ a center for biotechnology, health services and higher education.
It is home to the second-largest art museum in New England and the
New England Science Center. Two major building projects are under
way downtown: the $300 million Worcester Medical Center and the $40
million restoration of the historic Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the city has improved its schools, said Roberta
Schaefer, a Worcester resident who is also director of the
Worcester Municipal Research Bureau as well as a member of the
state education board.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, educators often cite Worcester as one of the success
stories of the state's education reform efforts. The city has
invested its share of the billions of dollars in new money
available under the Education Reform Act of 1993 into teacher
hiring, salary increases and new programs to promote professional
development, a new Worcester Municipal Research Bureau report due
out Friday says.
</P>
<P>
   Student test results have improved markedly, particularly in the
younger grades, the report says. Test scores have risen in all
subject areas for fourth graders and eighth graders since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significant, though, has been the fall in the
dropout rate: from 14 percent to 6.8 percent, the report says. An
innovative program has empowered police officers to nab students
found outside school and bring them back.
</P>
<P>
   These students are then put into a three-day program that
involves bringing them and their parents together with teachers,
counselors, social service agencies, police _ in an effort to
develop a plan to support the young person's attendence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we can show the president and the world is that we've
succeeded in our schools,'' Mariano says. ``We're looking forward
to telling our story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
