<HEADER>
A1882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-BEATING-COX     08-25 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-BEATING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DA upset that assailant avoided jail after beating coach
 &HT;    By Celia Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ DeKalb County District Attorney J. Tom Morgan said
Tuesday he is outraged that a judge declined to send a Dunwoody,
Ga. man to jail for beating his son's baseball coach with a metal
bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this case had occurred in almost any other county, there
would have been jail time,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Clarence Seeliger on Monday sentenced
defendant Joel Eisenberg to five years' probation for the attack on
Dr. Harvey Steinberg, a radiologist. It occurred May 20, 1997, at
Zaban Park, an Atlanta Jewish Community Center facility in
Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   A youth coach himself, Morgan said he attended a sports event
Monday where parents and children were discussing the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said this is totally unacceptable behavior. . . .
Probation is nothing. It's (just saying) don't go do it again,''
said Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Seeliger allowed Eisenberg to enter an ``Alford'' plea, a legal
mechanism that allows defendants to plead guilty it they think it
is in their best interest, even if they believe they are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Seeliger said he was concerned that Eisenberg's insurance would
not pay for the victim's medical expenses if Eisenberg entered a
straight guilty plea _ an admission that he intentionally harmed
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Anne Long asked Seeliger Monday to
sentence Eisenberg, who was charged with aggravated battery and
aggravated assault, to a year in jail and nine years probation. But
the judge said he did not believe the case warranted jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, who may suffer permanent nerve damage to his left arm
from the attack, is suing Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, on leave from work, regularly exercises the arm and
is still on medication. He hopes to return to radiology soon.
``It's been an unbelievable ordeal for me and my family,''
Steinberg said. ``I can't physically interact with the children the
way I want to because of the medicine I have to be on. What I wish
is to turn the clock back and never have been on the field that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack occurred after Eisenberg's son missed a fly ball, and
Steinberg, an assistant coach, made a comment on the error, said
Eisenberg's attorney, Cal Leipold. Eisenberg nudged Steinberg in
the back with a bat to let him know he heard the comment, Leipold
said. Steinberg said he then dropped his baseball glove, but some
witnesses said he threw it at Eisenberg's face, attorneys for both
sides said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
