<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE26-COX     08-25 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evacuations begin as Bonnie moves towards coast
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC BEACH, N.C._More than half a million people were
evacuated Tuesday from the coast of North and South Carolina as
beach communities braced for today's landfall of Hurricane Bonnie,
an erratic, sprawling storm that accelerated and wobbled toward
North Carolina's Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Gale-force winds hit Tuesday night, a preview of the estimated
top winds of 115 mph winds that will sweep ashore today in the
Atlantic season's first hurricane. Tourists cut short vacations,
while residents flocked to emergency shelters set up in schools.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt had a succinct warning for coastal
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out of there,'' he said. ``It's not the time to be
frolicking on the beach and tempting fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted that the storm's eye would hit land at
Carteret County, a peninsula just west of the Cape Lookout
lighthouse. One predicted track put popular family beaches and the
state port at Morehead City in the path of damaging Category 3
tidal surges and winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in for a blow,'' said Robert Miller, 47, owner of Beach
Hardware at Atlantic Beach, a narrow spit at the southern tip of
the fragile, heavily developed Outer Banks. ``If the brunt of the
storm hits at high tide, it is going to be pretty rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie was packing winds equal to those of Hurricane Fran, which
did extensive damage along the North Carolina coast in September of
1996. Riding behind Bonnie out in the Atlantic near the Virgin
Islands was Hurricane Danielle, with winds of 80 mph expected to
increase in the next several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case Bonnie decided to take a sudden sharp turn west off
its northwest path, South Carolina officials ordered the evacuation
of about 200,000 people in Georgetown and Horry counties, and
closed the Port of Georgetown to ships.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, where some 330,000 coastal residents were
evacuated and shelters were set up in 13 counties, Carteret County
officials said they were concerned about permanent residents who
had decided not to go to shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the tourists are gone, but permanent residents rarely
evacuate,'' said Mike Addertion, the county's emergency management
coordinator. ``A lot of people live on the water and in pine
forests. They could have a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   In Raleigh, the General Assembly recessed early to allow
lawmakers to head home to prepare for the storm, and the governor
declared a state of emergency and put 800 National Guardsmen on
alert.
</P>
<P>
   Along the coast, residents and business owners dragged out
plywood from past storms and nailed it over windows and doors. At
Ace Sound Hardware on Emerald Isle, owners posted a sign reading,
``My Bonnie lies over the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic backed up for miles as vacationers fled inland. On
Emerald Isle, Harry and Betty Rouse joined the caravan of
recreational vehicles and boats backed up on N.C. 58 waiting to
cross a two-lane bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The couple secured their 33-foot trailer home at Emerald Isle's
Beachfront RV Park, and then headed home to Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do all we can do, but I figure if the Lord wants it to
hit, it will hit,'' Betty Rouse said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Indian Beach Pier, owner Lib Heverly stretched duct tape
over windows of the office overlooking the nearly deserted
campground. She recalled that, two years ago, hurricanes Bertha and
Fran damaged the end of the pier, as well as flooded streets and
caused widespread damages to beach property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just getting back from Bertha and Fran,'' said Heverly,
61. ``We are just crossing our fingers on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertha barreled up the Cape Fear River at Wilmington on July 12,
1996. Fran, North Carolina's most costly natural disaster, followed
on Sept. 5 and caused an estimated $6 billion in damages and 22
deaths as it cut a swatch as far inland as Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency preparedness officials said beach residents and
vacationeers heeded evacuation orders, despite the uncertainty
Tuesday over Bonnie's exact landfall. Officials warned that the
Category 3 storm could cause severe coastal flooding and
destruction of homes and buildings, as Fran did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are taking this one seriously,'' said John
Smith, a Red Cross supervisor in Beaufort, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   On the two westbound lanes of U.S. 70, heading away from
Atlantic Beach, Morehead City, Emerald Isle and other spots near
the southern tip of the Outer Banks, loaded vehicles streamed away
Tuesday afternoon from a projected point of landfall.
</P>
<P>
   In the hustle, some people towed fishing boats and other
watercraft with names like Reel Pleasure, Big Duck and Out of
Control. Plywood covered the plate glass windows at the Winn Dixie
in Morehead City. Spray-painted in red was a reminder to customers:
Open. Open.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fuel Market in Riverdale, 30 miles northwest of the
beach, gas truck drivers Gray Pridgin and Harold Hacker topped off
the station's four 12,000-gallon, above-ground gas storage tanks to
help them stay put during the hurricane-force winds expected this
morning. At other locations, they topped off underground tanks.
</P>
<P>
   A deluge might spell trouble, said Hacker, which is why he made
his regular 90-minute fuel run to suppliers in Raleigh Tuesday.
``If the tanks run out of gas, they'll bust up through the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Cars packed around the Fuel Market's four pumps six-to-10 at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hardly see that all day long,'' Pridgin said.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Terry was one of the customers, filling up her aqua blue
Dodge Caravan. She planned to ride out the storm with her family of
six in Havelock, 15 miles inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to get some water and ice,'' said Terry, who
has boarded up her house. ``If I'm going to stay, I'm going to be
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
