</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARPOOL-SCOFFLAWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Column: Smile drivers, you could be on HOV camera
 &HT;    By Joey Ledford
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A high-tech version of ``Candid Camera'' might someday
be the answer for more effective policing of Atlanta's HOV lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by virtual waves of single-occupancy HOV violators,
the Georgia Department of Transportation and the Federal Highway
Administration asked Georgia Tech scientists to focus on the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gimmestad, principal research scientist for Tech's
Electro-Optics, Environment and Materials Laboratory, has devised a
way to identify the number of motorists in a vehicle without having
to rely on the vision of an enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   Officers often err, as I can personally attest. Last spring, I
was pulled over by a DOT enforcement officer who failed to spot my
10-year-old passenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only practical way was to get a picture of the people in
each vehicle,'' Gimmestad told Georgia transportation engineers at
a seminar last month. Standard still and video photography proved
impractical because of illumination problems. In addition, many
vehicles have tinted windows the naked eye or traditional cameras
can't penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   So Gimmestad devised an infrared strobe light, mounted on a
tripod by the roadside, to illuminate the interior of each passing
vehicle with a lightning-quick, invisible flash of infrared light.
</P>
<P>
   The infrared light even allows the camera to look through those
dark-tinted windows. ``We were sure happy to see that,'' said
Gimmestad.
</P>
<P>
   Gimmestad and his camera crew set up recently on an overpass,
focused on a single travel lane, and took some pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The detail was quite remarkable. One female driver photographed
was caught in the act of putting on her makeup.
</P>
<P>
   The device was able to take up to two pictures per second of
vehicles traveling up to 80 mph and store them on a computer hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the picture did not appear to be clear, the data ``could
be enhanced'' by the computer to determine the number of
passengers, even infants in back-seat child safety seats and
passengers in the back seats of full-sized vans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed this can be done,'' said Gimmestad. ``You can see
seat belts or lack of seat belts. You can see people talking on
cell phones as they drive.''
</P>
<P>
   When one considers that Gimmestad's cameras can be linked to
separate gear to record license plates, the possibility exists they
could be used to police HOV lanes if the Legislature made it legal.
HOV violators might one day receive citations in the mail, along
with a snapshot of the violation.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect it anytime soon, however. ``I don't think we could
put (together) a prototype that will work on the freeway for
several years,'' said Marion Waters, DOT's state traffic operations
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the device enhances what can be seen with the naked eye,
there is the real possibility of privacy law concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be very careful with the whole process,'' said
Gimmestad. ``You keep the traveling public aware of what you are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters rejects the argument that such a camera could be seen as
a prying Big Brother sticking his nose into your personal vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are breaking a law on a public road, I don't think
you'd have the same rights,'' he said. ``If you are smooching with
your girlfriend in the grocery store, everyone in that grocery
store has the right to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Ledford writes the ``Lane Ranger'' traffic column for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
