<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-BONNIE-ART-     08-25 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BONNIE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTER BANKS RESIDENTS EVACUATE AHEAD OF BONNIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Va., Md.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANTEO, N.C. _ The Outer Banks of North Carolina, an
elbow-shaped strand of barrier islands that have been battered time
and again by surging swells and withering gales, prepared Tuesday
for its latest assault from the sea as hundreds of thousands of
residents and tourists evacuated ahead of the anticipated landing
of Hurricane Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m., officials with the National Hurricane Center in Miami
predicted that the center of the category 3 storm, with sustained
winds of 115 mph, would come ashore by midday Wednesday. Using
satellite imaging and computer models, the center forecast that the
eye of the storm was most likely to strike between Wilmington,
N.C., and the southern end of the Outer Banks, near Cape Lookout
National Seashore. Hurricane warnings were in effect from Cape
Romain, S.C., to Chincoteague, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lepore, a public affairs officer for the hurricane center,
said that the most intimidating feature of the hurricane was its
breadth, with hurricane force winds extending 145 miles from the
eye and tropical storm force winds stretching across about 520
miles. ``It's about four or five times larger than Andrew in area
of extent,'' Lepore said, referring to the 1992 hurricane that
devastated south Florida with winds that reached 145 mph.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of sluggish movement in the waters north of
the Bahamas, Bonnie's momentum more than tripled as it approached
the southeastern coast. The hurricane was moving at 16 mph Tuesday
afternoon, compared with 5 mph on Monday. The hurricane center
warned that storm surges could reach 11 feet above normal tide
levels and that expected rainfall of 5 to 10 inches could cause
heavy flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The governors of both North Carolina and South Carolina declared
mandatory evacuations from coastal counties Tuesday, affecting
about 310,000 people in North Carolina and about 220,000 in South
Carolina. Motorists leaving those areas, many in cars with
surfboards and fishing rods strapped to their roofs, faced creeping
bumper-to-bumper rides for dozens of miles. Shelters opened in some
counties well before the storm approached.
</P>
<P>
   Both governors dusted off their best doomsday rhetoric to try to
persuade coastal residents and visitors to seek safer ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really could be killed,'' said Gov. Jim Hunt of North
Carolina. ``This is not a time to be frolicking on the beach and
tempting fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. David Beasley of South Carolina acknowledged that officials
could not force residents from their homes. But, he said, ``anybody
who does not abide by the mandatory evacuation, our law enforcement
has been instructed to ask them their next of kin.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials said that most residents and
visitors seemed to be heeding the call, influenced perhaps by fresh
memories of the two hurricanes, Fran and Bertha, that blasted the
Wilmington area in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are paying attention,'' said Dorothy Holt, a
spokeswoman for the emergency management office in Dare County,
N.C., which includes most of the Outer Banks. ``In fact, I've heard
quite a bit from folks who in the past may not have evacuated but
who say they are going this time.''
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon on a day of sunny skies and eerily placid seas, the
beaches along the Outer Banks were virtually deserted and
storekeepers were busy nailing sheets of plywood over their
windows. Workers at Seabreeze Florist in Kitty Hawk, just north of
here, adorned their plywood with a lyrical message: ``My Bonnie
lies over the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Red and black hurricane warning flags flew in front of fire
stations and real estate offices. Radio broadcasts buzzed with
announcements of school closings and postponements of PTA meetings
and Lion's Club bingo games. Deejays repeatedly offered
pre-hurricane advice from the Federal Emergency Management Agency:
Cut down dead limbs, drain half of the water from swimming pools,
leave toilet seats up so that pets left in houses will have water
to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Harrison, a 41-year-old tourist from Walkersville, Md.,
who had to cut short her vacation in Nags Head, N.C., near here,
could not hide her disappointment while packing beach chairs and
unopened cases of beer into her truck. ''It's just awful,'' she
said. ``We just got here Sunday. We were crushed when we heard.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, some leathery residents vowed to ride out the storm
despite warnings from authorities. ``I've been through too many of
these to be nervous,'' said David Bragg, a sport-fishing boat
captain who lives in south Nags Head. ``We're having a poker game
tonight. I'm going to try to win some money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the military was taking the approaching storm quite
seriously. About 60 Navy ships at Norfolk, Va., were instructed to
leave port and ride out the storm some 300 miles at sea. And at
Pope Air Force Base, N.C., ``every plane that is flyable is
leaving,'' said Lt. Tisha McGarry, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilmington, residents could not help but remember the vicious
one-two punch delivered by Bertha and Fran two years ago. Michael
Queen, pastor at First Baptist Church there, said contractors are
still replacing the historic steeple that crumbled in the storm.
``We put up a 40-foot section last Thursday and we've got another
60 feet to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in Buxton, N.C., residents worried about the potential for
damage to the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse, which the National Park
Service has proposed moving inland because of the threat from
encroaching seas. ``The lighthouse itself has withstood the type of
winds we're going to experience,'' said Bob Woody, a park service
spokesman. ``The difference will come with the erosional impact,
and that will depend on what quadrant of the storm it's in.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther out in the Atlantic, meanwhile, Hurricane Danielle moved
toward the U.S. Virgin Islands with 80 mph winds, and forecasters
predicted it could be as strong as Bonnie within days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
