<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARSH-SEDGWICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARSH &AMP; MCLENNAN TO BUY SEDGWICK GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fortifying its position as the world's largest
insurance broker, Marsh &AMP; McLennan Cos. of New York said Tuesday
that it had agreed to buy the London-based Sedgwick Group, the
largest independent broker in Europe, for $2.05 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal increases Marsh &AMP; McLennan's business with the largest
corporations in Europe and with midsized companies in the United
States, the two main areas that Sedgwick had developed. And while
Marsh &AMP; McLennan has a commanding presence in financial services,
Sedgwick brings the combined company expertise in marine and energy
coverage, from oil-drilling rigs to the suppliers of drilling
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest things we get in this are operations in places
where we were not operating, or not operating as well, and a
greater accumulation of professional expertise,'' said A.J.C.
Smith, Marsh &AMP; McLennan's chief executive. In Asia alone, he said,
``this doubles our scale.''
</P>
<P>
   To acquire the British company, Marsh &AMP; McLennan agreed to pay
2.25 pounds a share, or about $3.60 _ 58 percent more than
Sedgwick's closing price on the London Stock Exchange on Monday.
The price _ a total of 1.25 billion pounds, or $2.05 billion, works
out to about 15 times earnings under generally accepted accounting
principles in the United States at a time when other insurance
brokers have been trading at 10 or 11 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was the latest in a struggle for dominance in the
worldwide brokerage business between Marsh and its chief rival, Aon
Corp. of Chicago. And analysts said they thought Marsh had agreed
to pay such a premium partly to keep Sedgwick out of the hands of
Aon. Otherwise, said Ira Zuckerman, vice president for research at
Nutmeg Securities in Westport, Conn., ``they wouldn't have made as
high a bid as they did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling,'' Zuckerman added, ``is that it was sort of
pre-emptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Steel, a spokeswoman for Aon in Chicago, declined to
comment on whether Aon had been interested in buying Sedgwick. Nor
would she comment on analysts' speculation that Aon might submit a
higher bid for Sedgwick.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also suggested that, alternatively, Aon might
consider offering a higher bid for Willis Corroon Group, another
big London brokerage that an investor group led by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &AMP; Co., the New York buyout firm, said last month it had
agreed to buy for $1.4 billion. Steel would not comment on that
prospect either.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick and Willis Corroon were the last of the big competitors
of Marsh and Aon, leaving a handful of smaller insurance brokers
that analysts said were likely to be bought in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The American depository receipts of Sedgwick _ each representing
five shares _ rose $5.125, to $17.375, on the New York Stock
Exchange. Marsh &AMP; McLennan's shares fell $1.125, to $55.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh had a little more than $6 billion in revenue last year
compared with $5.7 billion for Aon. The combined revenue of Marsh
and Sedgwick at the end of last year would have been $7.6 billion,
putting the new company far ahead of Aon.
</P>
<P>
   Aon moved ahead of Marsh, the longtime leader in the business,
in January 1997 with the purchase of Alexander &AMP; Alexander Services
for $1.23 billion. But then Marsh reclaimed the No. 1 spot two
months later by taking over Johnson &AMP; Higgins for $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In growing ever bigger, the companies hope to gain economies of
scale, and to increase their market share and the range of
expertise they can offer customers. With more influence, they also
hope to be able to negotiate better prices for their corporate
clients with the world's insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Buckley, a senior vice president and analyst at Duff &AMP;
Phelps Credit Rating Company in Chicago, said corporate customers
could benefit from lower prices from Marsh if it succeeded in
cutting costs through the merger. ``But the downside is that
competition between the brokers will have lessened,'' he said.
``Corporate customers will be forced to deal with fewer, more
powerful brokers, which may not always have their best interests at
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, Marsh's chief executive, said he was ``comfortable that
the price'' his company was paying ``was a good one.'' Some
savings, he said, would come in trimming the combined work force of
52,000. But he said more of the reduction was expected through
retirements and turnover than through layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sedgwick deal coming so soon after the acquisition of
Johnson &AMP; Higgins, Cathy Seifert, an S&AMP;P Equity Group analyst, said
this raised questions about how smoothly Marsh would be able to
combine the two companies. ``If it is very disruptive,'' she said,
``that could be a positive for Aon.''
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to solidify the deal, Marsh's bankers obtained a
commitment from the holders of more than 40 percent of Sedgwick's
stock that they would accept the offer. There is a caveat, however.
If another bidder offers 10 percent more, the deal can be
reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he expected a counterbid from Aon, Smith said: ``I
would hesitate to be involved in a bid for a professional
management staff where the staff were committed to somebody
else.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
