<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY TEAM ROLLS ON, 5-3, OVER NORTH CAROLINA SQUAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: BBO-TOMS-RIVER) 
(JT) 
 By ED GUZMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ The Toms River second baseman Joey
Franceschini fielded a ground ball and stepped on the bag to record
the final out of a 5-3 victory over Greenville, N.C., Tuesday
afternoon and the celebrating erupted on the field and in the
stands. The New Jersey team had just added to its improbable run
through the Little League World Series by winning its third game in
as many days and assuring itself of a spot in the semifinals on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But shortstop Todd Frazier, who hit a two-run home run and
scored three times, was busy looking for his family in the stands.
The 12-year old Frazier, who just 18 hours before had pitched a
complete-game victory and as the leadoff hitter has been setting
the tone for the Toms River attack, just wanted to see the sheer
joy on the faces of his family.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty to see, as 14 cousins, according to his father
Charlie's count, were there along with his parents and two
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he misses us a lot,'' said Todd's older brother, Jeff,
who was on the 1995 Toms River team that made it to Williamsport.
``I mean, he hasn't really seen us in three weeks. I just miss
fooling around with him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Todd Frazier does miss his family, he is having too much fun
to really let on. In the post-game news conference, he was
displaying a sparkling smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' Frazier said of winning Tuesday's game. ``I
didn't think we'd go 3-0. I've had fun down here and it's a great
feeling to be in Williamsport.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he was going to tell Jeff about his experience,
he smiled and said: ``Now I can tell him that I hit two home runs
and he only hit one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff's team went 1-2 at Williamsport.
</P>
<P>
   As the Toms River Little League team marched toward Howard J.
Lamade Stadium before Tuesday's game, the players began to chant:
``Who let the dogs out? Who? Who?''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Tuesday afternoon's game, Greenville was wondering
the same thing about these 12-year-olds who refer to themselves as
Beasts from the East. They had won the longest game in Little
League World Series history Sunday night _ 11 innings _ and on
Monday had beaten a team that was 17-0 in West regional play,
topping Cypress, Calif., by 4-2. Toms River was ready to wrap up a
spot in the next round, and have some fun in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, Mike Gaynor, sent his son, Casey, to the mound to
face a tough Greenville lineup that impressed the manager in
Monday's batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a scary bunch of dudes,'' said Gaynor of Greenville's
hitters. He said he told Casey ``to go out there and do his
thing.'' It was his show now.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Gaynor was more than up to the task, going all six innings
and allowing only five hits and three earned runs. In the third
inning, Gaynor served up a slow curve that shortstop Justin Hardee,
a left-handed-batter, pulled down the right field line for a
two-run home run that put Greenville up, 2-1. After that, Gaynor
retired eight batters in a row before allowing one run in the final
inning.
</P>
<P>
   With Gaynor, whose older brother Colin also hit a home run for
that 1995 team, keeping it close, it gave Frazier the chance to be
a hero in the top of the fourth inning. Frazier had scored the
game's opening run in the first inning and came up to the plate
with a runner on first and one out. A right-handed batter, Frazier
drove a fastball on the outside corner over the right-center field
fence to put Toms River up, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   It had looked as if Toms River had added a run three batters
later on a sacrifice fly by Franceschini that scored first baseman
Scott Fisher. But the third-base umpire, James Tuck, called Fisher
out for leaving the base too soon when Greenville appealed the
play, keeping it as a one-run game. It ended up not mattering as
Toms River added two more runs in the sixth inning on a pair of
wild pitches that scored Frazier and Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River will wait to see whom it will face in Thursday
night's game, which will be for the United States championship and
a berth in the Series final.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Cypress (0-1) will play Jenison, Mich. (0-2). On
Wednesday night, Cypress will face Greenville (1-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to sit back and enjoy every bit of it,'' Mike
Gaynor said of the Little League World Series experience.
</P>
<P>
   For Frazier and his teammates, that means Ping-Pong games and
relaxing by the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the king of Ping-Pong,'' Frazier said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
