<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM-BOMBING-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA TO RESPOND TO PROPOSAL FOR PAN AM BOMBING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With prominent international allies pressing Libya
to accept an offer to allow two Libyans to go on trial in the
Netherlands for the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet, the Libyan
government said Tuesday that it would announce Wednesday whether it
would agree to the U.S. and British proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Arab League and South African President Nelson Mandela,
a leading international defender of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi,
suggested that Libya would accept the plan. Under the proposal, the
two Libyans, identified by U.S. officials as intelligence agents,
would be extradited to The Hague and tried by three Scottish judges
under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American-British proposal is compatible with the previous
Arab suggestions, which Libya has accepted,'' Arab League Secretary
General Esmat Abdel Meguid said after a meeting in Cairo with the
British ambassador to Egypt, Sir David Blatherwick. ``We have been
seeking this solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said he was confident that the plan ``should lead to the
resolution of this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gadhafi gave no indication of what his decision would be,
and senior Clinton administration officials would not hazard a
guess about the thinking of the notoriously unpredictable Libyan
leader. Still, the U.S. officials said they were pleased with the
statements from the Arab League and Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyan government news agency, Jana, reported Tuesday that
Libya's Foreign and Justice Ministries were closely studying the
proposal and that a decision whether to accept it was expected
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A Libyan lawyer for the two suspects was quoted Tuesday as
saying that his clients would voluntarily surrender to a special
court in the Netherlands ``if the conditions for a fair trial are
provided to protect their rights pending, during and after the
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   An agreement by Libya to allow the suspects to be tried in The
Hague, the Dutch city that is the headquarters for the
International Court of Justice, would be a milestone in the
decade-old search for justice by the families of the 270 people
killed in the explosion of the Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland,
in December 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain, which had once demanded that the
Libyans be tried in the U.s. or British court systems, announced
Monday that they would agree to holding the suspects' trial in the
Netherlands instead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The proposal effectively called Gadhafi's bluff, since his
government had suggested just such a plan. Libya had insisted that
the suspects, identified by the Justice Department as Abdel Basset
al-Megrahi and Lamin Khalifa Fhimah, could not receive a fair trial
in the United States or Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have vowed to seek to extend
sanctions on Libya. to include an oil embargo, if Libya turns down
the deal. If Gadhafi accepts, however, the existing sanctions on
Libya would be eased. The United States and Britain introduced a
resolution in the United Nations on Tuesday that would provide for
the suspension of the sanctions if the two suspects are handed
over.
</P>
<P>
   Although the end of the sanctions would be welcomed by Libya, a
trial of the two men risks exposure of evidence that could tie
senior officials in the Libyan government _ possibly including
Gadhafi himself _ to the decision to bomb the Pan Am jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he accepts, we'll be delighted, and we'll hold this trial
just as soon as we can,'' said a senior Clinton administration
official, speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``But I still
find it hard to believe that he'll allow this trial ever to take
place. You may see Gadhafi accept this offer initially and then try
to quibble over the details. I hope I'm wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investigators have suggested that the Pan Am jet was
destroyed in retaliation for the U.S. bombing of the Libyan
capital, Tripoli, in 1986. President Ronald Reagan ordered the
bombing of Tripoli in response to evidence linking Libyan
intelligence to a terrorist attack on a Berlin disco in April 1986
in which a U.S soldier was killed.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing an indictment of the two Libyans in 1991 for the
Pan Am bombing, Justice Department officials said that they had
tracked a part of the bomb's timing device to a Swiss company that
had sold it to a senior Libyan intelligence officer.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said that Fhimah held a cover job as a station
manager for Libyan Arab Airlines in Malta. He is alleged to have
placed the bomb in a suitcase there that was routed to Frankfurt,
where it was transferred to the Pan Am jet. Megrahi, the indictment
said, purchased clothing and an umbrella in a store in Malta that
were put into the luggage to hide the bomb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2052EDT &QL; 
