<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-JUPPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PREMIER OF FRANCE INVESTIGATED ON FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Former Prime Minister Alain Juppe was placed under
investigation Tuesday in the latest French political party
financing scandal.
</P>
<P>
   It involves the inquiry into allegedly phony payrolls at Paris
City Hall while he was at the right hand of the mayor, Jacques
Chirac, who is now France's President.
</P>
<P>
   Justice officials cited Tuesday by Le Monde said an
investigating magistrate, Patrick Desmure, was looking into charges
from a former city official that about 200 people on the municipal
payroll in the 1980s did not work for the city at all but, in
reality, for Chirac's party, the conservative Rally for the
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Desmure, the newspaper said, had sent Juppe a letter informing
him that he was under investigation for charges including misuse of
public funds and abuse of public trust. He could be cleared of the
charges by the investigation or formally accused and tried.
</P>
<P>
   Juppe, interviewed on television tonight, said he had not done
anything that was illegal at the time, and denied that there had
been any swindle or that he had been taking public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived on the scene, in 1988, there was no law
regulating political parties,'' he said, referring to the absence
of effective legislation before then on how parties could finance
themselves. He added that ``the legislature stepped in after 1988''
and that by the time he left the party presidency, ``everything was
legal.''
</P>
<P>
   Michel Roussin, Chirac's chief of staff when he was mayor, was
also notified Tuesday that he was under investigation on some of
the same charges as Juppe.
</P>
<P>
   Juppe, secretary general of the party from 1988 until 1994 and
its president from 1994 to 1997, was finance director of the City
of Paris from 1988 until he became Foreign Minister in 1993. Chirac
resigned as mayor in 1995 when he won the presidency and made Juppe
prime minister, a post Juppe held until the conservatives lost an
election last year. He is now mayor of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Socialists, conservative parties have come under
investigation in recent years for fund-raising practices that used
to be commonly accepted in France _ shakedowns, kickbacks and
padding the payrolls with no-shows in municipalities they
controlled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
