<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TOMS-RIVER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN N.J. TOWN WHERE BASEBALL IS KING, LITTLE LEAGUERS BATTLE FOR
CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. _ Perhaps it is the duty of a town's top leader
to be wise and calm amid pandemonium. And that's the role Mayor
Jerry Geoghegan was playing Tuesday afternoon at Mugsy's Bar and
Grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where your heart has to go out to the losers,''
Geoghegan said after Todd Frazier, Toms River's powerhouse
shortstop, blasted a two-run homer to give the team a 3-2 lead in
the Little League World Series in Williamsport, Pa. ``They are
trying as hard as Toms River is. It's just not happening for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the fans packed into Mugsy's, the mayor was in a
minority of one as the 12-year-old boys of Toms River East American
All-Stars went on to win, 5-3, picking up their third World Series
victory in as many days and clinching a spot in the U.S.
championship game on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing,'' said Frank Rosner, who is on the board of
directors of the Toms River East Little League and arrived at
Mugsy's to watch the last two innings. All around him, ecstatic
fans were hugging, clapping each other on the back and slapping
high-fives. ``This is a once in a lifetime opportunity for these
kids,'' Rosner said. ``And they are playing it to the hilt.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in four years that Toms River, the
working-class seat of Ocean County, has sent a team to Little
League's field of dreams in Williamsport. But by beating a squad
from Greenville, N.C., on Tuesday, and securing a spot in the
tournament's final four, Toms River has surpassed the fortunes of
its 1995 predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   While the source of the team's strength continues to be the
subject of much debate, one thing is certain: In Toms River, Little
League is an extraordinarily big deal. There are two leagues, Toms
River, which has about 600 players, and Toms River East, which has
1,200 players.
</P>
<P>
   In Toms River East, enrolling in a season of Little League costs
$80, not counting the purchase of a baseball mitt. (The league
provides bats, balls, helmets and uniforms.) In addition , the
league conducts private fund-raising efforts, like candy sales, and
solicits corporate sponsorships in order to meet operating expenses
of about $200,000 a year. There are seven ball fields in Toms River
East, one of which is equipped with lights for night games.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a huge commitment of time and energy from parents
who coach. The Toms River East All-Stars began practicing daily in
early July and have been on the road playing games throughout the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   And the league has just finished an indoor facility that will
allow batting and pitching practice to continue through the winter.
``It will help us to compete against Florida and California where
they are outdoors all year round,'' said Kevin Fox, a United
Airlines pilot, who is also on the league's board of directors.
``We have tryouts in the snow.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is hardly surprising that World Series mania has taken
hold in Toms River. On the streets and in local stores, signs and
banners urge the team on. Tuesday morning, two charter buses set
out to get fans to Pennsylvania in time for the first pitch and
even more people are expected to make the trip, either by bus or in
car pools, for Thursday's game. On Saturday, the winner of that
games faces the international champion.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials were planning a welcome home celebration and a
parade, no matter how the team fares. ``I think if you talk to the
average person on the street, everyone is proud as hell of these
kids,'' said Geoghegan. ``These kids are fantastic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They're pretty tough, too. On Sunday night, Toms River outlasted
Jenison, Mich., to win, 13-9, in 11 innings, the longest game in
Little League World Series history. Then on Monday night, Toms
River stunned a previously undefeated team from Cypress, Calif.,
beating them 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Both this year's squad and the 1995 World Series team were
managed by Michael Gaynor, the owner of a local chain of sports
apparel stores. In 1995, Gaynor's older son Colin pitched for the
team and played shortstop. This year, his younger son, Casey,
pitched a complete game Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Colin had been in Williamsport over the weekend, but was forced
to return to Toms River for the start of high school football
practice. Tuesday, he was in the crowd at Mugsy's as his brother
and father battled the North Carolina team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody thinks it's something in the water, but I don't
think so,'' he said. ``Toms River has got great programs and great
facilities down here. It just shows in our teams. They are
powerhouses every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in Mugsy's had other reasons to stay glued to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any kids playing Little League and I am so into
this,'' said Donna Asanza, who has two girls, ages 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my friends kids play in the league, plus my husband is an
orthodontist in town and if you notice,'' she said, gesturing at
the television, ``they all have braces on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
