<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 26
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ATTACK-RDP-NYT (moved on Monday, August 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 24,
about reports that Iraqi scientists had helped produce chemical
nerve gas components at the factory bombed by the United States in
Sudan misstated the title and tenure of Antonio Monteiro of
Portugal as head of the committee that monitors United Nations
sanctions on Iraq. He is chairman for two years, not president for
the month.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SUNBEAM-STRATEGY-NYT (moved on Monday, August 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 24,
about the Sunbeam Corporation's new strategy misstated the number
of regional headquarters under the plan. It will be 9, as well as
the corporate headquarters, not 17.
</P>
<P>
   BC-JAPAN-BANK-NYT (moved on Friday, August 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 21,
about a restructuring planned by Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
referred incorrectly to the indebtedness of three nonbank
affiliates. The three owe a total of 2.84 trillion yen to various
lenders, not to the bank alone.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LAW-PUBLISHER-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, August 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 23,
about Nolo Press, the legal publisher, misidentified one of the
promotional items that carry the company's motto. It is posters,
not toasters.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WILSON-PROFILE-NYT (moved on Friday, August 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 21,
about James Q. Wilson, a political and social scientist whose
writings have contributed to crime prevention, misidentified the
university he attended in California. It is the University of
Redlands, not Redmond.
</P>
