<SLUG> BC-CONGO-VOLUNTEER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KABILA ARRIVES BACK IN CONGO'S CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ As the rebel threat to his government shifted
away from the capital to eastern Congo, President Laurent Kabila
returned here Tuesday after an absence of 10 days and, amid reports
that his allies' jets were bombing the country's third-largest
city, urged ordinary Congolese to take up spears and arrows to
crush the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels said jets belonging to Kabila's two allies, Angola
and Zimbabwe, had bombed Kisangani, injuring civilians. Aides to
Kabila in this city said the planes attacked only rebel soldiers,
who have controlled Kisangani since Sunday. But Western diplomats
and international relief workers with colleagues in Kisangani said
there was no sign of bombing in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday began with Kabila's plane touching down at the Kinshasa
airport. Before Angola and Zimbabwe sent troops and arms to help
Kabila in the region southwest of here, a rebel takeover of the
capital had appeared imminent and Kabila had directed the war from
the southern city of Lubumbashi in his home region.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday morning, state television captured his arrival here.
It showed Kabila, wearing a black cowboy hat and a Hawaiian-style
shirt, as he walked from the plane and shook the hands of his
generals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victory belongs to the Congolese people,'' Kabila said before
television cameras. As he urged the citizenry to use traditional
arms to fight, he added, ``The people must be completely mobilized
and armed to crush the aggressors.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the rebel-controlled eastern Congo, Bizima Karaha,
a rebel leader and Kabila's former minister for foreign affairs,
said Angolan and Zimbabwean jets had bombed Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   ``No military objectives were hit, only civilian targets,''
Karaha said, The Associated Press reported. ``They cannot recapture
Kisangani, only bomb it from the air. This is terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Sakombi Inongo, a senior communications adviser to
Kabila, said no civilians had been hurt. ``There has been intense
bombing at Kisangani since this morning by planes from Angola and
Zimbabwe,'' Sakombi said. ``They are targeting the rebels' men and
arms.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-week civil war began after Kabila cut his ties with
the ethnic Tutsi Congolese and the Rwandan Tutsi, who plucked him
from obscurity less than two years ago and made him the Congolese
face of a successful coup against Mobutu Sese Seko, the longtime
dictator of Congo when it was called Zaire. Kabila's closeness to
the Tutsi had made him unpopular among other Congolese, who regard
the Tutsi as outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's aides, as well as most Western officials here, say that
Rwanda and Uganda, its close ally, are supporting the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the troops, planes and tanks from Angola and Zimbabwe,
Kabila's forces have almost eliminated the rebel threat southwest
of Kinshasa, government and Western officials said. The only
critical point still held by the rebels in the southwest is the
huge Congo River hydroelectric dam at Inga, whose supply to
Kinshasa and elsewhere the rebels still controlled Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
