<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1921 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWELL-OBIT-HNS &LR;      08-25 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWELL-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SUPREME COURT JUSTICE POWELL DIES AT 90 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Supreme Court Justice Lewis F. Powell Jr.,
whose landmark 1978 decision upholding the legality of
affirmative-action programs in higher education ignited a national
debate that still rages 20 years later, died of pneumonia in his
sleep Tuesday morning. He was 90 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who served on the court from 1972-87, also concurred in
the landmark 5-4 decision upholding the constitutionality of a
Georgia law banning sexual relations between homosexuals. After
retiring from the court, Powell said he ``probably made a mistake''
in that 1986 case.
</P>
<P>
   The justice's conciliatory style helped him forge majorities on
the court and earned him the praise of his peers. When he retired,
his fellow justices wrote in a letter: ``All of us admire your
extraordinary capacity to forcefully participate in our private and
public debates without ever allowing advocacy to degenerate into
contentiousness.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Monday praised Powell's judicial reasoning.
``He approached each case without an ideological agenda, carefully
applying the Constitution, the law and Supreme Court precedent
regardless of his own personal views about the case. His opinions
were a model of balance and judiciousness,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who joined the high court
the same day as Powell in 1972, offered his own tribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the very embodiment of `judicial temperament:'
receptive to the ideas of his colleagues, fair to the parties to
the case, but ultimately relying on his own seasoned judgment,''
Rehnquist said. ``He was also the epitome of a `Virginia gentleman'
in the very best sense of the phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's power of persuasion was perhaps never stronger than in
the Regents of the University of California vs. Bakke case. Writing
the 5-4 decision for a sharply divided court, Powell said that
state universities' ``substantial interest'' in having a diverse
student body permits them to devise admissions programs that
consider the race and ethnicity of an applicant.
</P>
<P>
   However, he also found that the University of California at
Davis illegally discriminated on the basis of race when it rejected
white medical-school applicant Allan Bakke because it had reserved
a number of seats for black candidates. Powell concluded the
university had failed to demonstrate that it was advancing a
substantial state interest by discriminating against Bakke.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, the Bakke decision still resonates in Texas.
The University of Texas, despite a federal appeals court decision
to the contrary, continues to maintain that its now-suspended
program to increase the number of minority students is
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Powell's controversial opinions was his concurrence
that the constitutional right to privacy does not include intimate
homosexual activity. ``I cannot say that conduct condemned for
hundreds of years has now become a fundamental right,'' Powell
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One week after deciding that Georgia case, the high court let
stand without comment a federal appeals court ruling upholding the
constitutionality of Texas' 1887 law banning homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University law Professor Laurence Tribe, who argued
against Georgia's anti-sodomy law before the justices, remembered
fondly an exchange he had with Powell during the oral arguments.
Tribe said his strategy was to avoid the controversial issue of
intercourse during the argument, opting instead to challenge the
statute as a violation of the constitutional right to privacy in
one's home.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, although eventually rejecting Tribe's position, leaned
forward and said, ```If I were you I would be arguing the case
exactly the way you are,''' the professor recalled. ``His demeanor
was always one of unusual civility.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell was a highly successful private attorney in Richmond,
Va., and a former president of the American Bar Association when
President Nixon tapped him for the high court in 1971 to succeed
Hugo Black, who had retired. At first Powell expressed reluctance,
saying that at age 64 he was too old to begin a new career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go onto the court with deep personal misgivings about
whether I will like it,'' Powell said then.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate confirmed Powell's nomination by a vote of 89-1. He
joined the Supreme Court on Jan. 7, 1972, and retired on June 26,
1987, his initial reluctance a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``My respect for it (the court) as a unique institution has been
enhanced by the privilege of serving here,'' Powell said in
announcing his retirement. ``I will miss being an active justice
more than I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's departure set off a volatile Senate battle over his
successor. The Democrat-controlled Senate rejected President
Reagan's first choice to fill the vacancy, conservative Judge
Robert H. Bork, after contentious Senate Judiciary Committee
hearings. The Senate's 58-42 vote against Bork on Oct. 23, 1987,
remains the largest margin of defeat for a Supreme Court nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's second choice, Judge Douglas H. Ginsburg, withdrew his
name after disclosures that he had smoked marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's third choice, Judge Anthony M. Kennedy, won Senate
confirmation and joined the court on Feb. 18, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Franklin Powell Jr. was born Sept. 19, 1907, in Suffolk,
Va. He earned his bachelor's and law degrees from Washington and
Lee University in Lexington, Va., and married Josephine Pierce
Rucker of Richmond in 1936. She died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from law school and serving as a military
intelligence officer in World War II, Powell built up a thriving
law practice in Richmond. His career highlights before joining the
high court included a stint as ABA president from 1964 to 1965 and
overseeing the peaceful desegregation of Richmond's schools while
serving as chairman of the school board from 1952 to 1961.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by four children, Josephine Smith of Houston;
Pendleton Bowen of Whidbey Island, Wash.; Molly Sumner of Salt Lake
City; and Lewis F. Powell III of Richmond, as well as nine
grandchildren and a great grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements have not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
