<SLUG> BC-BOEING-BRITISH-AIRWAYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING SAYS POLITICS PLAYED KEY ROLE BRITISH AIRWAYS AIRBUS
PURCHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politics _ and not who offered British Airways the best deal for
new jets _ was the deciding factor in Europe's largest airline
buying planes from Airbus Industrie for the first time, some Boeing
officials are privately suggesting.
</P>
<P>
   But British Airways says it was just a matter of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not about dollars and cents. It was about politics,''
said one person at Boeing familiar with the company's offer that
was on the table for its next generation 737. The airline announced
Tuesday that it will buy 59 single-aisle planes from Airbus, with
options for 129 more.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it plans to stick with Boeing for its
longhaul fleet, and underscored the point by buying 16 Boeing 777
widebody jets while placing options for 16 more.
</P>
<P>
   But several Boeing people close to the neogotiations with
British Airways over the past several months said the appearance of
British Prime Minister Tony Blair at Tuesday's news conference in
Toulouse, the headquarters of Airbus, served to underscore how much
politics played a role in the decision by one of Boeing's most
loyal customers to become the last major European carrier to end
its exclusive ties with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How often does the British prime minister show up at something
like this? Never,'' one of those Boeing people said.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus consortium is made up of aerospace companies from
Britain, France, Spain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   BA chief executive Bob Ayling told reporters Tuesday that
politics did not enter the decision to go with Airbus for the
smaller planes. Airbus simply beat Boeing's price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were significantly cheaper,'' Ayling said after flying in
an Airbus A320 to Toulouse for the announcement. ``The
Airbus-Rolls-Royce offer was a better value offer than the
competitive offer. If it had not been, we would not be here,'' he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought choosing a European supplier would help BA
get European Union approval for its controversial alliance with
American Airlines, Ayling indicated the decision was purely
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will make any difference,'' he said.
``British Airways bought these aircraft because they offered us the
best value.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair said the British government was fully behind the Airbus
consortium and he predicted Airbus would soon match Boeing with 50
percent of the world's commercial aviation market. Boeing now has
slightly more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus officials would not say what kind of discount they gave
British Airways for the 188-plane order. Typically, Boeing and
Airbus give their best customers discounts of as much as 20 percent
below list price. This price war between the world's two remaining
manufacturers of passenger jets with more than 100 seats has
contributed to Boeing's poor financial performance in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say Boeing was smart by not trying to beat the
offer from Airbus if it meant taking a loss on its planes just to
keep market share.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways did say that its net costs for the 75 firm
orders from Boeing and Airbus will be $1.4 billion pounds, compared
with a list price of about $3 billion pounds. But that net figure
includes proceeds that the airline expects to get from selling
older 737s, as well as its plans to replace some 747s now on order
from Boeing with the less expensive 777.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
