<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graffanino defends batting positioning as slump continues
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tony Graffanino's scouting report on Tony Graffanino:
</P>
<P>
   ''The stance is fine. The mechanics are fine. I don't know. Just
not hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the beauties of this stretch of the schedule is that
Graffanino has been granted several chances to get back on the
horse that just threw him. Houston's Mike Hampton was the third
straight left-hander the Braves had faced Tuesday night, giving
Graffanino a third consecutive start to straighten out a month gone
haywire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some days, he looks like Bill Mazeroski out there,'' said
manager Bobby Cox. ''Other days . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino went into Tuesday's game hitting .133 (6-for-45) this
month with a strikeout every 2.6 at-bats. After batting .356 in
July and feeling his season had turned around, he is having the
worst month of his career. His Monday performance 0-for-5, four
strikeouts, an error he said was his worst game as a professional
player.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no idea what to do,'' he said. ''I've tried a bunch of
different things. It's just one of those things you go through. I
just got to keep going out there and playing. Something will
happen, I hope. That's the way it's always worked out in the past.
Something just happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The .220 average he took into Tuesday's game was a five-week
low.
</P>
<P>
   Now in right
</P>
<P>
   Danny Bautista reported to the clubhouse Tuesday worse for wear
after his collision at the plate Monday and was scratched before
the Braves took batting practice. Gerald Williams was moved to left
field to take Bautista's place and Michael Tucker was granted a
rare start against a left-handed pitcher in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Bautista took a full running leap into Los Angeles catcher Tom
Price in a botched safety squeeze Monday and was left with a sore
right knee. Tucker, who was hitting .273 (9-for-33) against
lefties, has actually fared worse against righties (.252,
81-for-321). More precisely, he had been hitting less than walking
lately, with 10 walks in his previous seven games. In his last 20
plate appearances, he reached base 11 times with only four hits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just taking a lot of pitches that I'd usually swing at,''
Tucker said. ''There are only certain times in the game, like when
you lead off an inning, where you can do that. But you get up there
with guys in scoring position, you can't do that when runs are out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   No word
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had still not heard from the National League offices
Tuesday about suspensions and/or fines stemming from last
Saturday's brawl with the Los Angeles Dodgers. First baseman Andres
Galarraga is a candidate for a minimum three-game suspension but
don't expect anything to happen once the NL president Len Coleman
acts. Galarraga will appeal any penalty, which would put him in
line for a hearing when the Braves visit New York in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Dizzy Ryno
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko is trying to shake the effects of an inner ear
infection that has effected his equilibrium. He took batting
practice Tuesday and remains hopeful of playing tonight against
Houston right-hander Sean Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was really hard to keep my balance (Monday),'' he said. ''I
was really dizzy. I'm feeling better. I'll try to get in there
(Wednesday) but we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Condolences
</P>
<P>
   First base coach Pat Corrales left the team Tuesday to attend
the funeral of his brother, who died of congestive heart failure in
Fresno, Calif., over the weekend. Hitting coach Clarence Jones
manned Corrales' spot in the coach's box. Corrales is expected back
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
