<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Houston Astros
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Today 8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: Fox Sports South.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: RHP John Smoltz (12-2, 3.44;
13-12, 3.12 lifetime vs. Astros) vs. RHP Sean Bergman (11-6, 3.44;
1-2, 7.11 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Notes: After opening the season with a career 18-27 record and
a 5.22 ERA, Bergman has had a breakthrough in his fourth full
major-league season, flourishing under manager Larry Dierker.
Stranded in San Diego's bullpen last year, the Astros traded James
Mouton for him during the winter, and after earning a spot in the
rotation in the spring, he has been the team biggest surprise,
posting the lowest ERA by a starter, at least until Randy Johnson
showed up. A sinkerball pitcher, Bergman throws an excellent
slider, and the two pitches are enough to make an average fastball
seem better. The difference this year is probably under his hat,
where he has finally developed some confidence in what scouts have
long believed to be top-notch stuff. He abused the Braves in a May
17 start, in which he allowed three hits and one run while striking
out six and walking none in an 8-1 victory. Andres Galarraga will
be his acid test. The Braves first baseman has a .615 career
average (8-for-13) against Bergman with one homer. This is an
important test for Smoltz, who questioned last week whether he
should skip a start to let his body recover for a string of
12-straight starts since coming off the DL. Smoltz has won seven in
a row since the All-Star break, but he hardly has been untouchable
in his last three outings, giving up 11 runs and 21 hits in his
last 19 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
