<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T EVEN THINK OF TOUCHING DODGER STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The fine people at Fox make entertaining movies,
put together a network in little more than a decade, and bought
enough regional cable sports outlets to leave sweat stains on the
suits at Disney-owned ESPN. They are the quintessential aggressive
entrepreneurs for the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But as owners of our favorite major league baseball team, they
remind me of Abu Nidal.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger fans have never been terrorized like this. In six short
months, Fox has traded the franchise's most popular player,
dispatched a key ambassador from the Pacific Rim, and gutted the
front office and roster. The series of the trades designed to make
something of the lost 1998 season may have a negative impact for
the next five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how we long for the simple days, when diversity and the
temperature of the clubhouse were the Dodgers' biggest concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word that the initial cost projections of renovating
Dodger Stadium, bringing it up to revenue-producing snuff with
newer stadiums, was higher than anticipated, leading Fox to
acknowledge that it might make more sense to build a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Seismically speaking, this is The Big One. Fans and critics are
more likely to draw a line in the red clay of the infield over this
issue than any other.
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely nothing wrong with the 37-year-old Dodger
Stadium, still pristine at middle age as it was the day it opened.
Better even, at least for those who remember the facility lacked
drinking fountains back in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   There is not a single bad seat among the 56,000. The park is
warm. The view to the foothills beyond center field remains the
best in baseball. Engineering-wise, the stadium that was built into
the side of a foothill is still a marvel. It sits atop Los Angeles
like a jewel.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about Dodger Stadium reminds one of our own Coliseum,
which needed renovation in 1978 as much as it does today, or Yankee
Stadium, which is literally crumbling due to age, or Fenway, which
is no longer functional. In Boston, the affection for Fenway is
balanced against the reality that its time has come.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no primary reason for change here from a fan's
point of view. New parks erupted in Baltimore, Cleveland, Texas and
Anaheim because the old parks were out of date. Fans and ownership
in all of those cities were in agreement that a new park made
sense.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, nothing Fox has done as owner has made sense, so
the concept of them paving paradise is just another reason for fans
to be wary.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Graziano, the Dodgers' likable new president, has earned a
degree in crisis management this season, but nothing will test him
like the public relations problem he'll face if he and the Foxies
order heavy machinery.
</P>
<P>
   It is so premature for anyone to speculate on this, Graziano
said Tuesday. Our focus is not on a new stadium. Dodger Stadium is
a great stadium. We just want to make it more competitive with
other, newer stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The objective of any renovation would be to enhance the stadium
and make it competitive with Baltimore, Cleveland, Texas and
Colorado. When you're dealing with an existing facility, you have
to work within its confines, which is a different challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The initial dollar estimates for renovation were higher than we
expected. We needed to step back and make sure whether (projected)
revenue would support a renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano has been with the club since 1986. There was always
idle talk of converting the club level into luxury suites, but
there was never any real financial or architectural study
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're looking at it thoroughly, he said. We brainstormed on
everything we could possible add to the stadium. We looked at new
stadiums and what they offered, and how we could design them into
the park -- not because we would make all these changes, but
because we wanted to know if we could.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't made any decisions to go forward. We're just looking
at everything. It's part of the process, and it's not going to
impact anyone this year or in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Fans could care less about how the Dodgers compete with the
Orioles in luxury suites or the D-Backs in retail outlets.
Attending games at an annual pace of three million a season, Dodger
fans aren't likely to take the bait that the team is losing a lot
of money, either.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are more likely to wonder if this is a dodge to get around
the team's tradition of low ticket prices. Every new stadium built
in the '90s, be it for a baseball, football, basketball or hockey
team, has been accompanied by higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying this is the Dodger plan. But based on their
recent history, let's say it's a concern. Maybe now is the time to
get Dodger Stadium classified as California historical landmark. If
the Dodgers can say adieu to Mike Piazza and friends so easily,
they're not likely to get misty over the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As Mulder might say, Trust No One.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
