<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCENROE (PATRICK) DECLINES WILD CARD, THEN FAILS IN QUALIFYING
TOURNAMENT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a hot wind swirling through the premises,
Tuesday was a difficult day to play for a living at the National
Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows, Queens. And the odd thing was,
Patrick McEnroe did not have to be out there on Court 7
unsuccessfully battling the conditions and Michael Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe could have been home in Manhattan preparing for next
week's U.S. Open. Despite his woeful ranking of 656 and despite
playing precious little tennis in the last two years because of two
shoulder operations, he was awarded a wild card into the main draw
by the U.S. Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
   But McEnroe, like his more combustible and recognizable older
brother John, has a mind and plan of his own. On Sunday night, he
telephoned the tournament director, Jay Snyder, and said thank you
but no thank you. He preferred to try his luck in the qualifying
tournament and leave the wild cards to those who deserved them
more.
</P>
<P>
   Declining a wild card is not unprecedented. Zina Garrison did so
last year because she no longer felt she was competitive in
singles. Richey Reneberg did so this year because he did not feel
he had recovered sufficiently from a knee injury. But declining a
wild card to dive into the shark tank that is the qualifying
tournament had no precedent as far as Snyder could remember.
</P>
<P>
   And McEnroe will not see his name on the draw of the 1998 Open
after blowing a 4-1 first-set lead and losing, 6-4, 6-2, to Joyce.
Some fans at courtside immediately dubbed McEnroe's decision to
qualify a ``$9,000 mistake.'' First-round losers in the main draw
earn $12,000, while first-round losers in qualifying earn $3,000.
But as McEnroe sat and conversed somewhat glumly on a bench outside
the players' lounge, he made it clear that material concerns were
not primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to play some matches,'' he said. ``I know
myself, and I know that going into the Open without having any wins
was no way to feel good about myself. I was obviously glad and
appreciative they gave me the wild card. I feel like I was actually
hitting the ball well enough where I could win some matches, but I
had to prove to myself that I could. I wanted to feel like I
deserved that wild card, and so far I haven't done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that hard a decision. If I had taken the wild card,
I might have gotten lucky and snuck through and won a round or
something with a good draw, but I felt like if I could have
qualified and had a few matches under my belt, I would have been a
dangerous player to play. But it didn't happen, and now I just move
on and figure out what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, who turned 32 in July, still hopes to play doubles in
the Open with Brian Macphie (he will not turn that wild card down
if it is offered). But his singles career could soon be over. He
already has retired and reconsidered once, rejoining the circuit
this spring after retiring late last year. The reason for his
about-face was that he finally felt healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But tennis, as McEnroe or any club player can tell you, is much
more than a physical endeavor. ``Maybe I'm analyzing myself too
much,'' said the man who has made a second career of analyzing
tennis on television. ``I've got plenty of other things in my life,
but I still enjoy playing and competing. The thing that bothers me
about this match was that I didn't enjoy the competing part. For
some reason, my attitude was negative. I don't want to say that was
my last singles match, but I need to think over some things.''
</P>
<P>
   While McEnroe ponders, his fellow American Michael Russell will
prepare to play. Russell, ranked No. 302, is the player who was
given the wild card that McEnroe declined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
