<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RETURNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK IN PUBLIC, GORE GIVES NO HINT OF ANYTHING WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Calif.)   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Looking tan and relaxed after a two-week Hawaiian
vacation, Vice President Al Gore returned to full public view
Tuesday, giving little hint that anything of major consequence had
happened while he was away.
</P>
<P>
   In a daylong schedule here that included a rousing speech to a
convention of 5,000 civil servants, a stop at an elementary school
and a rally for the Hawaii Democratic Party, a noticeably energized
Gore emphasized the positive and the future, focusing on issues
like education, health care and the need for union members and
other Democrats to support the party in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks were unusually fiery for someone who has openly
joked about his reputation as a stiff and sometimes awkward
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Through much of his address to the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees advocating the Clinton
administration's strong support for labor, he belted out many of
his points, lacing his remarks with jokes and gestures that ignited
the crowd on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded with a challenge for the 1998 elections: ``Are you
willing to more than match the intensity that the right-wing
extremists will bring to the battles that lie ahead?''
</P>
<P>
   The response was a loud and long standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's remarks were equally notable for what he did not say,
leaving little doubt that the omissions were part of a calculated
effort to distance him from matters that roiled Washington last
week. He made no mention of President Clinton's acknowledgement of
a relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky nor
did he address new questions that have come up about his own
fund-raising activities in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In what a spokeswoman for the vice president indicated would be
the rule for at least the next few days as Gore and his wife,
Tipper, make their way back to Washington, he took no questions.
The Gores are scheduled to leave Hawaii on Wednesday for San
Francisco, where he plans to attend several more events before
leaving for Washington on Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, whose allegiance to Clinton over the last six years
serves as a springboard for his own presidential aspirations, the
months ahead are full of political peril for him and the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the president, Gore has enjoyed a virtually spotless
public persona throughout his long political career.
</P>
<P>
   But an important question facing him is whether voters will
continue to be able to separate the two men, or whether Clinton's
problems have so sullied his administration they will damage Gore
as well. And while voters may see Gore as more trustworthy, if less
magnetic, than Clinton, the vice president may have his own
troubles down the road as Attorney General Janet Reno reconsiders
whether to appoint a special prosecutor to investigate fund-raising
telephone calls he made from his office.
</P>
<P>
   If she does so, the campaign finance investigation, which has
failed to capture much public interest so far, may become an
enormous liability for him.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence of Clinton's difficulties, Gore must maintain a
delicate balance between his loyalty to a close friend who has been
damaged but who has done more than any other president to lay the
financial groundwork for his running mate's ascension, and a
detachment that enables him to preserve his own integrity, his
sense of loyalty and, of course, his political viability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to walk a fine line, the nature of which is pretty
clear,'' said Stuart Rothenberg, a political analyst in Washington.
``Bill Clinton has been Al Gore's No. 1 benefactor. He is also the
No. 1 reason Al Gore is the heavy favorite to become the party
nominee for president. So he needs to remain loyal to the president
but at the same time maintain a separate identity to avoid the
appearance he is Bill Clinton's toady.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical question for Gore is how to clutch all the
benefits of serving as Clinton's friend and adviser while avoiding
the obvious baggage of the president's relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With elections 10 weeks away and the administration eagerly
seeking support for its proposals on education, health care, the
budget surplus and other issues, Gore might be most helpful for the
party and himself, aides said, by campaigning around the country
for Democratic candidates and stressing the urgent need for
Democrats to vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   Even the schedule of his first two days after vacation suggests
that he is keen to get started. Here in Hawaii, where the economy
has sagged for seven years and Democrats have controlled state
government for nearly 40 years, Gov. Benjamin Cayetano is trailing
in polls to a Republican challenger. Both Cayetano and Rep. Patsy
Mink accompanied Gore on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Gore is scheduled to attend a reception
Wednesday night for Michela Alioto, a former Gore aide who is the
Democratic candidate for California secretary of state. Thursday he
will appear at a luncheon in Palo Alto for Gray Davis, the
California lieutenant governor who is running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   While many Democratic officials say that Gore might be an ideal
emollient to soothe any public disdain for a wounded president,
Republicans may be just as happy to have Gore out stumping _ but
for entirely different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore is coming to my state, I would have no problem or
hesitation raising the facts of the cloud of controversy about 1996
and his role in illegal or unethical behavior,'' said Republican
pollster Frank Luntz. ``If he comes to town, he becomes an issue
and a lightning rod to remind Republicans that they ought to take
the time to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   To many voters of both parties, the unresolved fund-raising
issues could prove far more problematic for Gore in 2000 than any
of Clinton's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about Gore's role were once put to rest, last
December, when Reno said she had found no evidence that Gore had
raised money for direct aid to the campaign. His solicitations, she
concluded, were for general party purposes, known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue rose again last week when it was disclosed that
the Justice Department had obtained a 1995 White House memorandum
with handwritten notations that appeared to contradict Gore's
account of his fund-raising telephone calls, according to
government officials. The notations indicate that Gore and several
campaign officials discussed how some of the large contributions
raised by the vice president for use only for general campaign
purposes would be diverted to accounts to directly finance the
Clinton-Gore campaign, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has until the end of the month to decide if she should
initiate a 90-day inquiry, after which she would make a decision on
whether a special prosecutor is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore have said that he was recently interviewed by
Justice Department investigators and that he would ultimately be
exonerated from any wrongdoing. But he has not commented publicly
on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has he said much about the president's problems. Shortly
after Clinton acknowledged relations with Ms. Lewinsky on Aug. 17,
Gore said in a statement that he was ``proud'' of Clinton as a
``person who has had the courage to acknowledge mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
