u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHWEST-PILOTS-NYT &LR;      08-25 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-PILOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES BRACING FOR NORTHWEST PILOTS' STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are stockpiling baby diapers, trying to line up extra buses
and appealing to other airlines for help, but authorities in
Minneapolis, Detroit and seven upper-Midwestern states from
Illinois to North Dakota admit that there is not much they can do
if pilots at Northwest Airlines strike on Saturday, shutting down
the region's largest airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact on us would be devastating,'' said Kevin Kramer,
the director of economic development for North Dakota, where
Northwest provides virtually all the state's jet service. ``We have
all our eggs in one basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is not much better in Detroit and Minneapolis,
which are home to the nation's 9th- and 13th-busiest airports. An
estimated 8 out of 10 flights in and out of both cities are
Northwest's.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to President Clinton earlier this month, the
governors of Minnesota, Michigan, Wisconsin and four other states
estimated that their economies would lose hundreds of millions of
dollars in the first week alone if Northwest, the country's
fourth-largest airline, stopped flying.
</P>
<P>
   No one can say for sure whether a strike will be averted before
the deadline _ one minute past midnight on Saturday morning. The
latest round of negotiations between Northwest and the pilots began
at an undisclosed location on Aug. 17 under the auspices of a
federal mediator, who has ordered both sides not to talk to
reporters. The negotiations are to continue right up to the strike
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say publicly that they are eager to reach a
settlement, and Donald J. Foley, Northwest's chief spokesman, said
some progress had been made during the recent negotiations. But the
key issue of pay remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   As Saturday draws closer, the belief among politicians and
business executives that there will be a strike appears to be
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest began notifying passengers Tuesday that it would
cancel about 100 domestic flights Friday to insure that its planes
are not stranded in far-off airports if the pilots walk out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made the appropriate preparations to pull down the
airline as of midnight on Friday night if we are unable to reach an
agreement at the negotiating table,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the pilots struck American Airlines, a unit of
AMR Corp., President Clinton intervened within minutes, ordering
the pilots back to work and the negotiators back to the table.
</P>
<P>
   But some believe that the president, in his politically weakened
state following his admission of an inappropriate relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, will be more reluctant to intervene now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told our clients early in the process that Clinton would
intervene,'' said Brent Garback, the chief executive of Total
Travel Management, the largest corporate travel agency in Michigan.
``But given his problems, we now think he won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may also be reluctant to interfere because the Air Line
Pilots Association, which represents pilots at Northwest and 49
other carriers, is a major contributor to the Democratic Party.
Earlier this month, 24 Democratic congressmen, including the
minority leader, Richard Gephardt of Missouri, and the Democratic
whip, David Bonior of Michigan, wrote the president, urging him not
to intercede.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official who insisted on anonymity said that, as
he had in the American strike, the president would not intervene
until after the strike deadline to maintain the pressure on both
sides to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reich, who was labor secretary during the American
strike, said the president was not likely to act this time unless
it was clear that both sides were looking for a face-saving way
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the president doesn't want to be viewed as
powerless,'' said Reich, now a professor at Brandeis University.
``He especially doesn't want to look that way now.''
</P>
<P>
   The average Northwest pilot is paid $120,000 a year, according
to the union. Northwest says it is offering its 6,200 pilots a 10
percent pay increase over five years, placing them on a par with
their counterparts at United Airlines, American Airlines and Delta
Air Lines, the three larger domestic carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots counter that Northwest is not offering the hefty
stock options and profit sharing that the other airlines give their
pilots. They are asking for a 15 percent wage increase over five
years, greater job security and more generous vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is what the pilots and other Northwest
workers feel they are owed for the sacrifices they made in 1993, to
save the airline when it was near bankruptcy. Northwest's 45,000
unionized employees accepted wage cuts and work-rule concessions
worth $886 million.
</P>
<P>
   The largest share, worth $365 million, came from the pilots, who
agreed to cut their wages and other benefits 15.5 percent for 39
months in exchange for three seats on Northwest's board of
directors and more than 14 million shares of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the airline industry and Northwest have rebounded,
registering four years of record profits. The unions say they want
their share.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the pilots, Northwest also faces tough
negotiations with five other unions. Last month, the International
Association of Machinists, which represents 27,000 Northwest
workers, rejected a tentative contract that would have given them a
14 percent pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   Workers have been particularly embittered by $73 million worth
of stock sold by Northwest insiders earlier this year when the
share price was near its 52-week high of $65.3125. The group was
led by John H. Dasburg, Northwest's chief executive, who sold
322,000 shares worth $19 million, according to CDA/Investnet of
Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   With a strike looming, Northwest stock has since slid more than
50 percent, reaching a 52-week low of $28.50 a share on Friday. It
closed Tuesday at $29.50, up 56.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Buttrick, an airline industry analyst at Paine Webber,
estimates that Northwest will have lost up to $100 million in the
month before the strike deadline because of lost bookings. But he
added that Northwest had $3 billion in cash, more than enough to
weather the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most analysts say they believe that a strike could last
only a short time before the pain would be too great for either the
pilots or the airline to bear. While public opinion now appears to
favor the pilots, it could turn quickly if they stop flying.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Minneapolis and Detroit said their appeals to other
airlines to send in extra planes during a strike had failed
because, with the booming economy, most airlines are flying at full
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Omodt, a spokesman for the pilots' union, called
concerns about the impact of a strike exaggerated. ``It is kind of
ridiculous to think there are no alternatives,'' he said. ``If
there is a strike, there will be an initial shock to the system.
But then some airlines will pick up the routes. It is found money
for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
