<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-MAINE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM SHOW FEATURES INDIAN ARTIFACTS AND HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., August 30)  
(rl) 
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAR HARBOR, Maine _ In 1922, Dr. Robert Abbe, a New York surgeon
who summered in this coastal town, was struck by inspiration. He
had just bought a small collection of ancient stone implements that
had been found in the region, filling him with wonder about the
hands that had held them in prehistoric times. And rather than
leave the artifacts on a shelf in his house, he wanted to create a
place where others could see them. So he set about enlisting the
support of other local collectors, and on Aug. 14, 1928, the Robert
Abbe Museum of Stone Age Antiquities opened in a quiet glen near
here at the edge of Acadia National Park _ an event Abbe himself
did not live to see; he had died a few months before.
</P>
<P>
   Although originally devoted to prehistoric cultures, the museum
has broadened its scope over the years to include artifacts and
evocative dioramas tracing the history of Maine's Indian tribes _
the Maliseet, Micmac, Passamaquoddy and Penobscot _ up to the
present. Today, the museum houses 50,000 objects, ranging from a
10,000-year-old Paleoindian spearhead to contemporary bead and
basket work.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, 100 people gathered at the museum, a one-story
Spanish Colonial Revival building, to celebrate its 70th
anniversary and to view the exhibition ``Beads, Bones and Ancient
Stones: 70 Years of Collecting, 10,000 Years of History.'' If
nothing else, the show demonstrates how vital Indian culture has
been to Maine's social fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which remains on view through Oct. 18, when the museum
closes for the year, was put together by the museum's curator,
Rebecca Cole-Will, and its exhibition designer, Betts Swanton, with
some selections made by others, including William C. Sturtevant
III, curator for Native American Ethnology at the Smithsonian
Institution, and members of Maine's tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the objects on view were acquired from archaeological
excavations, some sponsored by the museum's field school. Some of
the artifacts left by Indians who lived in the coastal areas were
found in shell heaps scattered along the many inlets and stony
beaches. Other objects were donated, many by local residents. A
19th-century coiled basket, for example, belonged to the famous
landscape gardener Beatrix Farrand, who designed Abbe's garden at
his summer house.
</P>
<P>
   Baskets, spanning 200 years, in fact, figure prominently in the
show. Made of birch bark, quill, ash or sweetgrass gathered from
the marshes, baskets were either utilitarian _ for storage or
harvesting _ or of the fancy variety, like one woven in 1861 for a
wedding present by Molly Molasses, an elder of the Penobscot tribe.
It is one of the earliest examples of the porcupine curly weave in
which ash strips are twisted into points, giving the basket its
prickly appearance. Molasses was so well known in her time that
Henry David Thoreau commented in ``The Maine Woods,'' after passing
her on the street in Bangor in July 1857, ``As long as she lives,
the Penobscots may be considered extant as a tribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoreau wasn't entirely correct. Watie Akins, a Penobscot who is
a structural engineer and who is on the museum's advisory board,
donated 70 baskets woven between 1930 and 1980, many by his
grandmother Philomene Nelson. Her sweetgrass sewing basket and
knitting basket, aged to a coppery patina, are as beautiful as they
are sturdy. Curly baskets made during the last decade by the
Passamaquoddy family named Neptune are of a whimsical bent, in the
shapes of strawberries, blueberries, pumpkins and corn. The day
after the anniversary celebration, the Neptune family took part in
the Maine Indian Basketmakers Alliance summer sale here, where 25
basket makers representing all four tribes demonstrated their art.
</P>
<P>
   Over thousands of years, Indian costumes were adorned with beads
made from shells, clay, bone, stone and native copper; the beads
used as currency, called wampum, were cut from clam shells. After
the Indians came into contact with Europeans in the 16th century,
glass beads became popular as a trading commodity and were more
easily worked into complex patterns on clothing and accessories
than traditional porcupine quills. A Penobscot beaded belt from
1807 in the show belonged to the mother-in-law of Thoreau's Indian
guide, and a beaded bag in a decidedly Victorian style with leaf
and curved-line designs was owned by the wife of Dr. Sockbesin, an
important Penobscot healer.
</P>
<P>
   Indian craftsmen left nothing to waste. The bone of a swan was
used to create a graceful flute, which could be 3,000 years old.
For fishing, there were netting needles from deer ribs and bone
harpoons that were attached to spears.
</P>
<P>
   Stone implements were fashioned either by flaking or grinding,
and a grooved gouge on view is shaped perfectly to fit any hand.
Even stone plummets used as weights on fishing lines possess a
streamlined elegance. Among these exhibits is a 5,000-year-old
stone abrader from Abbe's original collection.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is planning year-round quarters across from the
village green. The new complex, a modern structure that
incorporates one of the town's old shingled buildings, will offer
additional galleries as well as more space for storage and
educational programs. It will serve as a complement to the old
museum, and the two together will further Abbe's vision. Speaking
at the anniversary ceremony, Wayne Newell, a Passamaquoddy who is a
museum trustee, said the museum ``preserves not only the objects
but the breadth and spirit of our ancestors.'' &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
