<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HIDING BEHIND SKIRTS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During a Democratic debate in Denver in 1992, Bill
Clinton was asked if he would want half his Cabinet to be women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might want more than that,'' he said eagerly. Coming in the
wake of the Gennifer Flowers fiasco, his unwitting double-entendre
drew laughter from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you laughing about?'' he asked defensively. ``Women
have held most of the important positions in my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   That drew more howls.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton has always been good with women. And bad with
women.
</P>
<P>
   He kept his promise to appoint women to top jobs. And now it has
become the unsavory task of these high-level women to defend the
president's misalliances with low-level women.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is like a little boy, hiding behind the skirts of
his powerful women, hoping they can shield him from the effects of
his fatal attraction to big hair and big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In psychology, they have a term for a narcissist who never
emotionally matures, who throws tantrums and expects everyone else
to clean up his messes: the Highchair King.
</P>
<P>
   Our Highchair King is banging his spoon and screaming ``Enable
me or the Dow goes down to 500!''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's most authentic moment was his Monica speech. He
was unbound, unvarnished and true to himself. He resented
apologizing for his bad behavior. He did it sullenly, only because
all escape hatches were closed. He was still trying to blame others
and still expecting others to prop him up _ especially the strong
women in his life.
</P>
<P>
   It was a real upstairs-downstairs moment on Sunday as the
secretary of state tried to give the Highchair King some cover over
his affair with the Girl Who Delivered Mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an American citizen and as a friend of the president's, I
accept what he said on Monday,'' Madeleine Albright told Cokie
Roberts, adding, ``But you know what's interesting, Cokie, is I
have no problems whatsoever assuring other leaders about the
credibility of the United States and the president.''
</P>
<P>
   That may apply to our allies, but what about our enemies?
They're not exactly wowed by Clinton's credibility. Witness Saddam
and Milosevic both choosing this moment to spurn American dictates.
</P>
<P>
   When Cokie Roberts pressed about whether the dallying with
Monica was wrong, the steamed secretary of state shut down the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Just more Clinton wreckage. A role model for women forced to
defend scrofulous behavior toward women. A woman who knew the pain
of having a husband leave her for a younger woman forced to defend
a man having a fling with a younger woman. A man married to her
good friend Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's silence spoke loudly about how corrupting this
scandal is.
</P>
<P>
   She became the first female secretary of state with a boost from
women's groups. After a White House official anonymously told a
reporter that Albright was in ``the second tier'' of candidates for
the job, women's groups raised a fuss. Clinton took note.
</P>
<P>
   As a serious woman trying to pave the way for women in a whole
new field, didn't Albright have an obligation on Sunday to speak
one extra sentence that made it clear that it was wrong of the
president to have sex with an intern in the Oval Office and lie
about it, and send out his wife and Cabinet and aides to lie about
it?
</P>
<P>
   There is a long-term cost to the Democrats and women appearing
to be condoning Clinton's behavior _ or making strained arguments
trying to differentiate him from Clarence Thomas or Bob Packwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the Democratic Party, and Democratic women, the party
of consensual sex with interns and lying about it,'' says George
Stephanopoulos. '`And that's going to kill us for the next 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The president has a good record on women's issues. But he
doesn't deserve a lifetime pass.
</P>
<P>
   He has turned Hillary Clinton into Tammy Wynette, popular with
Americans now that she has been stripped of her swagger and
humiliated by her husband. She has been reduced to promoting the
millennium _ which is going to happen anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He has been lousy about returning the favor and defending women
who ran into trouble. Remember Zoe and Kimba and Lani and Dee Dee
and Joycelyn? He let them all go without lifting a finger _ or even
banging a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
