<P>
   (NYT14) CHICAGO -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- FOSTER-SIBLINGS, 8-25 --
Experienced foster mother, Mary Hardwick, 58, in the kitchen with
Veronica, 9, Chantel, 8, Jimmy, 5, and Jermaine 3, who she took in
under a new program that pays foster parents a premium to take care
of a group of brothers and sisters. Ms. Hardwick says the siblings
are the most troubled children she has cared for. ``I guess they
really love each other,'' she say. ``They just don't know how to
express it.'' (Cynthia Howe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) TOMS RIVER, N.J. -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- BBO-TOMS-RIVER,
8-25 -- Colin Gaynor, 16, at left, cheers along with other friends
who gathered Tuesday afternoon to watch the East team from Toms
River defeat the South team from Greenville, N.C. Casey Gaynor,
Colin's brother, threw a five-hitter as his father, Mike, coached.
(Mary DiBiase Blaich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ASBURY PARK, N.J. -- Aug. 25, 1998 --
HURRICANE-BONNIE-2, 8-25 -- Lifeguards and their stands have been
moved off the sand and onto the boardwalk as heavy surf pounds the
beaches. Life guards keep potential bathers out of the water. With
dangerous rip tide conditions from Hurricane Bonnie, swimming as
been prohibited on beaches up and down the east coast. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PORTLAND -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- EVANGELICAL-EDUC, 8-25 --
Rebecca Strong, who will enter Seattle Pacific University, a
``Christ-centered'' college of 2,470 students, next month, was
uncomfortable with class discussions and her friends' reaction to
the relationship between President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky. In
a Christian college, she is part of a surge in applicants that take
a strict view of relationships, and who say the White House scandal
was a focusing event in their decision. (Shane Young/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LITTLE FALLS, N.J. -- Aug. 25, 1998 --
COPLEY-MARKETPLACE, 8-25 -- Last month Agnes Varis, a member of the
board of directors Copley Pharmaceutical of which Hoechst A.G. has
a majority stake, quit. But unlike many, she did not go quietly.
Instead, she publicly accused Hoechst of mismanaging Copley and not
acting in the best interests of all investors. ``They look for
directors that are 'parsley on the fish,''' she says. (Don Hogan
Charles/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WILMINGTON, N.C. -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- HURRICANE-BONNIE,
8-25 -- Ronald Oswandel secures tape around the historic clock
outside Kingoff's Jewlers in downtown Wilmington. Kingoff's
employee Danny Watson, holds the ladder. Shop owners and homeowners
started hurricane preparations as warnings were posted from
Chincoteague, Va., to Cape Romain, S.C. and tourists and residents
were ordered to leave the Carolina coast as Bonnie gathered speed.
(Jamie Moncrief/Wilmington Star-News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DEL RIO, Texas -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- TEXAS-FLOOD, 8-25 -- A
member of the Texas Task Force, Urban Search and Rescue, looks into
a car along the banks of San Felipe Creek in Del Rio on Tuesday.
About 150 members of the special force combed the creek area
looking for flood victims. Authorities had accounted for everyone
believed to have been missing following the flooding that crippled
this town on Monday. (Taylor Johnson/Austin American-Statesman
Photo )
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- QUINTERO-ONEILL-PLAYS, 8-25
-- Jose Quintero speaks at a forum on Eugene O'Neill's plays from
the stage at the Provincetown Playhouse in Greenwich Village.
Quintero has been the pre-eminent director of O'Neill and the
artist most responsible for re-establishing the reputation of the
Nobel Prize-winning playwright. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- NAPOLEONS-2, 8-25 -- Eric
Ripert, chef at Le Bernardin, builds layers of contrasting flavors
in the crab napoleon. Its made with rice flour wafers alternate
with curried peekytoe crab and apple salad. (Boyd Hagen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- NAPOLEONS-1, 8-25 --
Napoleons aren't just for desert. At Manhattan's Judson Grill, Bill
Telepan makes a napoleon featuring layers of chanterelle mushrooms
and corn. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- FASHION-COLUMN-BOS, 8-25 --
This year's back to school fashion consists of some old favorites.
Even clothes you thought you'd never see again, like the famous
1978 ``original'' Calvin Klein jeans. Kids who spend $55 on these
jeans can buy the MTV pager for about $20. The pager, which comes
in colors like neon yellow and is adorned with an MTV logo
regularly sells for $69. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ANDOVER, Mass. -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- MA-MCGOVERN-BOS, 8-25
-- Patrica McGovern gives her nephew, Philip Stella, a hug as his
sister, Patrica, watches. At 57, Ms. McGovern, the former
chairwoman of the Senate Ways and Means Committee, is seeking for
the Democratic nomination governor. ``I did what I thought was
right,'' Ms. McGovern says, comfortably discussing her record. ``I
really believed with all my heart in what I was doing.'' (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 1998 -- NY-SKATE-FISH, 8-25 -- John
Schaefer, chef de cuisine at Gramercy Tavern, preparing braised
skate with fava beans and heirloom tomatoes in a rosemary lemon
vinaigrette. Skate, which is actually related to the ray and found
year-round and worldwide, has a flat, diamond shape. It has two
edible wings and is fan-shaped with a ribbed texture. Skate fillets
looklike pearlescent angel wings, pristinely white with occasional
tinges of pink. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 1988 -- WINDOWNS-SOMMELIER, 8-24 --
Andrea Immer, the sommelier at Windows on the World. Ms. Immer, 31,
is intimately acquainted with all 870 wines in the restaurant's
cellar. Not only was she named the sommelier of the year but also
spent a year studying thousands more to represent the United States
in the Sommelier World Championship, held earlier this summer in
Vienna. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
