<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAREDO-COX     08-25 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAREDO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laredo prepares for Rio Grande floodwaters
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi and Ben Wear
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ As floodwaters threatened to destroy hundreds of
the area's poorest homes Tuesday, Magadelan Garcia grabbed only
what she could carry and left her humble home with her two sons and
only the clothes they wore on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 41, took one last look at the Rio Grande, just feet from
her back door, and headed to a nearby shelter, where she prayed
that the home she could not afford to rebuild would survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that I have in the world is there,'' she said through a
translator. ``What little furniture and clothes I have are there.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was one of hundreds of residents in low-lying colonias
north and south of the river who packed up and went in search of
higher ground Tuesday, as debris-filled floodwaters from Del Rio
and Eagle Pass headed downstream to Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters, which were expected to peak this afternoon near
38 feet, more than 30 feet above initial flooding levels, also
closed three international bridges spanning the river, halting the
brisk traffic of tractor-trailers that cross daily. Several Laredo
neighborhoods lying near the river and in two creeks feeding the
river were also expected to get some flood damage. The river's rise
is a result of torrential rains upstream in the Del Rio area. Those
rains, spawned by the remnants of Tropical Storm Charley, sent a
flood wave down the Rio Grande measuring up to a mile wide and more
than 100 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gradual thing,'' said Daryl Williams, a forecaster for
the National Weather Service. ``It's not like a wall of water
rolling down the river like a tsunami.''
</P>
<P>
   The river at Laredo could remain above flood stage for a few
days, weather service officials said. Some members of a National
Guard contingent previously dispatched to Del Rio have been
diverted to Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters are expected to enter Falcon Reservoir, between
Laredo and McAllen, on Thursday or Friday. The influx poses no
threat to the structural integrity of the dam, said Ken Rakestraw,
chief of water accounting for the International Boundary and Water
Commission, which oversees Falcon and Amistad Reservoir, upstream
from Del Rio. Amistad is also rising as a result of flooding in the
Devils and Pecos rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the deluge, the reservoirs are not expected to refill
enough to break a five-year drought along the lower Rio Grande,
according to the Texas Water Development Board.
</P>
<P>
   In Eagle Pass, the flood wave spurred city officials to evacuate
about 5,000 people Monday night. The river swelled to about 35 feet
above its normal level, the highest in more than four decades.
About 30 homes and some downtown bsuinesses were flooded, and there
were no fatalities or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Across the river from Eagle Pass, about 3,700 people were
evacuated and 35 homes were washed away in the Mexican border town
of Piedras Negras. The home of Mabel and Armando Lechler sat in
waist-high water Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here the government does nothing to help us recover from the
floods,'' Mabel said. ``Not like they do in Eagle Pass.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Laredo area, the flood wave was expected to inflict the
most damage on two colonias south of the city, Rio Bravo and El
Cenzio, where 7,500 people live. Half of the homes were expected to
be flooded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of these houses are in poor condition,'' said Magdalena
Gonzales, who works at El Cenzio's Community Center. ``They won't
withstand any flooding. People here, they don't have insurance.
They don't have money to rebuild. It will be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The colonias -- with mobile homes, plywood shacks and
pastel-painted stucco houses -- are home to the poorest of the
poor. Dozens of houses lay just feet from the banks of the river,
where water was rising a foot and a half per hour Tuesday night.
Three shelters in the colonias and one in Laredo sat ready for
those displaced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, city officials said power and water supply would not
be affected by the flood, since the water plant was situated 61
feet above ground, well above the highest estimates for
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   But in the colonias, where some do not have running water and
open sewers run near streets, flooding is likely to make things
worse. And south of the border in Nuevo Laredo, officials expect
water supplies will be tainted by floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   At the C &AMP; C Kountry Store in El Cenizo, residents streamed in,
buying more bottled water than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been buying water by the gallons,'' said Izaguirre
Maricruz, 31, who works at the store and lives in El Cenizo with
her 4-year-old son. ``There are a lot of people worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were skeptical, refusing to leave their homes until they
saw the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard in Laredo to tell people it's flooding, because it
has not rained here,'' said Betty Flores, Laredo's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   At Riverdrive Mall, whose bottom floor of stores will be flooded
if the water reaches 31 feet or so. Workers began nailing wooden
sheets over the McDonald's looking down at the river about noon.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Radio Shack, manager Hector Salazar, operating on the
owner's instructions, had moved only a few large speakers to higher
ground, leaving scores of small electronic devices subject to
submersion.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Laredo workers, Salazar lives across the river in
Nuevo Laredo. With the bridges closing, he won't be able to make it
to work today. With the mall closing Wednesday due to the flood,
though, he won't have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with many other workers, who were faced with the hard
choice Tuesday of finding someplace to spend the night or crossing
the river and missing work for at least one day. Laredo, with about
175,000 people, is connected to Nuevo Laredo's 250,000 people by
three automobile bridges and a train bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Alcala, 21, walking home on International Bridge No. 1 to
Mexico late Tuesday, had to pick between missing work at a U.S.
electrical repair shop or missing college classes in Nuevo Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss, he gave me permission to don't show up tomorrow,''
Alcala said. But he will lose salary while he is stranded in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   They began closing bridges at noon Tuesday, beginning with one
direction of the Columbia Bridge about 20 miles upstream.
Commercial traffic _ about 5,000 truckers cross the river at Laredo
every day _ ceased at 3 p.m. Both downtown bridges closed
completely at 7 p.m. The only options now other than staying put
are to go 150 miles downstream to McAllen or 125 miles upstream to
Eagle Pass, where the bridge remained open.
</P>
<P>
   Although International Bridge No. 1 collapsed in a major flood
in 1954, Laredo officials say they're not concerned about one of
the bridges being washed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the dams that we do now,'' Flores said. ``It
was a different river. At the same time, the force of the river is
something to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Tanamachi and Ben Wear write for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
