<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE RUBLE FALLS STEEPLY, CAUSING NEW WAVE OF PANIC
</P>
<P>
   A fresh wave of panic swept through Russia's financial
institutions as the currency plunged, three banks announced a
merger to shore up their stability and the government disclosed a
plan to stretch out repayment of its debt. Coming at a moment when
Russia's newly designated prime minister is still negotiating with
the Parliament over the makeup of his government, the ruble's
abrupt drop stoked new fears of inflation similar to the spiraling
rates that sent Russia into a depression in the early 1990s. The
drop in the value of the currency was the deepest in four years. It
was stopped only when the central bank of Russia intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Most major market indexes were rallying strongly early
yesterday, but dropped slightly after hearing about the situation
in Russia. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 36.04 points, to
8,602.65. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index closed up 4.72
points at 1,092.86. The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index
gained 7.35 points, to 1,798.17. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller stocks hit a new 52-week low, falling 3.94 points, or 1
percent, to 389.76. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to
5.43 percent, from 5.46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY INTO MICROSOFT'S INTEL ROLE
</P>
<P>
   The government is investigating whether Microsoft has used its
market muscle to force even Intel to shelve new technology efforts
that conflicted with Microsoft's ambitions. The antitrust lawsuit
accusing Microsoft of using unfair business practices to protect
its monopoly in operating systems and to extend that monopoly into
the new markets for Internet software and commerce was filed by the
Justice Department and 20 states. The trial is scheduled to start
Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   MARSH &AMP; McLENNAN'S $2 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Marsh &AMP; McLennan has agreed to buy the London-based Sedgwick
Group, the largest independent broker in Europe, for $2.05 billion
in cash. The deal increases Marsh &AMP; McLennan's business with the
largest corporations in Europe and with midsized companies in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH AIRWAYS ORDERS AIRBUS JETS
</P>
<P>
   British Airways has ordered as many as 188 short-haul,
single-aisle jets from Airbus Industrie in a contract worth $8.5
billion. Until now, British Airways had relied on Boeing as its
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   UAW CRITICIZES GM SPINOFF
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Yokich, president of United Automobile Workers, has
condemned General Motor's plan to spin off its auto parts
subsidiary, and said another strike was always possible. But he
added that the union may not do anything until its agreement with
the Big 3 American automakers expires next fall.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER CONFIDENCE INDEX DROPS
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board's consumer confidence index declined to
133.1 in August, but analysts said the decrease did not signal a
big change in sentiment, although consumers might start to exercise
some caution. In another report, the National Association of
Realtors said that home resales rose 4 percent in July, to a record
annual rate of 4.93 million.
</P>
<P>
   IMF SOFTENING ITS POLICIES
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund is softening its policies,
becoming more tolerant of arrangements it would have rejected a
year ago, and even allowing some Asian debtors not to repay all
they owe to foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
   APPLIED MATERIALS CUTS 2,000 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   In response to a global downturn in the semiconductor industry,
Applied Materials announced plans to cut 2,000 jobs, or about 15
percent of its work force, mostly in Santa Clara, Calif., and
Austin, Texas, and executive salaries by 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
