<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL AT 6 AS BORDER TOWN SHIFTS FOCUS TO SEARCH AND RESCUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Pina) 
 
By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ Maria Pina and her husband, Armando, stood on
the bed in their two-room adobe house at 203 Elm and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   It was late Sunday night, and water surging from San Felipe
Creek had broken down the front door. Armando considered trying to
cut a hole in the roof, but that was a long shot. By the time the
elderly couple realized their only way out was the front door,
foaming brown water was up to their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Then their tiny yellow house imploded, the roof caving in and a
side of the house buckling under the force of the swift current.
Armando heard his wife scream and then saw her vanish in the
furious water as their house split in two.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed to the surface by a piece of furniture, Armando was
rescued minutes later by a family who tossed him a garden hose from
their roof. Maria was washed some two miles away, where she was
found dead Monday. Her body was identified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard her say, `Ayy,''' said the 63-year-old Pina, sitting
on a cot at the local civic center, his face swollen from a cut
that required seven stitches and his body badly scraped and
bruised. ``Then, no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pina is one of six confirmed dead in the flash floods that
ravaged this border town late Sunday and Monday, triggered by
torrential rains that came ashore on the Gulf Coast by Tropical
Storm Charley. Authorities said Tuesday that one man they listed as
a flood victim Monday died instead of a heart attack unrelated to
the floods.
</P>
<P>
   The water, which submerged much of this city at one point
Monday, receded almost as quickly as it came, and Tuesday the
town's focus turned to search and rescue and even some cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities confirmed the names of five of the victims and upped
the number of missing from 30 to 41. Known dead are Pina, 56;
Border Patrol trainee David Pyatte, 37; his mother-in-law, JoAnn
Schumann, whose age was not known; and Carmen Ruiz and Concepcion
Chacon, ages also unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they expected many of the missing to turn up
alive and well since as of late Tuesday they had still not
accounted for many of the people in temporary shelters. Among them
are as many as 700 weary souls bedding down at the civic center and
a local church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to determine who's at the shelters,'' said
Paty Mancha, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Border Patrol. ``We've had
groups of five coming in and only one person signing in.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the floods killed 11 people from the Hill Country to the
Rio Grande and another three in Ciudad Acuna, across the border
from Del Rio in Mexico. But Tuesday, Leonardo Ayala Torres, Mexican
consul in Del Rio, told one U.S. official that nine people were
missing and presumed dead, though he said flood damage was light
compared to Del Rio and offered the city help on behalf of Acuna.
</P>
<P>
   The floods destroyed as many as 400 homes and businesses in Del
Rio, causing damages that are expected to soar well into the
millions of dollars. Among the property damaged is the city's water
system, which was knocked out in the floods and left Del Rio
without drinking water Tuesday for the second straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Officials predicted it would not be restored until late in the
week. In the meantime, 200,000 gallons are being trucked in per day
through a combination of public and private efforts. Electric power
and gas were restored to most of this city of 34,000, but many
stores and restaurants remained closed.
</P>
<P>
   Down river, the water that surged through Del Rio caused some
flooding in Eagle Pass and was expected to do the same in Laredo.
But most low-lying areas in those cities were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gov. George W. Bush, U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla and
local leaders are expected to tour the flood damage. State
officials said they are considering whether to appeal for national
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Del Rio received anywhere from 18 to 25 inches
of rain in a 24-hour period from Sunday to Monday. Combined with
water cascading south from the Hill Country, the rain caused severe
flooding all over Del Rio, with the worst coming at San Felipe
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The creek, which snakes through downtown Del Rio, is what
attracted settlers when they first came to the city in 1860. The
San Felipe neighborhood, a poor but fiercely proud Hispanic
community, grew up around it. Tuesday, as some ventured back for a
glimpse of the damage, they found it destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall at Joseph Borrego's home the battery-operated clock
had stopped at 1:10 a.m. Monday. By that time, the water was about
6 feet high in the living room and the Borregos had moved to higher
ground. Tuesday, Borrego's daughter Jennifer slopped through the
muddy floors to recover a CD player she received last week for her
16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stay here,'' said Borrego, the father. ``You just go
on with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the creek bed cars, including the local fire chief's
official vehicle, were wrapped around shady pecan trees. Many trees
were uprooted, much like the homes that had been literally jerked
from their foundations. The ground was littered with everything
from frying pans to phone books.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas Army National Guard and Border Patrol helicopters
hovered overhead, search and rescue teams worked the area, some
with dogs trained to find survivors. Locals Maria and Frank
Esquivel took it upon themselves to search for Frank's uncle, an
80-year-old man who they said is missing.
</P>
<P>
   But searchers, unofficial and official, were frustrated. By
early afternoon the only thing one of the search dogs, Falco, had
found was a soaked stuffed animal, which he held in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said 56 people were rescued, most of them Monday,
while 35 were treated at local hospitals. Those who made it out
alive, like Jovita Casares, a neighbor of the Pinas, said they had
only God to thank. Clinging to a piece of her home's roof, she and
seven others, including a local policeman, were washed some two
miles downstream. They were there found early Monday morning,
clinging to a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children were saying, `We can't feel our legs,''' said
Casares, recounting the long, wet, nighttime wait in the tree while
water rushed by. ``I just told them, `Now you hang on, God's going
to save you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pyatte, the Border Patrol trainee, lost his life trying to make
a rescue north of town. The father of one and a native of San
Angelo, he drowned as he tried to pull his mother-in-law, Schumann,
from her house. A trailer home had been swept 1,500 feet across a
ravine into her home.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Casares laughed and cried as she told her tale in
the civic center. She recalled the cries for help as the water rose
and the bodies rushing by as she and her husband and their
grandchildren, ages 12 to 20, sought refuge on their roof, only to
have it splinter into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started praying to God and told the children, `If the roof
breaks, grab a tree,''' said Casares. ``It's a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
