<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-COLLEGES-EDUC-AR     08-25 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-COLLEGES-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK GAINS FOUND MEAGER IN OLD SEGREGATED STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first comprehensive study of public higher education in the
19 states that once operated racially separate colleges presents a
picture of continuing segregation fueled by political fatigue,
court rulings, and admissions and financial-aid policies.
</P>
<P>
   Historically black colleges in those states are still
overwhelmingly black, the study finds, while whites dominate
flagship state institutions in numbers disproportionate to their
share of the population.
</P>
<P>
   And while the number of black freshmen in the 19 states has
grown since the 1970s, the percentage of blacks among freshmen has
barely inched up, to 17 percent in 1996 from 15 percent in 1976 _
small numbers, given that in all but four of those states, the
percentage of blacks among freshmen is significantly lower than the
percentage of blacks among all 18- to 24-year-olds. Nine states, in
fact, reported a decline from 1991 to 1996 in the proportion of
blacks in their freshman classes.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Miles to Go,'' was issued Tuesday by the Southern
Education Foundation, an Atlanta advocacy group that works to
improve educational opportunities for black and poor Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   The study follows by more than three decades the last of the
desegregation battles on Southern campuses, and by six years a
Supreme Court order that the states take ``affirmative steps'' to
dismantle vestiges of dual systems. In that ruling, United States
vs. Fordice, the court said that in the states that once had
segregated systems, merely instituting race-neutral admissions
policies did not end illegal discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   With the states in question _ 15 in the South, plus Delaware,
Ohio, Pennsylvania and West Virginia _ accounting for
three-quarters of the nation's black freshmen at public
universities, the study's data, the authors said, have national
implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been a full commitment to leveling the playing
field,'' said Robert Kronley, a lawyer who is a senior consultant
to the foundation and who wrote the report with Claire Handley, a
foundation official. ``The key point we are trying to make is that
you can't change this educational inequality without dealing
directly with race. And what we found is not so much ill will as a
kind of fatigue with these issues. There is a desire not to have to
confront problems of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for that observation comes in a July survey by Public
Agenda, a nonpartisan public opinion research organization. In a
report titled ``Time to Move On,'' Public Agenda found that white
and black parents alike wanted the public schools to focus on
raising academic standards rather than promoting diversity.
</P>
<P>
   At the college level, Kronley said, officials are responding to
a growing political and legal climate against affirmative action as
evinced by a federal appeals court's 1996 decision in Hopwood vs.
Texas and by Proposition 209 in California, both of which bar
consideration of race in college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Kronley said that as a Supreme Court ruling, Fordice trumped
Hopwood, and that to overcome past discrimination the 19 states
might take race into account in issues like admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Pell, senior counsel at the Center for Individual
Rights, a conservative public-policy group in Washington, said
Kronley was reading the Fordice ruling too broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fordice speaks only of getting rid of policies that affect
student choice rooted in de jure segregation,'' Pell said. ``It
does not say that anything that affects educational opportunities
for blacks is fair game. Besides, all the civil rights groups want
to preserve historically black colleges, so you can't integrate
higher education as was done in elementary and secondary schools.
As long as blacks want to go to all-black colleges, who is to say
they are less good, especially if funding has been equalized?''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago the Southern Education Foundation issued a
similarly gloomy study on 12 of the 19 states. Since then, the new
report said, most states have focused on ways to improve education
generally, without specific regard for African-Americans' problems.
The authors said those changes _ liberalized financial aid
policies, higher admission requirements and limits on remediation _
either did not help blacks or in fact worked against them.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some changes in financial aid have involved tax
relief. But many black families in the 19 states earn so little _
on average less than two-thirds the income of the average white
family in 1995 _ that they have little or no taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report said, the 19 states distribute more than
one-third of all their financial aid without considering need (more
than 10 times the percentage of aid distributed on a non-need basis
in the 31 other states). Since schools in predominantly black areas
tend to be weaker, their students' chances of earning merit-based
scholarship aid have been low.
</P>
<P>
   Many state colleges have also adopted higher admissions
requirements, which can act as a barrier for students from poorer
schools. The new standards coincide with moves to abolish remedial
courses at state universities, making it even more difficult for
poorly prepared students to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that black students in disproportionate
numbers failed to graduate. In 1976-77, public institutions in the
19 states gave bachelor's degrees to 23,587 black students, 8.5
percent of all bachelor's recipients. By 1994-95, the number was up
to 36,402 black students, still only 10.3 percent of all those
graduating.
</P>
<P>
   And among blacks who do graduate, many do not go on to
postgraduate work. ``The higher the degree,'' the authors said,
``the lower the representation of blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, most graduate degrees earned by blacks are in just a
few fields. Nearly half of all doctoral degrees to blacks in the 19
states _ 47.2 percent in 1994-95 _ are in education, with fewer
than 5 percent in engineering or the physical sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, black faculty, seen as vital role models and mentors to
black students, are severely underrepresented, the report said. In
14 states, blacks made up fewer than 10 percent of full-time
faculty members in the 1995-96 academic year; in the 5 other
states, black faculty was largely limited to community or
historically black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shared history of these states,'' the report said, ``has
spawned a common condition: opportunity in public higher education
for black students remains substantially restricted and far less
than that of whites. Progress, where present, has been ragged, and
efforts to promote it have been fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
