<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-TEXAS-SIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIO GRANDE FLOODWATERS FAIL TO DRENCH EAGLE PASS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE PASS, Texas _ Down river on the Rio Grande from devastated
Del Rio, this community had girded itself for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The worst never came.
</P>
<P>
   The rain-fed Rio Grande crested at 35 feet Tuesday morning, but
the floodwaters that killed half a dozen people in Del Rio never
entered downtown Eagle Pass or most of its residential
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest business casualty here was Mayor Pepe Aranda's
``chicharrones''' factory, which produces fried pork rind snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens, that's just nature,'' Aranda said philosophically
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only about two dozen houses were flooded and no lives were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the thanks for that can probably rest with the city and
its evacuation of 2,400 residents; 5,000 total were evacuated
across Maverick County.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south on the Rio Grande, in Laredo, the three
international bridges were closed and many residents were urged to
evacuate in preparation for the fallout of the remnants of Tropical
Storm Charley.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 people live in the Rio Bravo and El Cenizo areas
near the Rio Grande that were designated for evacuation, Laredo
Mayor Betty Flores told The Associated Press. Not all would be
required to leave.
</P>
<P>
   She said the city's water supply was expected to be safe since
its water plant is built at an elevation of about 60 feet. But
across the border in Nuevo Laredo, residents were encouraged to
boil water once the flood hits.
</P>
<P>
   The preventive actions in Eagle Pass and Laredo were prompted by
the frightening news from Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel bad for Del Rio. They were caught up before
anybody had time to react there,'' the mayor said. ``We feel very
lucky, we feel blessed. We were lucky that the water didn't go up,
and we had ample time to react.''
</P>
<P>
   State troopers and national guardsmen were called in to assist
in the evacuation of nine subdivisions. Aranda said 800 people
stayed in four schoolhouse shelters overnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the less fortunate was Eduardo Hernandez, a 52-year-old
cook and drummer, whose home was located on low-lying Ryan Street a
block south of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, covered in mud, carried out muddied furniture and
saturated mattresses to a growing pile behind his green
cinder-block home. He then carefully took the soaked dress-blue
Marine Corps uniforms of his twin nephews to higher ground. He laid
the uniforms out, still wrapped in plastic from the cleaners,
hoping he could salvage them for his nephews stationed in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is gone. Nothing is left,'' said Hernandez, who
spent the night with his wife and two grandchildren in his pickup,
parked up the street from his home.
</P>
<P>
   Though his house had been flooded twice before, in 1974 and
1982, he remained undeterred and planned to remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stay. It's our property,'' he said. ``We can't
leave our property.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the border in Piedras Negras, damage also
was light. Aranda said parts of Piedras Negras were without water
and he offered his assistance, but was told water was being trucked
in.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagle Pass Creek, which had risen over its banks and
threatened neighborhoods north of the Rio Grande, was a muddied
culvert in most places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had warning _ &UR;  &LR; unfortunately through Del Rio _ we knew what
was happening and we were ready,'' said Mary Ann Contreras, Eagle
Pass High School principal, whose cafeteria sheltered about 450
displaced people Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Of the people sheltered at the high school, only four families
were looking for a place to spend the night Tuesday. Contreras said
she was particularly moved by one woman who had lost her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she was concerned most about was not her home,''
Contreras said. ``The main concern for this woman were the uniforms
for her children for school tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
