<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-UT-LAWSCHOOL-COX     08-25 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-UT-LAWSCHOOL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT Law School admits more minorities in 1998
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In its second year of admitting students without
affirmative action, the University of Texas law school opens today
to more blacks and Mexican Americans than a year ago but to fewer
than in 1996, when race was still being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still an improvement, and we're pleased with that,'' UT
law dean Mike Sharlot said, giving credit to stepped-up recruitment
efforts, alumni-sponsored scholarships and first-ever interviews
with hundreds of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary data show that eight blacks and 30 Mexican Americans
were among the 465 first-year students enrolled by early Tuesday
afternoon. That's just 8.2 percent of the overall class, but up
from four blacks and 26 Mexican Americans who entered last year and
comprised 6.5 percent of the first-year class.
</P>
<P>
   UT officials pointed out there also could be more black and
Mexican American students ``hidden'' among an unusually large
number of enrolled students who did not reveal their race _ 70 in
all.
</P>
<P>
   Even if all of the black and Mexican Americans who had accepted
admission to UT actually enrolled this year, UT still would not be
abe to match the 1996 numbers. That year, 31 blacks and 42 Mexican
Americans enrolled in the first-year class.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, deans at Texas' three other public law schools, which
are less selective in choosing students, said they were thrilled to
enroll similar numbers of first-year black and Hispanic students as
in 1996. They also credited aggressive recruitment and outreach
efforts for the increases.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks and Mexican Americans have been historically
under-represented in Texas higher education and were targeted for
affirmative action until the federal court's 1996 Hopwood ruling
said race could no longer be considered in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which took full effect in 1997, stemmed from a
lawsuit brought by Cheryl Hopwood and three other white applicants
against the UT law school. It led to a dismantling of affirmative
action in all student programs, including scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the race of college students in Texas has received
national attention. California colleges also are in the spotlight
because of an affirmative action ban in that state.
</P>
<P>
   California's premier law school at UC-Berkeley reported last
week that Hispanic enrollees were up from 10 last year to16 this
year and that African American enrollments increased from one to
nine.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday afternoon, UT law school still had five to 10
admissions offers pending, but none was to a black or Mexican
American applicant, Assistant Dean Shelli Soto said. It will be
another 12 class days before enrollment figures are official.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the racial identities of the 70 students will remain
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 70 could hide a lot,'' Soto said. ``But unless they
disclose it to us, we're not counting them'' by race.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the law school won't know how to fully gauge the
effects of the intensely watched Hopwood ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he were troubled by that, Sharlot said: ``If the
suggestion is that these unidentified students would total the same
kind of enrollment we had in the past, I'm sure that isn't true.
I'd be willing to put a lot of money on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that there are worse things than not having definitive
data on students by race. ``It would be (more) distasteful, if we
made them all line up and eyeball them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   W. Frank Newton, dean at Texas Tech School of Law, was surprised
that his school's minority enrollments exceeded 1996 levels. Just
two weeks ago, he said he was expecting minority enrollments to be
about the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, five blacks enrolled at the Lubbock school, compared
with one last year and four in 1996. Twenty-eight Hispanics
enrolled, compared with 17 last year and 23 the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really worried we couldn't do it,'' Newton said of the
increases. ``We simply got many more of the minority students we
accepted to enroll after having some personal contact with alumni,
faculty, students and the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Tech had rebounded from Hopwood, Newton said trends are
not made in a year. He also said he worried that private
scholarships and other help would fade if people thought Tech had
overcome the effect of the Hopwood ruling.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Houston Law Center, 10 blacks were enrolled
compared with nine last year and 11 in 1996, while 36 Hispanics
were enrolled compared with 32 in each of the two preceding years.
</P>
<P>
   The other public law school, Texas Southern University's
Thurgood Marshall School of Law, is historically black but
nonetheless experienced declines in black and Hispanic enrollments
last year. Preliminary data this year show the school enrolled 162
blacks compared with 145 last year and 161 in 1996. Sixty-eight
Hispanics enrolled, compared with 57 last year and 66 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the state's five private law schools also experienced
minority enrollment declines last year, but complete data was not
available this week.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
