<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-MEGANS-LAW-600&AMP;ADD     08-25 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-MEGANS-LAW-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
SEX-OFFENDER LIST WITHHELD IN CONNECTICUT AFTER SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ When Trenton E. Wright Jr. heard that an
11-year-old girl had been slain while delivering newspapers in his
town this month, he immediately asked police for the names of
convicted sex offenders in the area _ a list available to any
resident under Connecticut's ``Megan's Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright has a son who delivers papers and a daughter who is 10,
so he was anxious to see whether they should change their routes or
avoid certain blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a few days too late.
</P>
<P>
   The police in Willimantic, the village in northeastern
Connecticut where the papergirl was found dead of head and neck
injuries in woods near her home, refused to show him the list.
Although the police would not say whether the girl, Angelica
Padilla, had been molested, they said that everyone on the list of
sex offenders was now a suspect. The list, available before
Angelica died to anyone who walked into the Police Department, was
now a confidential part of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   From Wright's point of view, a powerful weapon for parents was
suddenly unavailable when it was needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last murder in Willimantic,'' said
Wright, 44, an administrator at a women's shelter. ``Then you have
it happen to someone down the street, you think: I do need to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wright is appealing for help from the Connecticut Freedom
of Information Commission and Attorney General Richard Blumenthal.
``This is an extremely serious personal and community safety
issue,'' Wright wrote in a letter to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Chen, a specialist on sexual-offender notification laws
at the Rutgers University School of Law, said the case was the
first of its kind he had heard of. He added that while he
sympathized with Wright, he thought the battle would be an uphill
one. ``In almost any case, preserving the integrity of an
investigation is going to outweigh the immediate need to know,''
Chen said. ``The police are going to win out.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelica's death on Aug. 13 has turned Willimantic, a town of
15,000, upside down. A boulder in a park near her mother's
apartment has become a shrine heaped with teddy bears, flowers,
poems and children's clothes, with candles burning at all hours.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days after the girl's death, the Willimantic Police
Department and the Connecticut State Police still have 25 to 30
investigators working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the investigators have young children themselves,''
said Trooper Richard Alexander, a state police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey lawmakers passed the first sexual-offender
registration and notification law in 1994, naming it for Megan
Kanka, a 7-year-old girl who was raped and strangled by a paroled
child molester in her neighborhood. The idea was a political
blockbuster, and the laws swept the nation, with more than 40
states adopting some version in just three years.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the laws say Wright's plight illustrates their
limitations. One of them, Steven B. Duke, a specialist in criminal
law at Yale University, contends that sexual-offender notification
laws can give parents a false sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to protect your children from sexual predators is to
keep an eye on them,'' Duke said. ``Suppose he got a list of sexual
predators in his town. How would that protect his children from a
sexual predator in the next town?''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's Freedom of Information Commission has scheduled a
hearing on the matter for Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   But by January, the issue may be moot. Connecticut amended its
notification law this year to require the state police to keep a
statewide database and make it available to all on the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A leading proponent of the laws, New Jersey Attorney General
Peter Verniero, said that while he did not want to comment on
Connecticut's version, the laws were conceived with people like
Wright in mind.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Megan's Law' is about information,'' Verniero said. ``It's
premised on the simple notion that parents and communities are
entitled to have information so they make take lawful steps to
protect their families.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Kanka family, Geoffrey S. Berman of Manhattan,
said the Willimantic case shows that parent-teacher associations
and other community groups need to do more to spread the
information available under notification laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents shouldn't wait for a tragedy,'' Berman said. ``If the
parent is vigilant all the time, the law is effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
