<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOBE-QUARK-NYT &LR;      08-25 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-QUARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING ADOBE REJECTS BID BY QUARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo.)  (Eds.: This story was added to the New York Times business front
page) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Graphic software publisher Quark Inc. said
Tuesday that it had offered to acquire rival Adobe Systems Inc. at
a premium to Adobe's current stock price, but had been turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Quark, which makes QuarkXPress, an industry rival of Adobe's own
Pagemaker, said it was making the offer public after being rebuffed
by Adobe last week. Quark said that it was disappointed by Adobe's
response and that while it would seek a friendly transaction, it
held out the possibility of a hostile tender offer.
</P>
<P>
   An Adobe spokesman said Tuesday night that ``Adobe has advised
Quark that it is not interested in pursuing discussions'' with
Quark. Adobe, based in San Jose, Calif., has a current market value
of $1.65 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Adobe executives last week, Quark, a privately
held company based in Denver, said that it believed it had the
financial support to complete the transaction. The company said it
would sell off some of Adobe's products in the takeover to dispel
regulatory obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said they were skeptical about Quark's chances of
successfully acquiring the larger public company, which was a
pioneer in the desktop publishing industry. In the mid-1980s, Adobe
successfully developed the Postscript language which began a
standard for the publishing industry and was crucial to the early
success of Apple's Macintosh computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quark is a private company. How are they going to finance
this?'' asked Peter Rogers, a financial analyst at Volpe, Brown
Whelan in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also noted that hostile takeover bids in high-technology
industries are rarely successful, principally because it is
difficult to insure that engineering talent will not leave in the
face of a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the offer comes at a time when Adobe, which is a dominant
force in the publishing business and which is approximately twice
Quark's size, has been retrenching financially.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Adobe announced a reorganization and layoffs and
said that its third-quarter earnings, which are scheduled to be
announced Friday, would fall below Wall Street expectation.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it was cutting as much as $50 million to
$60 million in expenses that would lead to a staff reduction of
between 240 and 300 employees and contractors. Adobe also said it
was planning to take a one-time restructuring charge and as a
result income for the quarter could result in a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe has also struggled because of an industry shift away from
the Macintosh, which has traditionally been the foundation of the
company's graphics and publishing-oriented users.
</P>
<P>
   Quark announced its interest in Adobe after the stock market
closed. Earlier, share of Adobe closed up 12.5 cents, at $24.5625,
in trading on the Nasdaq market. Monday, Adobe shares touched a
52-week low of $24.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Adobe, which in 1997 had revenues of $911.9
million and about 2,700 employees, Quark was estimated to have
revenue of about $200 million. The company was founded in 1981 by
its current chairman, Tim Gill. Gill and Quark chief executive F.
Fred Ebrahimi each own 50 percent of the company. The company has
about 550 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe was founded by two computer scientists, John Warnock and
Charles Goeshke. Both men had been researchers at Xerox Corp.'s
Palo Alto Research Center during the 1970s. After working at Xerox,
they started Adobe based on the notion that the personal computer
would revolutionize the publishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   After its initial proposal to Adobe, Ebrahimi wrote a second
letter to Adobe. ``It is our desire to enter into direct friendly
discussions with Adobe,'' the letter said. ``However, because of
the response we have received to our August 18, 1998, letter, we
have decided to publicly disclose our proposal. Although we reserve
the right to proceed with an offer directly to your stockholders,
we strongly prefer to negotiate a transaction supported by the
Adobe Board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
