u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NEELY-BOS &LR;      08-25 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NEELY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEELY WORKING OUT AMID COMEBACK RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ OK, Bruins fans, time to activate the dream machine.
</P>
<P>
   Cam Neely, forced into retirement two years ago by his aching
knee and hip, is back working out, leading to rumors around
Montreal Tuesday that he is contemplating a comeback with the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any conjecture about a comeback would be very premature,''
said Neely's agent, Jay Fee, who spearheads the hockey division at
Woolf &AMP; Associates in Boston. ``He is working out, but those
workouts have been aimed at affording him a better quality of life
on a day-to-day basis, providing him a better range of motion in
his hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely, who turned 33 in June, was not available for comment,
said Fee.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Neely began working out again at Sports
Acceleration North, the popular Burlington sweatshop owned and
operated by Mike Boyle, the Bruins' conditioning guru who aided
Neely in repeated comebacks earlier in the '90s. Neely now is
working with an exercise program designed by Dan Dyrek, the noted
Wellesley physical therapist who helped Larry Bird cope with a
cranky back in his later years with the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   According to Boyle, Neely has been helped considerably by the
Dyrek-prescribed program, which includes deep muscle massage,
stretching, and strengthening exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's been really helpful in terms of helping Cam get relief
that, a year or two ago, he didn't think he'd get,'' said Boyle.
``When he retired, he thought he'd have to live with that pain the
rest of his life. Now, he's dealing with less pain, his gait is
better; Dan's helped him immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes after Neely began working out in Burlington, said
Boyle, a number of the NHL players who work out there regularly
asked the former Bruin if he were considering a comeback. Boyle
would not answer that question, saying he preferred not to speak
for Neely.
</P>
<P>
   Question: So why was word circulating around Montreal about a
Neely comeback?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   The popular French-Canadian singer appeared at the FleetCenter
over the weekend, and according to a Montreal source, she was
presented with a memento from Bruins captain Ray Bourque and Neely
during a news conference Friday night that was broadcast on
Montreal television. Someone in the Dion party went home to
Montreal with the impression, after talking with Neely or Bourque,
that the former Bruins power forward was angling toward a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Fee confirmed that Neely did attend one of Dion's concerts at
the Fleet, but offered no other details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there is nothing immiment here,'' said Fee. ``You
aren't going to wake up some morning and see Cam skating with the
Bruins. That's not what we're talking about here.''
</P>
<P>
   The official position from his agent is that Neely is just
trying to get his body feeling better. Boyle says much the same,
noting that Neely and his wife are expecting their first child this
fall, and Neely's primary aim is to be able to do all the running
and jumping that dads hope to do when their children are young and
active.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, neither Boyle nor Fee wants to say much. That alone
says something. They see and talk to Neely nearly every day. If he
didn't have even a remote thought of again playing someday, he
would have made that clear and they would have said that on his
behalf. The fact that they're hesitant in declaring a comeback a
non-issue would indicate that Neely at least hasn't dismissed the
possibility. He's feeling better, and he's thinking, if perhaps
only dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   Neely's career came to an expected and somber close Sept. 5,
1996, his hip too sore, his body too torn and tattered for him to
consider even one more shift as the game's one-time premier power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. (Bert) Zarins and the many fine medical specialists ...
have concluded that my right hip injury,'' said Neely, his voice a
painful jumble of emotion that day at the FleetCenter, ``is a
severe disability that will prevent me from returning to
professional hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Neely is feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps, he is feeling differently about his future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
