NYT-08-25-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2000 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-DAVIE-HNS &LR;      08-25 1837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DAVIE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Like a boxer trying to wear out his opponent,
Bob Davie wasn't easily cornered. Bobbing and weaving, he nimbly
maneuvered out of harm's way each time the questions hinted at an
ugly turn, and for the longest time no one seemed able to lay a
glove on him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notre Dame's 43-year-old head coach stood for all the pictures
and mugged with a player or two on the school's recent media day.
At one point, he even posed for a shot alongside offensive tackle
Mike Rosenthal, whose testimony helped swing a court case against
Davie and the school.
</P>
<P>
   Distractions? What distractions?
</P>
<P>
   Why, anyone could see that things were looking up. The
``Infighting Irish'' of summer were, in fact, one big happy family
again _ or at least one well-schooled in getting its story
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really followed it,'' quarterback Jarious Jackson
said in dismissing a tumultuous offseason. ``People ask me, but
they know more than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jimmy Friday, a senior from Missouri City, echoed the
theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who ask me know more about all that than I do,'' he
insisted. ``As a team, we really don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Jackson and Friday could remain above the fray. They
weren't directly in the line of fire.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Rosenthal, who played a pivotal role in helping
former Irish assistant Joe Moore prevail in an age-discrimination
suit?
</P>
<P>
   He, too, claimed to be blissfully ignorant of the firestorm that
had engulfed the football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really never got caught up in that,'' he said. ``I don't
know what was said or what was happening. I didn't read anything or
watch anything about the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his best efforts, Davie wasn't going to get by quite
that easily. Much of the former Texas A&AMP;M defensive coordinator's
summer, after all, had been spent dealing with the Moore trial and
its fallout. Particularly damaging were revelations that he had
openly cited age in dismissing the former assistant (a stunning
gaffe in these litigious times) and at one point had questioned the
mental stability of former boss Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his second season in the hot seat fast approaching,
Davie hopes the focus finally will begin to shift from courtrooms
and NCAA investigations to X's and O's.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this football season is over and all the dust settles
people on the outside will say if we're successful that we did a
great job of handling the adversity and distractions of the summer
and overcame that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if not?
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say it was a distraction and it lingered on and we
lost focus.''
</P>
<P>
   As fall practice began in anticipation of the Sept. 5 opener
against Michigan, plenty of distractions remained. Not the least of
them was the ongoing sniping from the ever-savvy Holtz, whose book
tour provided no shortage of opportunity to lament that there had
been ``something missing'' his last three years in South Bend _
which just happened to coincide with Davie's tenure on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   So how are relations between Bob and Lou these days?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those things are personal,'' Davie said, a frown
crossing his face for the first time. ``There's no sense in me
going back and talking about all the things that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about Holtz's assessment that the trial would adversely
affect Notre Dame's image?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Lou's comment,'' Davie said. ``Lou had reasons to say
what Lou said.''
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair to this team and this coaching staff
for me to spend a lot of time talking about those situations,''
Davie said.
</P>
<P>
   Others seem more than willing to take up the debate, and many of
those same people who at first viewed Davie as a breath of fresh
air are beginning to take a second, more critical look. As if a 7-6
debut season hadn't been alarming enough, that incredible blunder
in the Moore case raises deeper questions about Davie's competence
to head college football's most lionized and scrutinized program.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to sum up Year One on the job, Davie shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything can really prepare you to be the coach
at Notre Dame,'' he said. ``I think by being here three years as an
assistant, I was pretty well prepared. No one knows what twists and
turns are going to happen, but if you're going to be head coach at
Notre Dame, there are going to be twists and turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he knows, the bloom is off the rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team and this coaching staff,'' he said, ``have a lot to
prove.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps not much time to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the news in South Bend has been bad. Just this week, in
fact, Notre Dame learned that the NCAA had cleared five players who
had been under investigation for taking gifts from a booster,
including a free trip to a Chicago Bulls basketball game. The
charge could have resulted in each being declared ineligible for
the coming season.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Irish aren't out of the woods quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   The program still faces potential penalties regarding the
activities of booster Kimberly Dunbar, whom the NCAA has deemed a
school representative while a member of the since-disbanded
Quarterback Club. An internal investigation determined that Dunbar
(who has a child with former player Jarvis Edison) gave gifts _
jewelry, clothing and trips _ to 12 current or former players,
including the Chicago trip.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar has troubles of her own: She faces up to 16 years in
prison and a fine of $20,000 after pleading guilty to embezzling
more than $1 million from her former employer, some of which went
to the gifts in question. Her attorney also has hinted that Dunbar
may go public with details of her relationships with those players,
perhaps creating more unpleasant headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Joe Moore affair remains unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Already awarded $86,000 in damages, Moore (dismissed in December
1996, soon after Davie took over as head coach) has filed a motion
for reinstatement to the staff, along with a request for more than
$600,000 in attorney's fees. The motion also seeks about $375,000
in front pay should reinstatement be denied.
</P>
<P>
   As one storm passes, then, another seems to gather on the
horizon, keeping spin doctors busy under the Golden Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a situation where the program has fallen apart,''
athletics director Michael Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, at least. Michigan has yet to come to town.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in talent that began in Holtz's final years had
become too glaring to ignore. Speed and playmaking were in short
supply on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as he led his first Irish team onto the field last
September, Bob Davie assumed everything would work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know there are some problem areas,'' he recalls. ``But you
think because you're the head coach, things are going to be better,
that all the positives are going to undo the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's ego. I just think that's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, you realize that some problems take time to solve. Now,
I know you take nothing for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Hints that things would not be easy came in the opener, a 17-13
squeaker over Georgia Tech. Losses to Purdue, Michigan State,
Michigan and Stanford dropped the Irish to 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame won six of its last seven before losing to LSU (a
rematch of an Irish win in Baton Rouge) in the Independence Bowl,
but the merits of the rally are debatable. The run included a
four-point win over Navy and a 23-22 escape at Hawaii, neither
likely to be celebrated in Irish lore.
</P>
<P>
   Jarious Jackson, who takes over from the much-maligned Ron
Powlus, may claim to know little of depositions and court
proceedings, but he has heard the boos at Notre Dame Stadium on
Saturday afternoons and understands the implication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the program is viewed differently because of our
record,'' he said. ``We were 7-6. People are used to 11-1 or 10-2.
We need to put Notre Dame football back where it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be even more difficult than winning lawsuits or fading
the heat of NCAA investigations. Davie talks about a renewed work
ethic, about getting bigger and stronger, but even he concedes a
lack of raw talent on a roster once routinely stocked with the
cream of the high school crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to recruit speed,'' he says. ``We still have to
get game-breakers. Maybe some of the young kids can provide that.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, Notre Dame may struggle to improve on last's year's
tepid results. With the first five games against Michigan, at
Michigan State, Purdue, Stanford and at Arizona State, another 1-4
start is hardly out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, there already are concerns about how to convince the
next wave of potential difference-makers to come to South Bend.
Davie knows that any recruiting visit in the near future will
involve damage control.
</P>
<P>
   What about Joe Moore?
</P>
<P>
   What about a head coach who can't fire an assistant without
being sued?
</P>
<P>
   What about the NCAA?
</P>
<P>
   What in the name of Knute Rockne is going on over there?
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably won't let them ask,'' Davie says. ``I'll probably
just come out and address it. But I don't think that's going to be
the focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many other things at Notre Dame. Everybody's
going to make mistakes; everybody's going to have their problems.
But I really think our problems are minimal compared to what other
people may have.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempting as it may be to create a siege mentality, Davie says he
regards that strategy as shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could almost paint the picture that it's this team and
this staff against the world,'' he said. ``And you may get some
short-range motivation out of that, but over the long haul I think
that's a negative way of looking at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't be motivated by looking back to last year by how
hard we worked then I think we have the wrong kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps, as some are beginning to suggest the wrong coach?
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame traditionally stands by its man, and Davie has four
years to go on a five-year contract. Even the hapless Gerry Faust
served out his full five-year term before departing with a 30-26-1
record.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the program struggles to restore its once-pristine
image, these are strange times in South Bend. Even now, Rosenthal
remains both adamant and vocal in his support of Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Moore is a great coach,'' he says. ``His actions speak for
themselves. The amount of guys he's coached and the respect they
have for him says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie says he has talked to Rosenthal. The matter, each says, is
settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the personalities involved,'' Davie says. ``I know the
specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie also knows things are different this time around. The
honeymoon is over, and Irish eyes no longer are smiling upon the
new man on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan is coming. Soon enough, Notre Dame will find out if a
painful and embarrassing summer was simply a prelude to the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
