u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FLOODS-1STLD-WR     08-25 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOTE TEXAS TOWN HAS 6 KNOWN DEAD, MORE MISSING AFTER FLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 5th graf that summarizes the dead and missing;
changes hed; makes minor language changes in first three grafs; )  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on
precipitation in Del Rio, Texas, is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ Pat Calderon was standing on tiptoe atop his
projection television console, the dark water in his living room so
deep it was licking the bottom of his chin, when his 82-year-old
disabled mother, who was floating nearby on an upholstered love
seat, asked if he would mind fetching her a dry blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Mom, look where we are, we're in a flood,''' said
Calderon, a fifth-grade teacher from San Felipe Estates in Del Rio.
``I was holding onto that love seat so it didn't tip over and dump
her in the water. I felt like that Titanic guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For six hours, they were stranded like that, the water slowly
rising and then slowly falling, revealing a jumble of sopping
carpet, furniture, books, videotapes, electronic equipment, all
covered in gunk. One lone candle had bobbed all night long on a
floating end table while lightning flashes revealed the swift
current tearing through what was left of his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the middle of this stuff and I couldn't believe it
was happening,'' Calderon said.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of mud-streaked residents picked through what was
left of their soggy belongings in San Felipe Estates Tuesday as
hundreds remained homeless and the town struggled to return to
normal after the disaster that left 10 dead on both sides of the
river and more than 20 still missing. Five others had also died in
flooding farther north in the Texas Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   The huge swell that put two-thirds of Del Rio under water early
Monday _ some of it, like Calderon's neighborhood, more than 8 feet
under water _ had gushed down the San Felipe Creek and its normally
dry tributaries, into the Rio Grande River and was already halfway
to the Gulf of Mexico by Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   All that was left was a swath of town covered with mud and
debris, collapsed buildings, buckling pavement, chewed-up bridges
and cars scattered everywhere, upside down, on their side, on top
of buildings, on top of one another, like Matchbox cars in an
untidy toy box.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came so quickly,'' said Del Rio City Councilwoman Gloria
Sotelo, who was helping to hand out drinking water at a Red Cross
shelter Tuesday afternoon. ``By the time you crossed the street,
the water was up to your knees. By the time you turned back, it was
up to your shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sotelo, like many of the more than 600 people seeking
shelter in the Del Rio Civic Center because their homes were gone
or uninhabitable, had known some of the six people in town who
officials said had died or the dozen or so who were swept away and
are still missing. ``It's too sad to think about now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the river, in Ciudad Acuna, Mexico, four people had died
in the floods and ten others remained missing, said Mario Neyra, a
Mexican disaster relief official.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sutherland, associate pastor at Grace Community Church,
which had been housing some of the flood victims, came into the
civic center Tuesday afternoon saying, ``We're out of food, can you
help us?'' Some food was found. An off-duty policeman delivered a
truckload of donated drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross doctors worked from folding tables on the civic
center's stage while hundreds of people sprawled on cots and foam
mattresses and children scampered through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Porras sat on a pillow on a metal folding chair in the
civic center, her one-day-old daughter, Ruby, squalling in her lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband was at work and I started having contractions
around 11 o'clock Sunday night,'' she said. ``It was all of a
sudden the rain came and the kitchen started filling up with water.
The water kept going up and the contractions kept getting worse, so
I finally called an ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Porras had her daughter at 2:14 a.m. while the water was
still rising and, when she returned to the neighborhood the next
morning, found her home flooded. Neighbors said she and the
ambulance had barely beat the deluge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you'd say I was lucky,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cyndi Wright, a Red Cross spokeswoman, said that 635 people had
slept in the center Monday night and at least as many were expected
Tuesday night. Two other shelters had been closed Monday night when
the rising water threatened to swamp them. In Eagle Pass, more than
700 people slept in five shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to have enough food, but water is still at a
premium,'' Ms. Wright said. ``The bigger problem is that there is
no rental housing or any kind of unoccupied housing in Del Rio.
There's no place for these people to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sotelo described the flood's victims as ``mostly poor, about
90 percent of them, and a lot of them without insurance, so I don't
know how we're going to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Rio is a remote town of more than 30,000 in the arid
scrublands along the Rio Grande River some 145 miles west of San
Antonio. Like the rest of Texas, it had been in the midst of the
biggest drought in at least four decades when the remnants of
Tropical Storm Charley dumped more than 17 inches of rain on Sunday
and early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is some ranching nearby, and a few small farms,
most of the town's economy flows from its border crossing, the
factories just south of the border and nearby Laughlin Air Force
Base. ``We're basically a small, working community, and this flood
hit the poorest part of town,'' Ms. Sotelo said. ``The whole county
has come out to help with this, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Local fast food outlets had sent hamburgers, tacos and
sandwiches to the shelters. Churches were collecting old clothes.
The flood had swamped the town's water pumps, and the taps are
expected to stay dry for several more days, forcing people to use
swimming pool water to wash. Dozens of people walked with plastic
buckets down to the still-swollen creek to fill them with muddy
water to flush their toilets.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At various spots around the city, lines stretched 20 or 30 deep
of people waiting for handouts of drinking water donated by the Air
Force and by local ranchers with untainted wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got a town that's full of precious people,'' said
Jackie Isenhour, a retired restaurant owner who was also helping
out at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The swell that hit Del Rio early Monday had passed through Eagle
Pass, the next significant town downriver, by late Monday night.
Unlike Del Rio, Eagle Pass had some warning. Hundreds were
evacuated and, while the water did flood into many city streets,
there were no deaths or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Across the river, in Piedras Negras, one person was killed in
the flooding, Neyra said, and three people were still missing
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Farther downriver, at Laredo, all three international bridge
crossings were ordered closed and the swell is expected to sweep
through town around 1 p.m. Wednesday. Just beyond Laredo is Lake
Falcon, which officials said will swallow up most of the flood
waters and stop it from pushing further downriver toward McAllen or
Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Calderon said his mother, Leonore, was resting comfortably
at a relative's house. She had resisted leaving their house when
the water started rising. ``She was in her wheelchair, grabbing
onto the wall saying she wouldn't go,'' he said. By the time it was
clear that they ought to leave, the water was too high to get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``First I put my other on her bed, then watched the water come
up the bedpost,'' he said. ``Then the mattress started floating.
The water came up to my chest. I had to stand on a chair, and it
came up to my chest again. If that love seat hadn't floated by, I
don't know what I would have done with my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked around the wreckage of his house, mud smeared across
it like peanut butter on a sandwich. The current had picked up his
blue Lincoln, carried it 50 yards up the street and dumped it on
the roof of his brother's auto parts store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we never go through anything like this again,''
Calderon said. ``At least we made it. We're a little stinky, but we
made it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
