<HEADLINE>
PURDUE CAN'T FIGURE UNTESTED USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC feels some uncertainty about its offense
heading into Sunday's game against Purdue, but it's probably
nothing compared to the stress felt by Boilermakers coach Joe
Tiller. With Trojans coach Paul Hackett in his first season, Tiller
has precious little information to prepare for the USC offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we'll try to guess,'' Tiller said Tuesday. ``Coach
Hackett's from the Chiefs, so I guess they'll use some of the
Chiefs' offense. Guessing is really what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe with their stable of running backs they
won't run the football,'' he said. ``Pull the guards, toss to the
tailback, run sweep. But Paul's not that type of offense; he's
going to that infamous West Coast attack, so we'll get ready to
play that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett disagreed, however, with Tiller's characterization that
there was any mystery surrounding his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be a two-back running team,'' he said. ``That's
no secret.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett quickly reverted to Lou Holtz mode after he asked
about the point spread for the Pigskin Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them or us?'' he said, when informed the spread was 6{ points.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, USC is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dual player: Travis Claridge continues to work out at both
tackle and guard during practices. It's meant to give the Trojans
some depth on the offensive line, especially since starting right
tackle Matt Welch has been injury-prone. Welch strained his
shoulder during Tuesday's practice but is expected to be OK for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Pearsall ready: Strong safety Grant Pearsall's knee remains a
concern; it's just not the knee everybody knows about. Pearsall,
who missed last season after having surgery on his left knee, has
been out for the past week with a twisted right knee.
</P>
<P>
   But after putting on a brace, Pearsall returned to practice
Tuesday and proclaimed himself ready to start against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing great. No pain at all,'' Pearsall said. ``I'm
anxious. It's been two years since I've played in a game. I'm just
looking forward and leaving my injuries behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Thomas hurt again: Freshman quarterback Jason Thomas limped
off the field during practice, his ankle wrapped in ice, as he
continued to be bothered by the chronic injury.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thomas is not healthy, he must be on call for Sunday's
game, because Hackett said he is the No. 3 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason Thomas is struggling,'' Hackett said. ``(The ankle) has
not responded. It gets fatigued. I would have to suspect we'll use
him in a game only if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happens if Mike Van Raaphorst and Carson Palmer get
injured against Purdue?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any choice (but to play him),'' Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
