</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GR-HURRICAN-PAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resident remember Bertha and Fran
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Most Hurricane Bonnie planning meetings
Tuesday didn't end without some mention of hurricanes Bertha and
Fran.
</P>
<P>
   The two storms wreaked havoc on Pitt County in 1996, knocking
out power, flooding streets and scattering debris. As officials
picked up the pieces then, they also picked up some pointers on
improving emergency plans.
</P>
<P>
   With Hurricane Bonnie expected to affect the area today, some of
those techniques are about to get their first test.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie will christen Pitt County's year-old Emergency
Operations Center, a consolidated communications hub housed in the
basement of the county's Fifth Street administrative building.
</P>
<P>
   During Hurricane Bertha in July 1996 and Hurricane Fran six
weeks later, county workers were scattered, with some in the
Administration Building, the courthouse downtown and in department
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew what the other was doing,'' Pitt County Emergency
Services Director Bobby Joyner said. ``Now, it's a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, which opened in May 1997, houses the 9-1-1 dispatch
center, the emergency management office and a command center
equipped with more than 21 phone outlets and a computer that
receives National Weather Service updates.
</P>
<P>
   Even without that center, the county handled the effects of
Bertha and Fran well, County Manager Tom Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things worked really well. The main thing we needed was a
better facility. We said then that we wanted to have a better
system, better facility in place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County Memorial Hospital also has moved its command center,
housed two years ago in a transformed waiting room. The new
headquarters will be in a larger room with more equipment, News and
Information Director Tom Fortner said.
</P>
<P>
   Handling hurricanes Bertha and Fran gave hospital personnel
experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having had those two very recently is very good preparation
for Bonnie,'' Fortner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenville Public Works Department also got disaster
experience, improving on its response during Fran's aftermath after
cleaning up from Bertha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bertha was our first real test, and we probably learned a
bit,'' Public Works Director Tom Tysinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials now don't wait to arrange emergency plans or assign
crews to areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another important lesson for city and county leaders was
bookkeeping. The Federal Emergency Management Agency's
record-keeping rules are strict, and if locals want reimbursement
for mileage and manpower, crews must keep detailed information.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenville Utilities Commission reviewed its emergency
strategy Tuesday, reaffirming the tactics that have proven
successful, GUC Director of Electric Systems Roger Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through this before. We've got a good plan,'' he
said. ``We handled Bertha and Fran very well considering those type
of conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, just living through a hurricane is a learning
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who never saw a hurricane before Bertha and Fran ... do
have some experience behind them. They've learned from that,'' said
Greenville Fire-Rescue Chief Raymond Carney, the city's emergency
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about it, but it's nothing like seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bryant writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
