<SLUG> BC-GR-HURRICANE-HOTEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hotels provide safe havens for visitors and local residents
 &HT;    By Bobby Burns
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Even though hurricanes have interrupted three
Outer Banks vacations, Karen Chizmar feels lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland resident found seven hotel rooms in Greenville for
herself, several family members, friends and 11 children.
</P>
<P>
   Staying at the Holiday Inn Express on Moye Boulevard, Chizmar
and her party were among hundreds of tourists who fled Hurricane
Bonnie and found refuge at local hotels. Innkeepers say the exodus
has filled about every room in town at least through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our vacation with our kids so we're making the best of
it,'' said Chizmar, clad in a fluorescent green, one-piece bathing
suit, a white hotel towel wrapped around her waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having fun at the pool and I've already had my first
margarita.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel clerks began fielding calls as early as 6 a.m. today from
Nags Head, Atlantic Beach, Wilmington and points between where
Bonnie prompted evacuation calls and at least stalled vacations for
many beach goers. Hurricane warnings were issued Tuesday for the
entire North Carolina coastline.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, hotel parking lots began to fill up with
cars and sport utility vehicles, many packed with bags and beach
chairs and topped with surfboards. County officials report that all
1,600 rooms are full. And clerks at the Ramada, Fairfield, Motel 6,
Red Roof and Holiday Inn attributed high occupancy to the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a lot of people checking in from evacuations and
we're having to turn people away,'' said Appie White, front desk
clerk at Red Roof Inn. ``As far as we know, the town of Greenville
has been booked tonight and tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenville is one of the first stops along coastal evacuation
routes. However, it is not immune from the storm's impact. Local
officials are preparing for the worst and say Greenville's guests
could face inland threats such as flooding, torrential rain, power
outages and high winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume they've heard Greenville is a safer place than the
Outer Banks and that's why they all are coming here,'' said Robin
Hardy, front desk supervisor at Holiday Inn Express. ``I hope they
are right.''
</P>
<P>
   Chizmar and her group simply hope the storm will blow back to
sea so they can return to their vacation. This is their fourth trip
to the Outer Banks in 15 years. The first was interrupted by Diana.
Two years ago, Felix sent them packing.
</P>
<P>
   The previous storm taught them lessons, however, such as get off
the beach before everyone else if you don't like traffic and want
to get a hotel room. They drove 70 miles in seven hours in the
evacuation from Felix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel safe here,'' Chizmar said. ``We couldn't stay at the
beach with the kids ... when you have the kids, you need to move
... We were in luck to get this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Burns writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
