<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GR-HURRICANE-BRACING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resident bracing for the worst
 &HT;    By Clejetter Pickett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ With memories of hurricanes Fran and Bertha
still fresh on her mind, Renee Willis of Greenville wasted no time
Tuesday preparing for the arrival of Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting prepared. I think that's the only way to approach
this and hope it will turn toward the sea,'' she said as she
shopped for bread and water at Food Lion on 10th Street. ``After
Fran and Bertha, the reality is that it could very well strike. It
has made this one much more real.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of Fran and Bertha may also explain why people stood in
line at the Greenville Lowe's store to buy power generators Tuesday
morning. Fran and Bertha, just two months apart in 1996, together
left nearly 40,000 local residents without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were here to get generators at 7 o'clock,'' Lowe's
employee Robb Burgan said. ``People are going crazy about this
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's, which normally sells between 100 and 150 generators a
year, sold 40 in just an hour Tuesday. Store Manager Ron Bradshaw
ordered 250 more, which he expects to arrive today and also sell
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a lot of people who are coming in and are
purchasing them for people who are on oxygen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But power generators were not the only hot-selling items
Tuesday. Stores couldn't open early enough for people wanting to
buy food, bottled water and building supplies to hurricane-proof
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been crazy,'' said Food Lion Manager Diane Bednarz.
``People were piling in at 6 a.m. this morning wanting to get in
the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Delivery trucks had to make extra rounds to keep up with
customer demands, she said. ``We're putting out twice as much bread
in one round than we normally would,'' said Wonder Bread delivery
man James Long . ``People are buying it as quickly as I'm putting
it on the shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Before 5 p.m. Tuesday, Wal-Mart had sold out of such items as
D-size flashlight batteries, generators, bottled water and bread.
</P>
<P>
   An ``emergency'' truck was scheduled to bring more
hurricane-popular items to the local store late Tuesday or early
today, said Wal-Mart Manager Heather Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think everybody is just being very precautious,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her efforts to prepare for Hurricane Bonnie, Mary
Peterson still wasn't optimistic that she had done enough Tuesday
afternoon. She has houses both in Pitt County and on the coast and
worried that at least one of them might bear the brunt of Bonnie's
wrath .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sweating this,'' she said. ``Anyway it goes, I'm in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie, the Atlantic season's first Category 3 hurricane under
the Saffir-Simpson intensity scale, is 300 miles wide and is
expected to cause widespread damage as far inland as Greenville and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Tony Mills, who was buying plywood to board up
the windows of his new home Tuesday, said he is wondering about his
decision to move here from Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through quite a few (hurricanes), that's why I
moved here. But it looks like we're going to go through one here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clejetter Pickett writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville,
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
