u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-MCCAUGHEY-NYT &LR;      08-25 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-MCCAUGHEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. GUBERNATORIAL CANDIDATE IS EVERYWHERE BUT ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ These days, Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross is
everywhere that a candidate for governor ought to be, from Long
Island to Niagara Falls, with one crucial exception: television.
</P>
<P>
   With just three weeks left until the Democratic primary, Ms.
McCaughey Ross has yet to begin a large-scale advertising campaign,
a lapse that has mystified political analysts and delighted her
opponents. It has also raised serious questions about the
willingness of her financier husband, Wilbur Ross, to spend
millions of dollars on the race.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Ms. McCaughey Ross led her primary opponents
in the polls, and the expectation in political circles _ fed by
some of her supporters _ was that she would try to bury the other
Democrats with a summertime advertising blitz. She and some of her
aides talked of Ross spending $10 million or more on the primary
and the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor has a larger war chest than any of her
rivals _ $2.6 million as of Aug. 15 _ but, even as she has fallen
behind her chief rival, Peter Vallone, in recent polls, her
campaign has been in no hurry to spend that money.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Vallone, the New York City Council Speaker,
began a major television and radio advertising effort Monday that
will continue through the Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. McCaughey Ross expressed annoyance with
questions about when her television advertising might begin and
what her husband might be willing to spend. She refused to answer
and tried repeatedly to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is anyone in New York state lying awake at
night wondering where my campaign ads are, but they are lying awake
if their children can't read,'' said Ms. McCaughey Ross, who this
week has been promoting her education platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a strategic decision,'' she said, ``and campaign
strategy is something that's kept very close to the vest, and when
I have an announcement to make about television advertising, I will
make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions are of more than the usual importance for Ms.
McCaughey Ross, whose primary opponents include Vallone, Brooklyn
District Attorney Charles Hynes and former state Transportation
Commissioner James Larocca.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that she is by far the best known of the Democrats in
the race. But her three opponents all enjoy a generally favorable
reputation among the Democratic voters who know them, while many
more voters rate Ms. McCaughey Ross negatively than positively.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom in politics is that such math would make
it difficult for her to expand her support, and imperative for her
to improve her image well in advance of the primary. In a state the
size of New York, the only effective way to do that, analysts said,
would have been to take to the airwaves early, before any of her
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign Consultant School 101 says she should have been on
the air a long time ago, and heavily, to define herself before
others do it for her,'' said Lee M. Miringoff, director of the
Marist Institute for Public Opinion at Marist College in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``Her strategy has left a lot of people
scratching their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lynch, a political consultant who is not involved in this
race but who supports Vallone, said, ``Waiting this long to spend
her money and do advertising doesn't make any sense if she really
wanted to win the primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Strategists for some of her opponents, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that whatever the motivation behind it, they are
pleasantly surprised not to be seeing Ms. McCaughey Ross' face on
their television screens.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, Ms. McCaughey Ross will be on the November
ballot, because she has the Liberal Party nomination. But if she
loses the Democratic primary, her role on the Liberal line is
likely to be no better than that of a spoiler who will damage the
Democratic nominee by splitting the anti-Pataki vote.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor continues to suffer from the bumps in
her unusual, and relatively brief, sojourn in politics. A
Republican until she switched parties last year, she had never held
public office until Pataki picked her, an obscure academic, as his
running mate four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a year spent as a Democrat attacking the Governor,
she is still mistrusted by many Democrats, who do not quite trust
the sincerity of her conversion. And she is still dogged by her
long-running feud with Pataki and by the complaints of many former
staff members, which have left her with a reputation for flaky and
sometimes abusive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the long procession of fired or bitterly departed
McCaughey Ross aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that
Wilbur Ross, the senior managing director of Rothschild Inc. in New
York, was never terribly serious about spending the amount of money
it takes to run a credible, statewide race.
</P>
<P>
   They said that, having gauged that his wife cannot win, he has
chosen to cut his losses, a decision that may have been bolstered
by the recent downturn in the stock market and Ross' financial
disputes with his former wife.
</P>
<P>
   Many political professionals subscribe to that view, though
there are other theories. One is that the lieutenant governor and
Ross naively believed that she could coast to the Democratic
nomination, saving her resources for the general election. Another
is that her campaign is in such disarray, with frequent turnover in
her cast of relatively inexperienced acolytes, that no coherent
strategy has ever been able to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. McCaughey Ross is stumping as hard as ever,
campaigning this week on Long Island and in the Hudson Valley to
talk about schools and health care, meeting with editorial boards,
flying to Buffalo to advocate casino gambling, returning Tuesday
night to New York City, where she spoke in favor of civil rights
for gay people to a gay group.
</P>
<P>
   She continues to hit her long-time favorite themes, that
government should provide better early-childhood education and arm
consumers to do battle with health insurers. ``This election is a
referendum on education and which candidate has shown the most
consistent and effective commitment to public schools,'' she
declared.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last year, Republicans and Democrats alike have
undermined the potency of those issues by co-opting them. State
lawmakers, including Pataki, have expanded prekindergarten
education and taken steps to lower early-grade class sizes _ based,
in part, on reports written by Ms. McCaughey Ross _ and they have
also created an appeals process for patients whose health insurance
companies deny them coverage for some procedures.
</P>
<P>
   And despite her obvious hard work, her campaign, late in the
game, still displays rough edges that have hurt her attempts to
draw attention to her appearances and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, she announced a news conference on the
steps of the State Capitol to lay out her health insurance
proposals. She then changed the location without alerting the
entire Capitol press corps, and then arrived for the event late.
Many reporters, thoroughly confused, gave up trying to find the
event, which received little coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
