<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-THEATER-SPACE-2TAK     08-25 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-THEATER-SPACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD BANKS ARE NEW THEATERS, FILLING BILL FOR OFFBEAT SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's probably safe to assume that the builders of the
old American Savings Bank near Union Square never imagined this
scene: performers tethered to wires and pulleys dip and soar above
a standing audience. Balloons cascade from the 40-foot ceiling,
followed by soaking blasts of water and a shroud of fog. One
performer loses his pants and zooms bare-bottomed into the crowd,
joining his colleagues, who are clad but drenched. Later the
spectators get into the groove, dancing furiously in this theater
with no seats.
</P>
<P>
   This mad scene is ``Villa Villa,'' one of the summer's biggest
off-Broadway hits. Its producers have found what they consider a
perfect home in a building designed not for the wild and surreal
performance of an Argentine troupe known as De la Guarda, but one
intended to convey to bank depositors in the early 1900's a sense
of sober security.
</P>
<P>
   The building, now known as the Daryl Roth Theater, is one of a
growing number of unconventional spaces that are providing homes
for New York theater companies. The phenomenon reflects both the
offbeat demands of particular shows, like Villa Villa (pronounced
VEE-zha VEE-zha), which capitalized on the bank building's vaulted
ceiling and open floor, and a soaring demand for theater space both
off- and off-off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off-Broadway is thriving,'' said Maria Di Dia, vice president
of the League of Off Broadway Theaters and Producers Inc. ``There
is almost the same number of off-Broadway productions as
on-Broadway productions. People are looking at new and interesting
places for space. Necessity is the mother of invention. As soon as
one show closes, there's someone else banging on a theater's door
trying to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Many producers have to wait before they can open a production
for lack of space. ``It happens a lot,'' said Daryl Roth, a
producer of ``Villa Villa'' and the owner of the former bank
building. ``You'll have a play ready to go and no place to put it
in. You lose momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Theaters have historically cropped up in odd corners of the
city, from the parlor floor of a brownstone (Provincetown
Playhouse) to the basement of a supermarket (Roundabout Theater).
New York's first historically significant theater to take up
residence in an unconventional place was the Castle Garden, which
had been a fortress near the Battery until the early 1800s, said
theater historian Mary Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   This recycling of buildings is especially pronounced in New
York, where space is limited and the cost of erecting a new
building is prohibitive, she said. Perhaps the most popular
unconventional spaces are churches, which have been converted into
theaters since the mid- to late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the banking industry contracting and the theater
industry booming, it makes sense that the Daryl Roth Theater would
inhabit the former American Savings Bank building and that Second
Stage Theater is preparing to do the same in an old Manufacturers
Hanover Trust building near Times Square, at 43rd Street and Eighth
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at storage houses, porn parlors, schools, libraries,
old recording studios, old video recording studios, churches, an
old Fedex office and the space under St. John the Divine,'' said
Carole Rothman, artistic director for Second Stage. ``Bank mergers
have made bank space available.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater companies covet old banks because they often have no
columns obstructing the floor space and have soaring ceilings. High
ceilings allow fly space (generous space from which to drop
scenery) and space to install balconies. They also offer better
acoustics, with the right sound designers.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Roth said she had spent two years looking at movie
theaters, a senior center and a church before finding the empty
bank at Union Square East and 15th Street. She paid $3 million for
the building, whose interior measures 50 feet by 100 feet and will
hold about 380 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Second Stage's new home in the old Manufacturers Hanover Trust
building is 17,000 square feet, including rehearsal space. Rem
Koolhaas, a Dutch architect who is overseeing the redesign of
Universal City in Los Angeles, and Richard Gluckman of Gluckman
Mayner Architects, a firm based in New York that did the Whitney
Museum expansion, have been hired to transform the space, which is
expected to open Feb. 22, after $6 million in renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothman said the new theater would offer more artistic
flexibility to Second Stage, a nonprofit troupe that has performed
since 1979 in relatively cramped quarters on 76th Street and
Broadway, in what was once the gymnasium of a monastery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a larger space,'' she observed. ``We can do musicals if
we want. Because the ceilings are so high, we have fly space. We
can get more people up on stage. The theater uptown is more suited
to solo performances.'' That theater, which can seat 108 people,
will continue running, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another theater in the making is the old Biofitness Center, a
shuttered health club at 121 E. 24th St. Blue Heron Theater is
reconfiguring the 10,000-square-foot space, which itself had been
converted from a furniture store, into a performing arts center. It
will have two small theaters (with 135 and 60 seats), a rehearsal
space, a backstage office and an art gallery, said Gary Bernstein,
managing director of Blue Heron.
</P>
<P>
   ``How nice it will be to have our own space, and a permanent
home,'' said Bernstein, whose nonprofit company has had to rent
space from other companies for the last 10 years. ``Literally, at
times, we've gotten the last theater available,'' he said. ``It's
like finding the last jacket on the rack, even if it isn't the
right size.''
</P>
<P>
   The former health club has 19-foot ceilings and columns that are
spaced 23 feet apart. ``We would have preferred no columns,'' said
Adelle Striker, Blue Heron's artistic director. The company signed
a 10-year lease, and is expected to spend $300,000 to $400,000 to
remodel.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just off-Broadway and off-off-Broadway theaters that
are settling into odd venues. ``Cabaret,'' the hit Broadway
musical, opened in a former disco in Time Square, Club Expo, in
February 1998. The theater, known as the Kit Kat Klub, is not set
up like other theaters. Small nightclub tables fill the room. Some
nights, after ``Cabaret'' closes, the place again turns into a
dance club or real cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Westside Theater Company's officers thought they had struck
gold last summer when they found the Hotel Riverview, at Jane
Street and the West Side Highway, where survivors of the Titanic
once took refuge. The hotel's old ballroom, they thought, would be
perfect for a new theater and a new production, ``Hedwig and the
Angry Inch.''
</P>
<P>
   But first seats had to be put in, the stage had to be raised and
extended, and the bar had to be scaled back.
</P>
<P>
   The new Jane Street Theater, as it was called, was designed
especially for ``Hedwig and the Angry Inch,'' a play about an East
German drag queen that became a cult hit and won an Outer Critics
Circle award for best off-Broadway musical.
</P>
<P>
   It took just two months to turn the former ballroom into a
250-seat theater. Eric Osbun, operations manager of the Jane Street
Theater, declined to say how much it cost to transform the space,
though the slightly tattered feel to the room was intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Trask, an actor and the musical's composer and lyricist,
said that performing in what he called ``a derelict hotel and an
inexpensive tourist hotel'' lent character and authenticity to the
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the toilets in bathrooms above us overflow and the
ceiling leaks, people think that's part of the show,'' he said.
``We just bring up buckets and people assume there's a leak every
night. Sometimes pieces of ceiling fall on us _ just plaster,
nothing serious. It's perfectly believable that Hedwig stays there.
It's like the audience has entered another reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
