<HEADLINE>
GET PAPER TICKETS, NORTHWEST FLIERS TOLD
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
Customers with paperless tickets for Northwest Airlines flights are
being advised to exchange them for paper tickets in case a strike
Saturday cancels flights.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Customers will need paper tickets in order to obtain a booking
on another airline if the pilots walk out.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest's 5,800 pilots have vowed to strike unless an
agreement can be reached before the deadline at 12:01 a.m. Eastern
time Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can switch to a paper ticket by calling the travel
agent who booked it, or by going to the Northwest ticket counter at
Sky Harbor International Airport or the Northwest ticket office at
3164 E. Camelback Road.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a strike, travelers are advised to get to the
airport early, because Northwest passengers will be clogging other
airline counters trying to rebook their flights.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has 12 flights per day in Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
