<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF THOUSANDS FLEE CAROLINA COAST AS BONNIE APPROACHES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC BEACH, N.C. _ Residents and tourists along the Carolina
coast evacuated by the hundreds of thousands Tuesday as Hurricane
Bonnie, a potentially dangerous storm with winds of 115 mph,
churned toward the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory evacuation orders were issued early Tuesday for more
than 250,000 residents in at least eight North Carolina coastal
counties, and the governors of both North Carolina and Virginia
declared states of emergency as the storm approached an expected
landfall Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 people were told to vacate coastal counties in
northern South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who does not abide by the mandatory evacuation, our
law enforcement has been instructed to ask them their next of
kin,'' South Carolina Gov. David Beasley told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted Bonnie, a large storm, would make landfall
in the vicinity of Beaufort near Cape Lookout around midday.
Hurricane warnings were issued for a lengthy stretch of coast from
South Carolina through Virginia. Beaufort is about 100 miles up the
coast from Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   As darkness approached Tuesday the storm was located 250 miles
south of Cape Lookout and was moving erratically to the northwest
at 16 mph. A day earlier, the storm's path had been so slow that
forecasters speculated that it might not move to landfall. But by
late Tuesday it began moving rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   On the coast, news of its size and newfound speed triggered a
steady stream of traffic headed inland.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for several of the threatened counties said many
people, still mindful of Hurricane Fran's landfall near here in
September 1996, heeded the call to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This storm has been out there for a while and we think that
also has had something to do with the fact that so many people have
evacuated,`` said Mike Addertion, emergency management coordinator
for Carteret County. ``Also, I think a lot of people remember
Fran.''
</P>
<P>
   Fran, with similar winds and carrying heavy rain, ripped through
the state and into Virginia, killing 17 as it smashed homes and
swamped lowland areas. Fran brought a 12- foot storm surge, and
officials warned Tuesday that Bonnie could pack an equally strong
surge. High tide occurs at about 11 a.m., and could exacerbate the
effect of the surge.
</P>
<P>
   On Atlantic Beach late Tuesday heavy surf pounded under a stiff
breeze, and light rain fell on mostly deserted and dark streets,
evidence that many had heeded the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Moulthrop, newly divorced and new in town, was one
of those who had elected to stay. Moulthrop, an assistant librarian
at a local elementary school, said she had moved to Atlantic Beach
in Carteret County only last Wednesday from Raleigh because she
``needed a new atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm petrified,'' she said. ``But I made the move here and I'm
not going to run from it. If the Lord wants me to go, he will come
and get me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents were still deciding whether to leave as darkness
fell. Dave Whitehead, a construction worker who had spent most of
the day fixing plywood to windows, was one of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't made up my mind yet,'' he said. ``I got a scared
little girl in there and so I might still get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Addertion said that up to 95 percent of the people in seaside
and low areas of Carteret County, located in the projected path of
the storm, had evacuated as of 6 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Havelock, 20 miles inland in Pamlico County, several business
had taped and boarded their windows.
</P>
<P>
   On Ocracoke Island to the north, ferry operator Barry Austin
said he had been shuttling people off Cape Hatteras all day Tuesday
and that by sundown, all those who wanted off had gotten off.
Having lived his 55 years on the Outer Banks and after sitting out
other hurricanes, Austin himself had no plans to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sir, I'm not going anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin said the eight or nine ferries that run between Cape
Hatteras and Ocracoke Island started moving at 5 a.m. Tuesday and
did not stop until 12 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we got everything closed up, and we're waiting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. James B. Hunt Jr. declared a statewide
emergency in the early afternoon. The Federal Emergency Management
Agency and the North Carolina National Guard were mobilized and
waiting in staging areas, said Sgt. Jeff Winstead of the State
Highway Patrol who was manning a telephone at the state Emergency
Management Service in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation of the coastal counties and other low lying areas
had proceeded smoothly, Winstead said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far at least, people are taking this storm seriously,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Beasley of South Carolina also sought evacuation of low
areas and Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore declared a state of emergency,
authorizing communities to order evacuations if they chose. Navy
ships at Norfolk, Va., left port during the day to ride out the
storm at sea.
</P>
<P>
   At Pope Air Force Base, N.C., ``every plane that is flyable is
leaving,'' Lt. Tisha McGarry told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, forecasters are watching another Atlantic storm,
Hurricane Danielle, building near the U.S. Virgin Islands.
Forecasters said that storm could develop into another Bonnie
within days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
