<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PILOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF LOOKS JUST LIKE OLD SELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Steffi Graf has become almost as renowned for
her injuries and family misfortunes over the last two years as for
the accomplishments that have made her one of women's tennis
greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, playing in her ninth tournament of the year,
Graf, winner of 21 Grand Slam events, found herself matched against
Henrieta Nagyova _ a far lesser-known player who is ranked 14
notches above Graf _ in the second round of the Pilot Pen
International.
</P>
<P>
   But the ranking, which has the 19-year-old Nagyova 24th and Graf
38th, is misleading since the 29-year-old Graf has played sparingly
since coming back after knee surgery. And this year the once nearly
invincible Graf's best finishes have been as the runner-up in three
events.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, Graf showed flashes of the form that enabled
her to be ranked No. 1 for a record 186 weeks between 1987 and 1991
as she crushed Nagyova, 6-1, 6-3, in 62 minutes before a crowd of
about 5,000 in the 15,000-seat Connecticut Tennis Center stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory by Graf, who returned in mid-February after being
sidelined for eight months, put her in the quarterfinals of this
28-player tournament. Her opponent on Thursday will be the winner
of Wednesday's match between seventh-seeded Amanda Coetzer, who
beat Graf three times last year, and 17-year-old Anna Kournikova of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely fine; there are no problems,'' Graf said after
overpowering and outsteadying the Slovakian teen-ager, whom she had
beaten, 6-0, 6-4, at Wimbledon in June in their only previous
meeting. ``I served reasonably well and did not make many
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagyova, by contrast, made many. Perhaps the most egregious was
enabling Graf to hit repeated inside-out forehand shots for
outright winners from the advantage court. Nagyova also had no
offensive weapon to hurt Graf, who kept her pinned to the baseline
most of the match with deep, penetrating ground strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, who never lost her service, moved well throughout and
later said that she had fully recovered from her knee injury but
still had a way to go to regain peak form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the shots and I've got the strength,'' said Graf, who
is seeded eighth for the U.S. Open, which starts Monday and which
she has won five times. ``I just need the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Her old match toughness was also still lacking, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``During practice I do all the right things, but then don't them
all during a match,'' said Graf who, before her knee injury, was
bedeviled by back, foot and hamstring problems. ``I really haven't
been very fit or played much now for the last year and a half.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACC0-APPEAL-COX     08-25 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACC0-APPEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco settlement interrupted by appeal
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A last-minute objection to the Texas tobacco
settlement sent lawyers scrambling like jet fighters chasing Iraqi
missiles to intercept who was behind the latest assault on the
multibillion-dollar deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing late Monday, lawyer Kenneth J. Chesebro gave notice
to the U.S. District Court in Texarkana, where Texas filed its
tobacco lawsuit, that he would appeal the settlement to the 5th
Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals. Chesebro contended in the filing
that a provision of the settlement illegally prohibited citizens of
Texas or people doing business in the state ``acting completely
independent of any party'' from challenging the tobacco settlement
in any court other than the one in Texarkana.
</P>
<P>
   Chesebro said Tuesday that he filed the notice of appeal for
himself and by himself, but he would not answer other questions
because he did not want publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is filed with me as the appellant,'' he said. ``I'm doing
this on my own behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   The special assistant attorney general in charge of the tobacco
litigation, Harry Potter, called Chesebro's challenge a ``very
strange set of events.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell where he's coming from,'' Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of Chesebro's challenge is to continue a delay in
transferring $335 million to Texas from the court registry that was
set to occur after the tobacco settlement became final at 5 p.m.
Monday. Chesebro's challenge was filed shortly before then.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco settlement _ at $17.3 billion, the largest civil
judgment in U.S. history _ has been challenged on so many issues so
many times by so many lawyers that the signature sheets to approve
changes ate a fair share of paper by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco lawsuit was filed by Texas in 1996 and settled in
January. It then was challenged on various issues by Republican
attorney general candidate John Cornyn; Sen. Troy Fraser,
R-Horseshoe Bay, and six other legislators; and by Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   All their objections challenged the prospect that private
lawyers Attorney General Dan Morales hired to try the suit might
collect more than $2 billion, based on the judge's 15 percent
award. That award reflected Morales' 15 percent contingency fee
contract with them, a contract under which they would collect only
if the state won the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Chesebro has been associated with Harvard law professor Laurence
Tribe, who assisted Texas in resisting challenges to the tobacco
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Tribe's litigation assistant, Jeff Jamison, said Chesebro still
works with Tribe on at least one active case.
</P>
<P>
   Chesebro, licensed in Texas to practice law since 1987, is a
Harvard law graduate. On his filing he listed an Austin address.
Records from Massachusetts show he owns a condominium in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Potter said Chesebro requested a copy of the tobacco settlement
from the attorney general's office Feb. 3. The language in the
settlement under the latest challenge duplicated language from the
original settlement reached in January. Chesebro's challenge, then,
was too late, Potter said, because it should have been filed when
he had first notice of it.
</P>
<P>
   Chesebro said the settlement did not become final for the
purpose of an appeal until July 24 and his notice was filed within
time limits.
</P>
<P>
   Potter also said Chesebro lacked standing to challenge the
settlement in part because he was a Massachusetts resident with
little contact with Texas. In his filing, Chesebro noted that he
could sue in the case because of the sweeping injunction against
challenges in state courts and federal courts other than where the
suit and settlement were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges to a federal judge's authority to restrict lawsuits
in any other court, similar to Chesebro's in the Texas tobacco
case, were argued in an asbestos-recovery class action decided by
the U.S. Supreme Court in 1997. Chesebro's associate, Tribe, led
the unsuccessful challenge there.
</P>
<P>
   Chesebro himself argued a similar position as a ``friend of the
court'' in a class action against Agent Orange manufacturers,
decided in 1993. In that case, he was on Morales' side, along with
20 other states.
</P>
<P>
   Chesebro, Tribe and another attorney who has assisted Texas in
the tobacco litigation, Jonathan Massey, were sued by a lawyer in a
New Jersey case who challenged their fees for an appeal of the case
the other lawyer tried. They counterclaimed for sanctions, arguing
his claim was baseless. In 1994, a federal court in New Jersey
sided with Chesebro, Tribe and Massey and referred the other lawyer
for disciplinary proceedings and criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
