<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2143 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     08-25 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO REDSHIRT OR NOT TO REDSHIRT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The decision to redshirt is rarely easy and often
agonizing. It is more difficult if you're an upperclassmen. It is
especially difficult if your name is Gabe Crecion and your athletic
future hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of long nights thinking about it,'' said
Crecion, UCLA's junior tight end. ``It wasn't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Crecion, a Chaminade High grad, discussed the situation with
Bruins coach Bob Toledo in the offseason and realized redshirting
in '98 would create the chance to start in the 1999 and 2000
seasons. The players ahead of him on the depth chart (Mike Grieb
and Ryan Neufeld) are seniors, and Crecion would retain two years
of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Crecion wasn't finished shaping his future. He also decided
to quit baseball after pitching for the Bruins for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football didn't use to be my first love, but now it is,'' he
said. ``I've been doing both for two years and it hasn't given me
an advantage in either. In football, I'm not as strong, because I
don't lift weights for baseball. And then when I go to baseball, my
arm isn't in shape because I've been playing football.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said Crecion (eight career catches) will play if either
Grieb or Neufeld is injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell the guys, `You aren't redshirting until after
the last game,' '' Toledo said. ``It's possible (Crecion) will end
up playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Crecion's decision means talented freshman Bryan Fletcher
becomes the No. 3 tight end, with junior college transfer Randy
Hakes the fourth-stringer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Movin' up, movin' down: The Bruins, who begin full-contact
work this morning, released an updated depth chart Tuesday. It
included some notable changes as the heralded freshman class begins
to make its presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Blake Worley is the second-string left tackle, behind
Kris Farris.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Mike Saffer is dueling Ed Anderson for the No. 2 right
guard spot, behind Andy Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Ken Kocher has passed Steve Sua and is challenging
starting Micah Webb for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-year senior Jayson Brown has passed Josh Webb as the
second-string defensive end, behind Kenyon Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Converted quarterback Ed Stansbury is the No. 2 outside
linebacker, behind Brendan Ayanbadejo. (Stansbury was recruited as
a linebacker by numerous schools, Nebraska among them, but chose
the Bruins because they let him try quarterback.)
</P>
<P>
   Converted safety Ryan Nece is the No. 2 inside linebacker,
behind Ramogi Huma. Freshman Robert Thomas trails Nece.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Whitfield is the No. 1 free safety _ Shaun Williams' former
position _ with Tod McBride and Jason Stephens competing for the
second-string spot.
</P>
<P>
   And Jermaine Lewis remains the starting tailback, ahead of Keith
Brown and freshman DeShaun Foster, who has missed several workouts
with a strained groin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
