<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-TV-NHL-NYT &LR;      08-25 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TV-NHL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC AND ESPN EXPECTING PROFIT FROM A 5-YEAR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC and ESPN vowed on Tuesday to make a profit from a new five-
year, $600 million television deal with the National Hockey League
that will begin in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bornstein, president of ESPN and ABC Sports, said he
expected to make money because of the cross promotion throughout
ESPN and ABC, the Internet and retail outlets that he said will
raise ratings and advertising rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make money,'' he said. ``This is a marketing machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will pay the rights fee then buy $50 million-a-year worth
of time on ABC for the games. Fox is paying $45 million for the
coming season, its last.
</P>
<P>
   But at $120 million a year, the new ESPN-ABC deal is 166 percent
higher on average than what Fox and ESPN are now paying. ``I didn't
attend the negotiations wearing a mask and a gun,'' said NHL
commissioner Gary Bettman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite falling ratings, ESPN sees value in the NHL for its
remaining strength among young male viewers; for the key
programming it provides ESPN, ESPN2 and ESPN Classic Sports, and
for distribution of games internationally.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal raises from three to four the number of weekly
games on ESPN2. ABC will carry up to seven weeks of regular-season
games, down from Fox's 11, but up to five Stanley Cup finals games,
more than Fox's maximum of three.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's key to profitability is the extra finals games, said Steve
Solomon, the league's executive vice president. ``The ad market for
those games is strong, very saleable'' he said. At $70 million a
year, ESPN will pay quintuple its current annual fee. ``But if you
look at the NBA on cable, Turner's paying $220 million a year. For
our rights, $70 million makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   One loose end for the league is dealing with Fox, which wants to
exit the coming last season of its deal and for the league to
compensate it for finals games it was unable to show because the
last four ended in four games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NJ-BONNIE-NYT &LR;      08-25 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NJ-BONNIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1 BELIEVED DEAD AS BONNIE ROILS N.Y.-AREA WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also HURRICANE-BONNIE)  
(mk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie made herself felt in the New York region with a
vengeance Tuesday, pounding beaches in New York and New Jersey and
apparently claiming at least one life.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard sea and air rescue teams resumed a search Tuesday
morning for Antonio Mandarino, 23, of Oakland, N.J., who was caught
by a riptide while wading in the surf at Point Pleasant Beach on
Monday evening, officials said. But by day's end Tuesday, the
search had been called off. Mandarino is presumed drowned, said
Coast Guard Lt. John Knotts.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were so dangerous along the New Jersey shore that
four lifeguards swimming in the rough surf off Point Pleasant Beach
had to be rescued by the Coast Guard when they were unable to swim
against a riptide to get back to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Guards were imposing restrictions on beachgoers, ranging from a
ban on entering the water in Point Pleasant Beach to allowing
bathers in up to their knees in Atlantic City. Bathers in Cape May
were allowed to get in the surf ``but I wouldn't call it
swimming,'' said a lifeguard lieutenant, Harry Back.
</P>
<P>
   Malu Iozza had come to Point Pleasant Beach from Palisades Park
with her 5-year-old daughter, Adela, only to find swimming
off-limits. ``I knew the hurricane was farther south,'' she said.
``I didn't think it would affect anything here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Vinnie Dallicardillo of Brick Township, a Point Pleasant
Beach lifeguard, said some beachgoers ``don't like it and we're
bored with no one to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Department of Parks, Recreation and Historic
Preservation closed Jones Beach and Robert Moses and Hither Hill
State Parks. ``We've had strong undercurrents and riptides that
have formed and it is unsafe for people to be in the water,'' said
George Gorman, a department spokesman. ``Even at low tide it's very
deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   High tide had extended 80 feet beyond its normal line, Gorman
said. Employees had removed all lifeguard equipment and stands.
Bulldozers were trying to build a wall of sand to protect the
boardwalk from the rising tide.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service said waves off Fire Island were
seven feet high and were expected to swell to 10 feet as the storm
moves closer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing the hurricane has brought so far has come close to
the summer of 1996, when 17 people drowned off New Jersey in stormy
surf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2324EDT &QL; 
