<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HASKELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOYD HASKELL, 82, EX-SENATOR FROM COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Floyd K. Haskell, whose tall frame and rugged good
looks made him seem chiseled for his role as a U.S. senator but who
never felt quite comfortable in the part, died Tuesday at a
hospital in Washington. He was 82 and lived in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News correspondent Cokie Roberts, a friend of the family,
said the cause of death was pneumonia, a complication that arose
from a brain hemorrhage that Haskell suffered four years ago when
he slipped on an icy sidewalk and hit his head. He had been
vacationing in Maine with his wife, Nina Totenberg, a legal affairs
correspondent for National Public Radio and ABC's ``Nightline''
program, when his condition deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell, D-Colo., where he had once been a state legislator, was
considered by some an ``accidental'' senator because of his narrow
surprise victory over a longtime Republican incumbent, Gordon
Allott, in 1972. By the end of his term, he had carved out a modest
niche not only as a tax reformer but also as an advocate for the
environment, having helped create wilderness areas and encouraged
experiments with solar energy.
</P>
<P>
   A liberal in a Republican state, he was defeated for re-election
in 1978 by Rep. William Armstrong, a conservative who ran an
aggressive, well-financed campaign against Haskell, who disdained
showmanship and had angered special-interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a registered Republican, Haskell said it was the
Vietnam War that drove him into the Democratic fold in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered myself well out of politics at the time,'' he
said in a 1978 interview. ``I never planned to run for office
again. I had become more and more opposed to the war in Vietnam,
and when Nixon invaded Cambodia, that was it. I just felt I
couldn't stay in the Republican Party any longer. I went down to
the courthouse and changed my registration. It was a private act of
conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Haskell was born in Morristown, N.J., the son of an investment
banker. He graduated from Harvard and then Harvard Law School,
where he took a fancy to tax law. He served in the Army during
World War II, seeing action in the Asian theater and achieving the
rank of major.
</P>
<P>
   Later he married Eileen Nicoll and, intent on proving his mettle
out West, soon afterward moved to Colorado, where he specialized in
tax law. From 1965 to 1969, he served in the Colorado state House
of Representatives, becoming assistant majority leader in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   After his one term in the U.S. Senate, he worked as a lobbyist,
served on the board of the watchdog group Common Cause and was
active with a bipartisan group of retired lawmakers pushing for
changes in campaign finance laws and trying to break congressional
gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his second wife, Ms. Totenberg; by three
daughters, Ione Haskell of New York, Eve Maxwell of Colorado and
Pam Haskell of California, all the children of his first wife, and
by three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-REVENGE-PROFILE-NY     08-25 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REVENGE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDCOVER REVENGE FOR A BROKEN MARRIAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Catherine Texier returned home from a visit to
her native France in the summer of 1996, her husband of 18 years _
Joel Rose, a novelist and screenwriter _ greeted her with the news
that he was packing up his books, clothes and photographs and
leaving. The marriage, he said, was over.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Texier, who is a novelist as well, persuaded her husband to
stay so they could try to work things out. But before you could
say, ``Hell hath no fury,'' she had decided to document the process
in a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either that or stick my head in an oven,'' she said on
a hot afternoon two years later and half an emotional universe
away. ``I became two people. One person was powerless and
humiliated. The other one was the writer who had control over the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple divorced last November, and Ms. Texier's portrait of
the marital meltdown has just arrived in bookstores. Titled
``Breakup'' (Doubleday), it has received a lot of attention in
certain literary circles because in the early 1980s, Ms. Texier and
Rose founded Between C and D, _ a Lower East Side literary journal
that published promising writers, including Patrick McGrath, David
Foster Wallace and Tama Janowitz.
</P>
<P>
   In their ``C and D'' days (the journal died before the marriage
did, in 1990) the couple were considered the very soul of
impoverished artistic virtue, publishing their journal and
supporting themselves and two children on $10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Rose finally left the marriage early last year for his editor at
Crown Books, who had paid him a handsome advance for his latest
novel, which came out last summer. It, too, is about a doomed love
affair _ but not about his failed marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Texier's memoir is unsparing in its detail of their
separation and divorce. It is laden with accounts of the poignant
sexual encounters between a separated husband and wife, and even
violent revenge scenarios Ms. Texier imagined. In
stream-of-consciousness prose, Ms. Texier chronicles the distressed
children and incredulous friends, the lost rituals and 3 a.m. phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   But at lunch on a recent steamy afternoon, Ms. Texier, 50,
fairly glowed with well-being. Wearing a black camisole top, 19
wriggly silver-wire bracelets and 4 silver rings, her corkscrew
hair glowing electric red in the sunlight, she was woman and she
was roaring.
</P>
<P>
   Born in a resort town on the Brittany coast to a single mother,
Ms. Texier was raised mostly by her grandparents in a suburb of
Paris. Her grandfather was the director of Bakelite in France. ``I
still collect Fiestaware,'' she said. ``Look, I am bourgeois.''
</P>
<P>
   She studied American literature at the University of Paris,
then, eager to get away from home, took a job at Women's Wear Daily
in New York for a summer. ``I remember stepping off the plane at
JFK,'' she said, ``and as soon as my foot touched the ground, I
knew. Within about two months I decided I was never going back.''
</P>
<P>
   She met Rose at a dinner party on New Year's Day in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was love at first sight, or something like that,'' she
said. They moved in together six months later and were married in
1981. She started writing in English _ of her three novels, only
the first was written first in French _ and has never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to shed my French identity,'' she said, in
English virtually devoid of an accent. ``Writing in English was so
liberating because it was not the language I grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly as an excuse to meet other writers, partly to publish
their own work, she and Rose started Between C and D, in 1983,
during what Ms. Texier calls the ``heyday'' of the East Village.
The magazine was even packed in glassine envelopes. ``The plastic
bag referred to the dope bags in the neighborhood,'' she said,
``and we played up that theme, because that's the kind of writing
we were getting, that we were writing. That rough, edgy,
sex-drugs-and-rock-and-roll thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``Breakup'' is just as rough; some reviews accuse
Ms. Texier of cashing in on the exhibitionist memoir boom, but she
defends her work. ``There was never any moment when I was pouring
out my feelings in a gratuitous way,'' she said. She said she
didn't know if her husband had read the book, and that their
conversation these days is limited to parenting responsibilities:
their two daughters, 17 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   Why write a book in which you fantasize about murdering your
husband's lover and which your children will probably read someday?
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the writer's responsibility to her children?'' she
asked. ``I don't know. My elder daughter has never read any of my
books, and she's not reading this one, by choice. Which is, I
think, a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ms. Texier is dating, she said, ``to use that funny
American phrase.'' She still lives in the apartment on East Seventh
Street that she shared with Rose, and has put aside most of her
post-divorce anguish to concentrate on her next novel _ ``about a
woman who is having an affair with a man 20 years younger,'' she
said with a sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   And what's the theme? How Catherine Got Her Groove Back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say it's close to my life,'' she said. ``And it's a
much lighter book. At least so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
