</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BARNES-CAMPAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWIMMING COACH SAVORS HIS TITLE SHOT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the swimming and diving coach at Mount Vernon (N.Y.) High
School, Larry Barnes has no concept of being in over his head. So
to make that suggestion about his coming bout against Yory Boy
Campas, for the International Boxing Federation junior middleweight
championship, would be useless.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes will be swimming in deep water for this fight,
because he normally fights as a 147-pound welterweight. Even so, he
believes he can stick with Campas, a hard-nosed slugger who has
lost just twice in 73 fights (71-2), at the higher weight. The
fight is on the undercard of the Oscar De La Hoya-Julio Cesar
Chavez welterweight championship fight at the Thomas and Mack
Center in Las Vegas, Nev., on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 154 pounds with Yory Boy, I don't have to look for him and
he doesn't have to look for me,'' Barnes said during lunch in
Manhattan on Tuesday. ``We can dance.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be Barnes' second world title fight. Felix Trinidad
scored a fourth-round knockout against Barnes (44-2) in 1995.
Barnes' other loss came against Saoul Mamby on Aug. 23, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he felt he was in control against Trinidad before he
got knocked out. Campas has also been knocked out in the fourth
round by Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix almost killed Yory Boy,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has always been a working boxer, which means that he held
a regular job between fights. About the time that Barnes lost to
Trinidad he had received a promotion at his alma mater to take over
as the swimming coach. As a student, he had been on the diving team
and was a place-kicker on the football team; soon after he
graduated in 1985, he took a job as the pool director and locker
room attendant.
</P>
<P>
   With the promotion came more responsibilities. He said he
decided to take some time away from boxing to help guide his team
in the state sectionals. He stayed away from boxing for nine
months, but Barnes didn't stop training. He would run around the
pool deck in the winter with the water temperature from the pool
heating the air to 80 degrees. He still works out in the pool by
throwing punches under water.
</P>
<P>
   After his layoff, Barnes returned with a sixth-round technical
knockout against Dave Clark on Aug. 16, 1996. Since the loss to
Trinidad he has won six straight bouts. He knocked Roger Brown out
in the fourth round on May 28 in his last bout.
</P>
<P>
   Right before he got the call for the fight against Campas,
Barnes was telling his wife, Annette, that he did not think he was
going to get another title shot, because he was 32 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking, tick-tock, tick-tock,'' Barnes said.
``It's now or never. It's sink or swim. I've had a lot of success
in this game. Nothing is promised in the sport of boxing. I'm very
fortunate to get this shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said a victory could lead to bigger and better things.
But a loss could force him to hang up his gloves and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would want to register me as a journeyman fighter,''
Barnes said. ``I don't think my wife and my manager would stand for
that. If you stick around fighting for just washing machine money,
you're not going to have all your marbles too tight at the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980825.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-GARDENS-NYT &LR;      08-25 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-GARDENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABOUT NEW YORK: THE SERPENT IN THE GARDEN OF RENEWAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Plump, green apples plopped to the ground as Jose
(Chema) Soto pried them loose from the branches. He climbed down
and caught his breath, a reminder that he should exercise more
since having a heart attack. He beheld the tree, which towered over
the Caribbean-style wooden shack that he and his friends built in
the middle of a Bronx community garden bursting with enough
vegetables and flowers to rival any greengrocer.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, this was just an empty lot on the corner of 158th
Street and Brook Avenue. Soto and his friends turned it into Rincon
Criollo _ Down-Home Corner _ where they nurture more than just
plants. It is a place where the traditional Puerto Rican music of
bomba and plena has flowered. It is ground zero for folklore.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for Soto that it is also near ground zero for the next
phase of the Melrose Commons urban renewal zone, where hundreds of
new homes have already arisen on surrounding blocks. For Rincon
Criollo and 14 other community gardens that have long thrived on
lots leased annually from the city, the future seems as
unpredictable as the weather. A few months ago, the city's
Department of Housing Preservation and Development took control of
the properties to allow for speedier development. Some gardens will
vanish under bricks and mortar. Soto is lucky, since borough
officials have proposed letting him start over a block south in
what is now a fenced thicket of weeds. Some luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we supposed to do, take our peach and apple trees out
by the roots?'' Soto said. ``Over there, the ground is full of
rocks. It took us more than 20 years to do this. Before we see
trees like this over there, we'll be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the proposed lot. ``Not even a curse would grow
there,'' he concluded. ``Don't move me anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The community gardeners have banded together to mount their own
urban land reform effort. They have met with politicians,
circulated petitions and enlisted the aid of advocacy groups. They
knew that their leases were temporary, but they wonder why the city
had to go after them, considering all the other lots that have lain
fallow and fenced in for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't they take it before, when it was dirty?'' said Luis
Gonzalez, whose garden is near Crotona Park. ``Are they showing it
to potential buyers because they saw how we cleaned it up?''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to their worries, they said they have yet to hear from
Housing Preservation officials to explain what plans lie ahead. A
spokeswoman for the agency did not respond to a reporter's
questions about the Melrose gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer said development plans,
still five years away from groundbreaking, are jeopardizing four
gardens. He said that a community effort to redesign the
neighborhood has included plans to relocate several existing
gardens and create three more acres of parkland. He suggested that
the city agency take a closer look at such local efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying very hard here to do the right thing for the
community so it can rebound with housing and gardens,'' he said.
``But with a plan. Not the way HPD does, which is, `Give me all of
it, and I won't talk with you.' It's mindless, to use a favorite
mayoral term.''
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen gardeners met at Rincon Criollo last week to map
new strategies. They were joined by residents of other communities
who were also fighting to preserve their oases. Some of them
munched on grapes picked from vines dangling above the maze of
spotless walkways between the garden plots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government never expected this,'' Soto said. ``This used
to have only rats, junkies and a hole that was 10 feet deep. Now it
is a place for deep culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Sierra, a plenero who has been active in Rincon Criollo
for 15 years, can attest to that. From the little shack on Brook
Avenue, he has gone on to perform at theaters and museums. In turn,
he has played host to countless musicians, athletes and politicians
who make sure they pay their respects at Rincon Criollo whenever
they visit the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the missing link between Puerto Rico and New York,''
he said. ``Here. We feel like we're in Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   The plenas that he sings add to that atmosphere. For years they
carried the news of the era in song. The gardeners' current plight
would seem like a logical topic for a plena. ``We are working on
one,'' Sierra said. ``It is our secret weapon. We will hold onto it
until the last minute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
