<SLUG> BC-TEN-HAMLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SHAKY MOMENTS, RAFTER AVOIDS EARLY EXIT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ Like an artist who suddenly finds his voice,
Patrick Rafter found his game at the Hamlet Cup a year ago. Before
he arrived, he was just another name, albeit 16th-ranked. Then
Rafter rode a devil-may-care serve and volley attack to the final
of the Hamlet and went on to capture the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter returned to the scene of his metamorphosis with mixed
results Tuesday night. Spraying volleys and backhands into the net
at inopportune moments, the second-seeded Australian, ranked third
in the world, still hung on for a 6-2, 4-6, 6-4 victory over
Spain's pesky Javier Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to scrap to get out of the rut I was in,'' Rafter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's yelp, which he employs on bad shots, reverberated
around the stadium court at the Hamlet Golf and Country Club. But
when he hit a crosscourt backhand that nicked the net and fell away
from Sanchez's outstretched racquet on match point, he could
breathe a sigh of relief. It was his third match point of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's resourcefulness and mobility also saved him from a
premature exit. He stabbed for balls as if his racquet were a
Ping-Pong paddle, and the shots made it over the net. He won most
of the long rallies, causing Sanchez to yell facetiously at one
point, ``I'm old, man.'' And Rafter had the lion's share of balls
that slapped the tape and trickled over the net.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Rafter needed no such help. But after his U.S. Open
triumph, he plummeted into an emotional trough, the victim of what
Australians call ``the tall poppy syndrome,'' his countryman Mark
Woodforde said. In another words, the poppy that grows the highest
must be cut the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Besieged by critical fans and reporters, Rafter slumped badly
after the Open, compiling an ordinary 19-13 record in matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more the expectation than the press,'' Rafter said.
``People were disappointed but not mad at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodforde, a 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) loser to Filip Dewulf of Belgium
earlier Tuesday, said: ``He was dragging his feet. You could tell
he wasn't happy with himself. He's a pretty upbeat guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's slide prompted John McEnroe to call him a ``One-Slam
Wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter did not appear Grand Slam ready Tuesday night, as Hamlet
organizers held their breath fearing that their biggest draw would
disappear. One fan, Sara Rand, of Roslyn, N.Y., focused on Rafter's
every move. She said if Rafter had been defeated, ``I wouldn't be
as excited but I would come back. However, I came primarily to see
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's sloppy performance belied his momentum of late. Since
receiving a ``chin-up, mate'' fax from the Australian great John
Newcombe during Wimbledon, Rafter has compiled a 21-3 mark, winning
four tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he broke Sanchez's serve immediately in the first set,
then salvaged three break points to push ahead, 5-2. His set-winner
in the subsequent game was another backhand passing shot that hit
the net and went over.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez attacked Rafter's second serve to earn a break and take
a 3-2 lead in the second set. It was the final break of the set,
and Sanchez, remaining steady while Rafter self-destructed, tied
the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second set I felt bad, flat,'' Rafter said. ``I was
just trying to pull through. Then I felt good again in the third
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's recovery on an off night bolstered his mission to
defend his Open title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go all the way here because it helps my
preparation,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
