<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRE WAS PRESENT AS WELLS SIGNED BASEBALLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Clark, the American League umpire under
investigation in the sale of baseballs that were purportedly used
in David Wells' perfect game, acknowledged Tuesday night that he
was present when Wells autographed balls but disputed an account
that he received any of them.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Yankee employee said Tuesday that Wells had signed
two dozen or more balls for Clark when the umpire worked a series
with the Boston Red Sox at Yankee Stadium 11 days after Wells' May
17 performance.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said before Tuesday night's Yankees-Angels game at the
Stadium that the balls were not for him.
</P>
<P>
   The balls, Clark said, were for Rich Gressle, a friend of his,
who subsequently sold six balls to a memorabilia dealer on Long
Island. The balls were accompanied by an authenticating letter that
bore Clark's signature and said he got the balls from John
Hirschbeck, one of the four umpires who worked the perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Gressle said in an interview that he wrote the
letter and forged Clark's name, adding that Clark had nothing to do
with the sale of the balls and knew nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who vehemently denied any involvement, said Gressle was
in the umpires' locker room with Clark because he had brought
photographs for Wells that the pitcher had requested. One of them
was a photo of Cal Ripken Jr. with Joe DiMaggio the night in 1995
that Ripken broke Lou Gehrig's consecutive-game streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Wells that Richie was here,'' Clark said. `I had
introduced Richie and David before. David wanted some pictures that
Richie had taken. I just put those two guys together. They made a
trade. What they did I don't know. Those guys were talking and I
was sitting there. He signed the balls for Gressle. I was not party
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had asked Wells to sign the balls, Clark said
he had not.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Gressle took the balls with him, he said: ``I
would imagine. At no time did I have any of those balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has declined comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the balls were not from the perfect game, even
though that was how Gressle portrayed them when he sold six balls
for $300 each to Mark Lewis, a memorabilia dealer in Centereach,
N.Y. A member of the Yankees clubhouse crew said that right after
the game ended, the ball boy took the ball bag containing 14 balls
and delivered it to Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who returned from a one-week vacation Monday night, had
been scheduled to work Tuesday night's game at third base, but he
was replaced by Terry Craft. Phyllis Merhige, the league's senior
vice president, said that a fifth umpire was added to the crew
because the Yankees and the Angels are scheduled to play a
day-night doubleheader Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
