<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS SET THE WNBA STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MELANIE HAUSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``Bring on da Bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   That sign, held high above the crowd at the Compaq Center here,
said it all Monday night. In a season in which the defending
champions of the Women's National Basketball Association have set
WNBA records for the games won in a season, winning percentage and
average winning margin, the Houston Comets could use some
competition.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the winner of Tuesday night's series
between Cleveland and Phoenix, the 1998 Comets are looking a lot
like recent versions of the Chicago Bulls. All of which means that
this WNBA title is the Comets' to lose. As was the two-game
semifinal sweep of the Charlotte Sting, concluded by 77-61 Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Texas brag? More like fact.
</P>
<P>
   In two short seasons, the Comets have set the standard for
women's professional basketball and lived out a dream that once
belonged only to the boys. Perhaps, then, it's fitting that the
Comets are led by a player like Cynthia Cooper, who came from
nowhere to put a league on the map, whose idols included Magic
Johnson, Larry Bird and Norm Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, Cooper's team ranks above some of the best the
NBA has had to offer. Consider that the 1998 Comets won 90 percent
of their games in the regular season (27-3), while the 1995-1996
Bulls set the NBA regular season record of 87.8 percent (72-10). Or
that the Comets outscored their opponents by an average of 12.6
points per game, compared to the NBA's best of 12.3 set by the
1971-72 Lakers, or the 12.2 margin by those '95-96 Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cooper, while sounding the apples-and-oranges refrain, was
surprised to hear the WNBA's numbers and how they compared with the
boys. ``That's really hard for me to think about,'' she said.
``Women's ball is so new. We don't have the history. We can't look
back and compare to anything. But I know it's something special.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you're associated with or compared to some great teams
in basketball history, that's awesome,'' Cooper said. ``A lot of
those guys were our role models growing up. That's who we
watched.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Comets lead their league in role models. Cooper, the
two-time league most valuable player, has been the heart and soul
of the WNBA in its first two seasons. She led the league in scoring
this year, but its her all-around game, developed in the European
leagues, that makes the Comets go. Add in Sheryl Swoopes, Tina
Thompson and the tiny defensive whiz Kim Perrott, and Houston sends
chills down the spines of opposing coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is at hand,'' said coach Van Chancellor, whose
team opens its title defense Thursday night in either Cleveland or
Phoenix. ``We're playing for a championship. I'm not saying we're
going to win a championship. I'm saying were playing for one.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Cleveland and Phoenix have beaten the Comets once this
season (New York handed them their third loss), and either one
poses problems for Houston. Cleveland has a good inside game and
good depth, while Phoenix relies on good shooting and a physical
style.
</P>
<P>
   Who would Chancellor rather play? ``Whoever's not there,''
Chancellor said with a grin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
