</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYC-COMPTROLLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KEEPING NEW YORK CITY IN SHAPE  
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 26:
</P>
<P>
   The New York City comptroller has done a big and important study
on the cost of fixing the city's shaky infrastructure. The danger
is that the numbers are so huge that New Yorkers will simply throw
up their hands in despair and turn their attention to issues that
seem more manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller Alan Hevesi estimates that the city would need to
spend $90 billion to get the subways, water mains, schools and
transit system in good repair within 10 years. Government agencies
have budgeted about $52 billion, and although these numbers can and
should be raised in some cases, the city will never be able to come
close to Hevesi's target. But by spending wisely it can keep
problems under control and avoid sliding backward into a worse
state of disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   The news from Hevesi's report is not all bad. The city has come
a long way since the financial chaos of the 1970s, and most
agencies now do a decent job of keeping track of their inventory
and setting priorities. The prison and court systems, along with a
few other areas, are in good shape or moving toward that goal
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   There are some cases in which the poor state of aging facilities
poses an opportunity to rethink the way city services are
organized. For instance, many of the city's firehouses were not
built to handle today's heavy equipment. But these firehouses are
often in the wrong place anyway, based on ancient deployment
patterns that were locked in by community pressure to retain the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing point made by the comptroller was not about
capital spending at all, but the inadequacy of maintenance
programs. A study done for the city found that New York spends only
about 40 percent of the private-sector standard on routine upkeep.
The cost of inadequate maintenance in the past has been driven home
so forcefully that it seems amazing the city has not learned its
lesson. Repairs on the long-neglected Williamsburg Bridge have been
so expensive and time-consuming that the report estimates it might
have been just as cheap to build a whole new span 10 years ago when
the scope of the problems was first uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   The school system presents both the most expensive
infrastructure challenge and the one where bad management poses the
greatest threat. The buildings are in a terrible state, and the
School Construction Authority has yet to prove it can renovate
buildings efficiently. Maintenance spending has been only about 10
percent of the private-industry standard, although a recent suit by
the teachers' union has forced a modest improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller's report notes, sensibly, that the Board of
Education could solve some of its facility problems by going to a
year-round schedule in overcrowded districts. But unless the board
is prepared to spend more money on maintenance, the billions of
dollars that have been poured into construction and renovation of
school buildings will turn out to have been wasted over the long
run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
