</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUKE-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DRUGS FOR A NUCLEAR DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 26:
</P>
<P>
   While the risk of a nuclear power plant disaster is very small,
state and federal disaster agencies owe it to people who live near
reactors to help them guard against the health dangers of a nuclear
leak or meltdown. The availability of potassium iodide pills can
help that effort.
</P>
<P>
   There is clear evidence that potassium iodide, if taken shortly
before or after a nuclear accident, can block the absorption of
radioactive iodine, which can cause thyroid cancer. This effect has
been known for many years, and the drug was approved by the Food
and Drug Administration in 1978. But federal and state agencies
involved with disaster planning, uncertain about health risks of
the drug and perhaps not wanting to alarm residents living near
nuclear reactors, have not publicized potassium iodide. Data from
Poland in the aftermath of the Chernobyl accident, however, have
shown that benefits of the drug outweigh risks of side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium iodide is not effective against all isotopes that can
cause illness. But coupled with aggressive evacuation plans, which
should remain the primary response strategy to a nuclear accident,
its use can be helpful. In June, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
endorsed a proposal that encourages states to make potassium iodide
available to the public and that provides federal funding for
supplies of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   The current policy in many states, including New York, is to
distribute the drug only to emergency workers and to prisoners and
hospital-bound individuals who cannot be evacuated quickly. An
advisory committee appointed by the New York state health
commissioner has recommended that the state consider giving the
pills to people living near reactors. The logistics of distributing
pills and insuring they are available when needed have yet to be
worked out. But these are not insurmountable problems.
</P>
<P>
   One concern is that distributing the drug would give people a
false sense of security in nuclear emergencies and create
resistance to evacuation. This problem can be addressed by
educating the public about the benefits and limits of potassium
iodide. It should not be used as an excuse to avoid acting on this
public health measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
